('ed24a551-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Jamari Williams: A Player Profile', 'jamari-williams-a-player-profile', NULL, '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Jamari Williams is a 6&#8217;5 junior wing forward from Miami, Florida, whose game has been steadily  evolving with each season. Known for his versatility on the court, Williams is a dynamic player  capable of impacting the game in many ways. This past season, he averaged 10.3 points per game,  6.5 rebounds per game, and 2.5 assists. Last season, he put up 12.7 points per game, 5.3  rebounds, and 2.1 assists, while also racking up over 30 steals in both seasons, showcasing his defensive prowess and hustle. His combination of scoring, rebounding, and playmaking has  made him a key asset for his team, and his growth as a player continues to shine through. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As a student-athlete, balancing the responsibilities of academics and basketball can be challenging. For Jamari, it’s all about managing his time efficiently and staying disciplined. &#8220;The  hardest part about being a student-athlete is carrying the image of yourself as a ‘leader.’ You’re  always looked up to, and there’s pressure to succeed both in the classroom and on the court,&#8221; he  explains. &#8220;It’s good pressure, though. It matures you in certain aspects of life and makes you  more of a man.&#8221; </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For Jamari, this pressure is part of the journey, helping him grow and learn the importance of  balance as he continues to pursue both his academic and athletic goals. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As Jamari looks ahead to his next step in basketball, he is currently in the transfer portal. He has received interest from several schools and is focused on finding the best fit for his future. &#8220;I like four of my options right now. They all seem good, and I’m really interested in playing at a Division II school in Hawaii,&#8221; Jamari says. His next move is one he’s approaching with careful  consideration, aiming to find a school that aligns with his goals and offers the right environment  for him to grow as a player. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Jamari’s ultimate goal is to have a lasting impact on the game of basketball. &#8220;My end goal is to  hopefully coach basketball at the highest level,&#8221; he says. &#8220;Before that, I want to play overseas  and gain experience at that level. After my playing career, I want to give back to the next  generation by becoming a trainer and teaching students what I’ve learned throughout my  journey.&#8221;</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">With a clear vision for his future, Jamari is determined to use his experiences to help others reach  their potential, whether as a player or a coach. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Jamari’s basketball journey started in a way that many may not expect. Originally a football  player, Jamari’s passion for basketball blossomed after an injury in football led him to fall in  love with the game. &#8220;I got hurt playing football, and that’s when I started playing in the rec </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">league when I was about 10 years old,&#8221; he explains. &#8220;I loved the excitement of basketball and began taking it seriously in my freshman year of high school.&#8221; </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This transition from football to basketball wasn’t easy, and Jamari had to prove himself to his </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">coaches. He started out on the JV team before making his way to varsity, where he earned the  respect of those who had doubted him. The journey was especially challenging, as he was the  only athlete from his high school going off to college far from home. Yet, his hard work and </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">determination paid off, and he found success in his new environment </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Jamari credits his resilience and mindset to the support of his family, particularly his uncle, who  has been a guiding influence throughout his journey. &#8220;My uncle always told me, ‘Enjoy the  traffic of it all through the journey,’&#8221; Jamari recalls. &#8220;It’s about embracing the ups and downs,  learning from each moment along the way.&#8221; </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Another quote that resonates with Jamari is, &#8220;Face everything and rise,&#8221; which has been a mantra  that’s helped him push through challenges both on and off the court. His ability to face adversity  head-on has been a key factor in his growth as both a player and a person. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As Jamari continues to evolve as a player and a leader, he remains focused on his goals for the  future. Whether it’s finding the right college program, succeeding in his basketball career, or  eventually coaching the next generation, Jamari Williams is determined to keep improving and  making the most of his opportunities. With his dedication, work ethic, and growth mindset, he is  well on his way to achieving great things both on and off the court.</span></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'AP963', NULL, '2025-04-15 17:09:03', 0, 'Jamari Williams is a 6’5 junior wing forward from Miami, Florida, whose game has been steadily  evolving with each season. Known for his versatility on the court, Williams is a dynamic player  capable of impacting the game in many ways. This past season, he averaged 10.3 points per game,  6.5 rebounds per game, and 2.5…\n', NULL, NULL, 7),
('ed25098c-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'video', 'New Media Blast!', 'new-media-blast', NULL, '<h2><strong>This Week on New Media Beat:</strong></h2>\n<h2></h2>\n<audio class=\"wp-audio-shortcode\" id=\"audio-11366-1\" preload=\"none\" style=\"width: 100%;\" controls=\"controls\"><source type=\"audio/mpeg\" src=\"https://newmediabeat.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/NMB-6-Web-2025-04-17.mp3?_=1\" /><a href=\"https://newmediabeat.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/NMB-6-Web-2025-04-17.mp3\">https://newmediabeat.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/NMB-6-Web-2025-04-17.mp3</a></audio>\n<h2></h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Will Labelling Social Keep You Safe?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Why Did Trump Kick the TikTok Ban Down the Road?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Youtube: Do Creators Care about Video Counts?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>New Social: Sez Us? Sez What?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Hey Gamer: Are Exploits Cheating?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Can Apps Sell Houses?</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.newmediabeat.org/\"><strong>New Media Beat</strong></a> covers new media news from around the world. NMB is a production of Media Studies students from <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/\" target=\"_self\" rel=\"noopener\">SUNY Old Westbury.</a>   We scour the web for news about about media and journalism.</p>\n<p>This week NMB is co-produced by Jaden Nunez, John Deliso, and Henry Wilson. Our engineer this week is Jaden Nunez. Our hosts are Ava Holdgruen and Juliana Vasquez.</p>\n<p>The NMB Podcast streams live on <a href=\"http://www.owwrny.org/\">Old Westbury Web Radio</a> Thursdays from 12:00-1:00 PM EST.  Can&#8217;t listen live? Our podcast will be <a href=\"https://newmediabeat.org/?cat=17\">posted</a> for your listening pleasure every Saturday afternoon.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-11373\" src=\"uploads/NMB-6-Fallen-Daf-NMB-GRB-Rect-600x373.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"373\" srcset=\"uploads/NMB-6-Fallen-Daf-NMB-GRB-Rect-600x373.jpg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/NMB-6-Fallen-Daf-NMB-GRB-Rect-1200x745.jpg 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/NMB-6-Fallen-Daf-NMB-GRB-Rect-768x477.jpg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/NMB-6-Fallen-Daf-NMB-GRB-Rect-1536x954.jpg 1536w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/NMB-6-Fallen-Daf-NMB-GRB-Rect-300x186.jpg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/NMB-6-Fallen-Daf-NMB-GRB-Rect.jpg 2001w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" /></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'TC527', NULL, '2025-04-20 17:23:20', 0, 'This Week on New Media Beat: Will Labelling Social Keep You Safe? Why Did Trump Kick the TikTok Ban Down the Road? Youtube: Do Creators Care about Video Counts? New Social: Sez Us? Sez What? Hey Gamer: Are Exploits Cheating? Can Apps Sell Houses? New Media Beat covers new media news from around the world….\n', NULL, NULL, 15),
('ed2561e7-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'video', 'Podcast Blossom!', 'podcast-blossom', NULL, '<h2><strong>This Week on New Media Beat:</strong></h2>\n<h2></h2>\n<audio class=\"wp-audio-shortcode\" id=\"audio-11383-1\" preload=\"none\" style=\"width: 100%;\" controls=\"controls\"><source type=\"audio/mpeg\" src=\"https://newmediabeat.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/NMB-7-Web-2025-04-24.mp3?_=1\" /><a href=\"https://newmediabeat.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/NMB-7-Web-2025-04-24.mp3\">https://newmediabeat.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/NMB-7-Web-2025-04-24.mp3</a></audio>\n<h2></h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Tariff War: Will China Say No to Hollywood?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Hey Dollface! Can A.I. Make You a Doll?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Why Does the NBA Have a Portal on X?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Hey Chloe, What&#8217;s an A.I. Influencer?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>How Did Dubai Chocolate Go Global on Social?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Does the Gotham Sports App Know What Fans Want?</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.newmediabeat.org/\"><strong>New Media Beat</strong></a> covers new media news from around the world. NMB is a production of <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/programs-courses/media-and-communications-ba\">Media &amp; Communications</a> students from <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/\" target=\"_self\" rel=\"noopener\">SUNY Old Westbury.</a>   We scour the web for news about about media and journalism.</p>\n<p>This week NMB is co-produced by Jaden Nunez and John Deliso. Our engineer this week is Jaden Nunez. Our hosts are Muhamed Doucouré and Deborah Flamenbaum.</p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_11386\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-11386\" style=\"width: 1200px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"wp-image-11386 size-large\" src=\"uploads/NMB-7-Sunflower-NMB-Y-Rect-Border-1200x754.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1200\" height=\"754\" srcset=\"uploads/NMB-7-Sunflower-NMB-Y-Rect-Border-1200x754.jpg 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/NMB-7-Sunflower-NMB-Y-Rect-Border-600x377.jpg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/NMB-7-Sunflower-NMB-Y-Rect-Border-768x483.jpg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/NMB-7-Sunflower-NMB-Y-Rect-Border-1536x966.jpg 1536w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/NMB-7-Sunflower-NMB-Y-Rect-Border-300x189.jpg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/NMB-7-Sunflower-NMB-Y-Rect-Border.jpg 2001w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-11386\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Sunflower photo: Deborah Flamenbaum</figcaption></figure>\n<p>The NMB Podcast streams live on <a href=\"http://www.owwrny.org/\">Old Westbury Web Radio</a> Thursdays from 12:00-1:00 PM EST.  Can&#8217;t listen live? Our podcast will be <a href=\"https://newmediabeat.org/?cat=17\">posted</a> for your listening pleasure every Saturday afternoon.</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'TC527', NULL, '2025-04-26 18:58:25', 0, 'This Week on New Media Beat: Tariff War: Will China Say No to Hollywood? Hey Dollface! Can A.I. Make You a Doll? Why Does the NBA Have a Portal on X? Hey Chloe, What’s an A.I. Influencer? How Did Dubai Chocolate Go Global on Social? Does the Gotham Sports App Know What Fans Want? New…\n', NULL, NULL, 15),
('ed25bcd8-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'video', 'SNL: From Live TV to TikTok', 'snl-from-live-tv-to-tiktok', NULL, '<p data-block-id=\"e14bd17f-6079-4d4d-8b85-6e73ddb8ff17\" data-pm-slice=\"1 1 []\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter wp-image-8904 size-full\" src=\"uploads/SNL-Skit-1.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"686\" height=\"290\" /></p>\n<p data-block-id=\"e14bd17f-6079-4d4d-8b85-6e73ddb8ff17\" data-pm-slice=\"1 1 []\">&#8220;Cause these men ain&#8217;t what?&#8221; You can find the answer to that question by watching Ego Nwodim&#8217;s SNL skit on TikTok. Viewers had a lot to say after watching this late-night skit go wrong. Popular clips from the show are now watched on social media. Users flocked to TikTok to create videos and comment on them.</p>\n<h1>How SNL became TikTok Famous</h1>\n<p>Does anyone watch live TV anymore? Millions of people are watching clips on social media instead. Saturday Night Live has turned 50, but is finding new fans on TikTok. Skits have gone viral as people continue to reuse the content. TikTok&#8217;s short-form style makes it the perfect platform to display SNL skits. Even the show has an <a href=\"https://www.tiktok.com/@nbcsnl?is_from_webapp=1&amp;sender_device=pc\">account</a> with clips updated every week. One of TikTok&#8217;s capabilities is that users can comment on videos. That is something that cannot be done with live TV.</p>\n<p>Some people have already noticed this shift from live TV to TikTok. <a href=\"https://variety.com/author/andrew-wallenstein/\">Andrew Wallenstein</a> discusses this on <a href=\"https://www.iheart.com/podcast/1119-strictly-business-30950719/\">&#8220;Strictly Business&#8221;</a>, his entertainment and business news podcast.</p>\n<blockquote><p>&#8220;TV shows and movies have taken a backseat to TikTok&#8217;s never-ending algorithmically targeted feed of short-form videos.&#8221;</p></blockquote>\n<p>Wallenstein had a lot to say about how TikTok is changing the future of the media. He even admits that he reaches for the app more than TV. He also often chooses TikTok over his paid streaming services.</p>\n<h1>Sketch Gone Wrong</h1>\n<p>In Season 50, episode 17, <a href=\"https://www.tvinsider.com/people/ego-nwodim/#biography\">Ego Nwodim</a> stops by the Weekend Update with <a href=\"https://www.tvinsider.com/people/colin-jost/\">Colin Jost</a> and <a href=\"https://www.tvinsider.com/people/michael-che/\">Michael Che</a>. The hot topic of conversation? How the White House Correspondents&#8217; Association <a href=\"https://www.npr.org/2025/03/29/nx-s1-5344487/white-house-correspondents-dinner-amber-ruffin\">canceled</a> their comedian for this year&#8217;s dinner. Nwodim&#8217;s stand up persona, &#8220;Miss Eggy&#8221;, gave her take on being the comedian. &#8220;Good god this food is bland tonight,&#8221; she said. Miss Eggy soon went off the main course and onto a new one. &#8220;I saw y&#8217;all got jicama on the menu. More like jicama another man with another excuse.&#8221;</p>\n<p>In this part of her skit, Nwodim did a call and response bit. The audience was unfamiliar with the catchphrases. It was supposed to lead &#8220;to (intentional) dead silence,&#8221; <a href=\"https://www.nbc.com/nbc-insider/snl-ego-nwodim-weekend-update-audience-watch#:~:text=Part%20of%20Nwodim%27s%20play%20on%20a%20typical%20club%20comedy%20set%20was%20her%20use%20of%20catchphrases%20no%20one%20in%20the%20audience%20was%20familiar%20with%2C%20leading%20to%20(intentional)%20dead%20silence\">said</a> NBC. What went wrong you may ask? When Miss Eggy said, &#8220;cause these men ain&#8217;t what,&#8221; the audience yelled &#8220;Shit!&#8221;. Everyone, including Jost and Che, erupted into laughter. &#8220;We finna get fined for that&#8221; said Nwodim. While incredibly hilarious in the moment, they may actually get fined for that.</p>\n<p>According to the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), federal law <a href=\"https://www.fcc.gov/consumers/guides/obscene-indecent-and-profane-broadcasts\">prohibits</a> &#8220;obscene, indecent, and profane content&#8221; from being aired on broadcast TV. The FCC does not have a specific list of curse words that are not allowed but, &#8220;shit&#8221; is known to be one of them. If a specific curse word is used, such as &#8220;shit&#8221; or &#8220;fuck,&#8221; it <a href=\"https://help.prx.org/hc/en-us/articles/360044988133-A-guide-to-broadcast-obscenities-and-issuing-content-advisories#:~:text=Can%20you%20give%20me%20some%20guidelines%20for%20indecent%20language%3F\">must be</a> noted to stations so that it can be bleeped. If not, the FCC could fine the broadcast show for using the word.</p>\n<h1>How did TikTok users react?</h1>\n<p>TikTok users are spreading around the uncensored version of the skit. Many TV watchers were upset that it was censored for them. SNL also uploaded the censored skit on their <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/@SaturdayNightLive\">YouTube</a> and TikTok.</p>\n<blockquote class=\"tiktok-embed\" cite=\"https://www.tiktok.com/@funwithtrivia/video/7490054750499573022\" data-video-id=\"7490054750499573022\" data-embed-from=\"oembed\" style=\"max-width:605px; min-width:325px;\">\n<section> <a target=\"_blank\" title=\"@funwithtrivia\" href=\"https://www.tiktok.com/@funwithtrivia?refer=embed\">@funwithtrivia</a> </p>\n<p>The S-bomb was dropped on Saturday Night Live during Ego Nwodim’s Weekend Update bit <a title=\"snl\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.tiktok.com/tag/snl?refer=embed\">#snl</a> <a title=\"snlsketch\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.tiktok.com/tag/snlsketch?refer=embed\">#snlsketch</a> <a title=\"saturdaynightlive\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.tiktok.com/tag/saturdaynightlive?refer=embed\">#saturdaynightlive</a> <a title=\"egonwodim\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.tiktok.com/tag/egonwodim?refer=embed\">#egonwodim</a> </p>\n<p> <a target=\"_blank\" title=\"♬ original sound - Preston - Pop Culture &#038; Trivia\" href=\"https://www.tiktok.com/music/original-sound-7490054751661361950?refer=embed\">♬ original sound &#8211; Preston &#8211; Pop Culture &#038; Trivia</a> </section>\n</blockquote>\n<p> <script async src=\"https://www.tiktok.com/embed.js\"></script></p>\n<p>Others have spread a rumor that the audience was given a script. It said the audience should have replied with &#8220;not worth a damn.&#8221; One audience member has used TikTok to debunk this. She said the audience was not supposed to respond with anything.</p>\n<blockquote class=\"tiktok-embed\" cite=\"https://www.tiktok.com/@amanduhhud/video/7490319148644355359\" data-video-id=\"7490319148644355359\" data-embed-from=\"oembed\" style=\"max-width:605px; min-width:325px;\">\n<section> <a target=\"_blank\" title=\"@amanduhhud\" href=\"https://www.tiktok.com/@amanduhhud?refer=embed\">@amanduhhud</a> </p>\n<p>Replying to @taylor SNL’s viral weekend update moment: audience member POV  <a title=\"snl\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.tiktok.com/tag/snl?refer=embed\">#snl</a>  <a title=\"egonwodim\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.tiktok.com/tag/egonwodim?refer=embed\">#egonwodim</a> <a title=\"satudaynightlive\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.tiktok.com/tag/satudaynightlive?refer=embed\">#satudaynightlive</a> <a title=\"weekendupdate\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.tiktok.com/tag/weekendupdate?refer=embed\">#weekendupdate</a> <a title=\"colinjost\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.tiktok.com/tag/colinjost?refer=embed\">#colinjost</a> <a title=\"michaelche\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.tiktok.com/tag/michaelche?refer=embed\">#michaelche</a> <a title=\"jackblack\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.tiktok.com/tag/jackblack?refer=embed\">#jackblack</a> <a title=\"viral\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.tiktok.com/tag/viral?refer=embed\">#viral</a> <a title=\"pov\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.tiktok.com/tag/pov?refer=embed\">#pov</a> </p>\n<p> <a target=\"_blank\" title=\"♬ original sound - Amanda\" href=\"https://www.tiktok.com/music/original-sound-7490319211873569567?refer=embed\">♬ original sound &#8211; Amanda</a> </section>\n</blockquote>\n<p> <script async src=\"https://www.tiktok.com/embed.js\"></script></p>\n<p>Viewers did not believe her at first. She had to make a <a href=\"https://www.tiktok.com/@amanduhhud/video/7490622479224950046?is_from_webapp=1&amp;sender_device=pc&amp;web_id=7413127637855503915\">separate video</a> with proof that she was actually there.</p>\n<p>TikTok users agree that this went hilariously wrong. They think the word should be allowed on late night TV. Will SNL get fined? Do you think these curse words should be allowed on TV?</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'AH996', NULL, '2025-04-29 11:40:02', 0, '“Cause these men ain’t what?” You can find the answer to that question by watching Ego Nwodim’s SNL skit on TikTok. Viewers had a lot to say after watching this late-night skit go wrong. Popular clips from the show are now watched on social media. Users flocked to TikTok to create videos and comment on…\n', NULL, NULL, 15),
('ed260ef9-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'video', 'Media News for You! Yes, You!', 'media-news-for-you-yes-you', NULL, '<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter wp-image-11403 size-large\" src=\"uploads/NMB-8-Jaden-Juliana-SQ-Crop-1200x1200.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1200\" height=\"1200\" srcset=\"uploads/NMB-8-Jaden-Juliana-SQ-Crop-1200x1200.jpg 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/NMB-8-Jaden-Juliana-SQ-Crop-600x600.jpg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/NMB-8-Jaden-Juliana-SQ-Crop-70x70.jpg 70w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/NMB-8-Jaden-Juliana-SQ-Crop-768x768.jpg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/NMB-8-Jaden-Juliana-SQ-Crop-1536x1536.jpg 1536w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/NMB-8-Jaden-Juliana-SQ-Crop-300x300.jpg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/NMB-8-Jaden-Juliana-SQ-Crop.jpg 1643w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px\" /></p>\n<h1>This Week on New Media Beat!</h1>\n<audio class=\"wp-audio-shortcode\" id=\"audio-11402-1\" preload=\"none\" style=\"width: 100%;\" controls=\"controls\"><source type=\"audio/mpeg\" src=\"https://newmediabeat.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/NMB-8-Web-2025-05-01.mp3?_=1\" /><a href=\"https://newmediabeat.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/NMB-8-Web-2025-05-01.mp3\">https://newmediabeat.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/NMB-8-Web-2025-05-01.mp3</a></audio>\n<h1></h1>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Saturday Night Live Takes TV to TikTok!</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Are Instagram&#8217;s Locked Reels the Key to Engagement?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Catnip for Brands: Snapchat&#8217;s AI Video Filters!</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Are Political Bots the Enemy of Democracy?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Brain Rot? What&#8217;s that?</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.newmediabeat.org/\"><strong>New Media Beat</strong></a> covers new media news