('ed2b4a92-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'podcast', 'New Media: Beaten not Stirred', 'new-media-beaten-not-stirred', NULL, '<figure id=\"attachment_11577\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-11577\" style=\"width: 600px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-medium wp-image-11577\" src=\"uploads/NMB-3-NMB-KP-SQ-600x598.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"598\" srcset=\"uploads/NMB-3-NMB-KP-SQ-600x598.jpg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/NMB-3-NMB-KP-SQ-70x70.jpg 70w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/NMB-3-NMB-KP-SQ-768x765.jpg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/NMB-3-NMB-KP-SQ-300x300.jpg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/NMB-3-NMB-KP-SQ.jpg 984w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-11577\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Media News for You:  Canada, China, UK, Afghanistan, Norway, India, &amp; Ukraine!</figcaption></figure>\n<h1>This Week on New Media Beat!</h1>\n<audio class=\"wp-audio-shortcode\" id=\"audio-11575-1\" preload=\"none\" style=\"width: 100%;\" controls=\"controls\"><source type=\"audio/mpeg\" src=\"https://newmediabeat.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/NMB-3-Web-2025-10-16.mp3?_=1\" /><a href=\"https://newmediabeat.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/NMB-3-Web-2025-10-16.mp3\">https://newmediabeat.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/NMB-3-Web-2025-10-16.mp3</a></audio>\n<h4></h4>\n<ul>\n<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Trump&#8217;s 100% Tariff on International Film.</strong></li>\n<li><strong>UK Social: Teen Mental Health Threat?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Afghanistan Press Freedom Under the Taliban.</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Diella: Albania&#8217;s AI-Generated Minister.</strong></li>\n<li><strong>We&#8217;re Number One! Press Freedom in Norway.</strong></li>\n<li><strong>India: Modi vs. the Press.</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Ukraine: Press Freedom during Wartime?</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.newmediabeat.org/\"><strong>New Media Beat</strong></a> covers media news from around the world. NMB is a production of Media Studies students from <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/\" target=\"_self\" rel=\"noopener\">SUNY @ Old Westbury.</a>   We scour the web for news about about media and journalism.</p>\n<p>NMB is co-produced by Kelvin Zalis, Jalaal McCoy and Emily Cevallos. Our engineer is Kelvin Zalis.  Our hosts are Kamsi Agu and Marwa Jalili.</p>\n<p>We are streaming live again on <a href=\"http://www.owwrny.org/\">Old Westbury Web Radio</a> Thursdays from 10:15-11:15 AM EST.  Can&#8217;t listen live? Our fall podcasts will be <a href=\"https://newmediabeat.org/?cat=17\">posted</a> for your listening pleasure every Friday afternoon from September through December 2025.</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'ADMIN001', NULL, '2025-10-21 13:36:07', 0, 'This Week on New Media Beat! Trump’s 100% Tariff on International Film. UK Social: Teen Mental Health Threat? Afghanistan Press Freedom Under the Taliban. Diella: Albania’s AI-Generated Minister. We’re Number One! Press Freedom in Norway. India: Modi vs. the Press. Ukraine: Press Freedom during Wartime? New Media Beat covers media news from around the world….\n', NULL, NULL, 5),
('ed2ba3fa-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Card for a Cause: SUNY Old Westbury Students Spread Thanksgiving Cheer', 'card-for-a-cause-suny-old-westbury-students-spread-thanksgiving-cheer-post-on-nov-18-2025', NULL, '<p>As the chill of November settles over campus, SUNY Old Westbury students will warm hearts by transforming gratitude into action through a colorful, creative act of kindness that will bring the Panther community together. The initiative invites students to make handmade Thanksgiving cards that will be delivered to patients in local hospitals and nursing homes.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><a href=\"https://oldwestbury.campuslabs.com/engage/event/11576927\">Cards for a Cause</a> will take place on Monday, November 24, from 1:30 to 2:30 p.m. in the<a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/student-union\"><span class=\"s1\"> Commuter Lounge</span></a>,. The initiative, hosted by the Office of Student Engagement and Leadership Development, invites students to make handmade Thanksgiving cards that will be delivered to patients in local hospitals and nursing homes. It is designed to bring the campus community together while spreading warmth to those who need it most.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">The goal is to remind people who might feel isolated during the holidays that they are seen, valued, and cared for. All materials—paper, markers, stickers, and envelopes—will be provided, making it easy for anyone to join in, no matter their artistic ability.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“CSA wanted to organize Cards for a Cause as a way to bring our campus community together through small but meaningful acts of kindness,” said Verina Anis, one of the event’s organizers.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Anis said the event helps remind students that even simple gestures can make a lasting impact.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“We wanted to create an opportunity for students to pause, reflect, and give back by writing words of encouragement, appreciation, or hope,” Anis said. “It’s super easy to join. We’ll have everything set up, so you can come make a few cards, hang out, and go whenever you need to.”</p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_11591\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-11591\" style=\"width: 225px\" class=\"wp-caption alignright\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-small wp-image-11591\" src=\"uploads/image-225x300.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" srcset=\"uploads/image-225x300.png 225w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/image-450x600.png 450w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/image-900x1200.png 900w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/image-768x1024.png 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/image-1152x1536.png 1152w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/image.png 1200w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 225px) 100vw, 225px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-11591\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Students enjoy a friendly game of ping pong inside SUNY Old Westbury’s Commuter Lounge on<br />OCT. 15, 2025. The Cards for Causes event will be held there on Mon., Nov. 24 at 1:30 p.m., when the room will come alive with laughing students, bright colors, sparkles and glitter. PHOTO BY: DESPINA<br />DRAKOPOULOS</figcaption></figure>\n<p class=\"p1\">Beyond its creative element, Cards for a Cause serves a deeper purpose. With finals approaching and academic stress rising, the event encourages students to slow down and focus on gratitude—something that research shows can reduce anxiety and boost emotional well-being.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">A <a href=\"https://greatergood.berkeley.edu/article/item/how_kindness_may_help_students_transition_to_college\"><span class=\"s1\">2023 study</span> from the University of California at Berkeley</a> found that simple acts of kindness and creative expression both help combat burnout, especially in college students. Researchers found that when students performed more kind and helpful acts—such as sharing notes, holding doors, or offering encouragement—they reported higher levels of happiness, resilience, and optimism, along with lower feelings of anxiety and loneliness.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“When students come to Cards for a Cause, they can expect a fun and uplifting experience,” Anis said. “There will be music, supplies, and plenty of space to get creative while writing thoughtful cards for people in need of a smile. It’s also a chance to meet new people, take a break from classes, and do something kind that makes an impact beyond campus.”</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">After the event, the team will collect, sort, and deliver the cards through hospital volunteer departments to ensure they reach patients who could use a morale boost.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“Something as simple as a handwritten card can mean the world to someone,” Anis said. “It shows that a stranger took the time to think of them and send a kind message. That genuine care can really lift people’s spirits, especially during rough times.”</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Events like Cards for a Cause highlight SUNY Old Westbury’s ongoing commitment to civic engagement and compassion.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“We’d love for Cards for a Cause to become a tradition on campus,” Anis said. &#8220;“Hopefully this is just the start of something that keeps growing year after year.”</p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><em><a href=\"https://oldwestbury.campuslabs.com/engage/event/11576927\">Cards for a Cause</a> Thanksgiving card decorating for local hospital patients. Mon.</em><em>, Nov. 20 at 1:30 p.m., Commuter Lounge, Campus Center Atrium at SUNY Old Westbury. Free admission.</em></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'DD275', NULL, '2025-11-18 09:58:09', 0, 'As the chill of November settles over campus, SUNY Old Westbury students will warm hearts by transforming gratitude into action through a colorful, creative act of kindness that will bring the Panther community together. The initiative invites students to make handmade Thanksgiving cards that will be delivered to patients in local hospitals and nursing homes….\n', NULL, NULL, 10),
('ed2c0d6d-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Love Island USA: Reel Talk Series brings real conversations about love and mental health to SUNY Old Westbury', 'love-island-usa-reel-talk-series-brings-real-conversations-about-love-and-mental-health-to-suny-old-westbury', NULL, '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Students at SUNY Old Westbury will soon be talking about more than who gets “voted out of the villa.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">On Wednesday, November 12, 2025 from 1:30 p.m. to 2:30 p.m., the Panther Pad in the Student Union Building will host an </span><a href=\"https://oldwestbury.campuslabs.com/engage/event/11389013\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">event</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> that uses the hit reality show Love Island USA to inspire meaningful conversations about emotional wellness, attachment styles and the search for genuine romantic connections in the world of social media and reality tv. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The discussion, hosted by Tatiana Mclean, a licensed mental health counselor with the Counseling and Psychological Wellness Services at SUNY Old Westbury, centers around the question: </span><a href=\"https://oldwestbury.campuslabs.com/engage/event/11389013\"><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Is this Love or Just Vibes</span></i></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">? The goal of this event is to encourage students to think more deeply about how popular media influences their understanding of healthy relationships, self-image and mental health.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Mclean launched the Reel Talk series this fall to engage students through pop culture and the topic of mental health. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> “Sometimes it&#8217;s hard for individuals to be able to talk about what is actually happening for them at the moment,” Mclean said. “So using things within pop culture such as TV shows and social media allows the conversation to begin in a way that’s more relatable and engaging.&#8221;</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> In recent years, </span><a href=\"https://www.npr.org/2025/07/14/nx-s1-5464947/season-7-love-island-usa-popularity\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Love Island USA</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> has become a staple of modern pop culture, captivating audiences with its mix of romance, competition and drama. Its catchphrases, fashion trends and social media presence have made it a cultural touchpoint, sparking conversations about body image, emotional expression and what love looks like in the age of instant connection. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Over the summer, I was attending Educational Opportunity Program workshops for students, and Love Island was the number one topic of conversation when it came to the discussion of boundaries, relationships and mental health,” Mclean added.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Students are eager to see how this popular show can turn into a learning experience and help to open up the conversation surrounding healthy relationships and mental health. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">&#8220;A lot of people watch Love Island for entertainment, but don’t realize the effect it has on real issues surrounding mental health and healthy relationships,” said Rayvin Dawkins, a junior Media and Communications major. “Bringing that into a space where we can talk about it honestly feels refreshing and relatable.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Through events like Love Island USA: Reel Talk Series, SUNY Old Westbury continues to bridge entertainment and education, showing that even a popular TV show can lead to real conversations surrounding self-awareness, mental health and modern relationships.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I want to meet students where they’re at,” Mclean said. “There’s such a high demand for therapy among our student population, so using tools like pop culture helps start the conversation in a way that’s relatable and fun for students.”</span></p>\n<p><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Love Island USA Reel Talk Series: Is this Love or Just Vibes? Wednesday, November, 12, 2025 at 1:30 p.m.. Panthers Pad, SUNY Old Westbury Student Union Building. Free Admission. Free food and beverages. </span></i></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'HM898', NULL, '2025-10-22 15:20:05', 0, 'Students at SUNY Old Westbury will soon be talking about more than who gets “voted out of the villa.” On Wednesday, November 12, 2025 from 1:30 p.m. to 2:30 p.m., the Panther Pad in the Student Union Building will host an event that uses the hit reality show Love Island USA to inspire meaningful conversations…\n', NULL, NULL, 10),
('ed2c6576-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'podcast', 'Globalize It!', 'globalize-it', NULL, '<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/NMB-4-NMB-Global-KP-M-Rect-Cat-600x456.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"456\" class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-11615\" srcset=\"uploads/NMB-4-NMB-Global-KP-M-Rect-Cat-600x456.jpg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/NMB-4-NMB-Global-KP-M-Rect-Cat-768x584.jpg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/NMB-4-NMB-Global-KP-M-Rect-Cat-300x228.jpg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/NMB-4-NMB-Global-KP-M-Rect-Cat.jpg 1173w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" /></p>\n<h1>This Week on New Media Beat!</h1>\n<audio class=\"wp-audio-shortcode\" id=\"audio-11612-1\" preload=\"none\" style=\"width: 100%;\" controls=\"controls\"><source type=\"audio/mpeg\" src=\"https://newmediabeat.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/NMB-4-Web-2025-10-23.mp3?_=1\" /><a href=\"https://newmediabeat.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/NMB-4-Web-2025-10-23.mp3\">https://newmediabeat.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/NMB-4-Web-2025-10-23.mp3</a></audio>\n<h4></h4>\n<ul>\n<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Censorship or Security? Why Did Kenya Prohibit Live Coverage of Summer Protests?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>BBC Roots: A Public Media Origin Story. </strong></li>\n<li><strong>What&#8217;s Spanish for Online Hate?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Securing Teens from Social in Australia?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Pirate Flags: Why Are Gen-Z Protesters Waving the One-Piece Skull and Bones?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Discord in Nepal: Private Servers for Protesters.</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Is Hong Kong Media Under China&#8217;s Thumb?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Under the Influence: Did Russian Disinfo Impact Moldovan Elections?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Were the Czech Elections Flooded with Russian Memes?</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.newmediabeat.org/\"><strong>New Media Beat</strong></a> covers media news from around the world. NMB is a production of Media Studies students from <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/\" target=\"_self\" rel=\"noopener\">SUNY @ Old Westbury.</a>   We scour the web for news about about media and journalism.</p>\n<p>NMB is co-produced by Kelvin Zalis, Jalaal McCoy and Emily Cevallos. Our engineer is Kelvin Zalis.  Our hosts are Heidi Ssempebwa and Adan Pleitez.</p>\n<p>We are streaming live again on <a href=\"http://www.owwrny.org/\">Old Westbury Web Radio</a> Thursdays from 10:15-11:15 AM EST.  Can&#8217;t listen live? Our fall podcasts will be <a href=\"https://newmediabeat.org/?cat=17\">posted</a> for your listening pleasure every Friday afternoon from September through December 2025.</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'ADMIN001', NULL, '2025-10-24 18:39:37', 0, 'This Week on New Media Beat! Censorship or Security? Why Did Kenya Prohibit Live Coverage of Summer Protests? BBC Roots: A Public Media Origin Story. What’s Spanish for Online Hate? Securing Teens from Social in Australia? Pirate Flags: Why Are Gen-Z Protesters Waving the One-Piece Skull and Bones? Discord in Nepal: Private Servers for Protesters….\n', NULL, NULL, 12),
('ed2cb6c1-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Asst. athletic trainer Ryan Duffy focuses on both the body and the soul', 'asst-athletic-trainer-ryan-duffy-focuses-on-both-the-body-and-the-soul', NULL, '<p><span class=\"FeedbackEditor__selected__H3jkg\">Most people walk past the training room without a second thought. But inside, stories unfold of quiet patience, small victories and people finding their way back to themselves.</span></p>\n<p>At the center of it all is Ryan Duffy, who has been the assistant athletic trainer at SUNY Old Westbury since 2017. His calm presence and steady energy make him the person people turn to when they need to be heard.</p>\n<p>“You’d be surprised how many times you just ask the innocent question of how are you, and they’ll start off by saying, ‘Oh, I’m good,’ and then they just start pouring things out,” Duffy said. “Sometimes they just need someone to listen.”</p>\n<p>That patience defines him more than any title. He is someone who notices when others do not.</p>\n<p>A person who pays attention when people say they are fine but are not.</p>\n<p>Growing up in Holtsville, New York, Duffy spent his childhood playing baseball and soccer before discovering running in high school.</p>\n<p>“After three years of coasting along, my senior year I decided I wanted to be one of the top runners,” he said.</p>\n<p>He credits his high school coach for teaching him focus and accountability.</p>\n<p>“My coach pressed all the right buttons to help me focus my energy and really dedicate myself,” he said.</p>\n<p>That lesson shaped how he approaches life. It taught him consistency and heart.</p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a247124dc91c sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>You can be in really good physical health, but if your mental health is not in a good place, it doesn’t really matter.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Ryan Duffy, assistant athletic trainer, SUNY Old Westbury</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a247124dc91c {\n    display: flex;\n    float: left;\n    margin: 30px 30px 30px 0;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247124dc91c p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a247124dc91c p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247124dc91c .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a247124dc91c p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247124dc91c .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247124dc91c .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247124dc91c .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p>Duffy believes mental and physical health go hand in hand.</p>\n<p>“You can be in really good physical health, but if your mental health is not in a good place, it doesn’t really matter,” he said. “You’re not functioning at an optimal state.”</p>\n<p>He’s learned that balance means slowing down.</p>\n<p>“I try to put my phone away, especially in the morning and at night,” he said. “I try to unplug, read a book, ride my bike or lift weights.”</p>\n<p>Those small moments of peace keep him grounded. They remind him that caring for others starts with caring for yourself.</p>\n<p>Duffy admits that empathy is both his strength and his weakness.</p>\n<p>“Maybe it’s a soft spot,” he said. “You want to be there for them, but you have to remember your job is to keep them safe.”</p>\n<p>That self awareness drives his honesty. He believes compassion means doing what’s right, even when it’s difficult.</p>\n<p>He still remembers one of the most rewarding experiences of his career.</p>\n<p>A basketball player he worked with had faced constant setbacks.</p>\n<p>“He had a laundry list of issues,” Duffy said. “Some were physical, some were general health, and every time he got close, something would set him back.”</p>\n<p>After years of frustration, that player finally stepped back onto the court.</p>\n<p>“We worked together for two years, and when he finally got back on the court at the end of the season, that was really rewarding,” Duffy said.</p>\n<p>Moments like that reflect who Duffy is a person driven by care.</p>\n<p>His strength doesn’t come from pressure or attention. It comes from quiet consistency and the belief that showing up for others matters most.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'AR706', NULL, '2025-10-29 14:37:28', 0, 'Most people walk past the training room without a second thought. But inside, stories unfold of quiet patience, small victories and people finding their way back to themselves. At the center of it all is Ryan Duffy, who has been the assistant athletic trainer at SUNY Old Westbury since 2017. His calm presence and steady…\n', NULL, NULL, 16),
('ed2d1ef5-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Behind the counter: Helen Karavis of the Halal Shack on working with — and without — two good legs', 'behind-the-counter-helen-karavis-of-the-halal-shack-on-working-with-and-without-two-good-legs', NULL, '<p>It’s Common Hour at SUNY Old Westbury, and the lunch rush has just begun. The buzz of blenders fills the Student Union while mingling with the smell of sizzling chicken.</p>\n<p>Amid the noise and motion, Helen Karavis, works with calm precision — even when she is healing from a leg injury.</p>\n<p>Whether they are grabbing food from the Market, Halal Shack or Freshens, students expect to encounter Karavis’s familiar warmth, though seeing her roll between stations often catches newcomers by surprise.</p>\n<p>This past summer, she broke her leg in three places on a trip to her home country of Greece— but even a major injury couldn&#8217;t keep her away for long. Returning to campus on a scooter, she continues to work while embracing the same positivity and patience that defines her.</p>\n<p>“It&#8217;s a little hard to move around but I’ll manage,” she said. “You don&#8217;t realize how much you need your legs until you can&#8217;t use them.”</p>\n<p>Karavis immigrated to the United States from Greece when she was 17 years old. Since then, she has spent most of her time working in the food service industry.</p>\n<p>For more than four years, Karavis has poured her energy into the service at the Student Union — not just as a supervisor but as somebody who is able to make a difference with every meal.</p>\n<p>“Food is my second nature,” Karavis said, laughing. “If the students are happy with the food, then I will be happy. It&#8217;s all that matters to me.”</p>\n<p>For Karavis, her work is not just about clocking in, but it reflects who she is.</p>\n<p>She describes her job as “challenging, but kind of exciting.”</p>\n<p>“Every day is different,” she said. “Even if it sounds the same, it&#8217;s always changing — with the crew, students, and the people you meet. You never get bored.”</p>\n<p>She has become a comforting and recognizable presence to both students and staff, her soft voice and laughter a part of lunchtime as much as the smell of the food.</p>\n<p>“I get to see my crew and the students; they’re like my second family — that’s my favorite part of the job,” she said with a smile.</p>\n<p>Her story is one about resilience and care, a reminder that for many, work isn&#8217;t just a job, but a reflection of their spirit.</p>\n<p>“Some students view me as if I am their mother, they tell me their stories and some even invite me to come to their graduation ceremonies,” she said. “Every student has their own unique story — I like that connection.”</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'MC975', NULL, '2025-11-04 03:00:04', 0, 'It’s Common Hour at SUNY Old Westbury, and the lunch rush has just begun. The buzz of blenders fills the Student Union while mingling with the smell of sizzling chicken. Amid the noise and motion, Helen Karavis, works with calm precision — even when she is healing from a leg injury. Whether they are grabbing…\n', NULL, NULL, 16),
('ed2d6d87-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'podcast', 'New Media Beat Is Not Scary!', 'new-media-beat-is-not-scary', NULL, '<figure id=\"attachment_11644\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-11644\" style=\"width: 600px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-medium wp-image-11644\" src=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/NMB-5-NM-Says-Boo-Cat-600x430.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"430\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/NMB-5-NM-Says-Boo-Cat-600x430.jpeg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/NMB-5-NM-Says-Boo-Cat-300x215.jpeg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/NMB-5-NM-Says-Boo-Cat.jpeg 650w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-11644\" class=\"wp-caption-text\"> Happy Halloween from The Catalyst &amp; New Media Beat.</figcaption></figure>\n<h1>This Halloween on New Media Beat!</h1>\n<audio class=\"wp-audio-shortcode\" id=\"audio-11633-1\" preload=\"none\" style=\"width: 100%;\" controls=\"controls\"><source type=\"audio/mpeg\" src=\"https://newmediabeat.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/NMB-5-Web-2025-10-30.mp3?_=1\" /><a href=\"https://newmediabeat.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/NMB-5-Web-2025-10-30.mp3\">https://newmediabeat.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/NMB-5-Web-2025-10-30.mp3</a></audio>\n<h4></h4>\n<ul>\n<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\n<ul>\n<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Does Germany Have a Russian Disinfo Problem?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>How Does Putin Control the Russian Internet?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Myanmar Scares Journalists.</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Is French Media Concentration Threatening Democracy? </strong></li>\n<li><strong>Paraguay&#8217;s Press Problem?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Why Are the U.K.Police Arresting Posters?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Is the EU AI Act Just Red Tape?</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.newmediabeat.org/\"><strong>New Media Beat</strong></a> covers media news from around the world. NMB is a production of Media Studies students from <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/\" target=\"_self\" rel=\"noopener\">SUNY @ Old Westbury.</a>   We scour the web for news about about media and journalism.</p>\n<p>NMB is co-produced by Kelvin Zalis, Jalaal McCoy and Emily Cevallos. Our engineer is Kelvin Zalis.  Our hosts are Kamsi Agu and Phylicia Cangemi.</p>\n<p>We are streaming live again on <a href=\"http://www.owwrny.org/\">Old Westbury Web Radio</a> Thursdays from 10:15-11:15 AM EST.  Can&#8217;t listen live? Our fall podcasts will be <a href=\"https://newmediabeat.org/?cat=17\">posted</a> for your listening pleasure every Friday afternoon from September through December 2025.</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'ADMIN001', NULL, '2025-10-31 14:21:22', 0, 'This Halloween on New Media Beat! Does Germany Have a Russian Disinfo Problem? How Does Putin Control the Russian Internet? Myanmar Scares Journalists. Is French Media Concentration Threatening Democracy? Paraguay’s Press Problem? Why Are the U.K.Police Arresting Posters? Is the EU AI Act Just Red Tape? New Media Beat covers media news from around the…\n', NULL, NULL, 12),
('ed2dbb6a-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'podcast', 'It’s Here!  A New Podcast Full of New Media News . . .', 'its-here-a-new-podcast-full-of-new-media-news', NULL, '<h4 style=\"text-align: center;\">Let Catalyst Photographer Miguel Castro Take You into Studio A!</h4>\n<snsgallery data-photo-ids=\"1201,1206,1208,1204,1202,1207\"></snsgallery>\n<h4>Listen to the latest New Media News recorded live in Studio A on Thursday February 15, 2018.</h4>\n<audio class=\"wp-audio-shortcode\" id=\"audio-1164-1\" preload=\"none\" style=\"width: 100%;\" controls=\"controls\"><source type=\"audio/mpeg\" src=\"http://www.oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/GMN-3-Web-021518.mp3?_=1\" /><a href=\"http://www.oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/GMN-3-Web-021518.mp3\">http://www.oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/GMN-3-Web-021518.mp3</a></audio>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/GMN-3-Web-021518.mp3\">Click Here to Download or Play!</a></p>\n<p><strong>This Week:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Labeled!  Why Is Youtube Labeling State Funded Videos?</li>\n<li>Crack Down on the Nasty? What Will Youtube Do About Negative Content?</li>\n<li>Can the Press Compete With Social Media News?</li>\n<li>How Social is Social Media?  Can We Talk?</li>\n<li>Are Their Real Consequences for Fake Apps?</li>\n<li>Clean Up Your Twitter History!</li>\n<li>Snap vs. Insta: What Do the Stats Say?</li>\n<li>Celebrity Twitter Hacks:  Who&#8217;s Hacking Who and Why?</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Global Media News is a weekly webcast covering new media news from around the world.  GMN is a production of  Media Studies students from the <a href=\"http://www.oldwestbury.edu/\" target=\"_self\">SUNY College @ Old Westbury.</a>   We scour the web for news about new media, journalism and technology.</p>\n<p>Listen to our next podcast streaming live on OWWR: Thursday February 22, 2018 @ 10 am EST.</p>\n<p>Can&#8217;t listen live? Our next podcast  will be posted by 2:00pm, Thursday February 22, 2018,  2018.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/GlobalMediaNews\" target=\"_self\">Subscribe Now!</a></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'AM327', NULL, '2018-02-15 13:38:49', 0, 'Let Catalyst Photographer Miguel Castro Take You into Studio A! Listen to the latest New Media News recorded live in Studio A on Thursday February 15, 2018. Click Here to Download or Play! This Week: Labeled!  Why Is Youtube Labeling State Funded Videos? Crack Down on the Nasty? What Will Youtube Do About Negative Content?…\n', NULL, NULL, 1),
('ed2e05e2-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Justin Burmeister: from coach to facilities director, he explains why teamwork is key', 'justin-burmeister-from-coach-to-facilities-director-he-explains-why-teamwork-is-key', NULL, '<p><span class=\"FeedbackEditor__selected__H3jkg\">What started on the sporting fields now fuels the foundation of campus operations. Justin Burmeister, interim director of facilities at SUNY Old Westbury, applies his coaching mindset to managing teams, solving problems, and leading with purpose.  </span></p>\n<p>“Whether you’re managing a sports team or a facilities crew, the goal is the same,” Burmeister said. “You want everyone working toward a common goal, understanding their role, and giving their best effort every day.”</p>\n<p>That philosophy has guided Burmeister throughout his career. Before taking on leadership roles in facilities management, he spent years coaching football and lacrosse, experiences that taught him how to motivate individuals, build trust and manage under pressure.</p>\n<p>“In sports, everyone knows the goal is to win,” he said. “In the workplace, it’s not as clear cut. So, it’s my job to set expectations, make sure everyone understands them and explain why they matter.”</p>\n<p>Preparation, Burmeister said, is key to handling the unexpected both on the field and on campus.</p>\n<p>“When you’re competing in a game, you prepare for every situation that might come up,” he said. “You can’t plan for everything, but you can prepare for most things. The same goes for facilities <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">—</span> you make sure you have the right people, the right resources and the right policies in place.”</p>\n<p>That mindset has helped him lead SUNY Old Westbury&#8217;s facilities team through complex operations that keep the campus running smoothly. From maintenance and custodial services to transportation and groundskeeping, each department has its own set of goals, but all work together toward one purpose: supporting students, faculty and staff.</p>\n<p>“Athletics taught me that success isn’t just about the final score,” Burmeister said. “On the field, it’s about seeing people perform at their best. In my professional role, it’s about helping others reach their goals and knowing the work we do adds value to the campus community.”</p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a247362a5510 sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>Sports teach you to show up every day, hold each other accountable and overcome adversity.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Justin Burmeister, interim director of facilities at SUNY Old Westbury</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a247362a5510 {\n    display: flex;\n    float: left;\n    margin: 30px 30px 30px 0;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247362a5510 p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a247362a5510 p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247362a5510 .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a247362a5510 p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247362a5510 .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247362a5510 .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247362a5510 .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p>For Burmeister, leadership also means staying calm and positive during challenges.</p>\n<p>“If your team is on a losing streak, you can’t panic,&#8221; he said. &#8220;You’ve got to keep them motivated and remind them things will turn around. It’s the same at work. When resources are tight or obstacles pop up, people need reassurance that you’ll get through it together.”</p>\n<p>Discipline, accountability, and teamwork are values Burmeister carries from the locker room to the office.</p>\n<p>“Sports teach you to show up every day, hold each other accountable and overcome adversity,” he said. “Those lessons build character, and I try to instill that same mindset in my team.”</p>\n<p>As he looks ahead, Burmeister hopes to continue mentoring others, both on the field and across campus.</p>\n<p>“Leadership is about constant improvement,” he said. “Whether it’s in my management style or my coaching, I’m always looking for ways to grow and to help others do the same.”</p>\n<p>Burmeister described his leadership and coaching style in three words:</p>\n<p>“Nurturing, passionate, and tough,” he said.</p>\n<p><span class=\"FeedbackEditor__selected__H3jkg\">It is a fitting description for a leader who sees every challenge as a chance to teach, motivate, and build something lasting, whether it’s a winning team or a well run campus. </span></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'KC639', NULL, '2025-11-10 15:40:04', 0, 'What started on the sporting fields now fuels the foundation of campus operations. Justin Burmeister, interim director of facilities at SUNY Old Westbury, applies his coaching mindset to managing teams, solving problems, and leading with purpose.   “Whether you’re managing a sports team or a facilities crew, the goal is the same,” Burmeister said. “You…\n', NULL, NULL, 16),
