('ed2eba62-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'podcast', 'We Got the Beat!', 'we-got-the-beat', NULL, '<h1><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-11686\" src=\"uploads/NMB-6-RSF-NMB-SQ-Bigger.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"467\" height=\"467\" srcset=\"uploads/NMB-6-RSF-NMB-SQ-Bigger.jpg 467w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/NMB-6-RSF-NMB-SQ-Bigger-70x70.jpg 70w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/NMB-6-RSF-NMB-SQ-Bigger-300x300.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 467px) 100vw, 467px\" /></h1>\n<h1>This Week on New Media Beat!</h1>\n<audio class=\"wp-audio-shortcode\" id=\"audio-11680-1\" preload=\"none\" style=\"width: 100%;\" controls=\"controls\"><source type=\"audio/mpeg\" src=\"https://newmediabeat.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/NMB-6-Web-2025-11-06.mp3?_=1\" /><a href=\"https://newmediabeat.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/NMB-6-Web-2025-11-06.mp3\">https://newmediabeat.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/NMB-6-Web-2025-11-06.mp3</a></audio>\n<h4></h4>\n<ul>\n<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\n<ul>\n<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Is De-<mark>InfoNile</mark> More than Just a River in Egypt?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Geocaching Goes Around the World Online!</strong></li>\n<li><strong>How Sharp Are Russia&#8217;s Foreign Agent Law&#8217;s Claws?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Why Doesn&#8217;t Milei Like the Press in Argentina?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Can the BBC Beat Netflix in the UK?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Why is Russia&#8217;s Defense Ministry Channel Generating Political Satire?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Is Media Polarization a Problem in India?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Can China Bridge Its Digital Divide?</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.newmediabeat.org/\"><strong>New Media Beat</strong></a> covers media news from around the world. NMB is a production of Media Studies students from <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/\" target=\"_self\" rel=\"noopener\">SUNY @ Old Westbury.</a>   We scour the web for news about about media and journalism.</p>\n<p>NMB is co-produced by Emily Cevallos, Kelvin Zalis, and Jalaal McCoy. Our engineer is Jalaal McCoy.  Our hosts are Angeles Neri and Krista Rakowicz</p>\n<p>We are streaming live again on <a href=\"http://www.owwrny.org/\">Old Westbury Web Radio</a> Thursdays from 10:15-11:15 AM EST.  Can&#8217;t listen live? Our fall podcasts will be <a href=\"https://newmediabeat.org/?cat=17\">posted</a> for your listening pleasure every Friday afternoon from September through December 2025.</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'NM744', NULL, '2025-11-10 17:49:57', 0, 'This Week on New Media Beat! Is De-InfoNile More than Just a River in Egypt? Geocaching Goes Around the World Online! How Sharp Are Russia’s Foreign Agent Law’s Claws? Why Doesn’t Milei Like the Press in Argentina? Can the BBC Beat Netflix in the UK? Why is Russia’s Defense Ministry Channel Generating Political Satire? Is…\n', NULL, NULL, 12),
('ed2f1f1a-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'First in family, first in line: navigating life as a first generation college student', 'first-in-family-first-in-line-navigating-life-as-a-first-generation-college-student', NULL, '<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>For many new students at SUNY Old Westbury, arriving on campus is just the beginning of a complicated journey.</p>\n<p>But for first-generation students <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">—</span> those who are the first in their families to pursue higher education <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">— that journey can </span>come with hidden obstacles, quiet pressures and significantly lower odds of graduating.</p>\n<p>At SUNY Old Westbury, first-generation students <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/news-events/suny-old-westbury-celebrates-first-gen-students\">make up 30 percent</a> of the student population, and the college has actively been working to address the unique barriers they face. That can include financial strain, family expectations and the challenge of simply understanding how the college system works.</p>\n<p>Adrian Ospina, a freshman in media and communications, said the pressure starts early.</p>\n<p>“Being first-generation, it comes with so much stress,&#8221; Ospina said. &#8220;The fear that you will let your family down if you don’t pick a major that they think pays well, because they will think I’m wasting the sacrifices they have made to get me to this point.”</p>\n<p>That pressure creates a difficult balancing act for students: choosing between a major they truly enjoy and one that might promise financial security after graduation.</p>\n<p>“I recently changed my major from computer science to media and communications, and the whole family feels I’m disappointing them, because I’m potentially not going to make all the money that they think that a computer science career would bring,” Ospina said.</p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_11735\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-11735\" style=\"width: 300px\" class=\"wp-caption alignright\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-small wp-image-11735\" src=\"uploads/Cordero-Garcia-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" srcset=\"uploads/Cordero-Garcia-300x225.jpg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Cordero-Garcia-600x450.jpg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Cordero-Garcia-1200x900.jpg 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Cordero-Garcia-768x576.jpg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Cordero-Garcia-1536x1152.jpg 1536w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Cordero-Garcia.jpg 2001w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-11735\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Maribel Cordero-Garcia, First-Generation Specialist at SUNY Old Westbury sits in her office. Oct. 28, 2025. PHOTO BY: HENRY M. WILSON</figcaption></figure>\n<p>Maribel Cordero-Garcia, the First-Generation student specialist at SUNY Old Westbury, says these pressures mirror what she sees every semester.</p>\n<p>“Families mean well, but they sometimes assume that college will be this guaranteed path of success, automatically leading to a high paying job,” Cordero-Garcia said. “First Generation students need guidance from the very beginning, from navigating financial aid, to enrolling in classes. They’re building the blueprint as they go.”</p>\n<p>According to <a href=\"https://www.firstgenforward.org/our-insights/fact-sheets\">2024 data from FirstGen Forward</a>, a non-profit that focuses on the success of first-generation students across the nation, only 24% of first generation students will earn a bachelor’s degree within six years, compared to 59% of their continuing generation peers. These numbers highlight a persistent gap rooted not in ability, but access to mentorship, guidance and financial stability.</p>\n<p>To better support this largely underrepresented group, the college has strengthened its support through mentorship programs such as TRIO Student Support Services, workshops and events such as <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/news-events/suny-old-westbury-celebrates-first-gen-students\">First Generation College Celebration Day</a>, which aims to bring visibility and validation to students navigating this journey on their own.</p>\n<p>“A student can be smart and determined, but a support network is crucial in understanding their realities, and ensuring they’re successful in their time here,” Cordero-Garcia said.</p>\n<p>Nationally, however, programs like TRIO are under increasing strain. The Trump administration’s broader crackdown on Diversity, Equity and Inclusion initiative programs has resulted in the closure of more than 120 TRIO initiatives at campuses across the country.</p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a247166ecb7c sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>They help to remind me that being first-generation is a strength, that we’re the ones that are breaking the cycle.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Sophomore Adrian Ospina on the support SUNY Old Westbury offers first generation students</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a247166ecb7c {\n    display: flex;\n    float: left;\n    margin: 30px 30px 30px 0;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247166ecb7c p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a247166ecb7c p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247166ecb7c .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a247166ecb7c p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247166ecb7c .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247166ecb7c .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247166ecb7c .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p>SUNY Old Westbury in 2020 received a $1.3 million TRIO grant that was supposed to last for five years. This federally-funded program serves low-income, first-generation, and underrepresented students, providing tutoring, counseling, and financial assistance that often make the difference between dropping out and graduating. The grant was renewed for the 2025-2026 school year, but administration is uncertain if it will be renewed again.</p>\n<p>“It is a scary time for students across the nation under this grant,&#8221; said Olivia Hughes, TRIO counselor at SUNY Old Westbury. &#8220;We don’t know what the future holds, but we will continue to do all that we can to ensure [students are] successful in their academic endeavours”</p>\n<p>Despite the uncertainty surrounding national policy, leaders like Cordero-Garcia and Hughes say SUNY Old Westbury remains committed to ensuring first generation students to not only get to attend college, but have the opportunity to be successful.</p>\n<p>“For first generation students, as well as others who fall under the TRIO grant, we offer them support in a variety of services such as specialized academic advising, peer mentoring, counseling and career and grad school preparation,” Hughes said.</p>\n<p>And for other first-generation students like Adrian Ospina, that guidance makes the difference between feeling alone and being seen.</p>\n<p>“Talking to mentors who understand the battle that I’m facing, it changes everything,” Ospina said. &#8220;They help to remind me that being first-generation is a strength, that we’re the ones that are breaking the cycle.&#8221;</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'HM898', NULL, '2025-11-25 10:30:46', 0, '  For many new students at SUNY Old Westbury, arriving on campus is just the beginning of a complicated journey. But for first-generation students — those who are the first in their families to pursue higher education — that journey can come with hidden obstacles, quiet pressures and significantly lower odds of graduating. At SUNY…\n', NULL, NULL, 1);
INSERT INTO `content` (`id`, `type`, `title`, `slug`, `description`, `content`, `url`, `approval_status`, `author_id`, `editor_id`, `created_at`, `is_featured`, `excerpt`, `video_url`, `featured_image`, `category_id`) VALUES
('ed2f9208-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', '“A Space to Just Be:” The Rise of the Trans Collective at SUNY Old Westbury', 'a-space-to-just-be-the-rise-of-the-trans-collective-at-suny-old-westbury', NULL, '<p>When student Alyssandra Membreno hung a small flyer outside the <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/school-arts-and-sciences/womens-gender-and-sexuality-studies/wgss-center\">Women’s, Gender &amp; Sexuality Studies Center</a>, often referred to as WGSS, nobody expected it to turn into something bigger. The poster didn’t have a name or a list of officers — just a barcode and the words: “<a href=\"https://forms.office.com/Pages/ResponsePage.aspx?id=NJAI9TPyEk-nFji39JBDcKMtAsBjerVAuY-nZLcylEZUOElRMEVKSjdIRjc3SERKMFY1RDRTQlJKVS4u&amp;origin=QRCode\">Scan here if you’re interested</a>.”</p>\n<p>Within weeks, students began stopping by. Some came out of curiosity, others out of need. What started as an idea for an internship project quickly became a student-driven community. They called it the Trans Collective—a space where trans, nonbinary and gender-diverse students could finally exhale.</p>\n<p>“I wanted this to be a collective thing,” Membreno said. “It’s not my group. It’s transpeople on campus coming together. I didn’t want to make it about a leader — it’s about all of us.”</p>\n<p>The flyer’s barcode was intentional too—both symbolic and practical.</p>\n<p>“The barcode was safer,” Membreno said. “If a trans student isn’t out or is still figuring things out, they can just scan it privately. It’s about protecting people’s comfort.”</p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_11706\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-11706\" style=\"width: 225px\" class=\"wp-caption alignright\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"wp-image-11706 size-small\" src=\"uploads/IMG_9106-e1763062180358-225x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" srcset=\"uploads/IMG_9106-e1763062180358-225x300.jpg 225w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/IMG_9106-e1763062180358-450x600.jpg 450w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/IMG_9106-e1763062180358-900x1200.jpg 900w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/IMG_9106-e1763062180358-768x1024.jpg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/IMG_9106-e1763062180358-1152x1536.jpg 1152w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/IMG_9106-e1763062180358.jpg 1501w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 225px) 100vw, 225px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-11706\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">A poster for the Trans Collective center hangs among other campus event flyers inside the Starbucks at SUNY Old Westbury on Oct. 30, 2025. PHOTO BY: DESPINA<br />DRAKOPOULOS</figcaption></figure>\n<p>The idea for the Trans Collective was born out of conversations between Membreno and Professor Jillian Crocker, who advises the WGSS Center. Both noticed that while Old Westbury offered LGBTQ+ programming, there wasn’t a specific space for trans and nonbinary students to meet, share experiences and exist without judgment.</p>\n<p>“This isn’t a faculty project,” Crocker explained. “It came from recognizing the need for the trans community on campus. The structure is non-hierarchical—students define what it becomes.”</p>\n<p>Membreno said they emphasized that approach from the start.</p>\n<p>“I never wanted this to feel like a club with rules or officers,” Membreno said. “It’s a hang-out, not a meeting. Sometimes it’s deep; sometimes it’s just fun.”</p>\n<p>A <a href=\"https://www.thetrevorproject.org/survey-2024/\">2024 Trevor Project survey</a> found that 65 percent of transgender and nonbinary youth experienced discrimination in the past year due to their gender identity.</p>\n<p>While 1.7 percent of U.S. college students identify as trans or nonbinary, many say their schools do not offer sufficient resources or support.</p>\n<p>According to the <a href=\"https://www.pewresearch.org/short-reads/2022/06/07/about-5-of-young-adults-in-the-u-s-say-their-gender-is-different-from-their-sex-assigned-at-birth/\">Pew Research Center</a>, about 5 percent of people under 30 in the U.S. identify as transgender or nonbinary — a number that has risen as awareness and visibility grow.</p>\n<p>“College can already be stressful — classes, jobs, commuting,” Membreno said. “Then imagine also having to explain your gender identity or correct people about your name every day. I wanted to build something that felt safe, where you could just exist.”</p>\n<p>Membreno also noted how being a commuter students adds to the feeling of distance.</p>\n<p>“When you’re not living on campus, it’s harder to find your people,” Membreno said. “Having a place to walk in and instantly feel seen means a lot.”</p>\n<p>For student Elio Bittman, that sense of belonging has been life-changing.</p>\n<p>“Being in a space where everyone has different experiences but one shared identity — it’s freeing,” Bittman said. “I don’t have to answer uncomfortable questions about my gender. I can just be myself.”</p>\n<p>Bittman has spent months trying to change their display name on platforms like Zoom, Brightspace and Outlook.</p>\n<p>“There’s no clear process,” Bittman said. “I’ve emailed multiple departments. I want to make it easier for the next student.”</p>\n<p>Membreno agrees this issue needs attention.</p>\n<p>“Something as small as seeing your real name on a screen matters,” Membreno said. “Faculty should know that too — it’s not just about paperwork; it’s about identity.”</p>\n<p>Trans Collective hangouts vary from week to week. Some include open discussions about gender identity, others focus on art projects or mental-health check-ins. But what stays consistent is the feeling of comfort and joy.</p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a2471681c06d sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>It starts with small things — asking pronouns, using the right names and just showing respect.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Alyssandra Membreno, SUNY Old Westbury student and founder of the Trans Collective, on how anyone can support trans and nonbinary students</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471681c06d {\n    display: flex;\n    float: left;\n    margin: 30px 30px 30px 0;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471681c06d p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471681c06d p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471681c06d .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a2471681c06d p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471681c06d .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471681c06d .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471681c06d .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p>Crocker said one of the most meaningful moments came during the first meeting.</p>\n<p>“Students showed up just to hang out,” she recalled. “That simple act — showing up — proved the need for this space.”</p>\n<p>The group has already sparked conversations about larger changes.</p>\n<p>“We need professors and administrators who listen to us,” Membreno said. “I’ve had people tell me they want to support, but they don’t know how. It starts with small things — asking pronouns, using the right names and just showing respect.”</p>\n<p>Crocker hopes the group will continue to evolve beyond this semester.</p>\n<p>“Whatever students want it to become, I’ll support that,” Crocker said. “If it’s a hang-out, if it’s advocacy, if it’s celebration — that’s their decision.”</p>\n<p>Membreno shares that vision.</p>\n<p>“Even if five people show up, that’s five people who feel a little less alone,” Membreno said. “I think that’s how change starts — small, but real.”</p>\n<p>What began as a simple flyer with a barcode has become something larger — a sanctuary where identity, conversation, and courage coexist. Now, every Thursday afternoon, laughter spills from the WGSS Center as students talk, snack, and build community. There are no judgments—just people who finally feel at home with a simple message to share.</p>\n<p>“You are trans enough,” Membreno said.</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'DD275', NULL, '2025-11-24 10:30:54', 0, 'When student Alyssandra Membreno hung a small flyer outside the Women’s, Gender & Sexuality Studies Center, often referred to as WGSS, nobody expected it to turn into something bigger. The poster didn’t have a name or a list of officers — just a barcode and the words: “Scan here if you’re interested.” Within weeks, students…\n', NULL, NULL, 1),
('ed2ff94c-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Heal your inner child at DIY slime event', 'heal-your-inner-child-at-diy-slime-event', NULL, '<p>Nostalgia is defined as a sentimental longing or craving to revisit a part of the past often associated with personal and happy memories.</p>\n<p>As a college student, when your inner child begins to resurface, what better way to connect with your nostalgia than to revisit a fond pastime?</p>\n<p>Look no further than the DIY Slime Event hosted by the Physical Health and Wellness club on Thursday, Nov. 20 at 1:30 p.m.!</p>\n<p>The Physical Health and Wellness is a “student led organization focusing promoting the well-being of the general student body,” said Matilda Asiedu, the vice president of the club.</p>\n<p>As exam season is in the air and stress clutters the mind, the Physical Health and Wellness club intends to give students a fun break from exams, promote community, and allow students to relieve themselves of stress.</p>\n<p>“Our club is to help students find balance in their day-to-day life physically, emotionally and mentally,” said, Maryum Faisal, the president of the club. “It helps get students engaged in physical activities with other people.”</p>\n<p>Students are equally ecstatic as they are curious as to why slime is the focus of the event.</p>\n<p>Faisal pitched the idea and refers to the slime trends back in 2016 when there was a huge trend with slime on YouTube for kids and teenagers alike.</p>\n<p>“The main reason I chose it is because there’s a lot of nostalgia in it — it’s also very therapeutic,” she said. “The texture of and feeling it and playing with it can help someone mentally decompress.”</p>\n<p>The sentiment is shared amongst students that anticipate this opportunity to create their own slime.</p>\n<p>“I have a lot of fond memories,” Faisal said. “I watched how to make slime with or without glue and other types of slime creation videos. It made me feel resourceful — it was simple and messy and a quick thing to make and you could share it with people. It’s a very connective activity.”</p>\n<p>The event will offer each student a DIY slime kit. Each slime starts out as transparent and opaque. From there, students will be able to dye the slime, accessorize, make it sparkly with glitter, mix with clay and fully transform the slime to their heart’s desire.</p>\n<p><em>Slime event hosted by the Physical Health and Wellness Club. Thursday, November 20, 2025, at 1:30 p.m. in the Student Union, room 312, at SUNY Old Westbury. Create the slime of your dreams at no additional cost.</em></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'NR274', NULL, '2025-11-14 11:58:31', 0, 'Nostalgia is defined as a sentimental longing or craving to revisit a part of the past often associated with personal and happy memories. As a college student, when your inner child begins to resurface, what better way to connect with your nostalgia than to revisit a fond pastime? Look no further than the DIY Slime…\n', NULL, NULL, 10),
('ed304694-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Men need mental health support, not ostracization', 'men-need-mental-health-support-not-ostracization-ready-to-publish', NULL, '<p><span data-contrast=\"auto\">If there is one thing in the world that a great deal of men struggle with, it would absolutely be their mental health. There has always been an issue when it comes to the ability of men to share their mental state with others, whether that be because of upbringing or other personal experiences. </span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;134233117&quot;:false,&quot;134233118&quot;:false,&quot;201341983&quot;:0,&quot;335559738&quot;:0,&quot;335559739&quot;:0,&quot;335559740&quot;:480}\"> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"auto\">There is a societal precedent that can be traced back as the primary cause of this issue — the idea that men have to always be strong and independent, never sharing their feelings, always being that perfect rock to hold everyone else down.</span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;134233117&quot;:false,&quot;134233118&quot;:false,&quot;201341983&quot;:0,&quot;335559738&quot;:0,&quot;335559739&quot;:0,&quot;335559740&quot;:480}\"> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"auto\">It’s likely that if somebody is to ask a man, boy, or anyone of the male gender about their mental health, they will likely not feel 100% comfortable talking about it, because they are never taught to be comfortable with discussing it. In fact, many men are they’re taught to ignore their feelings.</span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;134233117&quot;:false,&quot;134233118&quot;:false,&quot;201341983&quot;:0,&quot;335559738&quot;:0,&quot;335559739&quot;:0,&quot;335559740&quot;:480}\"> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"auto\">“I feel like we’re all kinda brought up to, y’know, you hear it all the time, be a man, push through it and I feel like obviously that has an effect on, y’know, the rest of your life probably,” said Luke Sommese, a senior at SUNY Old Westbury. “I’d say I am more likely to push past something rather than seek help, but, I again feel like that’s most men, honestly.”</span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;134233117&quot;:false,&quot;134233118&quot;:false,&quot;201341983&quot;:0,&quot;335559738&quot;:0,&quot;335559739&quot;:0,&quot;335559740&quot;:480}\"> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"auto\">The male population has a vastly higher suicide rate when compared to women, almost four times higher to be exact, <a href=\"https://www.aamc.org/news/men-and-mental-health-what-are-we-missing\">according to an article published by the Association of American Medical Colleges</a>, </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">a non-profit organization </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">dedicated to transforming health through medical education, health care, medical research, and community collaborations</span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">. </span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;134233117&quot;:false,&quot;134233118&quot;:false,&quot;201341983&quot;:0,&quot;335559738&quot;:0,&quot;335559739&quot;:0,&quot;335559740&quot;:480}\"> </span></p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a24713f2e74e sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>It far too often falls onto the poor men who suffer in silence to take the colossal blame for the issues that they feel unable to talk about.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Liam McCloskey, student at SUNY Old Westbury</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a24713f2e74e {\n    display: flex;\n    float: left;\n    margin: 30px 30px 30px 0;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24713f2e74e p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a24713f2e74e p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24713f2e74e .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a24713f2e74e p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24713f2e74e .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24713f2e74e .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24713f2e74e .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p><span data-contrast=\"auto\">The article said high rates of suicide are a byproduct of the lack of respect or care given to men suffering from mental health problems.</span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;134233117&quot;:false,&quot;134233118&quot;:false,&quot;201341983&quot;:0,&quot;335559738&quot;:0,&quot;335559739&quot;:0,&quot;335559740&quot;:480}\"> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"auto\">“Too often, society blames men themselves for their struggles,” the article said. “They are the ones who often turn to substance abuse and violent behavior rather than getting help for their mental health.” </span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;134233117&quot;:false,&quot;134233118&quot;:false,&quot;201341983&quot;:0,&quot;335559738&quot;:0,&quot;335559739&quot;:0,&quot;335559740&quot;:480}\"> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"auto\">It far too often falls onto the poor men who suffer in silence to take the colossal blame for the issues that they feel unable to talk about, and there is </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">much research </span><span data-contrast=\"auto\">that delves into why this needs to be rethought and how to rethink it. </span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;134233117&quot;:false,&quot;134233118&quot;:false,&quot;201341983&quot;:0,&quot;335551550&quot;:1,&quot;335551620&quot;:1,&quot;335559685&quot;:0,&quot;335559737&quot;:0,&quot;335559738&quot;:0,&quot;335559739&quot;:0,&quot;335559740&quot;:480}\"> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"auto\">Men will continue to suffer until society as a whole starts to realize that all of these men need proper care and support in order to finally recover from their degrading mental state as time goes on.</span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;134233117&quot;:false,&quot;134233118&quot;:false,&quot;201341983&quot;:0,&quot;335551550&quot;:1,&quot;335551620&quot;:1,&quot;335559685&quot;:0,&quot;335559737&quot;:0,&quot;335559738&quot;:0,&quot;335559739&quot;:0,&quot;335559740&quot;:480}\"> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"auto\">It really needs to be better understood why exactly the men of this world are constantly encouraged to keep their feelings in and always appear tough, and then it absolutely needs to be squashed.</span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;134233117&quot;:false,&quot;134233118&quot;:false,&quot;201341983&quot;:0,&quot;335551550&quot;:1,&quot;335551620&quot;:1,&quot;335559685&quot;:0,&quot;335559737&quot;:0,&quot;335559738&quot;:0,&quot;335559739&quot;:0,&quot;335559740&quot;:480}\"> </span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;134233117&quot;:false,&quot;134233118&quot;:false,&quot;201341983&quot;:0,&quot;335559738&quot;:0,&quot;335559739&quot;:0,&quot;335559740&quot;:480}\"> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"auto\">Hopefully society can one day be able to really weed out the societal sources of these terrible stigmas and squash them once and for all, making room for men to finally speak about their feelings. When the male population is finally able to truly open up, society will be made a little bit more healthy.</span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;134233117&quot;:false,&quot;134233118&quot;:false,&quot;201341983&quot;:0,&quot;335559738&quot;:0,&quot;335559739&quot;:0,&quot;335559740&quot;:480}\"> </span></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'LM794', NULL, '2025-11-20 10:30:50', 0, 'If there is one thing in the world that a great deal of men struggle with, it would absolutely be their mental health. There has always been an issue when it comes to the ability of men to share their mental state with others, whether that be because of upbringing or other personal experiences.   There is a societal precedent that…\n', NULL, NULL, 6),
('ed30b673-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Commuter students can feel disengaged and lonely, but is there more the school can do to help them?', 'commuter-students-can-feel-disengaged-and-lonely-but-is-there-more-the-school-can-do-to-help-them', NULL, '<p>Every day students at Old Westbury come from all over the place to get to campus. Some may have a short commute from towns like Mineola or Garden City, while others could have a commute much longer from places like Queens, Brooklyn or Suffolk County. While residential students can start their day with homework or breakfast, an average commuter student can start their day with an hour of traffic.</p>\n<p>At SUNY Old Westbury, commuter students make up the majority of the student body, with 4,448 students currently enrolled and only around 600 of them residing on campus, making around 85% of students commuters. The institution seems to understand this, with many commuter outreach programs available, as well as the university itself stating “off-campus and commuter students are an important part of our campus community.”</p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a24714019920 sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>I feel like I might spend more time in my car in between classes than I do actually on campus.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Danny Lopez, a senior at SUNY Old Westbury, on the isolation that can come from being a commuter student</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a24714019920 {\n    display: flex;\n    float: left;\n    margin: 30px 30px 30px 0;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24714019920 p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a24714019920 p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24714019920 .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a24714019920 p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24714019920 .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24714019920 .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24714019920 .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p>Unlike most residential Universities, Old Westbury is known for the commuter lifestyle, being marked by the flow of cars and buses in and out of the campus.And while the university is known as a commuter campus, commuter students can face challenges such as time management, isolation and campus engagement issues.</p>\n<p>“I have to wake up extra early every day,” says junior Brandon Centeno. “If I were to sleep in, I’d definitely miss class, and it’s added extra pressure onto my daily schedule. You know, waking up has become a chore itself when I see the commute ahead of me.”</p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_11743\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-11743\" style=\"width: 300px\" class=\"wp-caption alignright\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-small wp-image-11743\" src=\"uploads/BrandonCenteno-by-LukeSommese-300x234.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"234\" srcset=\"uploads/BrandonCenteno-by-LukeSommese-300x234.jpg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/BrandonCenteno-by-LukeSommese-600x467.jpg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/BrandonCenteno-by-LukeSommese-1200x934.jpg 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/BrandonCenteno-by-LukeSommese-768x598.jpg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/BrandonCenteno-by-LukeSommese-1536x1196.jpg 1536w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/BrandonCenteno-by-LukeSommese.jpg 2001w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-11743\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Brandon Centeno, a junior at SUNY Old Westbury, in the Campus Center. Nov. 2, 2025. PHOTO BY: LUKE SOMMESE</figcaption></figure>\n<p>Other students echo these feelings. “I feel like I might spend more time in my car in between classes than I do actually on campus,” said Danny Lopez, a senior at SUNY Old Westbury. “Having a break between classes almost makes me mad because there is nothing to do. I see some people hanging out, but it never feels worth it as I’m just tired from work and school.”</p>\n<p>This brings up another part of the issue. Commuters having trouble staying connected with campus life isn’t just about interest or courseload, it’s about balance especially for the ones who work while they are in school.</p>\n<p>“I work almost thirty hours a week on top of school,&#8221; said Centeno. &#8220;Thirty hours might not sound like a lot, but trust me when you have a full schedule on top of that it adds up and makes me crazy. I don’t have the option to not work, and when you have to do schoolwork and have a job, getting involved on campus seems like something that would make no sense for me.”</p>\n<p>As an institution designed to engage with commuter students, it seems like it should be impossible for students to feel like Centeno. Assets such as the Office of Commuter Outreach, the Panther Pad, game room and more make it seem like there is no more to be done for commuter students. But this is false.</p>\n<p>“It’s hard to even make friends with how busy I am, and if I even see a flyer for an interesting club it would just add more onto my plate which I can’t afford,” said Centeno. “It’s hard to even make friends with how busy I am, and if I even see a flyer for an interesting club it would just add more onto my plate which I can’t afford,” said Centeno.</p>\n<p>Since most students are commuters like Centeno and Lopez, there must be another way to help out and get them involved. Whether it’s moving around club and event meeting times or giving more notice before events, more attention should be paid to the majority.</p>\n<p>“There needs to be something that says, ‘Hey stop by!’ as I feel like I hear about these events all the time after they’ve actually happened,&#8221; said Professor Marty Cooper of the Psychology Dept. at SUNY Old Westbury. &#8220;There may be time constraints due to everyone having a different schedule, but maybe host multiple events then? We have this gorgeous space at our disposal.”</p>\n<p>From my observation, at least Cooper brings along valuable points, and some of his ideas seem promising. As a community it is important to support commuter students such as Centeno and Lopez.</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'LS775', NULL, '2025-11-17 15:46:18', 0, 'Every day students at Old Westbury come from all over the place to get to campus. Some may have a short commute from towns like Mineola or Garden City, while others could have a commute much longer from places like Queens, Brooklyn or Suffolk County. While residential students can start their day with homework or…\n', NULL, NULL, 6),
('ed31219b-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Read and nosh at Harmonia-Discordia’s release party on Dec. 1', 'read-and-nosh-at-harmonia-discordias-release-party-on-dec-1', NULL, '<p>There’s a familiar saying: “Eyes are the window to the soul.” While this holds truth, there’s a motto that reflects <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/school-arts-and-sciences/english/projects-organizations\">Harmonia-Discordia</a>’s philosophy: Writing is the window to the soul.</p>\n<p>On Monday, Dec., at 1:30 p.m., in the New Academic Building room 3123, Harmonia-Discordia will be hosting a release party for their newest issue of Harmonia-Discordia, the creative writing journal of the English department.</p>\n<p>At the event, Harmonia-Discordia will be giving out physical copies of the latest edition of their creative collection of student-made works of literature. Snacks plus refreshments ranging from savory, sweet delicacies to soda will be offered as students do readings of their work.</p>\n<h6>What is Harmonia-Discordia?</h6>\n<p>Harmonia-Discordia is a joint organization that aims to publish creative writing and academic writing alike.</p>\n<p>Harmonia, a name that references the Greek goddess of peace, harmony and concord, is the English Department&#8217;s creative writing journal that publishes poetry, lyrics, short stories and artwork.</p>\n<p>Discordia, a name that references the Roman goddess of entropy and chaos, is a scholarly journal that publishes things like book reviews, analysis papers and research papers. It was founded by Dr. Jessica Williams in 2013.</p>\n<p>Harmonia was founded by two students in 2003, Jessica Williams and Meredith Lehrman– Williams, the latter of whom would become a full-time Assistant Professor in the English department at SUNY Old Westbury and serve as faculty editor for Harmonia and Discordia until 2020.</p>\n<p>The torch in 2020 was passed onto Dr. Elizabeth Schmermund, a full-time assistant professor in the English department who became the faculty advisor and editor for both Harmonia and Discordia.</p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_11753\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-11753\" style=\"width: 231px\" class=\"wp-caption alignleft\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-small wp-image-11753\" src=\"uploads/HarmoniaDiscordia2-231x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"231\" height=\"300\" srcset=\"uploads/HarmoniaDiscordia2-231x300.jpg 231w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/HarmoniaDiscordia2-461x600.jpg 461w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/HarmoniaDiscordia2-923x1200.jpg 923w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/HarmoniaDiscordia2-768x999.jpg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/HarmoniaDiscordia2.jpg 969w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 231px) 100vw, 231px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-11753\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Harmonia-Discordia. Fall 2025 edition. Photo provided by Harmonia-Discordia.</figcaption></figure>\n<h6>Why merge the magazines?</h6>\n<p>In the fall of 2024, it was an executive decision to merge the two clubs under the mantle of Harmonia-Discordia.</p>\n<p>“Discordia did not have as much demand as Harmonia, the club did not want to deplatform the handful of important academic work our very intelligent students submit every semester,” said Lori Yamond, the president of Harmonia-Discordia as of Fall 2025.</p>\n<h6>The community of Harmonia-Discordia</h6>\n<p>The community of Harmonia unites everyone under the passion and love for writing and self-expression.</p>\n<p>“I was mainly compelled by the object of being published, but I soon realized I was sticking around for every club meeting and becoming an editor for the magazine because I loved the community it connected me with,” Yamond said.</p>\n<p>And while Yamond has only run the group a short time, the experience has impacted her deeply.</p>\n<p>“I never expected to fall in love with it the way that I did,” she said. “I never expected it to lead me to spring afternoons on the campus lawn with friends or lead me to this current moment as the club and magazine’s president.”</p>\n<p>Harmonia-Discordia has around 13 consistent members as well as group leaders. In addition to Yamond, Caitlyn Page serves as vice president, Magaly Garray is the treasurer and Mallory Vannoni serves as the public relations manager.</p>\n<p>These four women unite together in a progress of chaos, determination and eager joy to make the club thrive abundantly.</p>\n<h6>The theme of the new edition</h6>\n<p>This year&#8217;s aesthetic theme for Harmonia-Discordia was a difficult choice. Student artwork had been scarce in submissions. Hence, Yamond and Page took it upon themselves to dive into graphic design, deciding on a museum theme.</p>\n<p>“The museum theme intends to capture walking through living works, honoring the preservation of art, especially the art of writing an time when censorship is on the rise and AI is threatening to dismantle, or deplatform, human artists and art,” Yamond said.</p>\n<p>There are a huge number of stories, poems, lyrics and more featured within the new issue. With a wide array of genres, Harmonia-Discordia aims to exhibit every kind of writer, act as a place where every kind of writer can find a name for themselves or put themselves out there without restrictions.</p>\n<p>Harmonia-Discordia acknowledges that the writing process looks completely different from formal and informal writing.</p>\n<p>Academic writing reaches feats of concise structure, literary theories, and the synthesis of scholarly sources, whereas creative writing has a focus on emotions, experiences, and has a free-flowing or open-ended writing process.</p>\n<p>“When I write academically, I force myself to say something urgent about a work of literature,” Yamond said. “But, when I write creatively, I force myself to say something urgent about the world, my life, my damage, my love, my family and even about my body.”</p>\n<p>The previous issues are a time capsule published online. Past and present issues can be accessed online on the official website at <a href=\"https://owenglishwrites.wordpress.com/\">OWEnglishWrites.Wordpres.com</a></p>\n<p><em>Harmonia-Discordia fall 2025 release party. 1:30 p.m. on Monday, Dec. 1 in NAB room 3123 at SUNY Old Westbury. Free admission. </em></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'NR274', NULL, '2025-11-18 10:17:54', 0, 'There’s a familiar saying: “Eyes are the window to the soul.” While this holds truth, there’s a motto that reflects Harmonia-Discordia’s philosophy: Writing is the window to the soul. On Monday, Dec., at 1:30 p.m., in the New Academic Building room 3123, Harmonia-Discordia will be hosting a release party for their newest issue of Harmonia-Discordia,…\n', NULL, NULL, 10),
('ed316a38-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'SUNY Old Westbury joins statewide military tuition initiative', 'suny-old-westbury-joins-statewide-military-tuition-initiative-ready-to-publish', NULL, '<p>SUNY Old Westbury has joined a SUNY-wide initiative to expand affordable education for active service military members.</p>\n<p>Chancellor John B. King, Jr. announced the new tuition rate on November 11, 2025, which was Veterans Day. He stated the initiative reflected SUNY’s emphasis on social mobility and career security across New York State.</p>\n<p>Starting in spring, 2026, a handful of SUNY institutions, including SUNY OW, will offer a new system-wide initiative designed to make a SUNY OW education fully affordable for active-duty service members, members of the National Guard and members of the Reserves.</p>\n<p>Military-connected students will have access to the already affordable SUNY OW undergraduate degree and microcredential programs in person or online without additional costs or barriers.</p>\n<p>Currently, on the SUNY Old Westbury campus, there are 52 enrolled military-connected students, which includes students who are veterans and those who remain in active service, as well as their dependents.</p>\n<h3><strong>Application expectations and eligibility</strong></h3>\n<p>Eligibility is for the following: Active-duty service members, members of the National Guard and members of the reserves. The program requires military-connected students to show valid military identification. The application process has not yet been finalized, but the campus expects it to remain simple.</p>\n<p>Bryan Terry, the vice president of enrollment management and marketing has been working on this operation&#8217;s full and explicit launch for spring 2026, however a deadline has not been announced.</p>\n<p>“While the process hasn&#8217;t been fully developed, the students will need to identify themselves, but SUNY Old Westbury will ensure that the process will not be a tedious one,” said Terry. “Most of these students already know our military supporters on campus.”</p>\n<h3><strong>Campus support for military students</strong></h3>\n<p>SUNY Old Westbury has <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/division/office-academic-affairs/veterans-benefits-and-resources\">dedicated administrators</a> who are already involved with students of military status and will be more than happy to assist with this new military tuition program.</p>\n<p>Students could meet with Ann Denning in the Office of the Registrar or Jennifer Jaikaran, who worked closely with veteran students in recruitment and student success.</p>\n<p>“The program addresses a long-standing challenge faced by active service members whose federal tuition assistance often falls short of full tuition at public universities,” said Terry.</p>\n<p>When military-connected students are applying to higher education, either for the first time or as returning students, many will face hurdles of stress. The interconnected support-systems at SUNY Old Westbury are designed to dismantle confusion and become a compass for students&#8217; uncertainties. The Center of Excellence for Veteran Student Success serves as that centralized point of support.</p>\n<p>“This support gives them the information and guidance needed to navigate academic, professional, and personal challenges,” said Terry. “Over time, this consistent connection builds trust and empowers veterans to feel confident and support key to a successful transition to civilian life.”</p>\n<h3><strong>Still have questions?</strong></h3>\n<p>Students have asked whether the tuition program covered fees, books, or supplies, Terry said, but tuition is the only covered category at this time; students will not have out-of-pocket tuition costs under the program. Military-connected students who received scholarships, grants, or FAFSA assistance remain eligible for the program and can stack the benefits.</p>\n<p>Students who drop a course or withdraw will follow SUNY Old Westbury’s standard withdrawal policies the same as for all students receiving tuition benefits.</p>\n<p>For further information, students may reach out to <a href=\"mailto:jaikaranj@oldwestbury.edu\">Jennifer Jaikaran</a>, <a href=\"mailto:denninga@oldwestbury.edu\">Ann Denning</a>, <a href=\"mailto:kinanem@oldwestbury.edu\">Michael Kinane</a> or <a href=\"mailto:terryb@oldwestbury.edu\">Bryan Terry</a>.</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'NR274', NULL, '2025-11-19 10:30:32', 0, 'SUNY Old Westbury has joined a SUNY-wide initiative to expand affordable education for active service military members. Chancellor John B. King, Jr. announced the new tuition rate on November 11, 2025, which was Veterans Day. He stated the initiative reflected SUNY’s emphasis on social mobility and career security across New York State. Starting in spring,…\n', NULL, NULL, 1);
INSERT INTO `content` (`id`, `type`, `title`, `slug`, `description`, `content`, `url`, `approval_status`, `author_id`, `editor_id`, `created_at`, `is_featured`, `excerpt`, `video_url`, `featured_image`, `category_id`) VALUES
('ed31ccb9-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'SUNY Old Westbury was built on social justice. I want it to stay that way.', 'suny-old-westbury-was-built-on-social-justice-i-want-it-to-stay-that-way', NULL, '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Turning Point USA, the non-profit conservative organization co-founded by the late Charlie Kirk, plans to meet with the Student Government Association on December 2, 2025, in an effort to sway them to vote in favor of starting a Turning Point chapter on our campus. Rumor has it they also plan to host an event on campus on December 9.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Charlie Kirk is a name that has divided Americans along political ideologies — for better or for worse. Whether you loved or hated Kirk, his death in September at the hands of the very thing he loved so dearly – guns – sent ripples through the political hemisphere. </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Though supporters consider Kirk a “conservative activist,” others are not so sure. It seemed the central focus of Kirk’s “conservative activism” was to spread racial unrest, slander of the LGBTQ+ community, advocate for the</span><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WV29R1M25n8&amp;t=1054s\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> victims of rape to carry unwanted fetuses to term</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, and attempt to portray himself as an educated superior. This, despite the fact</span><a href=\"https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/cdxqnkwerj7o\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> that he holds no college degree </span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">himself. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In one of Kirk’s most famous debates, published to Youtube on the channel </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Jubilee </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">in 2024, Kirk was speaking to a college student who had proposed the idea: I</span><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WV29R1M25n8&amp;t=1054s\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">f your ten-year-old daughter was raped</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, would you force your daughter to carry and deliver that baby?</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Kirk, who has a young daughter, replied to this college student, </span><a href=\"https://ca.news.yahoo.com/fact-check-charlie-kirk-once-235100404.html?guccounter=1&amp;guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS8&amp;guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAHdl4ytyTxGSZc1Bn7qydmJ_Tp6xIgQHVnrSAyzriQgQq-jdWllJRphoIg5JjRhNEV4lIoz_wZokyyQdLQPJEra1qu-DhVmMDEvhFG5KDVN7mlKKpqO7_-S_GaODzA4pdweSjX1l-6Aijvv-64pQv89twjftISeXuPVAvJzmbHc4\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Calm down, the answer is yes, the baby would be delivered.” </span></a></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">When Kirk spoke earlier this year at a Leadership Summit in Grapevine, Texas, he spoke directly to a fourteen-year-old girl who wished to pursue political journalism, stating,</span><a href=\"https://www.tiktok.com/@independent/video/7517689632293801249\"> <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Interestingly, I think there&#8217;s an argument to bring back the &#8216;M-R-S degree’.” </span></a></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">M-R-S degree</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> is a slang term for young women getting married and pregnant as a &#8220;career.&#8221; Kirk then said, </span><a href=\"https://www.splcenter.org/resources/hatewatch/turning-point-usa-young-women-leadership-summit-agenda/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Just be clear, that’s why you’re going to college, right? Don’t lie to yourself…like, don’t like, [say] ‘Oh I’m going, I’m studying sociology.” No, you’re not. We know why you’re here and that’s okay.” </span></a></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">At a speaking summit for Turning Point USA, Kirk stood just 80 miles from the grisly murder site of George Floyd, a Black man killed by Minneapolis, Minnesota police officers. </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">And what did the Turning Point USA co-founder have to say about Floyd only a year after Floyd’s murder? Kirk said he would say things </span><a href=\"https://whyy.org/articles/how-a-right-wing-provocateur-is-using-race-to-reach-gen-z/?utm_source=chatgpt.com\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“no one dares say out loud”</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> then proceeded to call George Floyd a </span><a href=\"https://ca.news.yahoo.com/fact-check-charlie-kirk-called-110000512.html\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“scumbag”</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and made debunked claims about Floyd, despite saying that didn’t mean Floyd should die. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">On June 1, 2023, the first day of Pride Month, Kirk sent out a simple tweet: “Pride is a Sin.” He then said that when “groomers can’t reproduce,” they “go serve on school boards. And they go do drag queens. And they do all this other sort of disgusting, nauseating stuff.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It is worth pointing out that “</span><a href=\"https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/groomer\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">groomers</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">” is a derogatory term used by some people to imply that LGBTQ+ people spend their lives “grooming” children to be gay or engage in pedophilia. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Kirk is also a staunch advocate for the coagulation of church and state. Despite all evidence to the contrary, such as the U.S. Constitution, Kirk </span><a href=\"https://www.mediamatters.org/charlie-kirk/charlie-kirk-there-no-separation-church-and-state\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">on his podcast in 2022</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> said,“Of course, we should have church and state mixed together. Our Founding Fathers believed in that.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">On September 10, 2025,</span><a href=\"https://apnews.com/article/charlie-kirk-conservative-activist-shot-546165a8151104e0938a5e085be1e8bd\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Charlie Kirk was fatally shot in the neck</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> via sniper while he was engaging in discussion with college students on Utah Valley campus. While everyone of every political ideology should agree that there is no place in America for political violence, it seemed that Kirk himself – an ardent supporter of gun rights – was aware of the associated risks. </span></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.justjared.com/2025/09/10/charlie-kirks-past-quote-about-gun-deaths-second-amendment-rights-resurfaces-after-tragic-shooting/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I think it’s worth it. It’s worth to have a cost of, unfortunately, some gun deaths every single year so that we can have the Second Amendment,”</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> he said at a Turning Point USA Faith event in April 2023. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Now, while much of Kirk’s activism occurred far from the SUNY Old Westbury Campus, it might be easy to assume that it would not impact us. </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">But that assumption is wrong. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">To what degree of freedom is forcing your ten year old daughter to carry her rapist&#8217;s baby? </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">What degree of freedom is standing just yards from where a Black man was unjustly murdered by the police, and</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><a href=\"https://whyy.org/articles/how-a-right-wing-provocateur-is-using-race-to-reach-gen-z/?utm_source=chatgpt.com\"> call that man a scumbag</a>? </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">When does it change from freedom of speech to the enticement of hatred? </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Kirk’s organization holds that they are rooted in Christian faith, conservative ideals, and &#8220;Old American&#8221; freedom. They denounce any connection to violence or hate and say they hold no prejudice – simply that they hold conservative values and wish to spread them freely. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">From SUNY Old Westbury&#8217;s founding in 1965 to the present day, our school has prided itself on something immortalized in our mission statement: “</span><a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/about-us/mission-vision\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">a commitment to building a more just and sustainable world</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Today, as the university proudly celebrates 60 years of unwavering support of social justice, we are at a crossroad.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Will we cave, or will we stand strong?</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">When any potential club submits a constitution to the university&#8217;s Student Government Association, they are asked: What is your mission? In other words: What does your club exist to do? Some might answer to educate, to illustrate, to provide a space for all to come and be safe and feel validated. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">But what will Turning Point USA say? Perhaps conservatism? Or perhaps racism, homophobia or blatant bigotry disguised as “freedom of speech?” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The time is now for the student body, faculty and staff to make a decision. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Does Turning Point USA have a home at SUNY Old Westbury?</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It is evident by this article that I have made my decision. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It is now time for you to make yours.</span></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'AB347', NULL, '2025-11-21 08:26:18', 0, 'Turning Point USA, the non-profit conservative organization co-founded by the late Charlie Kirk, plans to meet with the Student Government Association on December 2, 2025, in an effort to sway them to vote in favor of starting a Turning Point chapter on our campus. Rumor has it they also plan to host an event on…\n', NULL, NULL, 6),
('ed3220c8-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Stressed over finals? Engage in stress-busting techniques at “From Stressed to Your Best” event on Dec. 3 in the Student Union', 'stressed-over-finals-engage-in-stress-busting-techniques-at-from-stress-to-your-best-event-on-dec-3-in-the-student-union', NULL, '<p>As the library begins to fill with students working late into the evening, it becomes clear that the semester is coming to an end and finals are quickly approaching. To support students during this stressful time, SUNY Old Westbury will host a workshop designed to help Panthers manage the pressure that often builds at the end of the term.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://oldwestbury.campuslabs.com/engage/event/11814348\">“From Stressed to Your Best”</a> will take place Wednesday, Dec. 3, from 1:30 to 2:30 p.m. in Multipurpose Room C of the Student Union. The event is being held in collaboration with CSTEP, TRIO SSS, CAPW, EOP and the ACE program to make sure students across campus feel supported.</p>\n<p>The workshop will include interactive exercises focused on reducing stress, along with guidance and advice from senior counselor Tatiana McLean. Students can expect to find support not only from campus professionals, but also from fellow Panthers who are experiencing the same pressures as finals approach.</p>\n<p>The goal of the event is to provide students with helpful tools and strategies to protect their mental health as academic pressure increases.</p>\n<p>It also aims to remind students that it is okay to struggle, and that they are not alone during one of the most demanding times of the semester.</p>\n<p>National research supports the reality many students are facing. A 2025 Healthy Minds Study conducted by the <a href=\"https://sph.umich.edu/news/2025posts/college-student-mental-health-third-consecutive-year-improvement.html\">University of Michigan’s School of Public Health</a> found that anxiety and depression remain common among college students across the country, even as some improvements have been reported in recent years .</p>\n<p>Another peer-reviewed study published by the <a href=\"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5609663/?\">National Institutes of Health</a> found that students experience significantly higher stress levels during exam periods, which can negatively impact sleep, performance and overall well-being .</p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_11799\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-11799\" style=\"width: 160px\" class=\"wp-caption alignright\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-full wp-image-11799\" src=\"uploads/ByAnnabellaRunyan.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"160\" height=\"120\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-11799\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">A mural highlighting the “8 Dimensions of Wellness” is displayed inside the SUNY Old Westbury Counseling Center on Nov. 24, 2025. PHOTO BY: ANNABELLA RUNYAN</figcaption></figure>\n<p>Student voices on campus reflect that national trend.</p>\n<p>“Everyone wants to give you like homework last minute,” said Stephanie Velez, a biology major with a minor in neuropsychology and a member of CSTEP. “And like, it’s just all due at the same time. You have to just like plan it out on like a little like agenda type of thing or like a calendar. Just like set out when to do what, like prioritize stuff that’s coming up sooner.”</p>\n<p>Velez said events like this matter because “it’s an important event to show that you’re not alone and that you’re able to like overcome any obstacles that you face no matter how stressed you are. And that there is a support group for you, not by yourself.”</p>\n<p>Faculty members also recognize how stress affects student performance.</p>\n<p>“I think the perception piece is key here like the perceived demands of finals like feeling like it’s high stakes and also coupled with the sleep,” said Jill Farber, a physiology professor who teaches applied psychology at SUNY Old Westbury. “Because a lot of students sleep a lot less during finals time or they are so stressed that they’re like losing sleep, and sleep quality really impacts your ability to perform on exams.”</p>\n<p>Farber said that learning coping skills can make a meaningful difference.</p>\n<p>“I think they’re super valuable because, like learning to cope with stress and manage stress, like stress is all about perception,” she said.</p>\n<p>She said that students are often balancing intense responsibilities.</p>\n<p>“Trying to balance school, extracurriculars, pre-professional experiences, exams, writing demands, and then also like family and friends and social things,” she said. “So there’s just a lot to juggle during such a formative time in your life.”</p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_11801\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-11801\" style=\"width: 146px\" class=\"wp-caption alignleft\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-full wp-image-11801\" src=\"uploads/OliviaHughesTRIByAnnabellaRunyan.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"146\" height=\"110\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-11801\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Olivia Hughes, director of the TRIO program, stands inside the Student Union at SUNY Old Westbury on Nov. 19, 2025. PHOTO BY: ANNABELLA RUNYAN</figcaption></figure>\n<p>TRIO Director Olivia Hughes said helping plan events like these is important because midterms and finals are probably the most stressful exams students take.</p>\n<p>“We do have something in our office called Trio Talks where students can come and just have conversation with one another,” she said.</p>\n<p>Campus initiatives like “From Stressed to Your Best” aim to give students practical tools and community-based support to help them finish the semester in a healthier way, Hughes said, and that mental health should remain a priority.</p>\n<p>“I hope that students understand that, as important as their academics are, their mental health is just as important,” she said.</p>\n<p><em>&#8220;From Stressed To Your Best,&#8221; hosted by TRIO Student Services at SUNY Old Westbury. 1:30 p.m. on Wed., Dec. 3 in Multipurpose Room C of the Student Union. Free admission.</em></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'AR706', NULL, '2025-12-01 08:02:23', 0, 'As the library begins to fill with students working late into the evening, it becomes clear that the semester is coming to an end and finals are quickly approaching. To support students during this stressful time, SUNY Old Westbury will host a workshop designed to help Panthers manage the pressure that often builds at the…\n', NULL, NULL, 10),
('ed32659e-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Civil unrest and ICE raids spark fear and reflection for some students', 'civil-unrest-and-ice-raids-spark-fear-and-reflection-for-some-students', NULL, '<p><span data-contrast=\"none\">It was supposed to be a simple night out. </span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;335559739&quot;:0}\"> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"none\">A SUNY Old Westbury student and her friends had gone into the city to eat dinner in Chinatown. They laughed, shared food and talked about school. </span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;335559739&quot;:0}\"> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"none\">But when they walked out of the restaurant, flashing lights filled the street. ICE agents were moving quickly, stopping people and leading several away in handcuffs. What was a normal city street just hours before suddenly resembled a scene from a dystopian nightmare.</span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;335559739&quot;:0}\"> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"none\">“Every siren makes my heart race,” said one undocumented SUNY Old Westbury senior who witnessed the aftermath of the unsettling scene. The student asked not to be named out of fear for their personal safety.</span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;335559739&quot;:0}\"> </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">“It’s hard to focus on the class when you’re scared your family might not be at the house when you get back,” they said.</span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;335559739&quot;:0}\"> </span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;335559739&quot;:0}\"> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"none\">Across the country, </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">civil unrest</span><span data-contrast=\"none\"> has intensified. In June 2025, protests erupted after federal authorities launched a new wave of ICE raids that included </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">National Guard</span><span data-contrast=\"none\"> and Marine deployments in multiple cities.</span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;335559739&quot;:0}\"> </span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;335559739&quot;:0}\"> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"none\">“I look at the news, like, what the hell, you know?” said the SUNY Old Westbury student. “The people in the streets are no different than me. Like, what if I was there? What if it was me?”</span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;335559739&quot;:0}\"> </span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;335559739&quot;:0}\"> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"none\">More recently, </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">New York City’s Chinatown</span><span data-contrast=\"none\"> became the site of public protest following ICE deployment in New York City. Protestors chanted throughout the streets following the arrest of nine people who the Department of Homeland Security alleged were in the US illegally. </span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;335559739&quot;:0}\"> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"none\">The tension surrounding these events extends beyond the confines of city streets. On the campus of SUNY Old Westbury, the national debate over enforcement and rights is resonating among students returning to a new academic year under a climate of uncertainty. Here, these lessons are unfolding not just in textbooks but in real time.</span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;335559739&quot;:0}\"> </span></p>\n<snspoll data-poll-id=\"11823\"></snspoll>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"none\">The Politics, Economics &amp; Law program, also known as PEL,“introduces students to the disciplines of political science, political economy, and economics … how these different areas intersect to shape U.S. and international law, institutions, and policies,” according to the SUNY Old Westbury </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">website</span><span data-contrast=\"none\">.</span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;335559739&quot;:0}\"> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"none\">That mission took on a more profound meaning this fall as students witness those same systems under public scrutiny.</span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;335559739&quot;:0}\"> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"none\">Students in the program are now examining how government decisions ripple through communities like their own. They are questioning what it means to feel protected or targeted by the same institutions they study. For some, the classroom is no longer a neutral space but one where national policy becomes personal reflection.</span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;335559739&quot;:0}\"> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"none\">Rozelle Thompson, a SUNY Old Westbury alumnus who earned her degree in a PEL and now attends graduate school at Stony Brook University, is not undocumented, but has compassion for those who are living in fear. </span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;335559739&quot;:0}\"> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"none\">“I used to love the city, now I can’t even think about going after what happened to Chinatown,” she said. </span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;335559739&quot;:0}\"> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"none\">Thompson said faculty members at Stony Brook University are encouraging students to connect current events to their coursework, bridging theory with reality. The timing, she said, has made that effort both necessary and difficult. </span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;335559739&quot;:0}\"> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"none\">The story unfolding at SUNY Old Westbury and nearby universities reflects a larger national pattern: when trust in government wavers, students, especially those studying politics and law, can be among the first to feel it. The students’ reactions can offer a glimpse into how young people interpret civic responsibility and public accountability in times of crisis.</span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;335559739&quot;:0}\"> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"none\">At Old Westbury, many students come from </span><a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/division/office-academic-affairs/institutional-effectiveness/institutional-research/fast-facts\"><span data-contrast=\"none\">immigrant and mixed-status families</span></a><span data-contrast=\"none\">. For them, the recent ICE raids are not abstract headlines but reminders of vulnerability. For others, they can represent a moment to reconsider what justice and equity mean in practice.</span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;335559739&quot;:0}\"> </span></p>\n<p><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;335559739&quot;:0}\"> </span><span data-contrast=\"none\">The experiences of these students show that the effects of national enforcement policies extend far beyond the communities directly targeted. They reach into classrooms, challenge ideals and shape the perspectives of future leaders.</span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;335559739&quot;:0}\"> </span></p>\n<p><span data-contrast=\"none\">“The kids in class don’t know better, they don’t know they are talking about me,” said the SUNY Old Westbury senior who asked not to be named. “It’s exhausting to live being scared like that.”</span><span data-ccp-props=\"{&quot;335559739&quot;:0}\"> </span></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'MA394', NULL, '2025-12-02 11:59:44', 0, 'It was supposed to be a simple night out.   A SUNY Old Westbury student and her friends had gone into the city to eat dinner in Chinatown. They laughed, shared food and talked about school.   But when they walked out of the restaurant, flashing lights filled the street. ICE agents were moving quickly, stopping people and leading several away in…\n', NULL, NULL, 1),
('ed32c56c-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'video', 'Caribbean Club fashion show at SUNY Old Westbury. November, 2025. VIDEO BY: SOFIE POPOTTE', 'caribbean-club-fashion-show-at-suny-old-westbury-november-2025-video-by-sofie-popotte', NULL, '', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'SP154', NULL, '2025-12-02 12:25:19', 0, '', NULL, NULL, 15),
('ed331c0c-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'video', 'SUNY Old Westbury student fearful after Halloween 2025 robbery at dorm. VIDEO BY: BRANDON HERNANDEZ', 'suny-old-westbury-student-fearful-after-halloween-2025-robbery-at-dorm-video-by-brandon-hernandez', NULL, '', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'BH388', NULL, '2025-12-02 13:08:25', 0, '', NULL, NULL, 15),
('ed336c6e-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'A greener future: SUNY Old Westbury’s upgrades to the Natural Sciences Building', 'a-greener-future-suny-old-westburys-upgrades-to-the-natural-sciences-building', NULL, '<p>In a milestone moment for SUNY Old Westbury, the Natural Sciences building is currently receiving a major upgrade of its facilities. The upgrade is expected to be <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/news-events/groundbreaking-celebrates-expansion-improvements-science-facililty\">50% more energy efficient</a> and will boast a geothermal system for heating and cooling, as well as energy efficient glazing on the facility’s windows.</p>\n<p>SUNY Officials broke ground this past February on the $200 million project, and it will be the first major update to the building since it was built in 1985.</p>\n<p>The project will be completed in three phases. Phase one will include installation of <a href=\"https://www.newsday.com/long-island/education/natural-sciences-suny-old-westbury-xty8pu0g\">geothermal wells</a>, providing energy-efficient heating and cooling; phase two will consist of an addition to the existing building; and phase three will be the renovation of the interior of the building.</p>\n<p>“We will be fully electric,&#8221; said Ray Maggiore, the university’s assistant vice president for capital planning. &#8220;Instead of using gas to send heat to our air handlers, we&#8217;ll be getting that from the earth.”</p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_11854\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-11854\" style=\"width: 600px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"wp-image-11854 size-medium\" src=\"uploads/emf6_kboi_210111_ss4mp_generated-600x415.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"415\" srcset=\"uploads/emf6_kboi_210111_ss4mp_generated-600x415.jpg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/emf6_kboi_210111_ss4mp_generated-1200x831.jpg 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/emf6_kboi_210111_ss4mp_generated-768x532.jpg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/emf6_kboi_210111_ss4mp_generated-1536x1063.jpg 1536w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/emf6_kboi_210111_ss4mp_generated-300x208.jpg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/emf6_kboi_210111_ss4mp_generated.jpg 1920w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-11854\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Image courtesy of Matt Cole via Vecteezy.com</figcaption></figure>\n<p>This project is expected to exceed the school&#8217;s energy and carbon reduction goals by approximately 9%, and this will <a href=\"https://www.longislandpress.com/2025/02/04/suny-old-westbury-renovations/\">help assist in the goal</a> of 100% zero emission electricity by 2040 and 85% reduction of greenhouse gas emissions by 2050. And it doesn’t end there.</p>\n<p>According to the school website, the final phase will include a green roof. A green roof provides a multitude of benefits, such as a building with better <a href=\"https://worldgreeninfrastructurenetwork.org/key-definition-green-roof/\">thermal performance</a>, reducing the both level of temperature regulating required and improving the efficiency at which they run through reduced leakage.</p>\n<p>“For heating and cooling the building they’re using geothermal energy and they&#8217;re using a vertical model which means they’re going down and drilling boreholes,” said Prof. Timothy Strout, who specializes in environmental science. “It&#8217;s a closed loop system so that everything&#8217;s kept within. They won’t be affecting groundwater. So we won’t have to burn fossil fuels or anything like this for energy. It’s essentially a win-win.”</p>\n<p>Strout emphasized how much of a victory this is for the university and the environment around it.</p>\n<p>“It will be much better for the environment while also being cost efficient,” said Strout. “It&#8217;s an old building and our programs are advancing, and if we’re gonna keep a competitive STEM program, we need to have a more updated facility. We could use the space and more labs, and this will help the school into the future.”</p>\n<p>A closed-loop geothermal system will be powering the new building, and this should dramatically cut energy use. By relying on this system to power the new building instead of fossil fuels, it will be better for the environment.</p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a2471630b916 sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>. . . the new science building will leave no carbon footprint — it will rely mainly on geothermal energy which will be clean energy, saving money and the environment at the same time.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Prof. Fernando Nieto, environmental sciences expert at SUNY Old Westbury</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471630b916 {\n    display: flex;\n    float: right;\n    margin: 30px 0 30px 30px;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471630b916 p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471630b916 p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471630b916 .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a2471630b916 p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471630b916 .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471630b916 .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471630b916 .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p>Prof. Fernando Nieto of the science department at Old Westbury stressed how key it is that we will be using clean energy.</p>\n<p>“It’s part of the efforts of the state of New York to kind of free ourselves of fossil fuels,” said Nieto. “In the context of ameliorating climate change or slowing it down. So, new construction and in particular this construction of the new science building will leave no carbon footprint &#8211; it will rely mainly on geothermal energy which will be clean energy, saving money and the environment at the same time.”</p>\n<p>The new system represents one of the most ambitious sustainability upgrades for campus to date. With the building expected to serve as a centerpiece for STEM programs, administrators hope this will serve as a real life example of modern clean energy technology for everyone in the community.</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'LS775', NULL, '2025-12-08 09:43:26', 0, 'In a milestone moment for SUNY Old Westbury, the Natural Sciences building is currently receiving a major upgrade of its facilities. The upgrade is expected to be 50% more energy efficient and will boast a geothermal system for heating and cooling, as well as energy efficient glazing on the facility’s windows. SUNY Officials broke ground…\n', NULL, NULL, 1),
('ed33d0c0-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'video', 'SUNY Old Westbury men’s volleyball team member Tyler Nimmons on balancing sports and schoolwork. VIDEO BY: SOPHIA JULIANNE ZELAYA VELÁSQUEZ', 'suny-old-westbury-mens-volleyball-team-member-tyler-nimmons-on-balancing-sports-and-schoolwork-video-by-sophia-julianne-zelaya-velasquez', NULL, '', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'SJ424', NULL, '2025-12-04 13:43:26', 0, '', NULL, NULL, 15),
('ed342c11-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Construction of new Natural Sciences Building frustrating some students, but officials say state-of-the-art facility will be worth it', 'construction-of-new-natural-sciences-building-is-frustrating-some-students-but-officials-say-the-state-of-the-art-facility-will-be-worth-it', NULL, '<p>Construction of SUNY Old Westbury’s new <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/news-events/groundbreaking-celebrates-expansion-improvements-science-facililty\">Natural Sciences Building</a> has brought both excitement and frustration to campus this semester. While the new facility is expected to transform academics on campus, the road to completion has created dust, debris and reduced parking near the construction site.</p>\n<p>The <a href=\"https://www.setty.com/portfolio-of-experience/suny-old-westbury-natural-science-building\">new facility</a> promises modern laboratories, expanded research spaces, and updated classrooms for the School of Arts and Sciences.</p>\n<p>Jolline Andre, one of many commuter students here at SUNY Old Westbury, says these conditions have made navigating campus a daily challenge.</p>\n<p>“Sometimes when I am walking from the Student Union parking lot to my classes, I can see the dust and construction exhaust in the air, especially when the wind shifts,” she said. “It’s not every minute, but on busy construction days it makes breathing feel tighter, and it does worry me the effect this has for those on campus.”</p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_11846\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-11846\" style=\"width: 300px\" class=\"wp-caption alignleft\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-small wp-image-11846\" src=\"uploads/Ray-Maggiore-Pic-300x204.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"204\" srcset=\"uploads/Ray-Maggiore-Pic-300x204.jpg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Ray-Maggiore-Pic-600x409.jpg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Ray-Maggiore-Pic-1200x817.jpg 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Ray-Maggiore-Pic-768x523.jpg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Ray-Maggiore-Pic-1536x1046.jpg 1536w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Ray-Maggiore-Pic.jpg 2001w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-11846\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Raymond Maggiore, assistant vice president of capital planning at SUNY Old Westbury. Nov. 19, 2025.<br />PHOTO BY: HENRY M. WILSON</figcaption></figure>\n<p>Raymond Maggiore, the Assistant Vice President of Capital Planning at SUNY Old Westbury, said that the college has implemented measures to ensure safety and limit dust and exhaust exposure.</p>\n<p>“We’re making sure that the heaviest work happens in the early morning hours, to mitigate any disruptions to students and staff on campus,” Maggiore said. “In the area where the construction is taking place, we’re ensuring that the exhaust from the site is centralized to one area, away from the main campus center. With most of the project being completed by the end of 2026, these issues should subside within the next year.”</p>\n<p>Megan Valenti, assistant prof of Biological Sciences at SUNY Old Westbury, said that temporary adjustments have been necessary while the new building is under construction. One of those is moving some of the science offices and classrooms across campus to the Woodlands building 5 and to a temporary building called the Annex.</p>\n<p>“While it’s farther than our original home, the new classrooms and labs being built will offer modern, fully equipped spaces that will greatly enhance student learning and research opportunities once the project is complete,” she said.</p>\n<p>Parking has become another challenge, particularly in the Student Union Parking lot, where several areas of spaces have been moved to make way for new geothermal heating systems for the new facility.</p>\n<p>“Last semester, a majority of the student union lot was closed, but with the other section currently under construction, parking has become a gamble on campus,” said Solaris Yan, another commuter student.</p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a247163f3d53 sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>With a facility that rivals those at private institutions, SUNY Old Westbury will be able to better compete without rising costs for students.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Raymond Maggiore, Assistant Vice President of Capital Planning at SUNY Old Westbury on the new Natural Sciences building</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a247163f3d53 {\n    display: flex;\n    float: right;\n    margin: 30px 0 30px 30px;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247163f3d53 p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a247163f3d53 p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247163f3d53 .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a247163f3d53 p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247163f3d53 .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247163f3d53 .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247163f3d53 .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p>Maggiore said the university is aware of how these changes affect its primarily commuter population and is working to ease the strains for students and staff.</p>\n<p>“We understand the frustrations students are facing, and we’re continuing to explore ways to improve traffic flow and accommodate parking needs while construction is underway,” he said, explaining that the 60 parking spaces currently out of commission will be back in action by the Fall 2026 semester.</p>\n<p>Despite the ongoing disruptions, campus officials like Maggiore say the long term benefits will outweigh the temporary inconveniences. The new Natural Sciences building is designed to support growing STEM enrollment, expand research capacity and modernize SUNY Old Westbury’s academic infrastructure.</p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_11845\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-11845\" style=\"width: 300px\" class=\"wp-caption alignleft\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-small wp-image-11845\" src=\"uploads/NSB-300x174.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"174\" srcset=\"uploads/NSB-300x174.jpg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/NSB-600x348.jpg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/NSB-1200x695.jpg 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/NSB-768x445.jpg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/NSB.jpg 1389w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-11845\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Rendering of the new 70,000-square-foot Natural Sciences building at SUNY Old Westbury, with completion<br />scheduled for late 2026. Courtesy of Setty &amp; Associates</figcaption></figure>\n<p>The new Natural Sciences building, slated to be completed in three phases, will bring state of the art facilities designed to meet the needs of a rapidly expanding STEM community. When finished, the 70,000 square foot complex will feature modern laboratories, interactive classrooms, collaborative research areas and updated faculty offices, all aimed at strengthening hands-on learning and scientific training on campus.</p>\n<p>Maggiore says the building will not only upgrade the college’s infrastructure but also create new opportunities for students across disciplines.</p>\n<p>“This project represents a long term investment in the future of SUNY Old Westbury,” he said. “Our goal is to create an environment where students can learn, innovate, and pursue advanced research in an environment that truly supports them.”</p>\n<p>As the campus continues to navigate dust, noise and parking challenges, officials like Maggiore remain confident that the final result will be worth the wait. By late 2026, the new Natural Sciences building will begin to stand as a centerpiece of SUNY Old Westbury’s academic landscape, a sign of growth, renewed investment and a commitment to preparing students for an increasingly STEM driven future.</p>\n<p>“We’ve been waiting for this monumental change, one that lifts the quality of our education and pushes our STEM programs forward,” Maggiore said. “With a facility that rivals those at private institutions, SUNY Old Westbury will be able to better compete without rising costs for students.”</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'HM898', NULL, '2025-12-05 08:58:10', 0, 'Construction of SUNY Old Westbury’s new Natural Sciences Building has brought both excitement and frustration to campus this semester. While the new facility is expected to transform academics on campus, the road to completion has created dust, debris and reduced parking near the construction site. The new facility promises modern laboratories, expanded research spaces, and…\n', NULL, NULL, 1),
('ed3479bf-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'video', 'You eat WHAT? SUNY Old Westbury college students try weird stuff.  VIDEO BY: FIDA SIDDIQUI', 'you-eat-what-suny-old-westbury-college-students-try-weird-stuff-video-by-fida-siddiqui', NULL, '', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'FS542', NULL, '2025-12-08 09:53:23', 0, '', NULL, NULL, 15),
('ed34d1d9-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Got a zero for supposedly AI-generated content you actually wrote? Me, too.', 'got-a-zero-for-supposedly-ai-generated-content-you-actually-wrote-me-too', NULL, '<p><a href=\"https://www.nasa.gov/what-is-artificial-intelligence/\">Artificial intelligence</a> has become part of <a href=\"https://www.trails.umd.edu/news/detecting-ai-may-be-impossible-thats-a-big-problem-for-teachers?\">education today,</a> whether we like it or not. Students use it the same way people use calculators, spell-check, or even Google, which is to get ideas, fix sentences, or figure out something that we are confused about.</p>\n<p>In a lot of college classrooms, the reaction to AI has gone from curiosity to straight-up panic.</p>\n<p>For example, I turned in an assignment I wrote myself, only to have my professor tell me she thought I used AI. I remember staring at my failing grades in complete confusion. I emailed her and asked her to explain what part seemed “AI-generated,” but weeks went by with no response. My grade is still sitting at a zero for something I actually wrote.</p>\n<p>Another student, Caroline Brucato, told me she went through almost the exact same thing.</p>\n<p>“I worked so hard on that paper,” Brucato said. “When my professor said it looked like AI, I honestly felt sick. I didn’t even know how to defend myself. She told me it was 53% likely written by AI and ‘most likely not written by a human. I just sat there thinking, how am I supposed to argue with a percentage on a screen?”</p>\n<p>And a screenshot, Brucato said, was the only evidence the professor provided.</p>\n<p>“My professor showed me a screenshot like it was solid proof of something I didn’t do,” Brucato said. “I felt guilty before I even opened my mouth.”</p>\n<p>Something more is being shown within these experiences: The real issue isn’t AI, it’s how schools are reacting to it.</p>\n<p>Some professors say students can use AI responsibly, but few agree on what that actually means. Is brainstorming allowed? Is grammar checking allowed? Can you use it to help rewrite a rough paragraph? Every professor has their own rules, and students are sometimes supposed to magically know all of them. All these questions just lead us to be confused.</p>\n<p>On top of that, AI-detection tools are becoming the new lie detector tests — even though research keeps proving they’re unreliable.</p>\n<p>A <a href=\"https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s40979-023-00146-z\">2023 study</a> published in Springer Nature Link found that detectors mislabeled writing as AI 61% of the time, even when it was completely human-written. Another review basically said accurate detection might be “impossible.”</p>\n<p>Being accused of using AI isn’t just annoying. It changes how you write. When it happened to me, I started wondering, am I supposed to just write worse? Should I avoid certain words? Do professors think anything that sounds “smart” has to be AI?</p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_11868\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-11868\" style=\"width: 300px\" class=\"wp-caption alignleft\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"wp-image-11868 size-small\" src=\"uploads/Screenshot-2025-12-08-at-11.39.56-AM-300x213.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"213\" srcset=\"uploads/Screenshot-2025-12-08-at-11.39.56-AM-300x213.png 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/Screenshot-2025-12-08-at-11.39.56-AM.png 584w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-11868\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">A picture of an AI-generated version of the Declaration of Independence determined to be written by a human. SUNY Old Westbury on Dec. 1, 2025. PHOTO BY: DESPINA DRAKOPOULOS</figcaption></figure>\n<p>Brucato said the same thing.</p>\n<p>“I kept second-guessing everything,&#8221; she said, &#8220;I didn’t want my sentences to sound ‘too good,’ because what if they accused me again?”</p>\n<p>A 2023 <a href=\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1477388025000131?\">peer-reviewed study</a> published in Science Direct found that both human reviewers and AI detectors wrongly labeled real, human-written papers as AI-generated. So the technology we’re being judged by isn’t even stable.</p>\n<p>If colleges actually want to handle this new reality, a few things need to change. Teachers could try setting clear rules, talking to students before accusing them, normalizing AI as a tool rather than something evil, and paying attention to the writing process like drafts, peer reviews and reflections that encourage growth.</p>\n<p>What would have been helpful to me would have been a simple conversation or honestly, just a reply. I reached out to my professor asking for more information, anything that could explain why my real work was labeled as AI. It’s been a full month, and I still haven’t heard a single word back.</p>\n<p>If colleges want students to use AI responsibly, communicate honestly, and trust the learning process, then students and educators must work together. Accountability can’t be one-sided. Until that changes, AI isn’t the real issue. How we respond to it is.</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'DD275', NULL, '2025-12-09 10:30:50', 0, 'Artificial intelligence has become part of education today, whether we like it or not. Students use it the same way people use calculators, spell-check, or even Google, which is to get ideas, fix sentences, or figure out something that we are confused about. In a lot of college classrooms, the reaction to AI has gone…\n', NULL, NULL, 6);
