('ed352576-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'podcast', 'Stir It Up!', 'stir-it-up', NULL, '<figure id=\"attachment_11877\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-11877\" style=\"width: 600px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-medium wp-image-11877\" src=\"uploads/NMB-7-India-NMB-Nations-Sq-600x600.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"600\" srcset=\"uploads/NMB-7-India-NMB-Nations-Sq-600x600.jpg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/NMB-7-India-NMB-Nations-Sq-70x70.jpg 70w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/NMB-7-India-NMB-Nations-Sq-768x768.jpg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/NMB-7-India-NMB-Nations-Sq-300x300.jpg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/NMB-7-India-NMB-Nations-Sq.jpg 894w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-11877\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Screenshot</figcaption></figure>\n<h1>This Week on New Media Beat!</h1>\n<audio class=\"wp-audio-shortcode\" id=\"audio-11873-1\" preload=\"none\" style=\"width: 100%;\" controls=\"controls\"><source type=\"audio/mpeg\" src=\"https://newmediabeat.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/NMB-7-Web-2025-11-13-1.mp3?_=1\" /><a href=\"https://newmediabeat.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/NMB-7-Web-2025-11-13-1.mp3\">https://newmediabeat.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/NMB-7-Web-2025-11-13-1.mp3</a></audio>\n<h4></h4>\n<ul>\n<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\n<ul>\n<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\n<ul>\n<li style=\"list-style-type: none;\">\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Australia: Gen-AI Hate on Social?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>India: Less Privacy More AI?</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Estonia: Keeping Russian Disinfo Out!</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Iran: No Free Pass for the Press.</strong></li>\n<li><strong>North Korea: No Free Press!</strong></li>\n<li><strong>China: Censoring Social.</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Saudi Arabia: Managing the Brand.</strong></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.newmediabeat.org/\"><strong>New Media Beat</strong></a> covers media news from around the world. NMB is a production of Media Studies students from <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/\" target=\"_self\" rel=\"noopener\">SUNY @ Old Westbury.</a>   We scour the web for news about about media and journalism.</p>\n<p>NMB is co-produced by Emily Cevallos, Kelvin Zalis, and Jalaal McCoy. Our engineer is Jalaal McCoy.  Our hosts are Kamsi Agu &amp; Marwa Jalili.</p>\n<p>We are streaming live again on <a href=\"http://www.owwrny.org/\">Old Westbury Web Radio</a> Thursdays from 10:15-11:15 AM EST.  Can&#8217;t listen live? Our fall podcasts will be <a href=\"https://newmediabeat.org/?cat=17\">posted</a> for your listening pleasure every Friday afternoon from September through December 9, 2025.</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'NM744', NULL, '2025-11-14 18:07:05', 0, 'This Week on New Media Beat! Australia: Gen-AI Hate on Social? India: Less Privacy More AI? Estonia: Keeping Russian Disinfo Out! Iran: No Free Pass for the Press. North Korea: No Free Press! China: Censoring Social. Saudi Arabia: Managing the Brand. New Media Beat covers media news from around the world. NMB is a production…\n', NULL, NULL, 12),
('ed359e04-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Emmy Award-winning photojournalist Brianne Barry to talk about the art of storytelling at upcoming event', 'emmy-award-winning-photojournalist-brianne-barry-to-talk-about-the-art-of-storytelling-at-upcoming-event', NULL, '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><a href=\"https://muckrack.com/brianne-barry\">Brianne Barry</a> is a SUNY Old Westbury alum as well as an Emmy and Edward R. Murrow Award-winning journalist. When she returns to campus Mon., Feb.9 to speak, she will not be just coming back to talk about her career but to talk about the future of journalism itself. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Barry will have</span> <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">a talk that is focused on multimedia journalism in today’s rapidly evolving media landscape. Drawing from her 13-year career across broadcast, digital, and social platforms, Barry plans to explore the realities of modern journalism.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I’m coming down to talk about multimedia journalism in today’s industry – the pros and cons, the challenges and the successes,” Barry said. “But also journalism as a whole, and why it’s important even if you’re not entering the industry as your job.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Barry’s career has included high-profile moments such as interviewing Hillary Clinton, climbing the George Washington Bridge, and </span><a href=\"https://muckrack.com/brianne-barry\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">reporting</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> from a helicopter, to her present job at Marist University where she works as an adjunct professor. </span></p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a24735f78a06 sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>It challenges you to step outside of your own narrow vision – and that’s essential in journalism. Everyone has bias. The key is identifying it, acknowledging it and challenging it.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Brianne Barry, SUNY Old Westbury alumnus and Emmy Award-winner on how positive exposure to diversity helped shape her as a journalist. </p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a24735f78a06 {\n    display: flex;\n    float: left;\n    margin: 30px 30px 30px 0;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24735f78a06 p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a24735f78a06 p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24735f78a06 .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a24735f78a06 p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24735f78a06 .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24735f78a06 .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24735f78a06 .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">She said the most meaningful moments have not been the flashiest. Instead, they have been quieter, more personal exchanges with people who trusted her enough to share their stories. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“A lot of work I&#8217;ve done centers around voices that are traditionally underrepresented in the media,” Barry said. “When you can see someone’s walls come down and know they trust you to tell their story and that’s when I always felt validated that I was doing the right thing.”</span></p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_11897\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-11897\" style=\"width: 221px\" class=\"wp-caption alignright\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-small wp-image-11897\" src=\"uploads/Bronx-NY-2015-Photo-courtesy-Peter-Gerber.-Barry_Field-1-221x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"221\" height=\"300\" srcset=\"uploads/Bronx-NY-2015-Photo-courtesy-Peter-Gerber.-Barry_Field-1-221x300.jpg 221w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Bronx-NY-2015-Photo-courtesy-Peter-Gerber.-Barry_Field-1-442x600.jpg 442w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Bronx-NY-2015-Photo-courtesy-Peter-Gerber.-Barry_Field-1-885x1200.jpg 885w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Bronx-NY-2015-Photo-courtesy-Peter-Gerber.-Barry_Field-1-768x1041.jpg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Bronx-NY-2015-Photo-courtesy-Peter-Gerber.-Barry_Field-1.jpg 1000w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 221px) 100vw, 221px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-11897\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Brianne Barry filming in Bronx, NY during the early years of her career as a journalist PHOTO BY: PETER GERBER</figcaption></figure>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The emphasis on trust and perspective traces back to her time at SUNY Old Westbury. Barry credits the campus’s diverse student body and classroom discussions with shaping how she approaches storytelling today.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“You’re exposed to so many different perspectives there,” Barry said. “It challenges you to step outside of your own narrow vision – and that’s essential in journalism. Everyone has bias. The key is identifying it, acknowledging it and challenging it.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">During the talk, Barry will also address long-form and investigative storytelling — areas  she is especially passionate about. In a media environment driven by speed and headlines, she believes depth and context matter more than ever. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“So often, the news just scrapes the surface,” Barry said. “There’s always a deeper story. Long-form pieces give you the space to explain what’s really going on instead of just triggering an emotional reaction.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Barry plans to discuss how journalists today balance attention-grabbing formats with meaningful reporting, especially as audiences increasingly consume news through short-form content and algorithm-driven platforms such as social media. Because of that, she said, journalism is more important than ever in helping the public determine what is real. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For students interested in journalism, media, or storytelling of any kind, Barry emphasized that the most important skills are timeless ones: listening, observation, flexibility and practice. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Your skills shouldn&#8217;t be dependent on your tools,” Barry said. “Technology will change, but listening, observing and being open to different perspectives – that’s what will carry you through.” </span></p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_11898\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-11898\" style=\"width: 300px\" class=\"wp-caption alignleft\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-small wp-image-11898\" src=\"uploads/2018-Long-Island-NY-Photo-courtesy-Josh-Robin.-Screenshot_20260202_123401_Instagram-1-300x224.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"224\" srcset=\"uploads/2018-Long-Island-NY-Photo-courtesy-Josh-Robin.-Screenshot_20260202_123401_Instagram-1-300x224.jpg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2018-Long-Island-NY-Photo-courtesy-Josh-Robin.-Screenshot_20260202_123401_Instagram-1-600x447.jpg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2018-Long-Island-NY-Photo-courtesy-Josh-Robin.-Screenshot_20260202_123401_Instagram-1-1200x894.jpg 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2018-Long-Island-NY-Photo-courtesy-Josh-Robin.-Screenshot_20260202_123401_Instagram-1-768x572.jpg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2018-Long-Island-NY-Photo-courtesy-Josh-Robin.-Screenshot_20260202_123401_Instagram-1-1536x1145.jpg 1536w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2018-Long-Island-NY-Photo-courtesy-Josh-Robin.-Screenshot_20260202_123401_Instagram-1.jpg 2001w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-11898\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Brianne Barry, SUNY Old Westbury graduate and Emmy Award winning journalist, films along the Long Island shoreline PHOTO BY: JOSH ROBIN</figcaption></figure>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Ultimately, Barry said she hopes students leave the event feeling less intimidated by journalism and more empowered by it. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Journalism isn’t fancy or unattainable,” Barry said. “It’s created by humans, for humans. And everyone, in some way, is part of it.”</span></p>\n<p><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Media Mentors, Alumni Spotlight series. Brianne Barry: From the Field to the Story. Mon., Feb. 9, 1:30 p.m. in NAB 1100. Light refreshments will be served.</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'DD275', NULL, '2026-02-05 13:07:29', 0, 'Brianne Barry is a SUNY Old Westbury alum as well as an Emmy and Edward R. Murrow Award-winning journalist. When she returns to campus Mon., Feb.9 to speak, she will not be just coming back to talk about her career but to talk about the future of journalism itself.  Barry will have a talk that…\n', NULL, NULL, 10),
('ed35f835-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Back to college at 50, radio personality Allison Roberts is giving the young folks a run for their money', 'allison-roberts-sunyoldwestbury-back-to-college-at-50', NULL, '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">SUNY Old Westbury student Allison Roberts recalls exactly how she felt when she received a call from <a href=\"https://www.ibsradio.org/\">Intercollegiate Broadcasting System</a> telling her she had been nominated for Best On-Air Personality.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“When he called me to tell me that I was nominated, I was shocked,” Roberts said. “I am grateful to just be nominated.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The IBS represents hundreds of college radio stations nationwide, making the recognition a significant milestone for Roberts, she said. The nomination recognizes her work as a host of a radio show on </span><a href=\"https://spinitron.com/WHPC/pl/20181398/Sistah-Chattah\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">90.3 WHPC</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, a radio station where Roberts interviews Black entrepreneurs, creatives, playwrights and community leaders. Award winners will be announced Sat., Feb. 21 at the Sheraton Times Square in New York City. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Her show is called “Sistah Chatta,&#8221; which is designed to uplift Black women through product review and brand opportunities. One of its defining features was a jingle written and recorded by her best friend, who later died from COVID-19. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“She came up with this cool jingle and ran over to my house and sang it, and I was blown away,” Roberts said. “We used to harmonize that song for years.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Many of her guests launched their business during the COVID-19 pandemic in 2020, and the show focuses on sharing their journeys and experiences. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I interview people who are doing things in the Black community — people who are starting businesses and making new waves,” Roberts said. </span></p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a247296e83e9 sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>I had to start from the beginning. I was on the air at one o’clock in the morning, three o’clock in the morning, five o’clock in the morning – when nobody was even listening.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Alison Roberts on the early days of her radio career</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a247296e83e9 {\n    display: flex;\n    float: left;\n    margin: 30px 30px 30px 0;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247296e83e9 p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a247296e83e9 p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247296e83e9 .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a247296e83e9 p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247296e83e9 .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247296e83e9 .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247296e83e9 .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Her program blends interviews with music, asking guests to share songs that inspire them. She also incorporates giveaways and listener engagement segments. Over time, the audience has grown beyond Long Island. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I have had people from Los Angeles applying for my focus group,” Roberts said. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Roberts did not begin her broadcasting career with immediate recognition. After enrolling at Nassau Community College as a marketing major, she was encouraged by a fellow student to explore opportunities in radio. She started with overnight shifts and production work at the school&#8217;s radio station, <a href=\"https://www.ncc.edu/studentlife/whpcradiostation/\">WHPC</a>. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I had to start from the beginning,” Roberts said. “I was on the air at one o’clock in the morning, three o’clock in the morning, five o’clock in the morning – when nobody was even listening.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Around the same time Roberts launched &#8220;Sista Chatta,&#8221; she was navigating additional hardship. Her brother was diagnosed with stage four pancreatic and lung cancer and she was undergoing treatment for breast cancer. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I was dealing with a lot of grief at that time,” Roberts said. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">After more than a year of working early morning hours, she had her own show. Today, her nomination by the <a href=\"https://www.ibsradio.org/\">Intercollegiate Broadcasting System </a>marks a milestone for Roberts, she said. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">On the heels of the success of her radio show, Roberts, now 50 years old, transferred to SUNY Old Westbury for the 2026 spring semester. This, </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">after facing significant personal and health challenges, including surviving stage three breast cancer and coping with the loss of close family members and friends. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I did not want to leave this world feeling like I did not accomplish what I was supposed to do – what I was brought here to do,” Roberts said.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Now at SUNY Old Westbury, Roberts said, she appreciates the campus environment as a nontraditional student. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I feel a little more adult here,” Roberts said. “I really do love the atmosphere here.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Beyond academics and radio, Roberts is a mother of four. </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Still, she manages to balance her coursework, caregiving and family responsibilities while remaining focused on moving forward. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“And I’m grateful,” Roberts said. “I’m just grateful.” </span></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'DD275', NULL, '2026-02-13 09:46:13', 0, 'SUNY Old Westbury student Allison Roberts recalls exactly how she felt when she received a call from Intercollegiate Broadcasting System telling her she had been nominated for Best On-Air Personality. “When he called me to tell me that I was nominated, I was shocked,” Roberts said. “I am grateful to just be nominated.” The IBS…\n', NULL, NULL, 16),
('ed364637-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Filmmaker Byron Hurt talks masculinity, misogyny, gender and homophobia', 'filmmaker-byron-hurt-talks-masculinity-misogyny-gender-and-homophobia', NULL, '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Byron Hurt, documentary filmmaker and SUNY Old Westbury professor, has spent nearly three decades challenging conversations around masculinity, race and power – turning topics that many shy away from into national dialogue. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Now SUNY Old Westbury students will have the opportunity to hear directly from him at two talks on Monday, March 2. The double period events will feature clips from his films and a discussion about how his storytelling has evolved from his 2006 film, </span><a href=\"https://www.pbs.org/independentlens/documentaries/hiphop/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Hip Hop: Beyond Beats and Rhymes </span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">to one of his most recent films, </span><a href=\"https://share.google/EU2Ae5hOWiP0TUbYq\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Hazing (2022).</span></a></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">But Hurt&#8217;s talk is more than a screening. It is a reflection on a career built around asking difficult questions about masculinity, violence, cultural norms and accountability – especially the ones people often avoid.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I decided that I was going to use documentary storytelling to explore masculinity, misogyny, gender and homophobia,” Hurt said. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Hurt did not begin as a trained filmmaker. He graduated from Northeastern University in Boston, Massachusetts with a degree in journalism, not film. His first documentary was created during his senior year of college. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I did not go to film school, so I really didn’t know how to make a film,” Hurt said. “I didn’t know how to structure a story. I didn’t know much about cinematic language. I was just kind of learning as I went along.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">That early uncertainty, he said, shaped his growth. Over time, his approach became more intentional and crafted. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I put a lot of time into thinking about what my film is going to look like, what it’s going to feel like, how it’s going to be structured, and what I want to leave the audience with,” Hurt said. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">His filmmaking was also deeply influenced by the late filmmaker </span><a href=\"https://share.google/LmxJ1TFa8el71HK42\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Marlon Riggs</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, whose work explored race, gender and sexuality. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I often attribute him as being the person who inspired me to become a documentary filmmaker,” Hurt said. “His work transformed me.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Shortly after graduating, Hurt became involved in the </span><a href=\"https://www.mvpstrat.com/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Mentors in Violence Prevention</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> program, a gender violence prevention program founded in 1993 at Northeastern University. That experience helped define the themes that would shape his career.</span></p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a247288dc4aa sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>A lot of people think that my film is a documentary about rap music and hip hop culture. But I beg to differ. I believe the film is really about gender. It’s about masculinity in the larger culture.</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a247288dc4aa {\n    display: flex;\n    float: left;\n    margin: 30px 30px 30px 0;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247288dc4aa p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a247288dc4aa p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247288dc4aa .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a247288dc4aa p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247288dc4aa .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247288dc4aa .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247288dc4aa .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">When Hip-Hop: Beyond Beats and Rhymes premiered at the Sundance Film Festival in 2006, it sparked national discussion. The film examines representations of masculinity within hip hop culture, but Hurt insists it goes beyond music. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“A lot of people think that my film is a documentary about rap music and hip hop culture,” Hurt said. “But I beg to differ. I believe the film is really about gender. It’s about masculinity in the larger culture.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Nearly two decades later, Hurt believes the film continues to resonate for a simple reason. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“The issues are still relevant,” Hurt said. “They still exist.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In the film, Hurt critiques how Hip Hop and broader American culture often show masculinity with dominance, aggression and emotional suppression. Rather than condemning the genre itself, he challenges audiences to reconsider how narrow definitions of manhood can contribute to violence and gender inequality. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">That ongoing relevance is one reason the film remains screened on college campuses across the country. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Hurt’s 2022 documentary, </span><a href=\"https://share.google/EU2Ae5hOWiP0TUbYq\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Hazing,</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> marked one of the most personal projects of his career. The film examines hazing culture in colleges, including within the Black Greek-letter organizations – communities Hurt himself has been part of. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Raising all of the money to get it done was probably the biggest challenge,” Hurt said, noting it was the largest budget he had worked with. </span></p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_11924\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-11924\" style=\"width: 300px\" class=\"wp-caption alignright\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-small wp-image-11924\" src=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Byron-Director-Shot-2-300x169.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"169\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Byron-Director-Shot-2-300x169.jpeg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Byron-Director-Shot-2-600x338.jpeg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Byron-Director-Shot-2.jpeg 640w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-11924\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Documentary filmmaker Byron Hurt works behind the camera during production as part of his decades-long career in socially-engaged storytelling. Photo courtesy of Byron Hurt.</figcaption></figure>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">But funding was not the only obstacle. Addressing his own fraternity experience publicly required courage. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“It took a lot of courage for me to make the film,” Hurt said. “I still have close relationships with many of my fraternity brothers, and I talk about my own involvement in hazing.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">At the time of the film’s release, openly discussing hazing within the Black Greek organizations was widely considered taboo. In Hazing, Hurt reflects on his own pledging experience and examines some initiation traditions, while framed as bonding, can cause physical and emotional harm. The film does not condemn fraternities as a whole, but questions the culture of silence that can allow dangerous practices to continue.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I choose stories that I feel have not been adequately addressed,” Hurt said. “I want my films to make a difference. I want my films to make an impact.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Throughout his career, one of Hurt&#8217;s most consistent audiences has been college students. He has screened his films at hundreds of campuses nationwide, engaging in discussion that extends beyond the screen. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I’ve screened my work at hundreds and hundreds of colleges across the country,” Hurt said. “That’s where incredible civic dialogue is taking place.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">He values being challenged by students and hearing their perspectives. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“To have that kind of engagement with students — to hear their questions, to hear what they’re thinking about — is incredibly fulfilling,” Hurt said. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For Hurt, storytelling and confronting difficult topics are inseparable. He believes stories have the power to move audiences in ways statistics and lectures cannot.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Storytelling is extremely powerful,” Hurt said. When you create a story, whether it’s your own or someone else’s — you’re giving people permission to share a piece of themselves. And by doing that, people grow — just get out there and start telling stories.”</span></p>\n<p><em><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Byron Hurt talk and film retrospective. Monday, March 2 from 2:30 p.m. – 4:20 p.m. and again at 4:30 p.m. – 6 p.m. in the </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Duane L. Jones Recital Hall</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> in the Campus Center. The event is free and open to the public. </span></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'DD275', NULL, '2026-02-18 07:28:43', 0, 'Byron Hurt, documentary filmmaker and SUNY Old Westbury professor, has spent nearly three decades challenging conversations around masculinity, race and power – turning topics that many shy away from into national dialogue.  Now SUNY Old Westbury students will have the opportunity to hear directly from him at two talks on Monday, March 2. The double…\n', NULL, NULL, 10),
('ed36ac45-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Student Research Day is coming! Are you ready?', 'student-research-day-is-coming-are-you-ready', NULL, '<p>The spirit of intellectual progress will fill <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/\">SUNY Old Westbury</a> this April as classrooms turn into galleries and lecture halls transform into laboratories of imagination. For one day, the campus will trade ordinary schedules for discovery, debate and artistic expression.</p>\n<p>That day is <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/division/office-academic-affairs/student-research-day\">Student Research Day</a>, returning on April 16, 2026, as an annual celebration of academic and creative excellence. The event, under the <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/ow-steam-program\">OW STEAM program</a>, gathers students, faculty, and staff to share research, showcase innovation, and highlight the spirit of curiosity that defines the Old Westbury experience.</p>\n<p>“Most of the time in universities, we’re in our little silos,” said associate professor of chemistry and physics and organizer of the event Matthew Lippert. “Physics students are doing physics research, biology students are doing biology. Research Day breaks those walls down so we can hear about all the cool stuff students are doing across campus.”</p>\n<p>Student Research Day isn’t just an academic fair; it’s a campus-wide showcase that reflects the university’s commitment to hands-on learning, faculty mentorship and student achievement.</p>\n<p>Sponsored by the <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/school-arts-and-sciences\">School of Arts and Sciences</a>, <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/school-education\">School of Education</a>, and the <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/school-business\">School of Business</a>, the event encourages students to present their work in a professional setting while connecting with peers and mentors across disciplines.</p>\n<p>From scientific experiments and social science surveys to multimedia projects, art installations, and performances, the day will feature a wide range of presentations. The students will assume control of the classrooms, providing insight into the ongoing student research activities at Old Westbury.</p>\n<p>Faculty mentors play an essential role by guiding and approving student projects, ensuring the event maintains high academic standards. Many students view the opportunity to share their research publicly as both a professional milestone and a valued experience.</p>\n<p>The event is free and open to the entire Old Westbury community, with activities planned across multiple campus venues. Attendees can walk through the classrooms and public halls to view presentations throughout the day. Any student that wishes to apply can do so through an online application, and they will be available for the spring semester.</p>\n<p>“We’re really making a big effort this year to reach out to departments that are maybe not as well represented, like Education, Business, English, and Visual Arts,” said Lippert.</p>\n<p>The theme of this year’s Research Day is ‘Bridging The Divide.’ The theme calls attention to the opportunity to come together as people through shared research.</p>\n<p>“There are many things that divide us… in the country and even in the university,&#8221; said Lippert. &#8220;The goal of this year’s theme is to bring people together and get them talking across disciplines.”</p>\n<p>The April 2026 showcase is expected to feature dozens of student presenters and faculty mentors. Planning is already underway to make the event a highlight of the spring semester. All students are encouraged to participate and attend.</p>\n<p><em>Student Research Day. April 16, 2026. Displays at designated areas throughout campus. Admission is free and open to the public.</em></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'MA394', NULL, '2026-04-07 08:00:01', 0, 'The spirit of intellectual progress will fill SUNY Old Westbury this April as classrooms turn into galleries and lecture halls transform into laboratories of imagination. For one day, the campus will trade ordinary schedules for discovery, debate and artistic expression. That day is Student Research Day, returning on April 16, 2026, as an annual celebration…\n', NULL, NULL, 1),
('ed371a72-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', '“In the Summers” film screening and Q&A with director Alessandra Lacorazza', 'in-the-summers-film-screening-and-qa-with-director-alessandra-lacorazza', NULL, '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">SUNY Old Westbury’s Spring 2026 programming continues with a special screening on March 2 of “In the Summers” followed on March 4 by a question and answer session with film director</span><a href=\"https://alessandra-lacorazza.com/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Alessandra Lacorazza</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. The award-winning film is an intimate portrait of family, memory and identity. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The film, which won the</span><a href=\"https://www.company3.com/in-the-summers-reigns-at-sundance-2024/#:~:text=The%2040th%20Sundance%20Film%20Festival,outstanding%20contributions%20to%20this%20film!\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> U.S. Dramatic Grand Jury prize</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> at the</span><a href=\"https://festival.sundance.org/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Sundance Film Festival,</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> follows two sisters navigating their evolving relationship with their father through a series of summer visits over the years. Told in fragments, the story captures how memory, distance and emotional growth reshape how children come to understand their parents the older they get. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a24735ea0d21 sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>I wanted to be able to show that side of Latin fatherhood — something that was complex and beautiful, but also did not shy away from the hard parts.</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a24735ea0d21 {\n    display: flex;\n    float: left;\n    margin: 30px 30px 30px 0;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24735ea0d21 p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a24735ea0d21 p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24735ea0d21 .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a24735ea0d21 p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24735ea0d21 .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24735ea0d21 .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24735ea0d21 .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\nFor Lacorazza, the story began with a desire to see more honest representation on the screen. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I think, growing up in the United States, I wanted a more varied representation of Latins and queers,” Lacorazza said. “I wanted something that was a little bit more true to my life.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Rather than framing the father as simply good or bad, the film leans into emotional complexity. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I had a very complicated relationship with my father, but he is one of the most beautiful human beings I ever met,” Lacorazza said. “I wanted to be able to show that side of Latin fatherhood — something that was complex and beautiful, but also did not shy away from the hard parts.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The film’s structure – moving through summers instead of a continuous timeline – was one of the first ideas she developed. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“After my dad had died, my sister and I were just around a dinner table going through a timeline of our lives with our father,” Lacorazza said. “It ended up being in these fragments through time because we didn’t really talk to him outside of the summers we spent with him.&#8221;</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">That fragmentation, she explained, became a way of building a portrait of someone through emotional shifts felt years apart. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The desert setting also carries symbolic meaning. Though Lacorazza did not grow up in Las Cruces, the landscape blends elements from different parts of her upbringing. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I see them as these prickly flowers that grow in barren land,” Lacorazza said. “I thought that was an apt metaphor for them.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The wide, open desert becomes more than just a backdrop. It mirrors the emotional  isolation between the characters while also highlighting their resilience – showing how growth can happen even in difficult environments. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The film has received national attention not only for its storytelling but also for its creative choices, including the decision in its original release not to subtitle certain Spanish dialogues – a choice that has sparked discussion among audiences. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“That always provides an interesting conversation around my decisions for that,” Lacorazza said. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">By leaving portions untranslated, the film challenges the viewers to sit with the moments of uncertainty and linguistic distance. This shows an experience that reflects how language and belonging shape identity within immigrant and bilingual families. </span></p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_11941\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-11941\" style=\"width: 300px\" class=\"wp-caption alignright\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-small wp-image-11941\" src=\"uploads/CarmensBarBTS-1-300x203.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"203\" srcset=\"uploads/CarmensBarBTS-1-300x203.jpg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/CarmensBarBTS-1-600x405.jpg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/CarmensBarBTS-1-1200x811.jpg 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/CarmensBarBTS-1-768x519.jpg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/CarmensBarBTS-1-1536x1038.jpg 1536w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/CarmensBarBTS-1.jpg 1779w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-11941\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Director Alessandra Lacorazza (right) speaks with a young cast member between takes on the set of In the Summers. PHOTO BY: RYAN ROBSON</figcaption></figure>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For students attending the March 2 screening, the conversation will not end with just the credit rolls. Lacorazza will return for a live question and answer session on Wednesday, March 4, giving students the opportunity to ask questions about the film’s structure, symbolism and personal inspiration. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I love Q&amp;As and I love talking to people about the film,” Lacorazza said. “I find college students to be really good watchers of films and always come with really interesting questions and perspectives.&#8221;</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As students leave the room, Lacorazza hopes one idea lingers. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“The complexity of our relationships with our parents and how hard that is,” she said. “It’s an ever-evolving process that, at every stage of your life, you’re going to be reflecting on.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For Lacorazza, the film is less about answers and more about understanding. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“When someone dies, your relationship with them sort of continues, but it becomes one-sided,” she said. “There was a lot to understand about his version of events that happened after he died.” </span></p>\n<p><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“In the Summers” film screening. Mon., March 2 at 2:40 p.m. at the Duane L. Jones Recital Hall in NAB211. Free and open to all students. </span></i></p>\n<p><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Question and answer with “In the Summers” director Alessandra Lacorazza. Wed., March 4 at 2:40 p.m. Duane L. Jones Recital Hall in in NAB2111. Free and open to all students.</span></i></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'DD275', NULL, '2026-02-25 10:37:22', 0, 'SUNY Old Westbury’s Spring 2026 programming continues with a special screening on March 2 of “In the Summers” followed on March 4 by a question and answer session with film director Alessandra Lacorazza. The award-winning film is an intimate portrait of family, memory and identity.  The film, which won the U.S. Dramatic Grand Jury prize…\n', NULL, NULL, 10),
('ed379b24-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'PHOTO GALLERY: Fun and frustration on the Hicksville shuttle bus', 'photo-gallery-fun-and-frustration-on-the-hicksville-shuttle-bus', NULL, '<snsgallery data-photo-ids=\"11949,11950,11952,11953,11954,11951,11955,11956,11957,11958\"></snsgallery>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'CJ673', NULL, '2026-02-27 09:43:11', 0, '', NULL, NULL, 13);
INSERT INTO `content` (`id`, `type`, `title`, `slug`, `description`, `content`, `url`, `approval_status`, `author_id`, `editor_id`, `created_at`, `is_featured`, `excerpt`, `video_url`, `featured_image`, `category_id`) VALUES
('ed37e784-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'SUNY Old Westbury ranks on Newsweek list: America’s Best Colleges for Women 2026', 'suny-old-westbury-ranks-on-newsweek-list-americas-best-colleges-for-women-2026', NULL, '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">SUNY Old Westbury has been named to Newsweek’s and Gender Fair’s inaugural </span><a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/news-events/suny-old-westbury-recognized-americas-best-colleges-women-2026\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“America’s Best Colleges for Women 2026”</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> list, ranking number 143 and landing in the top 150 out of more than 1,200 colleges and universities nationwide. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“It’s a confirmation of our values,” said SUNY Old Westbury President Timothy E. Sams, who framed the recognition as a public confirmation of values the campus has emphasized since its founding.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">He said that success, equity, inclusion and social justice are central to the institution&#8217;s identity. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Women are expected to be central to the life of the university,” Sams said. “Women lead at our university.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The recognition places SUNY Old Westbury in a broader national conversation about gender equity in higher education. Women now make up the majority of college students nationwide, yet representation in leadership roles and access to equitable opportunities vary significantly by institution. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Founded nearly 60 years ago on principles of expanding educational opportunity, SUNY Old Westbury has long positioned itself as an institution committed to removing barriers and fostering transformational education. Sams said the ranking reinforces that identity. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“When we open our doors, everybody should feel like they belong and they matter,” he said. And everybody should leave empowered to own their future.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For student Nisa Santos, the ranking didn’t feel like a surprise – it felt like something she could point to on any normal day. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“It definitely fits,” Santos said. “There’s a lot of women in this school… it’s a very safe place for women in general… and a lot of clubs are run by women.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">To her, the recognition reflects something visible during Common Hour in the Campus Center, in classrooms, and in student organizations: women showing up, leading and shaping campus culture. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“There’s a lot of help,” Santos said. “A lot of places where women can go and just feel safe.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">That day-to-day experience is exactly what the list claims to measure. The </span><a href=\"https://rankings.newsweek.com/americas-best-colleges-for-women-2026\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Newsweek and Gender Fair </span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">rankings are built from federal datasets including the</span><a href=\"https://nces.ed.gov/ipeds/use-the-data\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Integrated Postsecondary Education Data System</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and the Campus Safety and Security Database. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Colleges are evaluated across four categories: leadership, pay and policies, safety and opportunity.SUNY Old Westbury posted online that the ranking draws from the </span><a href=\"https://unglobalcompact.org/take-action/action/womens-principles\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">UN Women and UN Global Compact</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> “women’s empowerment principles.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">But beyond metrics and statistics, students say the recognition feels personal. </span></p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a2471625ffa8 sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>“t’s just a place to empower women and include LGBTQ. It doesn&#8217;t matter what race you are or what your sexuality is – you&#8217;ll feel safe over there.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Nisa Santos, SUNY Old Westbury student </p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471625ffa8 {\n    display: flex;\n    float: right;\n    margin: 30px 0 30px 30px;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471625ffa8 p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471625ffa8 p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471625ffa8 .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a2471625ffa8 p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471625ffa8 .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471625ffa8 .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471625ffa8 .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Santos said resources that meet students where they are – including free menstrual products and supportive health services.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“The nurses… they really help and they make sure that what you’re feeling isn’t … shying you away,” Santos said. ‘I’ve been here for about two and a half years and I&#8217;ve never dealt with anything… negative… I just feel very safe at this school.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">She also highlighted the Women’s, Gender and Sexuality Studies center as a space that fosters empowerment and inclusion. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“It’s just a place to empower women and include LGBTQ,” Santos said. “It doesn&#8217;t matter what race you are or what your sexuality is – you&#8217;ll feel safe over there.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Sams, the president of SUNY Old Westbury, connected the recognition directly to leadership culture across campus.From his cabinet to student organizations, Sams described women occupying prominent leadership roles at multiple levels. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“When I go to clubs and organizations, women are leading them,” Sams said. “They’re stepping up. They’re not on the sideline about it.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Santos echoed that observation, describing how leadership stands out at a smaller campus. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“You notice it quickly,” Santos said. “It’s easier to find your group here, and a lot of times, women are the ones organizing things or running meetings.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For prospective students considering SUNY Old Westbury, Santos kept her advice simple. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“You’re gonna get your education, you’re gonna be safe and you’re just gonna have a lot of fun,” she said. “You should definitely choose Old Westbury.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Faculty perspectives brought both pride and reflection. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Sociology professor Jillian Crocker said her initial reaction to the designation was curiosity about how the ranking defined “best,” but she also emphasized that SUNY Old Westbury has invested for decades in creating academic spaces. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“As a sociologist, I always wonder about the measures,” Crocker said. “But certainly, this is something the university should be proud of.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Crocker described the recognition as reflective of long-standing efforts to support students across demographic groups, particularly women and gender-diverse students. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“We have faculty who are invested in students being successful,” Crocker said. “Especially those who might be overlooked in other contexts.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">She pointed to mentorship, inclusive classroom practices, and leadership development opportunities across campus – including WGSS – as key components of that environment. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Students are able to pursue internships, volunteer opportunities, and develop the skills to share their passions,” Crocker said. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">At the same time, Crocker emphasized that continued recognition requires continued investment. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“If we are to maintain the standard that allowed us to achieve this recognition, then we need to continue to invest in the people and initiatives that made it possible,” Crocker said. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">That investment, she noted, includes faculty, expertise, staff support and financial resources to sustain programming and mentorship. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">At SUNY Old Westbury, students say what makes the difference isn’t just representation — it is atmosphere. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“It just feels supportive,” Santos said. “You don’t feel judged. You don’t feel out of place.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For her, the ranking is not just a number. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“It just makes sense,” Santos said. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">And on a campus where women visibly lead discussions, clubs, classrooms and conversations – that lived experience may be the strongest measure of all. </span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'DD275', NULL, '2026-03-02 16:19:44', 0, 'SUNY Old Westbury has been named to Newsweek’s and Gender Fair’s inaugural “America’s Best Colleges for Women 2026” list, ranking number 143 and landing in the top 150 out of more than 1,200 colleges and universities nationwide.  “It’s a confirmation of our values,” said SUNY Old Westbury President Timothy E. Sams, who framed the recognition…\n', NULL, NULL, 1),
('ed386824-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'PHOTO GALLERY: A day in the life of students at Media Innovation Center', 'photo-gallery-a-day-in-the-life-of-students-at-media-innovation-center', NULL, '<snsgallery data-photo-ids=\"11966,11969,11970,11971,11976,11973,11977,11975\"></snsgallery>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'RM815', NULL, '2026-03-04 09:32:41', 0, '', NULL, NULL, 13),
('ed38aa33-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Diaper-clad, vodka-chugging internet prankster disrupts class', 'diaper-clad-vodka-chugging-internet-prankster-disrupts-class', NULL, '<div>\n<p class=\"Paragraph SCXW33150509 BCX0\">What started as a discussion on the price of oil in room 1107 at SUNY Old Westbury quickly <a href=\"https://www.instagram.com/reel/DVcTqnYjLUe/?utm_source=ig_web_copy_link&amp;igsh=MzRlODBiNWFlZA==\">descended into madness</a> after internet prankster Tommy Maloney, otherwise known as bigtommym, barged into a class on Tuesday.</p>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p class=\"Paragraph SCXW33150509 BCX0\">Across Maloney’s chest was written “FREE DIDDY” and all he had on was an adult diaper. After entering the classroom on March 3 with loud music, a bottle of alcohol and a friend videotaping him, Maloney then rubbed baby oil all over himself, proceeding to spray it on the floor.</p>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p class=\"Paragraph SCXW33150509 BCX0\">Maloney then took a drink of Ciroc Apple Vodka, a brand founded by Sean &#8220;Diddy&#8221; Combs, who is currently serving four years in federal prison on sex trafficking charges, and began dancing at the front of the classroom, screaming unintelligible words as he did so.</p>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p class=\"Paragraph SCXW33150509 BCX0\">“It got musty,” said student Sarah Padovani, who witnessed the spectacle. “It was very gross.”</p>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p class=\"Paragraph SCXW33150509 BCX0\">After covering the classroom floor in baby oil, Maloney began “rolling around on the ground like a seal,” Padovani said.</p>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p class=\"Paragraph SCXW33150509 BCX0\">Once Maloney was done with his act, he gathered his belongings and prepared to leave the class, telling the teacher “It’s a freak-off . . . you know Diddy?”</p>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p class=\"Paragraph SCXW33150509 BCX0\">This is not Maloney&#8217;s first stunt in public, nor in a school.</p>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p class=\"Paragraph SCXW33150509 BCX0\">On his social media page, Maloney uploads videos entirely focused on going into public spaces and disrupting classrooms and bars under the guise of pranks.</p>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p class=\"Paragraph SCXW33150509 BCX0\">The video at SUNY Old Westbury was posted with the caption, “Should we start a series of trying to get banned from every college in the (American flag emoji)?”</p>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p class=\"Paragraph SCXW33150509 BCX0\">Andrew Curotto, a student at SUNY Old Westbury and former bartender, said he knew Maloney before this incident.</p>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p class=\"Paragraph SCXW33150509 BCX0\">“Back then he wasn’t on Instagram yet…he would always get kicked out of bars,” Curotto said. “He would slam together two cans of beer and make a mess. He would buy a bunch of shots, pay for them and throw them into the crowd so people would get soaked with liquor.”</p>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p class=\"Paragraph SCXW33150509 BCX0\">The day after Maloney’s stunt at SUNY Old Westbury, he wreaked havoc on another college campus.</p>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p class=\"Paragraph SCXW33150509 BCX0\">In this latest video, Maloney enters a classroom with a safety vest and phone, telling the teacher of the class that he had gotten approval from administration to move the class from the room.</p>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p class=\"Paragraph SCXW33150509 BCX0\">When the classroom did not move, he revealed it was a prank and gave them free pizza. This, after plugging a gambling website.</p>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p class=\"Paragraph SCXW33150509 BCX0\">While some may find Maloney&#8217;s acts funny, Padovani said she was less than amused.</p>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p class=\"Paragraph SCXW33150509 BCX0\">“I felt a little bit concerned because I thought: Did he escape from the hospital?” said Padovani. “Did he have a gun?”</p>\n</div>\n<div>\n<p class=\"Paragraph SCXW33150509 BCX0\">University Police did not immediately responded to a request for comment.</p>\n</div>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'AB347', NULL, '2026-03-06 08:00:38', 0, 'What started as a discussion on the price of oil in room 1107 at SUNY Old Westbury quickly descended into madness after internet prankster Tommy Maloney, otherwise known as bigtommym, barged into a class on Tuesday. Across Maloney’s chest was written “FREE DIDDY” and all he had on was an adult diaper. After entering the…\n', NULL, NULL, 1),
('ed38ef0c-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'PHOTO GALLERY: Students step up to support New York Blood Center', 'photo-gallery-students-step-up-to-support-new-york-blood-center', NULL, '<snsgallery data-photo-ids=\"11993,11990,11987,11988,11994,11989\"></snsgallery>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'MM948', NULL, '2026-03-10 12:48:59', 0, '', NULL, NULL, 13),
('ed393f9d-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Muslim students reflect on faith, discipline and community during Ramadan', 'muslim-students-reflect-on-faith-discipline-and-community-during-ramadan', NULL, '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As the holy month of Ramadan draws to a close, Muslim students at SUNY Old Westbury are balancing academics, daily routines and spiritual commitments while observing one of the most important periods in the Islamic calendar. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Ramadan is the ninth month of the Islamic Lunar calendar and is observed by Muslims around the world through fasting, prayer, charity and reflection. Because the Islamic calendar follows the moon’s cycle, the start of Ramadan depends on the sighting of the crescent moon and shifts slightly earlier each year in the Gregorian calendar. This year, Ramadan runs from about Feb. 17 to about March 18. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">During the month, Muslims fast daily from dawn until sunset, abstaining from food and drink while focusing on spiritual growth and discipline. Fasting is one of the Five Pillars of Islam, the core practices that guide Muslim faith and daily life. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For many Muslim students, Ramadan is not only a religious obligation but also a meaningful time for reflection and self-improvement. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“It’s one of the pillars of Islam,” said Keya Farruqui, a student observing Ramadan this year. “During this month, you try to control yourself, pray more, help others and give to people who are in need.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Students observing Ramadan begin their days early. Before sunrise, Muslims eat a pre-fast meal called <em>suhoor</em>, which provides energy for the day ahead. After sunset, they break their fast during a meal called <em>iftar</em>, traditionally starting with water and dates. </span></p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a24711488c70 sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>It’s a special month. You feel grateful to be alive and to have another chance to do good things.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; SUNY Old Westbury student Keya Farruqui on celebrating Ramadan</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a24711488c70 {\n    display: flex;\n    float: right;\n    margin: 30px 0 30px 30px;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24711488c70 p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a24711488c70 p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24711488c70 .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a24711488c70 p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24711488c70 .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24711488c70 .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24711488c70 .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Farruqui said the routine can be challenging, especially while managing school.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I usually break my fast with water and dates and then eat dinner,” Farruqui said. “It’s not always traditional food here, but it’s still meaningful.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Despite the challenges, she says Ramadan remains a joyful time. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“It’s a special month,” Farruqui said. “You feel grateful to be alive and to have another chance to do good things.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For Noora G. Almardahi, a student at SUNY Old Westbury, Ramadan represents an opportunity for personal renewal. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Ramadan feels like a time where you can start over,” Almardahi said. “You can set goals for yourself and build better habits.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">During the month, Muslims are encouraged to avoid negative behaviors such as gossiping or arguing and instead focus on discipline and spiritual reflection. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“You’re fasting from dawn to sunset,” Almardahi said. “You’re not eating or drinking, but it is also about controlling yourself and becoming a better person — it is really about discipline.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For college students, the challenge comes from balancing that discipline with everyday responsibilities. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“You’re managing school, commuting and classes while you’re hungry and thirsty,” Almardahi said. “Sometimes I&#8217;ll have to break my fast while I am on the way home.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Many Muslims carry dates with them so they can break their fast at the exact time sunset occurs. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“The time is very specific,” Almardahi explained. “You break your fast right when the time comes, even if you’re on the bus.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">A typical day for Muslim</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">s, during Ramadan begins well before the sun rises. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I wake up around 4:30 in the morning to eat before the fast starts,” Almardahi said. “Then I pray, commute to school, go to class, and manage everything during the day without food or water.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Despite the physical difficulty, the moment of breaking the fast brings a sense of relief and reflection.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Physically, drinking water feels so refreshing,” Almardahi said. “Emotionally, it feels good knowing you completed another day and that you are lucky enough to experience another Ramadan.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Family and community are also central to the Ramadan experience. Many families cook and prepare meals together each evening before breaking fast. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“My family does everything together,” she said. “We cook together, set the table together and break out fast together.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For students living away from family, that sense of community can be harder to maintain. Some turn to the university’s </span><a href=\"https://oldwestbury.campuslabs.com/engage/organization/msa\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Muslim Student Association (MSA)</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, which hosts iftar gatherings where students can break their fast together. </span></p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a24711489417 sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>I think that’s really sweet. It shows that the school is thinking about Muslim students.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; SUNY Old Westbury student Noora G. Almardahi on the fact the university offers Ramadan meals</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a24711489417 {\n    display: flex;\n    float: left;\n    margin: 30px 30px 30px 0;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24711489417 p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a24711489417 p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24711489417 .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a24711489417 p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24711489417 .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24711489417 .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24711489417 .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The campus dining hall provides Ramadan meal accommodations for students observing the fast. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I think that’s really sweet,” Almardahi said. “It shows that the school is thinking about Muslim students.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Both students emphasized that many people on campus are curious and supportive when learning about Ramadan. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I think people should ask questions,” Almardahi said. “As long as you’re respectful, curiosity is a good thing.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">She also noted that non-Muslim students should not feel uncomfortable eating around those who are fasting. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“You don’t have to feel bad for eating in front of us,” she said. “We chose to fast.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For Farruqui, the deeper purpose of Ramadan lies in reflection and spiritual growth.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“It is about prayer, helping others and being part of the community,” Farruqui said. “It brings happiness.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As Muslim students continue observing Ramadan this month, their experiences highlight the balance between faith, discipline and daily life on campus–while offering an opportunity for the broader university community to learn more about the traditions that shape their peers’ lives. </span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'DD275', NULL, '2026-03-12 15:10:55', 0, 'As the holy month of Ramadan draws to a close, Muslim students at SUNY Old Westbury are balancing academics, daily routines and spiritual commitments while observing one of the most important periods in the Islamic calendar.  Ramadan is the ninth month of the Islamic Lunar calendar and is observed by Muslims around the world through…\n', NULL, NULL, 1),
('ed39a204-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Bald for a cause: community rallies to support childhood cancer research', 'bald-for-a-cause-community-rallies-to-support-childhood-cancer-research', NULL, '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Community members, local officials, and SUNY Old Westbury students will come together on Sunday, March 22 for the 16th annual </span><a href=\"https://www.stbaldricks.org/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">St. Baldrick’s</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> head-shaving fundraiser at The Downtown Café in Glen Cove. The event is dedicated to raising awareness and funds for childhood cancer research.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The event, scheduled to begin at 1 p.m. at </span><a href=\"https://downtowncafegc.com/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Downtown Café</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> on School Street, is part of the nationwide </span><a href=\"https://www.stbaldricks.org/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">St. Baldrick’s Foundation</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> initiative, which supports research and treatment for pediatric cancers. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Throughout the day, </span><a href=\"https://www.owwrny.org/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Old Westbury Web Radio – OWWR</span></a> <a href=\"https://www.owwrny.org/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">–</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> will broadcast live music and coverage from noon to 5 p.m., while also livestreaming a video of the event so supporters can watch from anywhere. The broadcast often includes appearances by local leaders, firefighters and police officers who come to show their support.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a247112d3107 sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>For kids dealing with such a horrible disease, seeing adults shave their heads for them is probably a really bright light for them.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Angelina Zavala, SUNY Old Westbury student and production director at OWWR</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a247112d3107 {\n    display: flex;\n    float: left;\n    margin: 30px 30px 30px 0;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247112d3107 p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a247112d3107 p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247112d3107 .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a247112d3107 p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247112d3107 .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247112d3107 .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247112d3107 .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For Angelina Zavala, a SUNY Old Westbury student and production director at OWWR, seeing volunteers shave their heads for the cause sends a strong message of solidarity to children battling cancer.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I think it’s really powerful,” she said. “For kids dealing with such a horrible disease, seeing adults shave their heads for them is probably a really bright light for them.”</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Joe Manfredi, a lecturer in the Media and Communications department at SUNY Old Westbury and station manager of OWWR, said the Glen Cove event has become a meaningful tradition for the station and its students.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“St. Baldrick’s is a fundraiser held annually really around the nation,” Manfredi said. “People go out and get money in their community or from friends and family, and then they sit in the barber’s chair and get their head shaved in solidarity for a pediatric cancer patient.”</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Glen Cove event has been taking place for nearly two decades, and OWWR has participated for about 14 years. The radio station was originally invited to help promote the fundraiser and has continued its involvement ever since.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“It’s the one day of the year where we’re not doing anything for ourselves,” Manfredi said. “We’re doing something for someone else. It’s community service and real community coming together for real people.”</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The event is hosted by </span><a href=\"https://downtowncafegc.com/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Downtown Café</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and features volunteer barbers from Strong Island Styles, a local hair salon led by Brian Basile. Together with OWWR students and staff, the partnership has helped create a unique community tradition in Glen Cove.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In addition to supporting the St. Baldrick’s Foundation, the event also raises money for the </span><a href=\"https://www.fighthardsmilebig.org/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Nicholas Pedone Foundation</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, which supports families affected by neuroblastoma, a form of childhood cancer.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Students from OWWR take on a variety of roles during the event, from hosting the broadcast to conducting interviews with attendees and operating production equipment. These interviews are often edited into a program called OWWR Spotlight, which highlights community voices and stories from the event.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_12003\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-12003\" style=\"width: 300px\" class=\"wp-caption alignright\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-small wp-image-12003\" src=\"uploads/44089C37-08CB-4EDA-844C-5AB44C5C20CA-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" srcset=\"uploads/44089C37-08CB-4EDA-844C-5AB44C5C20CA-300x225.jpg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/44089C37-08CB-4EDA-844C-5AB44C5C20CA-600x450.jpg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/44089C37-08CB-4EDA-844C-5AB44C5C20CA-1200x900.jpg 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/44089C37-08CB-4EDA-844C-5AB44C5C20CA-768x576.jpg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/44089C37-08CB-4EDA-844C-5AB44C5C20CA-1536x1152.jpg 1536w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/44089C37-08CB-4EDA-844C-5AB44C5C20CA.jpg 2001w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-12003\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Joe Manfredi, station manager of Old Westbury Web Radio and Angelina Zavala, production director for OWWR, in Studio A on the second floor of the Student Union at SUNY Old Westbury, on Mar. 10, 2026. PHOTO BY: KATHERINE CAMPBELL</figcaption></figure>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Zavala participated in the event last year and said it was one of her first major off-campus broadcasting experiences. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“The first thing I learned about the event was that people were going to shave their heads, and that piqued my interest because I wanted to see it,” Zavala said. “But learning that we’re raising money for kids with pediatric cancer made it even more meaningful.”</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Zavala said the event brings together community members and students in a powerful way.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“The street gets packed, and inside The Downtown Café it’s packed too,” she said. “You’re really communicating with everyone and enjoying each other’s presence.”</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As part of her role with OWWR, Zavala helps produce promotional announcements and live reads that encourage listeners to attend or donate.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Because we’re a global internet radio station, people anywhere in the world can hear about St. Baldrick’s,” Zavala said. “Someone in another country might learn about the cause and decide to donate.”</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a247112d3c36 sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>You don’t have to shave your head. You can make a donation, support a participant, or just come down and enjoy the day. It’s a celebration of life.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Joe Manfredi, lecturer in Media and Communications at SUNY Old Westbury and OWWR station manager </p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a247112d3c36 {\n    display: flex;\n    float: left;\n    margin: 30px 30px 30px 0;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247112d3c36 p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a247112d3c36 p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247112d3c36 .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a247112d3c36 p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247112d3c36 .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247112d3c36 .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247112d3c36 .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Both Manfredi and Zavala emphasized that community involvement is essential to keeping charitable events like St. Baldrick’s going.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Younger generations play a really big role,” Zavala said. “If we don’t continue to support these causes, where are they going to be in 20 or 40 years?”</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Manfredi echoed that sentiment, encouraging anyone interested to come out and support the event in whatever way they can.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“You don’t have to shave your head,” he said. “You can make a donation, support a participant, or just come down and enjoy the day. It’s a celebration of life.”</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Attendees can participate by shaving their heads, donating, or supporting participants and learning more about childhood cancer research efforts.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">St. Baldrick’s fundraiser. Sun., Mar. 22 at 1 p.m., The Downtown Café, at 4 School St., Glen Cove. </span></i></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'KC639', NULL, '2026-03-14 09:44:55', 0, 'Community members, local officials, and SUNY Old Westbury students will come together on Sunday, March 22 for the 16th annual St. Baldrick’s head-shaving fundraiser at The Downtown Café in Glen Cove. The event is dedicated to raising awareness and funds for childhood cancer research.  The event, scheduled to begin at 1 p.m. at The Downtown…\n', NULL, NULL, 1),
('ed39f30e-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Beyond Perks and Policies: panel discussion aims to help students set healthy workplace boundaries', 'beyond-perks-and-policies-panel-discussion-aims-to-help-students-set-healthy-workplace-boundaries', NULL, '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">What if the biggest lesson you learn in college isn’t in the classroom, but in how you expect to be treated in your future workplace? </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">That question sits at the heart of Beyond Perks &amp; Policies: Redefining Workplace Culture, an upcoming panel hosted by the <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/division/institutional-advancement/alumni/alumni-association\">Alumni Association at SUNY Old Westbury</a> on March 31 from 6 p.m. to 8 p.m. The event aims to move past surface level benefits like flexible schedules and office perks, instead focusing on the real, everyday experiences that define workplace environments.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For alumnus and media creative Amira Francois, the conversation is deeply personal. A 2025 graduate who played a major role in the campus’s MIC, Media Innovation Center, Francois has had many experiences that shaped her understanding of leadership and responsibility.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Culture is ultimately shaped by behaviors, decisions and the values that are lived in practice,” Francois explained. “The perks and policies of a workplace don’t fully define how employees experience an organization day to day.”</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">During her time at Old Westbury, Francois not only built an impressive portfolio, but also mentored fellow students and interns. That role, she said, came with both rewards and challenges. Taking on heavy responsibilities sometimes became overwhelming — an experience that inspired her to create space for more honest conversations about workplace expectations.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I wanted to bring that conversation outside of the media center,” she said, “so different groups within the Old Westbury community could hear one another out to hear expectations, hear what actually goes on and talk about how to move forward.”</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The panel will explore key themes such as how employees treat one another, what behaviors are truly rewarded and how leadership actions, not just mission statements, shape organizational culture. It will also emphasize concepts like trust, accountability, inclusion and psychological safety.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Unlike traditional career events, “Beyond Perks &amp; Policies” is designed as an open dialogue. Students will have the rare opportunity to engage directly with faculty, administrators, trustees and alumni.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“It’s more like an open conversation,” Francois said. “Students get to talk with higher ups they don’t usually have access to.”</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The timing of the event is especially relevant. As recent graduates navigate a challenging job market, Francois noted that many struggle to find roles in their chosen fields. While she considers herself fortunate to have secured a position within media and communications, she recognizes that not all students have the same outcome.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">That reality makes understanding workplace dynamics even more critical.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“You may go into the real world and experience hardships that you’re not supposed to,” she said. “It’s better to hear about it now rather than experience it later and not know there are ways to protect yourself.”</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a24716f518ce sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>Learn how to set boundaries and recognize when someone is crossing them.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Amira Francois, SUNY Old Westbury alumnus and media creative </p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716f518ce {\n    display: flex;\n    float: left;\n    margin: 30px 30px 30px 0;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716f518ce p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716f518ce p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716f518ce .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a24716f518ce p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716f518ce .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716f518ce .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716f518ce .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Francois emphasized that students, regardless of where they are in their academic journey, can benefit from attending. One key takeaway includes recognizing when workplace expectations become unhealthy.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Know your bandwidth,” she advised. “Learn how to set boundaries and recognize when someone is crossing them.”</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The event also highlights the importance of collaboration, especially in creative industries like film production, where Francois specializes as a cinematographer. On set, where teams often work long hours under pressure, workplace culture can determine the success or failure of a project.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“You can’t run a production properly without a healthy workplace culture,” she said. “If you can’t work collaboratively, it affects everything like time, budget and the final product.”</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Ultimately, Beyond Perks &amp; Policies is about empowerment. It encourages students and faculty alike to rethink what a healthy workplace should look like and to recognize that they have a role in shaping it.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If attendees leave with one message, Francois hopes it’s this: </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Whatever you’re going through in a workplace, you don’t have to go through it alone. There are people who can help and there are ways to protect yourself.”</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As students prepare to enter an unpredictable workforce, the event offers something more valuable than career advice. It offers awareness, community, and the tools to advocate for better environments wherever they go.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Beyond Perks and Policies: Redefining Workplace Culture. Tues., Mar. 31, from 6 p.m. to 8 p.m. Duane L. Jones Recital Hall at SUNY Old Westbury.</span></i></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'KC639', NULL, '2026-03-23 07:31:00', 0, 'What if the biggest lesson you learn in college isn’t in the classroom, but in how you expect to be treated in your future workplace?  That question sits at the heart of Beyond Perks & Policies: Redefining Workplace Culture, an upcoming panel hosted by the Alumni Association at SUNY Old Westbury on March 31 from…\n', NULL, NULL, 10);
INSERT INTO `content` (`id`, `type`, `title`, `slug`, `description`, `content`, `url`, `approval_status`, `author_id`, `editor_id`, `created_at`, `is_featured`, `excerpt`, `video_url`, `featured_image`, `category_id`) VALUES
('ed3a457e-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'New multimedia journalism microcredential offers real-world experience to media majors and students across various disciplines', 'new-multimedia-journalism-microcredential-offers-real-world-experience-to-media-majors-and-students-across-various-disciplines', NULL, '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">SUNY Old Westbury is introducing something new, exciting, and actually useful for students looking to stand out after graduation – a journalism microcredential that focuses on real-world skills, creativity and collaboration. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">According to Wendy Rhodes, an assistant professor in the media and communications department and the faculty advisor to the student news site, The Catalyst, the idea behind the new microcredential is simple: help students become more competitive in today’s job market. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“The job market is wicked competitive,” Rhodes said. “When students leave here, they’re competing against people with strong credentials. We want to make sure our students are as prepared as possible.” </span></p>\n<p style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter wp-image-12266 size-medium\" src=\"uploads/1000069262-450x600.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"450\" height=\"600\" srcset=\"uploads/1000069262-450x600.jpg 450w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/1000069262-900x1200.jpg 900w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/1000069262-768x1024.jpg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/1000069262-1152x1536.jpg 1152w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/1000069262-225x300.jpg 225w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/1000069262.jpg 1501w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 450px) 100vw, 450px\" /></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">While a degree in media and communications is valuable on its own, Rhodes explained that adding a microcredential shows employers something extra. It highlights specialized skills and deeper knowledge in areas like multimedia journalism, giving students an advantage when applying for jobs. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“The goal is really to make students better at their craft and more marketable when they graduate,” Rhodes said. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The program focuses on giving students hands-on experience that reflects what it is actually like to work in the media industry. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“This is going to be the closest thing to what you would experience if you were actually out working in a digital news environment,” Rhodes said. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">A major part of the microcredential is learning how to tell a story. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Students have to know the art of storytelling,” Rhodes said. “How to know when something is timely and newsworthy and make it into an engaging story that people will interact with.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Whether it is written, visual, or audio, Rhodes emphasized, storytelling is at the center of everything. </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Students will also learn how to adhere to Associated Press style – better known as AP Style – writing, which is a critical skill in journalism. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“You have to have that skill when you leave here,” Rhodes said. “Most digital news sites in the country, if not the world, use it.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The program includes three main courses. The first introduces students to the fundamentals of journalism, including how to identify strong stories and write in AP style. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The second allows students to begin producing content for </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Catalyst</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“You’re actually getting news clips that you can use when you apply for jobs,” Rhodes said. “They’re not really looking for a paper you wrote for a class – they want to see something published.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The final course, Digital News Lab, simulates a real newsroom, giving students a full professional experience before they graduate.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Rhodes also stressed that the microcredential isn’t just for journalism majors. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“These are skills that are transferable to anything,” she said. “It doesn’t matter what your major is.” </span></p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'storysidebar sno-6a247110dc033 sno-animate\'>\n                            <h5>Have a special skill? The Catalyst wants you! </h5>\n                </p>\n<p>Work as a volunteer, intern or within a four-credit class. The Catalyst is actively recruiting for the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Social Media Expert</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Videographer</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Audio News Reporter/Podcaster</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-6a247110dc033 {\n	width: 100%;background-color: #c3d6ba;border: 5px solid #006325;box-shadow: -1px 0 2px 0 rgb(0 0 0 / 12%), 1px 0 2px 0 rgb(0 0 0 / 12%), 0 1px 1px 0 rgb(0 0 0 / 24%);width: calc(100% - 40px); margin: 30px auto !important; float: none;	position: relative;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-6a247110dc033 p:not(.infographic-widget-container p), \n.segment-body .sno-6a247110dc033 p:not(.infographic-widget-container p), \n.sno-story-body .sno-6a247110dc033 h5,\n.segment-body .sno-6a247110dc033 h5 {\n    color: #000000;\n}\n</style>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">She added that storytelling is valuable across fields, from law to science, because it helps people communicate complex ideas clearly.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Beyond career benefits, Rhodes hopes students enjoy the experience. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“The goal is not only to learn, but to have fun and collaborate,” Rhodes said. “You might as well have fun while you’re here.”</span></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'DD275', NULL, '2026-05-06 08:30:36', 0, 'SUNY Old Westbury is introducing something new, exciting, and actually useful for students looking to stand out after graduation – a journalism microcredential that focuses on real-world skills, creativity and collaboration.  According to Wendy Rhodes, an assistant professor in the media and communications department and the faculty advisor to the student news site, The Catalyst,…\n', NULL, NULL, 1),
('ed3b1c92-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'John Friedman — SUNY Old Westbury professor and Academy Award-winner — to be honored at April 7 celebration', 'john-friedman-suny-old-westbury-professor-and-academy-award-winner-to-be-honored-at-may-7-celebration', NULL, '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">After nearly two decades at SUNY Old Westbury, John Friedman, an associate professor in the American Studies Department, is preparing to reflect on a career that spans journalism, documentary filmmaking and teaching. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Friedman will be honored at a special event on Tues., April 7, where colleagues and students are invited to help celebrate his career and contributions to the university.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">His career is one defined as much by professional achievement as by a deep commitment to students.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Friedman, who has taught at SUNY Old Westbury for more than 19 years and served as faculty advisor to The Catalyst for much of that time, has witnessed significant changes on campus. While the institution’s core mission of social justice has remained steady, he says the classroom itself has been transformed by technology.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“When I began, the internet really was not used that much,” Friedman said. “Now, with cell phones and artificial intelligence, it’s changed what it means to be a professor.”</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">He points to distractions in the classroom and the rise of AI-generated work as growing challenges. </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“If a student presses a button and a paper comes from a machine, how can anyone learn that way,” he said. “They’re not doing the thinking or the imagination required.”</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_12029\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-12029\" style=\"width: 300px\" class=\"wp-caption alignright\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-small wp-image-12029\" src=\"uploads/IMG_0261-1-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" srcset=\"uploads/IMG_0261-1-300x225.jpg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/IMG_0261-1-600x450.jpg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/IMG_0261-1-1200x900.jpg 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/IMG_0261-1-768x576.jpg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/IMG_0261-1-1536x1152.jpg 1536w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/IMG_0261-1.jpg 2001w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-12029\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">John Friedman, associate professor, journalist and filmmaker, in Manhattan in front of a theater where Hotel Terminus: The Life and Times of Klaus Barbie, the 1988 Academy Award-winning film he produced, was playing. Photo provided by John Friedman.</figcaption></figure>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Despite these shifts, Friedman’s approach to teaching has remained rooted in engagement and dialogue. He describes his method as an “organic theory of teaching,” where discussions often move beyond the syllabus to explore broader cultural and ethical questions.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In addition to teaching, Friedman has built an extensive career as both a journalist and filmmaker. He worked as a war correspondent and a Washington correspondent for The Baltimore Sun and has written for outlets including The New York Times and The Nation magazine. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">His documentary work includes producing “Hotel Terminus: The Life and Times of Klaus Barbie,” which won the Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature, as well as later projects such as “Stealing the Fire” and the recent PBS documentary “Plunderer: The Life and Times of a Nazi Art Thief.”</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Rather than seeing his professional success separate from teaching, Friedman believes the two are closely connected.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“My filmmaking and journalism add to the classroom,” he said. “I can bring different perspectives, and it shows students that you can combine different careers.”</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">At the heart of his teaching philosophy is the idea that education should go beyond job preparation. While he acknowledges that many students are focused on career outcomes, he encourages them to explore a broader range of interests.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“The ultimate purpose of an education is to understand your own abilities and interests,” Friedman said. “It’s about fulfilling yourself.”</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">That philosophy shapes what he hopes students carry with them after leaving his classroom, not just knowledge, but awareness, ethics and a deeper understanding of themselves and others.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I hope they learn about values and the choices they’re going to have to make,” he said. “And that they become more aware of themselves, of their environment, and of the world.”</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Still, Friedman acknowledges that a long career brings challenges and frustrations. In journalism, he struggled with the limits of objectivity and the expectation to present “both sides,” even in the face of clear injustice. In filmmaking, the biggest obstacles have been time and funding, with documentary projects often delayed or constrained by limited resources.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a24716dbeb28 sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>I’d like to be remembered as someone who cared about his students. If I’ve helped them, expanded their horizons, or had a positive effect on their lives, that’s more important than anything.” </p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; John Friedman, SUNY Old Westbury professor and Academy Award-winning documentarian</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716dbeb28 {\n    display: flex;\n    float: none;\n    margin: 30px auto;\n    width: 100%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716dbeb28 p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716dbeb28 p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716dbeb28 .pullquotepic {\n    width: 250px;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a24716dbeb28 p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716dbeb28 .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716dbeb28 .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716dbeb28 .quotebody {\n    width: 100%;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In the classroom, his frustration is more personal.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I can’t reach every student,” he said. “Some are engaged and want to learn, but others are withdrawn, they’re on their phones, they don’t participate. A teacher can only do so much. At some point, it has to come from the student.”</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_12030\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-12030\" style=\"width: 300px\" class=\"wp-caption alignleft\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-small wp-image-12030\" src=\"uploads/John-while-a-war-correspondent-1-300x216.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"216\" srcset=\"uploads/John-while-a-war-correspondent-1-300x216.jpg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/John-while-a-war-correspondent-1.jpg 373w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-12030\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">John Friedman, associate professor, journalist and filmmaker, working as a war correspondent as a journalist. Photo provided by John Friedman.</figcaption></figure>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Reflecting on his career, Friedman says one of the hardest lessons he has learned is that life itself is inherently difficult.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“There are always going to be problems and obstacles,” he said. “The challenge is how we navigate them and how we help other people along the way.”</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Looking ahead, Friedman is not slowing down. He hopes to continue making documentaries, writing, and possibly return to teaching in a limited capacity.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“The main thing is to make more films,” he said.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As he considers how he will be remembered at SUNY Old Westbury, Friedman’s answer returns to the classroom.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I’d like to be remembered as someone who cared about his students,” he said. “If I’ve helped them, expanded their horizons, or had a positive effect on their lives, that’s more important than anything.”</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For Friedman, a career marked by awards and publications ultimately comes down to impact, not just on audiences, but on the students he has taught along the way.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n<p><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">John Friedman — a celebration of his career. Tues, April 7 from 1 p.m. to 3:30 p.m., NAB 1100. Light refreshments. Free admission. </span></i></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'KC639', NULL, '2026-03-26 11:32:24', 0, 'After nearly two decades at SUNY Old Westbury, John Friedman, an associate professor in the American Studies Department, is preparing to reflect on a career that spans journalism, documentary filmmaking and teaching.  Friedman will be honored at a special event on Tues., April 7, where colleagues and students are invited to help celebrate his career…\n', NULL, NULL, 10),
('ed3b5b5c-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Director of Athletics Lenore Walsh on coaching, life lessons and SUNY Old Westbury pride', 'director-of-athletics-lenore-walsh-on-coaching-life-lessons-and-suny-old-westbury-pride', NULL, '<p>Since 2012, <a href=\"https://www.oldwestburypanthers.com/staff-directory/lenore-j-walsh/35\">Lenore Walsh</a> has led athletics at SUNY Old Westbury with a clear philosophy that the student athlete experience comes first. As director of athletics, Walsh oversees a department that balances competition, academics, and personal growth — three priorities she sees not as separate goals but as one unified identity.</p>\n<p>“To me, it’s all one thing, being a student athlete,” Walsh said.</p>\n<p>For Walsh, the most rewarding part of her journey isn’t measured in championship banners, but in commencement caps. She lights up when talking about graduation day, about watching student athletes cross the stage with degrees in hand, knowing they also spent four years playing the sports they love.</p>\n<p>“I love commencement,” she said. “It’s bittersweet. Some of these students have been here for four years, sometimes two. I’ve had transfers tell me they wish they had come here all four years. When you hear that, that’s the most rewarding experience.”</p>\n<p>At SUNY Old Westbury, Walsh takes pride in offering something she believes is rare in today’s college sports landscape: flexibility. Unlike Division I or II programs where athletes often feel locked into a single sport, athletes at SUNY Old Westbury sometimes compete in multiple sports across seasons, like soccer players joining lacrosse or basketball players trying flag football. For Walsh, that freedom reflects a fuller, healthier student athlete experience.</p>\n<p>“Are you really getting your full student athlete experience at those larger athletic programs?” she said. “Here, they’re able to enjoy themselves, smile and still get their education.”</p>\n<p>A former student athlete herself, Walsh understands the pressures firsthand. She remembers juggling practices, games, schoolwork and sometimes jobs. That lived experience shapes how she mentors athletes today. Her advice is simple but powerful: “Do one thing a day.”</p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a24729223737 sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>When you check off one thing, it’s not on your to do list tomorrow,. It makes you feel good about yourself. And you keep moving.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Lenore Walsh, athletic director at SUNY Old Westbury, on ways student athletes can manage heavy workloads</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a24729223737 {\n    display: flex;\n    float: left;\n    margin: 30px 30px 30px 0;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24729223737 p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a24729223737 p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24729223737 .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a24729223737 p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24729223737 .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24729223737 .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24729223737 .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p>When student athletes feel overwhelmed, Walsh encourages them to focus on checking off a single task rather than staring at a list of ten.</p>\n<p>“When you check off one thing, it’s not on your to do list tomorrow,” she explained. “It makes you feel good about yourself. And you keep moving.”</p>\n<p>The lessons learned on the field, like time management, quick decision making and teamwork, translate directly to life beyond college. Walsh describes it as “locker room to board room.” The same instincts used to scan a field for a teammate are the ones used to manage a department or solve an emergency.</p>\n<p>And emergencies are part of the job.</p>\n<p>While athletics may look like “sunshine and rainbows” from the outside, Walsh says. the reality is closer to running a business. On some days, she’s navigating budgets, human resources, contracts, facilities issues, and capital projects. A burst pipe, a blocked road affecting operations, a last minute staffing gap, nothing is ever truly quiet.</p>\n<p>During the COVID-19 pandemic, that reality intensified. Staff turnover left the department short handed. Walsh found herself jumping in wherever needed, helping with game statistics, supporting operations, doing whatever it took to preserve the student athlete experience.</p>\n<p>“Sometimes you just have to jump in to make it happen,” she said. “We got through it because it was important to maintain that experience.”</p>\n<p>Walsh’s leadership is guided by honesty, even when conversations are difficult. She admits disciplining student athletes is her least favorite part of the job. But she views it as a teaching moment, reminding them they represent not just themselves, but the institution.</p>\n<p>“You’re ambassadors to this institution,” she tells them. “You’re representing Old Westbury.”</p>\n<p>The same candor applies to coaches. Recruiting is essential in college athletics, which is enrollment driven, and Walsh makes clear that building and sustaining programs requires consistent effort.</p>\n<p>Still, she is proud of what her department has built. Under her leadership, initiatives like the PAWS, Panther Academics Will Succeed, support struggling but eligible athletes to keep them on track academically. The Athletic Director’s Honor Roll recognizes high achievers, contributing to a department wide GPA above 3.0. She actively promotes NCAA professional development programs, recently sending a men’s basketball player to the NCAA Convention to explore the business side of athletics.</p>\n<p>That commitment to growth extends beyond her own campus. One of the biggest changes Walsh has seen in college athletics is the rise of women in leadership. When she first joined the Skyline Conference, she was one of only two female athletic directors. Today, the majority are women, and the conference also has a female commissioner.</p>\n<p>“It’s really great to see that glass ceiling breaking,” she said.</p>\n<p>At the same time, Walsh acknowledges the evolving landscape of college sports, from the transfer portal to Name, Image, and Likeness, NIL, policies. While these changes create opportunities for athletes, they also introduce new challenges around loyalty, recruiting and stability.</p>\n<p>Looking ahead, Walsh’s vision is ambitious. She hopes to see a turf facility installed at SUNY Old Westbury, a move she believes would transform the department. With turf and improved facilities, the college could potentially add programs like men’s lacrosse, field hockey, or even track and field.</p>\n<p>“We want to keep up with other SUNY schools and be competitive,” she said. “We’re always striving to be better.”</p>\n<p>Even without identical budgets or resources as other institutions, Walsh remains focused on growth. Men’s volleyball has already been added, and flag football will soon transition from a club sport to an NCAA program.</p>\n<p>Through it all, her philosophy remains steady, academics, athletics and development, three prongs, equal in importance. She wants every student-athlete who leaves Old Westbury to say they graduated, improved in their sport, and grew as a person.</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'KC639', NULL, '2026-03-27 10:36:44', 0, 'Since 2012, Lenore Walsh has led athletics at SUNY Old Westbury with a clear philosophy that the student athlete experience comes first. As director of athletics, Walsh oversees a department that balances competition, academics, and personal growth — three priorities she sees not as separate goals but as one unified identity. “To me, it’s all…\n', NULL, NULL, 16),
('ed3bb385-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Karima Ziali, writer and scholar, to host conversation bridging literature, lived experience and cultural dialogue', 'karimaziali', NULL, '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">SUNY Old Westbury will welcome Karima Ziali on March 30 for a talk exploring migration, identity and the power of storytelling. The event, hosted by <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/department/el-conuco-latinx-and-ibero-american-center\">El Conuco</a>, the Latinx and Ibero American Center, will invite students into a conversation that bridges literature, lived experience and cultural dialogue. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Born in Morocco’s Rif region and raised in Catalonia, Ziali grew up navigating Riffian, Catalan and Spanish cultures. That multicultural upbringing, she says, shaped her understanding of identity as something fluid rather than fixed. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“For me, trying to live my identities in plural was very creative,” Ziali said.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As a teenager, however, she struggled to feel fully accepted and even rejected her Moroccan roots for a time. She recalls not seeing many public figures in Spain with Moroccan backgrounds she could look to as mirrors. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Over time, discovering writers and artists who shared similar backgrounds helped her embrace what she describes as a constant “process of mixing and dialoguing” between cultures.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I never can say I am 100% Riffian, or 100% Catalan, or 100% Spanish,” she said. “It’s always a process.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Ziali’s scholarship focuses on sexuality and family relationships among young people from Muslim backgrounds in Spain. Rather than approaching the topic from a distance, she describes herself as deeply connected to the subject.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I am part of this research,” she said. “I am not a researcher who’s seeing this issue far away.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In her conversations with younger women, Ziali has found that many of the taboos surrounding sexuality remain unchanged across generations.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“We still have a lot to do on how we understand our bodies and how we live our sexuality,” she said.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">While she sees progress in the growing number of young women publicly addressing taboos and even abuse through social media, she emphasizes that silence around sexuality is still powerful. </span></p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a24716ce145e sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>If society treats migration as someone else’s problem, it risks becoming a sick society, disconnected from a vital part of itself.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Karima Ziali, writer and scholar</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716ce145e {\n    display: flex;\n    float: none;\n    margin: 30px auto;\n    width: 100%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716ce145e p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716ce145e p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716ce145e .pullquotepic {\n    width: 250px;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a24716ce145e p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716ce145e .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716ce145e .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716ce145e .quotebody {\n    width: 100%;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Her academic research intersects with her literary work, especially in her debut novel, “<a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Una-Oracion-Dios-KARIMA-ZIALI/dp/8412683862\">Una Oración sin Dios</a>.” Ziali argues that fiction can sometimes reach emotional truths that academic writing cannot.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Research is always partial,” she said. “The creative language that writing this book gave me is much more close to the truth.”  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Through fiction, she explains, she can place emotions and inner struggles at the center of the narrative in ways that academic categories and definitions often limit. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The novel follows a young man from a Muslim immigrant family in Spain as he navigates multiple identities and personal conflicts. Rather than neatly separating cultural or religious identities, Ziali portrays them as an internal struggle.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Inside the main character, there is no ‘today I’m Catalan and tomorrow I’m Riffian,’” she said. “You feel all these identities as a little war inside you.”  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Ángel Lara, director of El Conuco and professor of Modern Languages at SUNY Old Westbury, said Ziali’s work resonates strongly with the campus community. He describes her as “a well-known writer and scholar in Spain” whose first novel was a tremendous success.  </span></p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_12041\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-12041\" style=\"width: 300px\" class=\"wp-caption alignright\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-small wp-image-12041\" src=\"uploads/81E2F5FF-67F9-47C2-A012-62915C9687A5-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" srcset=\"uploads/81E2F5FF-67F9-47C2-A012-62915C9687A5-300x225.jpg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/81E2F5FF-67F9-47C2-A012-62915C9687A5-600x450.jpg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/81E2F5FF-67F9-47C2-A012-62915C9687A5-1200x900.jpg 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/81E2F5FF-67F9-47C2-A012-62915C9687A5-768x576.jpg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/81E2F5FF-67F9-47C2-A012-62915C9687A5-1536x1152.jpg 1536w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/81E2F5FF-67F9-47C2-A012-62915C9687A5.jpg 2001w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-12041\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Ángel Lara, director of El Conuco and professor of Modern Languages at SUNY Old Westbury on March 26, 2026. PHOTO BY: KATHERINE CAMPBELL</figcaption></figure>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For Lara, Ziali’s story of being born in Morocco and raised in Spain parallels the experiences of many Old Westbury students who come from Latin American backgrounds but were born or raised in the United States. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Somehow they are like Karima, border people from the cultural and identity perspective,” Lara said.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">That shared inbetween experience, he believes, will make the conversation especially meaningful for students. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Lara also connects Ziali’s work to his own teaching on Spanish history and culture, particularly the often overlooked coexistence of Muslim, Jewish and Christian communities in medieval Spain. By highlighting Muslim and Arabic influences that are sometimes hidden in official narratives, he sees Ziali’s perspective as expanding students’ understanding of Spanish identity. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Beyond its cultural themes, the March 30 conversation will also center on the craft of storytelling. Many attendees are literature students, and Lara hopes Ziali’s visit will serve as both inspiration and provocation.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“All events at El Conuco are kind of provocations,” he said. “And bringing an acclaimed novelist to campus encourages students not to abandon books in an increasingly digital world but to think of literature as something so important.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For Ziali, the ultimate goal of her talk is to challenge the idea that migration stories belong only to “others.”  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“This is not an issue that belongs to the others,” she said. “It’s an issue that belongs to the whole society. If society treats migration as someone else’s problem, it risks becoming a sick society, disconnected from a vital part of itself.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">By sharing her work, Ziali hopes to send a clear message, “We exist, and our experiences matter.”  </span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><em>A Liminal Storytelling: A Conversation with Writer and Scholar Karima Ziali</em><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><em>.</em> Mon., Mar. 30 at 11:40 a.m., NAB 3101 at SUNY Old Westbury.</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'KC639', NULL, '2026-03-27 13:41:15', 0, 'SUNY Old Westbury will welcome Karima Ziali on March 30 for a talk exploring migration, identity and the power of storytelling. The event, hosted by El Conuco, the Latinx and Ibero American Center, will invite students into a conversation that bridges literature, lived experience and cultural dialogue.  Born in Morocco’s Rif region and raised in…\n', NULL, NULL, 10),
('ed3bfcfb-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Dance your heart out learning flamenco with Spanish artist Cristina Candela', 'dance-your-heart-out-learning-flamenco-with-spanish-artist-cristina-candela', NULL, '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Flamenco will take center stage at SUNY Old Westbury on April 2 as Spanish dancer and multidisciplinary artist Cristina Candela brings rhythm, history and movement to campus for an immersive workshop designed to introduce students to the heart of the art form. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The event, presented through <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/department/el-conuco-latinx-and-ibero-american-center\">El Conuco</a> as part of its annual spring flamenco programming, will blend cultural context with hands on dance instruction. Candela, now based in New York City after building her career between multiple cities, said the session is designed for everyone, even those who have never encountered flamenco before. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Since I don’t really know if there’s someone who knows anything about flamenco, I will try to put a very short explanation so we give some context,” Candela said.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The workshop will begin with rhythm exercises, including clapping patterns central to flamenco’s structure, before transitioning into movement. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“We will learn something,” she said. “The goal of the class is that we end up able to clap and to dance to a flamenco lyric in fiesta, party style.”  </span></p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a24716bbbca0 sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>It’s very beautiful when I arrive to a place where all my students know nothing about flamenco,. My challenge is first to make them curious about it. Then to see them dancing and enjoying.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Karima Ziali, flamenco dance artist</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716bbbca0 {\n    display: flex;\n    float: right;\n    margin: 30px 0 30px 30px;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716bbbca0 p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716bbbca0 p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716bbbca0 .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a24716bbbca0 p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716bbbca0 .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716bbbca0 .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716bbbca0 .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">By the end of the session, participants won’t just be watching flamenco, they’ll be part of it.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“The goal is that you can join a flamenco party, knowing what it is about,” Candela said. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For Candela, who describes herself as both a traditional flamenco dancer and a multidisciplinary artist, teaching beginners is both a challenge and a joy.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“It’s very beautiful when I arrive to a place where all my students know nothing about flamenco,” she said. “My challenge is first to make them curious about it. Then to see them dancing and enjoying.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Her extensive training and work with diverse groups, from musicians to dancers to students simply curious about the art form, has shaped a flexible teaching style.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“With experience, you’re quicker reading the room,” Candela said. “Some groups gravitate toward rhythm, others toward body technique. And sometimes you end up in a flamenco party with people that didn’t know about flamenco an hour ago.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">That spontaneous, communal spirit reflects flamenco’s roots. Though its influences stretch back centuries, flamenco as a formalized art emerged in the mid-19th century. It grew from marginalized communities before eventually moving onto major stages and gaining global recognition. Today, it is recognized by UNESCO as Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity, a testament to its depth and cultural importance. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Candela emphasized that flamenco’s history makes it especially meaningful in contemporary society. Born from communities “not wanted by society,” she said, the art form ultimately “stole the heart of a lot of people.”  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In a time when cultural differences can feel divisive, she sees flamenco as a powerful reminder of how expression from the margins can shape the mainstream. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Improvisation is also central to her approach. Flamenco, she explained, functions like a shared language developed over time.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“When you hang out with your friends and you sing or dance, you don’t prepare choreography beforehand, you just go there and have fun,” she said. “If you do that regularly, you end up creating a language.”  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Her workshop offers what she calls “a first visit to the flamenco language,” starting with rhythm, then song, then dance layered on top. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Angel Lara, director of El Conuco and associate professor of sociology at SUNY Old Westbury, said bringing artists like Candela to campus helps challenge misconceptions about flamenco as merely a tourist spectacle. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“By bringing real flamenco artists to campus, we are showing a deeper understanding of that particular culture,” Lara said. </span></p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_12047\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-12047\" style=\"width: 300px\" class=\"wp-caption alignleft\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-small wp-image-12047\" src=\"uploads/81E2F5FF-67F9-47C2-A012-62915C9687A5-1-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" srcset=\"uploads/81E2F5FF-67F9-47C2-A012-62915C9687A5-1-300x225.jpg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/81E2F5FF-67F9-47C2-A012-62915C9687A5-1-600x450.jpg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/81E2F5FF-67F9-47C2-A012-62915C9687A5-1-1200x900.jpg 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/81E2F5FF-67F9-47C2-A012-62915C9687A5-1-768x576.jpg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/81E2F5FF-67F9-47C2-A012-62915C9687A5-1-1536x1152.jpg 1536w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/81E2F5FF-67F9-47C2-A012-62915C9687A5-1.jpg 2001w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-12047\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Ángel Lara, director of El Conuco and professor of Modern Languages at SUNY Old Westbury on March 26, 2026. PHOTO BY: KATHERINE CAMPBELL</figcaption></figure>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For Lara, flamenco represents more than music or dance. It is a living, evolving cultural expression.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Flamenco is like a living animal,” he said. “It’s not an object that belongs to the past. It’s involved in a continuous process of innovation and change, and Candela’s blend of traditional technique with contemporary and narrative elements demonstrates that evolution.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Beyond cultural education, Lara hopes the workshop expands students sense of what academic life can include.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Dancing has to do with the body,” he said. “It’s different from the usual things that we do here in college.”  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">He believes events like this broaden learning beyond lectures and exams, integrating performance and embodied knowledge into campus life. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As a sociologist, Lara also sees performing arts as essential to understanding cultural memory and identity. Through flamenco, students can explore the historical experiences of marginalized communities in Spain and across the Hispanic world.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Performing arts have to do with expression, cultural expression,” he said. “Bringing artists from Spain, Latin America and Latino communities in the U.S. contributes to what he describes as one of SUNY Old Westbury’s defining qualities, diversity.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For students interested in dance or performance, Candela offered simple but profound advice to remain open.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“You have to be really tender and careful with yourself,” she said. “If you allow yourself to be you, you will find your voice, and you will enjoy much more your artistry.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Come step into the rhythm, learn the language, and discover how flamenco transforms from history into lived experience, one clap at a time. </span></p>\n<p><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Flamenco Workshop with Cristina Candela. Thurs. Apr. 2 at 1:30 p.m., Duane L Jones Recital Hall at SUNY Old Westbury.</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'KC639', NULL, '2026-03-30 07:06:36', 0, 'Flamenco will take center stage at SUNY Old Westbury on April 2 as Spanish dancer and multidisciplinary artist Cristina Candela brings rhythm, history and movement to campus for an immersive workshop designed to introduce students to the heart of the art form.  The event, presented through El Conuco as part of its annual spring flamenco…\n', NULL, NULL, 10);
INSERT INTO `content` (`id`, `type`, `title`, `slug`, `description`, `content`, `url`, `approval_status`, `author_id`, `editor_id`, `created_at`, `is_featured`, `excerpt`, `video_url`, `featured_image`, `category_id`) VALUES
('ed3c4c96-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Senior Chevaun Cooper’s long road to the finish line', 'senior-chevaun-coopers-long-road-to-the-finish-line', NULL, '<p>On a quiet afternoon at SUNY Old Westbury, Chevaun Cooper sits closer than ever to a milestone that once felt out of reach. After nearly a decade of college, the 26-year-old graphic design major is preparing to graduate this fall — a moment shaped by years of setbacks, responsibility and persistence.</p>\n<p>“I originally wanted to do game design, but it didn&#8217;t turn out like that,” Cooper said. “Once game design didn&#8217;t work out, I knew I still wanted to do something creative.”</p>\n<p>What began as a straightforward college journey quickly became something much more complicated. Over the years, Cooper’s path was slowed not by a lack of ambition but by circumstances that forced him to move at a different pace than those around him.</p>\n<p>“Managing work and school,” he said. “I could have finished earlier if I didn&#8217;t have to work so much. I had to pay for classes out of pocket because I didn&#8217;t qualify for financial aid. At a point, I had to take one class a semester.”</p>\n<p>The extended timeline wasn’t just about academics. Outside the classroom, Cooper was balancing responsibilities that many traditional students never face.</p>\n<p>“Plenty of times,” he said when asked if he ever thought about quitting. “It was annoying having to juggle work and school. My parents are older too, so taking care of them on top of everything slowed my progress down.”</p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a247175637ec sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>It was gut-wrenching. Hanging out with friends and family, and people talking about accomplishments, new positions, and whatnot. I could have let it dissuade me, but I had to use it as motivation instead.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Chevaun Cooper, SUNY Old Westbury senior, on the importance of self-motivation</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a247175637ec {\n    display: flex;\n    float: none;\n    margin: 30px auto;\n    width: 100%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247175637ec p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a247175637ec p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247175637ec .pullquotepic {\n    width: 250px;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a247175637ec p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247175637ec .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247175637ec .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247175637ec .quotebody {\n    width: 100%;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p>As the years passed, another challenge emerged — watching others move forward while he remained in place.</p>\n<p>“It was gut-wrenching,” Cooper said. “Hanging out with friends and family, and people talking about accomplishments, new positions, and whatnot. I could have let it dissuade me, but I had to use it as motivation instead.”</p>\n<p>That motivation often came down to something simple and urgent.</p>\n<p>“Money,” he said with a laugh. “I knew if I could hunker down, I could create a better standard for my family and me.”</p>\n<p>A turning point came when Cooper made the decision to change his academic direction. Letting go of his original plan forced him to reevaluate what he truly wanted.</p>\n<p>“When I changed majors,” he said. “After game design didn&#8217;t work out for me. I had to really think and decide what I wanted for myself in life going forward. Graphic design was right for me to focus on.”</p>\n<p>That decision gave his college experience new clarity. It also revealed more about who he is beyond the challenges he faced.</p>\n<p>“Caring, kind  . . . goofy,” he said with a chuckle, describing how others might see him.</p>\n<p>Now, with graduation finally within reach, Cooper is beginning to reflect on what the journey has meant.</p>\n<p>“It&#8217;s exciting, it&#8217;s finally over,” he said, laughing. “I can finally focus on work and building a career.”</p>\n<p>Looking back, he recognizes that his path was different — but not without purpose.</p>\n<p>“I&#8217;d tell him to get a job,” Cooper said, laughing as he reflected on his younger self. “Take what you do seriously. It&#8217;s better to do what you gotta do now and have fun later. Everyone&#8217;s different. Find what works for you.”</p>\n<p>After 10 years of persistence, setbacks and growth, Cooper is finally approaching the finish line — not behind, but on his own terms.</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'TS932', NULL, '2026-03-31 17:21:49', 0, 'On a quiet afternoon at SUNY Old Westbury, Chevaun Cooper sits closer than ever to a milestone that once felt out of reach. After nearly a decade of college, the 26-year-old graphic design major is preparing to graduate this fall — a moment shaped by years of setbacks, responsibility and persistence. “I originally wanted to…\n', NULL, NULL, 16),
('ed3c90fa-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'From academic probation to confidence and success: one student’s journey', 'from-academic-probation-to-confidence-and-success-one-students-journey', NULL, '<p class=\"p1\">SUNY Old Westbury junior Shaquana Ricketts remembers the moment her world began to crumble.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">The public health major was a sophomore at the time and was sitting in the Campus Center when she opened an email informing her that she had been placed on academic probation.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“I remember opening the email and just staring at it,” Ricketts said. “It felt like everything I had been trying to keep together just fell apart at that moment.”</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">For Ricketts, the notice confirmed fears she had quietly carried for months. Like many commuter students, she was juggling multiple responsibilities outside of the classroom. Long travel times to campus, part-time work and the pressure to maintain good grades created a constant sense of stress.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“At first I didn’t want to tell anyone,” she said. “I felt embarrassed and worried people would think I just wasn’t trying hard enough.”</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Instead of asking for help right away, Ricketts said she tried to handle the situation on her own. She continued going to class, completing assignments and working her job while keeping the news of her probation to herself.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“I kept thinking, ‘What if I can’t fix this?” Ricketts said. “What if this means I’m not meant to be here?”</p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a24717455884 sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>You start to question yourself. You wonder if everyone else has it figured out and you’re the only one struggling.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Shaquana Ricketts, SUNY Old Westbury junior, on learning she was on academic probation</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a24717455884 {\n    display: flex;\n    float: right;\n    margin: 30px 0 30px 30px;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24717455884 p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a24717455884 p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24717455884 .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a24717455884 p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24717455884 .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24717455884 .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24717455884 .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p class=\"p1\">Those thoughts stayed with her during long commutes to campus and late nights studying. The pressure began to affect her confidence as a student.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“You start to question yourself,” she said. “You wonder if everyone else has it figured out and you’re the only one struggling.”</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Eventually, Ricketts decided she could not manage the situation alone. Earlier this semester, she made the decision to reach out to Counseling and Psychological Wellness Services on campus. The office provides confidential counseling and support sessions for students experiencing stress, anxiety or academic pressure.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Even then, she said, taking the first step was difficult.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“I was really nervous before my first session,” Ricketts said. “I didn’t know what to expect, and I was afraid of being judged.”But once she arrived, that fear began to fade.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Listening to other students share their experiences made her realize she was not alone in feeling overwhelmed.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“When I walked in, I realized a lot of people were dealing with the same kinds of pressures,” she said. “Hearing that made me feel less alone.”</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Over time, the sessions helped her build confidence and develop better ways to manage stress. One moment in particular stood out to her as a turning point.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“One day I finally spoke up and talked about everything I had been holding in,” Ricketts said. “It felt like a weight had been lifted off my shoulders.”</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">For Ricketts, the experience changed the way she viewed asking for help. What once felt like a sign of weakness began to feel like an important step toward improvement.</p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a24717456120 sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>I realized getting support doesn’t mean you’re failing. Sometimes it’s exactly what you need to move forward.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Shaquana Ricketts, SUNY Old Westbury junior, on the positive impact from the support she received from the university\'s Counseling and Psychological Wellness Services</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a24717456120 {\n    display: flex;\n    float: left;\n    margin: 30px 30px 30px 0;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24717456120 p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a24717456120 p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24717456120 .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a24717456120 p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24717456120 .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24717456120 .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24717456120 .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p class=\"p1\">“I realized getting support doesn’t mean you’re failing,” she said. “Sometimes it’s exactly what you need to move forward.”</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Her story reflects a broader reality for many college students. Across campuses nationwide, conversations about student mental health and academic stress have become more common, especially during demanding times in the semester like midterms.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Ricketts said she now hopes other students who may be struggling will consider using the resources available to them.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“A lot of people think they have to deal with everything by themselves,” she said. “But there are people here who actually want to help.”</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Today, Ricketts says she feels more hopeful about her future at SUNY Old Westbury. Although the experience of being placed on academic probation was difficult, it ultimately pushed her to find support and regain confidence in herself.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“I’m still working through things, but I feel stronger now,” she said. “I know I’m not alone, and that makes a huge difference.&#8221;</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'JC956', NULL, '2026-03-31 17:36:39', 0, 'SUNY Old Westbury junior Shaquana Ricketts remembers the moment her world began to crumble. The public health major was a sophomore at the time and was sitting in the Campus Center when she opened an email informing her that she had been placed on academic probation. “I remember opening the email and just staring at…\n', NULL, NULL, 16),
('ed3cdac4-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Terry Phebe: MIC center manager, mentor and . . . hip-hop artist?', 'terry-phebe-mic-center-manager-mentor-and-hip-hop-artist', NULL, '<p>Terry Phebe is widely known at SUNY Old Westbury as a mentor, manager and media creator. Few, however, know of his alter ego:<a href=\"https://open.spotify.com/artist/2ybr42w0XvMFdBqi6G8RUV?si=OebEijqGTKqOdRid5cMI1g\"> KingCasso</a>.</p>\n<p>KingCasso is Phebe&#8217;s moniker — a name he takes on to create hip-hop and R&amp;B music.</p>\n<p>“I started off making music for me,” Phebe said. “I had no intention of showing it to anybody. It just so happened that one day I was playing back something I recorded and someone overheard it and asked ‘What is this?’ And I was like, ‘Ahh you got me.’”</p>\n<p>But creation isn’t just a hobby for Phebe. In high school, he began writing to deal with grief.</p>\n<p>“I’ve had a lot of friends and family members who passed away,” said Phebe. “To figure out how to cope, I used to write poetry, but for some reason music elevated that sense of healing for me.”</p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a2471738362a sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>It’s my safe space, and I allow people to enter that space and understand me better, by making my music.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Terry Phebe, manager of the Media Innovation Center at SUNY Old Westbury</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471738362a {\n    display: flex;\n    float: left;\n    margin: 30px 30px 30px 0;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471738362a p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471738362a p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471738362a .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a2471738362a p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471738362a .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471738362a .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471738362a .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p>After four years as KingCasso, hip-hop and R&amp;B still provide a place where Phebe can let out stifled feelings. And let people in.</p>\n<p>“Pouring out emotional turmoil or when I’m having a mental lapse,” said Phebe. “It’s my safe space, and I allow people to enter that space and understand me better, by making my music.”</p>\n<p>As a former student at SUNY Old Westbury, Phebe was a part of several clubs that aided in his creative journey. These clubs held open mic nights where Phebe was able to share his work.</p>\n<p>“When I attended SUNY Old Westbury, I was just doing spoken word, and I had the luxury of being part of an event called ‘poetry me, please’,” Phebe said. “That helped me get comfortable doing things in front of people.”</p>\n<p>Phebe’s friends and family have been his greatest supporters in publishing his work, including his most recent album ‘<a href=\"https://open.spotify.com/album/3d1NRgwX1fjPkgKdLZlXqQ?si=yzH8QuucSTOHkepmr0Yhew\">(E)Motion</a>’ that was released on Valentine’s Day.</p>\n<p>“Without them, I don’t think I would be releasing any music, to be honest,” Phebe said of his family. “They would listen to it and enjoy it, they liked the stories that I told.”</p>\n<p>Phebe, who immigrated from Haiti, grew up in Elmont. Both have lasting impact on his art. He uses his voice to amplify the stories he hears to give them justice.</p>\n<p>“A lot of my inspiration is from my culture,” said Phebe. “We have our war stories. Sometimes I write and I’m not talking about myself, I’m talking about somebody else through first person.”</p>\n<p>After hours, once everyone has gone home and finished up, Phebe ensures everything is ready for the next day; then allows any students lingering to listen to his music.</p>\n<p>“We have a DJ set up in the studio,” said Phebe. “Sometimes it&#8217;s a group of four, sometimes it&#8217;s just one, just to get a general consensus of if this is going to work, or what&#8217;s missing.”</p>\n<p>Having graduated SUNY Old Westbury in 2019, Phebe returned to campus in 2024; beginning part time, then taking on full time as of 2026. Yet working does not stop Phebe’s creation. If anything, he said, it enhances it.</p>\n<p>“I like to be around creatives,” Phebe said. “There’s a lot of musical students on campus, even some staff who make some stuff too. I’m still taking it as I’m a student of music and learning from everyone.”</p>\n<p>SUNY Old Westbury has given Phebe plenty of opportunity to mingle with other music artists, appreciators, and DJs as well.</p>\n<p>“Anytime I’ve bumped into fellow staff, students, or even some faculty who have heard what I’ve done, they’ve enjoyed it,” said Phebe. “They’ve requested more music, some have given criticism of what I could try or what they want to hear from me.”</p>\n<p>For Phebe, there is only up, only progress from here. He wants to create more, whether that is a new EP or singles, and said SUNY Old Westbury is one of his longest supporters.</p>\n<p>“One thing about SUNY Old Westbury is that it&#8217;s always been very tight knit,” said Phebe. “It’s like a second family, everyone wants the best for you, to see you do what makes you happy, and also do good at it.</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'AB347', NULL, '2026-04-06 07:35:37', 0, 'Terry Phebe is widely known at SUNY Old Westbury as a mentor, manager and media creator. Few, however, know of his alter ego: KingCasso. KingCasso is Phebe’s moniker — a name he takes on to create hip-hop and R&B music. “I started off making music for me,” Phebe said. “I had no intention of showing…\n', NULL, NULL, 16),
('ed3d22de-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Women’s flag football team debuts at SUNY Old Westbury', 'womens-flag-football-team-debuts-at-suny-old-westbury', NULL, '<p class=\"p1\">It may be shocking that one of the most popular American sports, football, has never had an official program at SUNY Old Westbury. Until now. In spring of 2027, the women’s flag football team will be fully introduced into the National College Athletic Association.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">The <span class=\"s1\">NCAA</span> is an organization operating as a non-profit that regulates athletics for over 1,000 schools across the United States for competitions, conferences and leagues. SUNY Old Westbury&#8217;s Scott Bickard, head coach and intramural sports and recreation coordinator, found humor in how he became the first coach of the team.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“It was funny because, originally, I was just supposed to be like the interim coach,” Bickard said. “I think I was chosen to be the original coach because I had started the flag football intramural league here.”</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Bickard said the games, that started March 15, have been simply “practice games.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Football at universities and colleges doesn&#8217;t just build admissions, but culture. Teams have own sense of identity by having a collective moral compass and core values of what builds their team, such as power, courage and teamwork.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“We don’t really have staff assistant coaches,” Bickard said. “But we do have 44 guys that play in our intramural flag league.”</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Those 44 men have all put in the time to help be assistant coaches, helping teach the team how to properly play a game of football.</p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_12076\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-12076\" style=\"width: 300px\" class=\"wp-caption alignright\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-small wp-image-12076\" src=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_0246-300x225.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_0246-300x225.jpeg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_0246-600x450.jpeg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_0246-1200x900.jpeg 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_0246-768x576.jpeg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_0246-1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_0246.jpeg 2001w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-12076\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Panther&#8217;s scoreboard on a soccer field at SUNY Old Westbury on April 1, 2026. PHOTO BY: ROBERT ABRUZZO</figcaption></figure>\n<p class=\"p1\">Paige Francis, a freshman player on the team, who has played flag football since high school, supported the idea of the guys helping.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“The men, they’re really helpful,” Francis said. “They help you get more aggressive.”</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Though getting the benefits of a finished team is great, starting a team can be difficult, especially when they have never played together.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“I feel like we could have better team chemistry,” Francis said. “I feel like because we’re still new and we still don’t really know each other . . . so we’re trying to build that up.”</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Gender is also a factor in the struggle for the new program. Football is a predominantly male sport, with few places for women of all ages to fully participate.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“Since they’re girls, they didn’t play in leagues because there were none when they were younger,” Bickard said. “So, they’re new to the movements of football.”</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Though the practice season has not been exactly what some players would like, players hope the team bonds get stronger as next spring season rolls around.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“I feel like we&#8217;re a really strong team,” Francis said. “We just need to work on our communication.”</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'RA338', NULL, '2026-04-06 08:46:57', 0, 'It may be shocking that one of the most popular American sports, football, has never had an official program at SUNY Old Westbury. Until now. In spring of 2027, the women’s flag football team will be fully introduced into the National College Athletic Association. The NCAA is an organization operating as a non-profit that regulates…\n', NULL, NULL, 14),
('ed3d67d4-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Rock painting fun with first-year students', 'rock-painting-fun-with-first-year-students', NULL, '<snsgallery data-photo-ids=\"12083,12084,12085,12086,12087,12088,12089,12090,12091,12092\"></snsgallery>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'CJ673', NULL, '2026-04-06 08:10:01', 0, '', NULL, NULL, 13),
('ed3daaf4-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Is it love or lust? Campus event tackles modern relationship realities', 'is-it-love-or-lust-campus-event-tackles-modern-relationship-realities', NULL, '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Students at SUNY Old Westbury will have the opportunity to unpack the complexities of modern relationships at the upcoming event “Is It Love or Lust? A Red, Yellow &amp; Green Flag Conversation” taking place Monday, April 13 from 7 p.m. to 9 p.m. in Hall 3 Lounge.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Hosted by the Theta Chapter of Hermandad de Sigma Iota Alpha, Inc. in collaboration with Alpha Phi Alpha Fraternity, Inc., the event aims to create an open, judgement-free space where students can explore relationship dynamics, recognize warning signs and better understand the difference between genuine connection and surface-level attraction. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“We really wanted to form an educational event… highlighting modern relationships,” said Kimberly Luna, a 2025 alumna involved in organizing the program. “The toxic side of relationships is often romanticized in the media, and the bad signs are not always talked about.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The interactive event will focus on identifying red flags, yellow flags and green flags in relationships. Attendees can expect group discussions, role-playing activities and opportunities to actively participate by evaluating different scenarios. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“It’s an interactive dialogue,” Luna explained. “Students will get to engage, share their thoughts and even decide for themselves: &#8220;Is this a red flag or a green flag?’”</span></p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a24716af052e sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>Sometimes people confuse things like love bombing with real interest. There’s a lot of miscommunication, and important conversations – like intentions and consent – are not always happening.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Kimberly Luna, a 2025 alumna involved in organizing the event</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716af052e {\n    display: flex;\n    float: none;\n    margin: 30px auto;\n    width: 100%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716af052e p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716af052e p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716af052e .pullquotepic {\n    width: 250px;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a24716af052e p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716af052e .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716af052e .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24716af052e .quotebody {\n    width: 100%;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Organizers said one of the biggest challenges students face is distinguishing between love and lust, especially in a social media-driven culture. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Sometimes people confuse things like love bombing with real interest,” Luna said. “There’s a lot of miscommunication, and important conversations – like intentions and consent – are not always happening.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Jaden Blackwood, an alumnus of Alpha Phi Alpha, emphasized how platforms like Instagram and Tik Tok can blur those lines even further. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“A lot of people base what they think love or lust looks like off social media,” Blackwood said. “But real-life relationships are different. People need to learn how to distinguish between the two.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The event will also break down what different “flags” can look like in everyday situations. Red flags may include controlling behavior or emotional inconsistency, while green flags center on honesty, communication, and mutual respect. Yellow flags, organizers say, represent behaviors that may need improvement but can be addressed through open conversations. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Beyond education, the event is rooted in building community.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“We really just wanted to create a space where students feel supported,” Luna said. “Sometimes it is easier to talk to someone new than to your close friends about what you’re going through.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The collaboration between the two organizations also reflects their shared commitment to unity and dialogue. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“It is important to get different perspectives,” Blackwood said. “We could have done this alone, but having both organizations involved makes the conversation stronger.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Open to all students, faculty, and campus organizations, the event encourages anyone interested in relationships, communication or personal growth to attend. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As conversations around dating and relationships continue to evolve, events like this aim to give students the tools to navigate them more confidently – and more consciously. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“We just want people to walk away knowing they deserve healthy, honest relationships—and that they’re not alone in figuring that out,” Luna said.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><em>Is It Love or Lust? A Red, Yellow &amp; Green Flag Conversation. Monday, April 13 from 7 p.m. to 9 p.m. in The Woodlands Halls, hall 3 lounge. Free admission.</em> </span></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'DD275', NULL, '2026-04-08 08:00:04', 0, 'Students at SUNY Old Westbury will have the opportunity to unpack the complexities of modern relationships at the upcoming event “Is It Love or Lust? A Red, Yellow & Green Flag Conversation” taking place Monday, April 13 from 7 p.m. to 9 p.m. in Hall 3 Lounge. Hosted by the Theta Chapter of Hermandad de…\n', NULL, NULL, 10),
('ed3de9c4-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'As retirement looms, custodian Desmond Lochlan reflects on his joyous life and many careers', 'as-retirement-looms-custodian-desmond-lochlan-reflects-on-his-joyous-life-and-many-careers', NULL, '<p>When Desmond Lachlan, custodian at SUNY Old Westbury, walks through the campus center; greets of “Wagwan” — slang for &#8220;what&#8217;s going on&#8221; — handshakes, and a “Hey, Mr. Desmond” follow him wherever he goes.</p>\n<p>“Students make me day,&#8221; Lachlan said. &#8220;Without them, we wouldn’t have a job. We have to be kind to them, help them where they need help. It&#8217;s part of the job.”</p>\n<p>Lachlan, born in Trinidad and Tobago, takes pride in holding his cultural values across seas.</p>\n<p>“Everybody was very nice — it&#8217;s in the genes,&#8221; Lachlan said. &#8220;You have to be respectful to everyone. We used to swim in the river and the sea, I have my mom and my niece there and I go back every year.”</p>\n<p>While his joyous attitude is known by staff, students or administration, few know the man behind the smile.</p>\n<p>“When we was working, we watched the waters, I saw the second plane going into the tower,” Lachlan said of witnessing the terrorist attack on the Twin Towers. “By the time we ran upstairs, one plane already hit the tower; we didn’t know what was going on. Then we saw the next plane hit the tower.”</p>\n<p>Lachlan immigrated here in 1993 and worked in Manhattan on the day of 9/11. His boss said that the United States was under attack. Lachlan was told to go home.</p>\n<p>“I walked from Manhattan to Queens,” Lachlan said. “There was a lot of people crossing the Queensborough bridge. It was very sad. You didn’t even feel safe.”</p>\n<p>Yet working in Manhattan was only one of many diverse careers Lachlan had.</p>\n<p>“I was a rookie on the Trinidadian police force,” Lachlan said. “The salary was small, so when you check yourself, you have to move on to something better.”</p>\n<p>After a six-month stint at another job, he switched careers again.</p>\n<p>&#8220;Then I began working with Trinidadian aviation services for eighteen years,” he said.</p>\n<p>While working for Trinidad and Tobago’s air carrier service, he moved between a few positions.</p>\n<p>“I started off as a driver,” Lachlan said. “Then I was promoted, working with the airline&#8217;s mail, documents, even the government’s documents.”</p>\n<p>In 1993 in New York, Lachlan was sponsored by his brother, received all the correct paperwork, and began his varied career path in America.</p>\n<p>“I started working in a flower shop,” Lachlan said. “Then I worked in a restaurant, and I worked in Manhattan too, then I worked with Volkswagon.”</p>\n<p>Despite a wide array of work, Lachlan ended up at SUNY Old Westbury by pure chance.</p>\n<p>“I came for vacation,” Lachlan said. “But I ended up helping a girl, she needed her Volkswagen fixed.”</p>\n<p>That Volkswagen needing repair changed the trajectory of Lachlan’s entire professional journey.</p>\n<p>“If she had not brought it in that Saturday, she would have had to pay a lot,” Lachlan said.</p>\n<p>Lachlan spoke to the owner of the Volkswagen as he tended her car and asked where she worked. She said: SUNY Old Westbury.</p>\n<p>“I asked if they had any jobs available,” said Lachlan. “She told me, perhaps a custodian.”</p>\n<p>That fateful conversation between Lachlan and the Volkswagen owner led to Lachlan’s current job.</p>\n<p>“The first interview I got down,” Lachlan said. “By the second interview, I got the job, and I’ve been here for ten years.”</p>\n<p>Despite his variety of jobs and memorable experiences, Lachlan maintains a positive outlook on it all.</p>\n<p>“All my jobs were good,&#8221; Lachlan said. &#8220;I can’t damn the bridge on none of them. Every job was good.”</p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a2471722850e sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>After I finish here, I’m going to retire. It’s time to relax, lay back and visit the islands.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Desmond Lachlan, SUNY Old Westbury custodian, on his looming retirement</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471722850e {\n    display: flex;\n    float: left;\n    margin: 30px 30px 30px 0;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #b6d6a0;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471722850e p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471722850e p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471722850e .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a2471722850e p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471722850e .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471722850e .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471722850e .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p>Lachlan has worked at SUNY Old Westbury for a decade, ensuring the halls are clean and set up for any events it needs; but it&#8217;s his last vocational stop.</p>\n<p>“After I finish here, I’m going to retire,” Lachlan said. “It’s time to relax, lay back and visit the islands.”</p>\n<p>As his retiring wish, Lachlan asks one thing of his successors.</p>\n<p>“I want to leave something good, anyone coming in, I want them to enjoy SUNY Old Westbury,” Lachlan said. “And other custodians: treat the kids as good as it&#8217;s supposed to be.”</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'AB347', NULL, '2026-04-14 08:00:03', 0, 'When Desmond Lachlan, custodian at SUNY Old Westbury, walks through the campus center; greets of “Wagwan” — slang for “what’s going on” — handshakes, and a “Hey, Mr. Desmond” follow him wherever he goes. “Students make me day,” Lachlan said. “Without them, we wouldn’t have a job. We have to be kind to them, help…\n', NULL, NULL, 16),
('ed3e2c86-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'SUNY Old Westbury junior Hamadi Martin on his journey of self discovery. Part 1: Learning his real name', 'suny-old-westbury-junior-hamadi-martin-on-his-journey-of-self-discovery-part-1-learning-his-real-name', NULL, '<p>For most of his childhood, Hamadi Martin didn’t even know he was being called the wrong name.</p>\n<p>Growing up in Rockland County in the town of Nanuet, Martin was called “Marcus” by family and friends. The name change was not accidental.</p>\n<p>He said his mother chose to call him Marcus because she disliked the name Hamadi, which he shares with his father. Because of the strained relationship between his parents, she avoided using the name altogether, leaving Martin unaware of his actual name for years.</p>\n<p>It was not until second grade that he realized his real name was Hamadi,  the name on his birth certificate and the same name as his father. From that moment, he made a decision that would shape how he saw himself.</p>\n<p>“If my name is Hamadi, that’s what I want to go by,” he said.</p>\n<p>Martin’s experience reflects a larger journey many college students face as they navigate identity, independence and personal growth while adjusting to life away from home.</p>\n<p>Martin, a twenty-one-year-old junior majoring in management information systems at SUNY Old Westbury, is still figuring out who he is but those choices have become more complicated.</p>\n<p>Choosing where to live for college was not just about distance. It meant stepping away from home and from a family dynamic that had never been simple.</p>\n<p>Martin grew up primarily with his mother and grandmother, while his father worked long hours building his career. His parents have been separated for years. Their relationship remains strained.</p>\n<p>Recently, Martin made the decision to move out of his mother’s home and live with his father, who purchased a house following the success of his company. Although his mother did not fully support the decision, he moved forward with it, knowing it was a necessary step for his growth.</p>\n<p>“That was probably one of the biggest decisions of my life,” Martin said.</p>\n<p>At the same time, he chose to live on campus at SUNY Old Westbury instead of commuting, even though it meant being more than an hour away from home.</p>\n<p>At a time when more students are choosing independence and campus involvement over long commutes, Martin’s decision reflects a shift toward prioritizing personal growth and immersion in college life.</p>\n<p>“I didn’t want to stay at home,” he said. “It’s distracting. I wanted to be somewhere I could lock in.”</p>\n<p>Living on campus has given Martin the independence he was looking for, but it has also come with challenges. From inconsistent dining options to shared dorm spaces, daily life is not always easy.</p>\n<p>“You’re living with so many different people,” he said. “Not everyone is clean or respectful.”</p>\n<p>Still, Martin embraces the experience. He describes himself as driven and focused, someone who continues pushing forward even when his schedule becomes overwhelming. He works long hours at his father’s logistics company, Breakaway Courier Systems, while balancing classes.</p>\n<p>Some days begin at five a.m., when he leaves for work in New York City. He returns to campus in the late afternoon for night classes, often not finishing until late at night.</p>\n<p>The schedule is demanding, but he sees it as part of his growth.</p>\n<p>“I don’t mind doing both,” he said. “It benefits me because I’m learning.”</p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a247172d3655 sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>You have to understand your flaws. Once you know them, nobody can use them against you.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Hamadi Martin, a junior at SUNY Old Westbury, on gaining confidence</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a247172d3655 {\n    display: flex;\n    float: none;\n    margin: 30px auto;\n    width: 100%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247172d3655 p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a247172d3655 p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247172d3655 .pullquotepic {\n    width: 250px;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a247172d3655 p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247172d3655 .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247172d3655 .largequote {\n	color: #b6d6a0;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247172d3655 .quotebody {\n    width: 100%;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p>After high school, Martin described himself as naive and too willing to give people the benefit of the doubt. Now, he is more confident and more aware of his strengths and weaknesses.</p>\n<p>“You have to understand your flaws,” he said. “Once you know them, nobody can use them against you.”</p>\n<p>Even as he continues to grow, Martin is still figuring out his future. While he studies business and works in his father’s company, he is also exploring other interests and trying to find his own path, even as he considers the possibility of taking over the family business.</p>\n<p>“I want to try different things,” he said. “I don’t want to be single-minded.”</p>\n<p>As Martin continues navigating independence and preparing for a future in business, his college experience marks a turning point in his life.</p>\n<p>Looking back, he sees every challenge, from family struggles to personal growth, as part of a larger journey.</p>\n<p>“All the different things that have happened to me are the reasons I am the way I am today,” he said.</p>\n<p>For Martin, independence is not just about living away from home. It is about becoming the person he chooses to be.</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'JW623', NULL, '2026-04-13 08:00:14', 0, 'For most of his childhood, Hamadi Martin didn’t even know he was being called the wrong name. Growing up in Rockland County in the town of Nanuet, Martin was called “Marcus” by family and friends. The name change was not accidental. He said his mother chose to call him Marcus because she disliked the name…\n', NULL, NULL, 16);
INSERT INTO `content` (`id`, `type`, `title`, `slug`, `description`, `content`, `url`, `approval_status`, `author_id`, `editor_id`, `created_at`, `is_featured`, `excerpt`, `video_url`, `featured_image`, `category_id`) VALUES
('ed3e7076-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Senior and aspiring videographer Rayvin Dawkins on passion and fear', 'skateboarder-and-aspiring-videographer-rayvin-dawkins-on-passion-and-fear', NULL, '<p>Rayvin Dawkins is riding the half pipe of life and as a senior and skateboarding enthusiast at SUNY Old Westbury. He&#8217;s set to trick back down the half pipe as a<br />\ngraduate with still much to figure out for his future — but he knows that skateboarding will be a part of it.</p>\n<p>The half pipe, two ramps pushed facing each other in a U shape, is a common sight at many skate parks around the world. Skaters ride it up and down, while some stop at the peak of the ramp to rest or enjoy the view.</p>\n<p>Dawkins is at the metaphoric top of that ramp, asking himself where to next after college.</p>\n<p>“I think I&#8217;m very interested in the television and the filming aspects,” said Dawkins.</p>\n<p>Dawkins&#8217; only way is forward, and the way forward is in a field he has much experience in. As a successful skateboarding <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCy3tR9MIRVdtQ_lqjBhUYQw\">YouTuber</a>, and more recently a documentarian, Dawkins is working hard to find his way in life.</p>\n<p>“I feel like when I&#8217;m skateboarding, it&#8217;s when I can really seize the present moment,” said Dawkins. “Oftentimes, I&#8217;m always catastrophizing and stuff, I feel like I can really tune my body and my mind into one similar plane and really just keep going forward.”</p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'storysidebar sno-6a247170c285e sno-animate\'>\n                            <h5>Like this story? Read about other SUNY Old Westbury Panthers!</h5>\n                </p>\n<p class=\"sno-story-headline\"><a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/12057/student-life-clubs-events/profiles/senior-chevaun-coopers-long-road-to-the-finish-line/\">Senior Chevaun Cooper’s long road to the finish line</a></p>\n<p class=\"sno-story-headline\"><a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/11533/student-life-clubs-events/profiles/freshens-at-suny-old-westbury-serves-lunch-with-side-of-good-cheer/\">Freshens at SUNY Old Westbury serves lunch with side of good cheer</a></p>\n<p class=\"sno-story-headline\"><a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/12063/student-life-clubs-events/profiles/from-academic-probation-to-confidence-and-success-one-students-journey/\">From academic probation to confidence and success: one student’s journey</a></p>\n<p>    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-6a247170c285e {\n	width: 100%;background-color: #dddddd;border: 5px solid #888888;box-shadow: -1px 0 2px 0 rgb(0 0 0 / 12%), 1px 0 2px 0 rgb(0 0 0 / 12%), 0 1px 1px 0 rgb(0 0 0 / 24%);width: calc(100% - 40px); margin: 30px auto !important; float: none;	position: relative;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-6a247170c285e p:not(.infographic-widget-container p), \n.segment-body .sno-6a247170c285e p:not(.infographic-widget-container p), \n.sno-story-body .sno-6a247170c285e h5,\n.segment-body .sno-6a247170c285e h5 {\n    color: #000000;\n}\n</style>\n<p>Skateboarding has been Dawkins&#8217; escape and his outlet for his creativity and passion, although without monetization.</p>\n<p>“I&#8217;m not really too worried about it,” said Dawkins. “I&#8217;ve realized that numbers aren&#8217;t everything. I think connection is also very important, and just because my videos aren&#8217;t blossoming doesn&#8217;t mean that I&#8217;m not doing a good job.”</p>\n<p>As Dawkins moves towards his future as a filmmaker, he still holds tight to his passion.</p>\n<p>“Skateboarding, it will always be in my top five,” said Dawkins.</p>\n<p>Wondering what is next is not new for Dawkins. In fact, the last time he asked himself what was next, it culminated in the genesis of his YouTube channel, where he showcases his skills on the skateboard.</p>\n<p>“I think the reason why I partly did it was kind of out of passion, but also, I guess, kind of out of fear,” said Dawkins.</p>\n<p>Despite the fear and what he said was a lack of support from his family, he decided to turn something he loved into something great. Dawkins&#8217; YouTube channel has continued to blossom since its start. Dawkins said that his internship at SUNY Old Westbury&#8217;s Media Innovation Center and his class load helped him improve his channel as well.</p>\n<p>Last semester, he began his first venture into filmography with a documentary about skateboarding. Dawkins views this project as the foundation of showing people what he can do.</p>\n<p>“I think the passion was able to speak for itself and I really wanted to see how skateboarding not only impacted my life, but also the lives of others,” said Dawkins.</p>\n<p>Dawkins said he has interests to be in television and film after graduation and this documentary is the perfect start.</p>\n<p>“I don&#8217;t have to worry about yesterday or tomorrow,” said Dawkins. “I can really be present. I think when I&#8217;m skateboarding, that&#8217;s when I&#8217;m the most present.”</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'TC272', NULL, '2026-04-15 08:00:07', 0, 'Rayvin Dawkins is riding the half pipe of life and as a senior and skateboarding enthusiast at SUNY Old Westbury. He’s set to trick back down the half pipe as a graduate with still much to figure out for his future — but he knows that skateboarding will be a part of it. The half…\n', NULL, NULL, 16),
('ed3eb688-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Sophomore Makayla Reid works to start new theater club by fall 2026', 'sophomore-makayla-reid-works-to-start-new-theater-club-by-fall-2026', NULL, '<p>Makayla Reid fancies herself as an actress. Right now, she is a SUNY Old Westbury sophomore looking to run a theater club in the university for the upcoming fall semester.</p>\n<p>From a young age, Reid has always had a passion for acting since it allows her to express herself through her characters.</p>\n<p>“I like the idea of playing somebody outside of yourself,” Reid said, “It truly brings me out of my shell.”</p>\n<p>Due to her love of acting, Reid researched the school’s ties to theater and found that the Duane L. Jones Recital Hall located in the Campus Center was named after Duane L. Jones, a former English professor at SUNY Old Westbury and the previous director of the Maguire Theater. He was also the first Black man to break out into horror films in a major role with his character Ben in the famous horror film Night of the Living Dead.</p>\n<p>“I feel like not a lot of people know about him and that’s sad,” Reid said, “I never knew him or met him but his work speaks to me deeply.”</p>\n<p>Inspired by Jones’ legacy and work, Reid had looked into the school’s roster of clubs and organizations. She found that in 2020, the school had previously held a theater club that had later gone defunct due to little interest at the time.</p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'storysidebar sno-6a2471700b2a4 sno-animate\'>\n                            <h5>Like this story? Read about other interesting SUNY OW Panthers! </h5>\n                </p>\n<p class=\"sno-story-headline\"><a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/12063/student-life-clubs-events/profiles/from-academic-probation-to-confidence-and-success-one-students-journey/\">From academic probation to confidence and success: one student’s journey</a></p>\n<p class=\"sno-story-headline\"><a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/12057/student-life-clubs-events/profiles/senior-chevaun-coopers-long-road-to-the-finish-line/\">Senior Chevaun Cooper’s long road to the finish line</a></p>\n<p class=\"sno-story-headline\"><a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/12104/student-life-clubs-events/profiles/as-retirement-looms-custodian-desmond-lochlan-reflects-on-his-joyous-life-and-many-careers/\">As retirement looms, custodian Desmond Lochlan reflects on his joyous life and many careers</a></p>\n<p>    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-6a2471700b2a4 {\n	width: 100%;background-color: #dddddd;border: 5px solid #888888;box-shadow: -1px 0 2px 0 rgb(0 0 0 / 12%), 1px 0 2px 0 rgb(0 0 0 / 12%), 0 1px 1px 0 rgb(0 0 0 / 24%);width: calc(100% - 40px); margin: 30px auto !important; float: none;	position: relative;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-6a2471700b2a4 p:not(.infographic-widget-container p), \n.segment-body .sno-6a2471700b2a4 p:not(.infographic-widget-container p), \n.sno-story-body .sno-6a2471700b2a4 h5,\n.segment-body .sno-6a2471700b2a4 h5 {\n    color: #000000;\n}\n</style>\n<p>Over time however, Reid said that she had noticed more students who expressed their interest in acting but had mentioned being too shy to do this. She said that creating a theater club would help students to overcome their insecurities and express their authentic selves.</p>\n<p>“Our generation is too afraid to be cringe,” Reid said, “But that’s the whole point. As a shy person, I feel like it’s the one space that people get me.”</p>\n<p>Additionally, Reid is also the vice president of the Old Westbury Rainbow club for LGBTQ+ students. She talked to fellow SUNY Old Westbury junior student and OW Rainbow treasurer Sam Hamilton about joining the theater club’s executive board and using OW Rainbow to advertise the theater club. Reid said that having a theater club would provide a safe space for all students, but especially for LGBTQ+ students and students of color.</p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a2471700ba6e sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>I hope in the next few years, people will find a second home and appreciate the arts, especially in this day and age. We need that now more than ever.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Makayla Reid, SUNY Old Westbury sophomore and aspiring actress</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471700ba6e {\n    display: flex;\n    float: left;\n    margin: 30px 30px 30px 0;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471700ba6e p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471700ba6e p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471700ba6e .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a2471700ba6e p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471700ba6e .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471700ba6e .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471700ba6e .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p>Looking to revive the theater club for the upcoming fall semester, she spoke to the Center of Student Leadership and Involvement director Paul Ferrante, who greenlit the club. Gaining the approval of the CSLI, Reid and Hamilton created flyers to help grow the school’s theater community.</p>\n<p>“When I graduate, I hope to see it growing and thriving because it makes me sad that not much has been said about it,” Reid said, “I hope in the next few years, people will find a second home and appreciate the arts, especially in this day and age. We need that now more than ever.”</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'KA576', NULL, '2026-04-16 08:00:28', 0, 'Makayla Reid fancies herself as an actress. Right now, she is a SUNY Old Westbury sophomore looking to run a theater club in the university for the upcoming fall semester. From a young age, Reid has always had a passion for acting since it allows her to express herself through her characters. “I like the…\n', NULL, NULL, 16),
('ed3f0943-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Annessa Babic: adjunct professor, union leader, civil rights activist, adventurer', 'annessa-babic-adjunct-professor-union-leader-adventurer', NULL, '<div class=\"elementToProof\">\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Annessa Babic is in a constant state of motion.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I can’t sit in one spot,” Babic said. “When I was watching TV with my dad I actually sat there. We were watching The Madison and I actually didn&#8217;t knit for an hour and he was like ‘Huh? You never do that.’”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Babic is an adjunct professor of American Studies at SUNY Old Westbury, the Chapter President for United University Professions at SUNY Old Westbury and a writer. She is also an experienced traveler.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Both of Babic’s parents were part of the military, and like many other military dependent children, she moved states often.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Babic said that she has lived in over 10 different U.S. states, and has traveled to about as many countries. Greece, Turkey, France, Bulgaria, Ecuador and Romania are a part of a large and ongoing list of the many places Babic has traveled.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I fell in love with the idea of France when I was little,” said Babic. “I had a friend in college, and we talked about Greece and all kinds of things. I developed a romance in my head about it. Which is good, because now I know how much I love Greece.”</span></p>\n</div>\n<div><aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a24712284425 sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>Things I don’t recommend? You probably should not take the shot of vodka from a random woman in a communal shower, but I did that day.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Annessa Babic, adjunct professor, union leader and adventure traveller </p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a24712284425 {\n    display: flex;\n    float: left;\n    margin: 30px 30px 30px 0;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24712284425 p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a24712284425 p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24712284425 .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a24712284425 p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24712284425 .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24712284425 .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a24712284425 .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n</div>\n<div>\n<div class=\"elementToProof\">\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Her interest in travel extends to her work. She is an avid writer, and especially focuses on travel literature.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“One of my favorite pieces was a few years ago,” said Babic. “I did one about these Cleopatra mud baths in Turkey. I was the American on a tour with a bunch of Russian women. Things I don’t recommend? You probably should not take the shot of vodka from a random woman in a communal shower, but I did that day.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Babic said that that story was one of the “strangest” things she has ever experienced, but that those are the travel experiences she likes to write about.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Beyond her travel stories, Babic has been active in protests for years. Posters from various “No Kings” protests are scattered on tables and a couch in her office. UUP union-themed cups, signs, informative books and pins fill her office space.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I’m not gonna protest just to protest,” said Babic. “But I have spent my entire adulthood and my entire career on these causes like labor and equal rights.”</span></p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'storysidebar sno-6a24712284c66 sno-animate\'>\n                            <h5>Like this story? Read about other SUNY Old Westbury Panthers!</h5>\n                </p>\n<p class=\"sno-story-headline\"><a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/11625/student-life-clubs-events/profiles/behind-the-counter-helen-karavis-of-the-halal-shack-on-working-with-and-without-two-good-legs/\">Behind the counter: Helen Karavis of the Halal Shack on working with — and without — two good legs</a></p>\n<p class=\"sno-story-headline\"><a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/11570/student-life-clubs-events/profiles/aspiring-filmmaker-joshua-ramirez-lopez-on-why-perseverance-trumps-perfection/\">Aspiring filmmaker Joshua Ramirez-Lopez on why perseverance trumps perfection</a></p>\n<p class=\"sno-story-headline\"><a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/12104/student-life-clubs-events/profiles/as-retirement-looms-custodian-desmond-lochlan-reflects-on-his-joyous-life-and-many-careers/\">As retirement looms, custodian Desmond Lochlan reflects on his joyous life and many careers</a></p>\n<p>    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-6a24712284c66 {\n	width: 100%;background-color: #dddddd;border: 5px solid #888888;box-shadow: -1px 0 2px 0 rgb(0 0 0 / 12%), 1px 0 2px 0 rgb(0 0 0 / 12%), 0 1px 1px 0 rgb(0 0 0 / 24%);width: calc(100% - 40px); margin: 30px auto !important; float: none;	position: relative;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-6a24712284c66 p:not(.infographic-widget-container p), \n.segment-body .sno-6a24712284c66 p:not(.infographic-widget-container p), \n.sno-story-body .sno-6a24712284c66 h5,\n.segment-body .sno-6a24712284c66 h5 {\n    color: #000000;\n}\n</style>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As an adjunct professor, Babic said that a source of struggle for her is how she feels that adjunct professors are treated differently in academia.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I’m the first adjunct UUP President in SUNY Old Westbury’s history,” said Babic. “I am the second one statewide.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Babic said that she is a “humanist,” and that she is on the side of equality and care for all. She also said that it is why she advocates for labor rights.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“In college, I was a part of a group, and we used to send a notification up to the ACLU,” she said. “It was to the NAACP, we actually sent it to them about my college. They still called the Spring Formal the Old South Ball. And we thought ‘You owned people at one time, so please don’t tell me it’s tradition.’ That’s why they renamed it to Spring Formal.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Babic said that she is currently putting together a first-of-its-kind event for April 21 where UUP will be having coffee with the Human Resources department at SUNY Old Westbury, where members of UUP can ask questions and address concerns with participating staff from human resources. She says that with UUP, she averages two events a month, and that many of them are over food.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Food is so class based,” said Babic. “Food is a universal form to get people talking. This is why so many meetings happen during lunch, because if you get people eating they’ll talk more. Most relationships are developed over food. When you go on a date, you go to dinner.”</span></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'JZ672', NULL, '2026-04-21 08:00:37', 0, 'Annessa Babic is in a constant state of motion.  “I can’t sit in one spot,” Babic said. “When I was watching TV with my dad I actually sat there. We were watching The Madison and I actually didn’t knit for an hour and he was like ‘Huh? You never do that.’”  Babic is an adjunct…\n', NULL, NULL, 16),
('ed3f4ab4-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'How psychology major Despina Drakopoulis became a lead reporter for The Catalyst', 'how-psychology-major-despina-drakopoulis-became-a-lead-reporter-for-the-catalyst', NULL, '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Catalyst covers stories on students, professors and other faculty all over campus, however, it is uncommon for readers to be given a chance to look behind the curtain and see who’s behind the article.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Despina Drakopoulis is a senior at SUNY Old Westbury majoring in psychology. She also started this semester as an intern for The Catalyst, which is the university&#8217;s student news site.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Her interest in journalism began last semester after taking an elective journalism course with Professor Wendy Rhodes, who had reached out, suggesting she sit in on meetings with The Catalyst.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This suggestion would soon evolve into the internship that she is taking this semester.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Journalism isn’t something I dread doing,” said Drakopoulis.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">While it is not unusual to be in an organization that does not correlate to your major, Drakopoulis manages to express passion in both psychology and journalism alike.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As a teen, Drakopoulis struggled finding out where to place herself in the professional world. That was the case until she had taken a few psychology courses in high school.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I was really good at talking to people and giving advice, and when I took psychology I felt like it was the only subject I was really consistent in,” she said.</span></p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'storysidebar sno-6a2471218e76b sno-animate\'>\n                            <h5>Like this story? Read about other SUNY Old Westbury Panthers!</h5>\n                </p>\n<p class=\"sno-story-headline\"><a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/12108/student-life-clubs-events/profiles/suny-old-westbury-junior-hamadi-martin-on-his-journey-of-self-discovery-part-1-learning-his-real-name/\">SUNY Old Westbury junior Hamadi Martin on his journey of self discovery. Part 1: Learning his real name</a></p>\n<p class=\"sno-story-headline\"><a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/12066/student-life-clubs-events/profiles/terry-phebe-mic-center-manager-mentor-and-hip-hop-artist/\">Terry Phebe: MIC center manager, mentor and . . . hip-hop artist?</a></p>\n<p class=\"sno-story-headline\"><a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/11902/student-life-clubs-events/profiles/allison-roberts-sunyoldwestbury-back-to-college-at-50/\">Back to college at 50, radio personality Allison Roberts is giving the young folks a run for their money</a></p>\n<p>    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-6a2471218e76b {\n	width: 100%;background-color: #dddddd;border: 5px solid #888888;box-shadow: -1px 0 2px 0 rgb(0 0 0 / 12%), 1px 0 2px 0 rgb(0 0 0 / 12%), 0 1px 1px 0 rgb(0 0 0 / 24%);width: calc(100% - 40px); margin: 30px auto !important; float: none;	position: relative;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-6a2471218e76b p:not(.infographic-widget-container p), \n.segment-body .sno-6a2471218e76b p:not(.infographic-widget-container p), \n.sno-story-body .sno-6a2471218e76b h5,\n.segment-body .sno-6a2471218e76b h5 {\n    color: #000000;\n}\n</style>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">She decided to make a career out of something she was a natural at, but now that she is an intern at The Catalyst, she visualizes a future where she can explore her options.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“My real goal is to open my own business,&#8221; Drakopoulis said. &#8220;I want to open my own practice up. I could connect with other psychologists. I would love that, but before that I could be a school psychologist.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Now, Drakopoulis is pursuing her degree while working around forty hours a week on top of her internship with The Catalyst.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Literally, the only time I have to do work is a five-hour gap between classes and sometimes after work,&#8221; she said. &#8220;I know when it comes to the weekend, I will not be opening my computer up.&#8221;</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Despite the workload, interning for The Catalyst has helped her integrate with campus life.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I’m not in any clubs — The Catalyst is what I’m in right now,&#8221; she said. &#8220;I just want to leave the school having done something that isn’t just class,” she said.</span></p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a2471218eeee sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>I was really shy, but now that I have to do interviews on my own, that will help me in psychology.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; psychology major Despina Drakopoulis on skills she gained interning for The Catalyst</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471218eeee {\n    display: flex;\n    float: left;\n    margin: 30px 30px 30px 0;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471218eeee p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471218eeee p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471218eeee .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a2471218eeee p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471218eeee .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471218eeee .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a2471218eeee .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As she ventures towards her career, she works hard to expand her social network, which is a far cry from a time when she defined herself as a shy person. She emphasized that engaging with a variety of subjects can serve as new perspectives that benefit someone personally and academically.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I was really shy, but now that I have to do interviews on my own, that will help me in psychology,” said Drakopoulis of the people skills she has learned while reporting.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Drakopoulis continues to pursue a degree in psychology while interning for The Catalyst. Her story serves as a manual for those who want to escape their personal bubble and explore their future.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Professor Rhodes hyped me up a lot, so I do it for myself and I do it for the school,” she said. “I want to leave the school with something.”</span></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'EI902', NULL, '2026-04-22 08:00:03', 0, 'The Catalyst covers stories on students, professors and other faculty all over campus, however, it is uncommon for readers to be given a chance to look behind the curtain and see who’s behind the article. Despina Drakopoulis is a senior at SUNY Old Westbury majoring in psychology. She also started this semester as an intern…\n', NULL, NULL, 16),
('ed3f8d28-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Eliliana Martinez on 38 years of service, faith and the importance of ‘thank you’', 'eliliana-martinez-on-38-years-of-service-faith-and-the-importance-of-thank-you', NULL, '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Year-round, students preparing for or entering college are consistently reminded to complete </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">their financial aid applications. For many, financial aid is not just an option but a necessity, </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">serving as the bridge between ambition and access to higher education.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Yet despite its importance, the process can feel overwhelming and confusing, especially for </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">students who lack guidance with forms like FAFSA and TAP.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">At SUNY Old Westbury, that guidance begins with Eliliana Martinez, the Senior Financial Aid </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Advisor for the Educational Opportunity Program, also known as EOP. A graduate of the </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">university’s class of 1981, Martinez returned to the very institution that shaped her, dedicating </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">the past 38 years to supporting students from underserved backgrounds.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“When you work in higher education and you work directly with a student like I do, you have to </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">love what you do,” said Martinez. “You are human. You can get upset or whatever, but at the </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">end of the day, you know your responsibility and you have to do your job.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">She has guided countless students through applications, answered urgent questions and helped </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">transform uncertainty into a possibility.</span></p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'pullquote sno-pullquote-6a247120c953b sno-animate pullquote-shadow\'>\n                <div class=\"quotebody\">\n                        <div class=\'largequote\'>&ldquo;</div>\n                                    <p class=\'pullquotetext\'>It&#8217;s a word I wish would be used more often because we forget it often.</p>\n                            <p class=\'quotespeaker\'>&mdash; Eliliana Martinez, senior financial aid advisor for the Educational Opportunity Program at SUNY Old Westbury, on the importance of \'thank you\'</p>\n                        <div class=\"clear\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-pullquote-6a247120c953b {\n    display: flex;\n    float: left;\n    margin: 30px 30px 30px 0;\n    width: 50%;\n    border-color: #888888;\n    border-top-width: 5px;\n    border-right-width: 5px;\n    border-bottom-width: 5px;\n    border-left-width: 5px;\n    background-color: #ffffff;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247120c953b p.pullquotetext,\n.sno-pullquote-6a247120c953b p.quotespeaker {\n    color: #000000 !important;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247120c953b .pullquotepic {\n    width: 33%;\n    margin-left: 25px;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-pullquote-6a247120c953b p.pullquotetext {\n    font-size: 22px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247120c953b .quotebar {\n    background: #dddddd;\n    flex: 0 0 90px;\n    margin-top: -15px;\n    margin-left: -15px;\n    padding-left: 15px;\n    padding-top: 15px;\n    margin-right: 15px;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247120c953b .largequote {\n	color: #888888;\n}\n.sno-pullquote-6a247120c953b .quotebody {\n    width: unset;\n}\n</style>\n\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Student appreciation is what Martinez sees as one of the most rewarding aspects of her role, </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">particularly when students acknowledge the assistance they receive.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“When they say thank you,” said Martinez. “Thank you for your help. Thank you for helping me </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">pay my bill. I think that’s the most rewarding thing. It&#8217;s a word I wish would be used more often </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">because we forget it often.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Yet behind the title and responsibilities lies a person whose story, motivations and lasting impact </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">are often overlooked, even by those she has helped the most.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I believe I was a good daughter,” said Martinez. “I was raised by my grandmother, aunt and </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">father. Growing up with a huge family, in DR was hard, because my grandmother and my aunt </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">were very harsh in their parenting. I don’t blame them; I don’t hate them. It was the opposite, as I </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">grew older, I thanked them.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Martinez grew up in the Dominican Republic in a large household where she was raised by her </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">grandmother, aunt and father because she lost her mother when she was only six years old. She </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">described her upbringing as strict and noted that her perspective on those experiences changed </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">over time.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Regardless of that, Dominican Republic still holds a place in her life.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I still love my country, it&#8217;s a beautiful country,” said Martinez. “The weather, you cannot beat </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">that. Like every country, it has problems, but there’s nothing I can do there.”</span></p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\'storysidebar sno-6a247120c9e37 sno-animate\'>\n                            <h5>Like this story? Read about other SUNY Old Westbury Panthers!</h5>\n                </p>\n<p class=\"sno-story-headline\"><a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/12104/student-life-clubs-events/profiles/as-retirement-looms-custodian-desmond-lochlan-reflects-on-his-joyous-life-and-many-careers/\">As retirement looms, custodian Desmond Lochlan reflects on his joyous life and many careers</a></p>\n<p class=\"sno-story-headline\"><a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/12123/student-life-clubs-events/profiles/sophomore-makayla-reid-works-to-start-new-theater-club-by-fall-2026/\">Sophomore Makayla Reid works to start new theater club by fall 2026</a></p>\n<p class=\"sno-story-headline\"><a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/12063/student-life-clubs-events/profiles/from-academic-probation-to-confidence-and-success-one-students-journey/\">From academic probation to confidence and success: one student’s journey</a></p>\n<p>    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-6a247120c9e37 {\n	width: 100%;background-color: #c6d6be;border: 5px solid #000000;box-shadow: -1px 0 2px 0 rgb(0 0 0 / 12%), 1px 0 2px 0 rgb(0 0 0 / 12%), 0 1px 1px 0 rgb(0 0 0 / 24%);width: calc(100% - 40px); margin: 30px auto !important; float: none;	position: relative;\n}\n.sno-story-body .sno-6a247120c9e37 p:not(.infographic-widget-container p), \n.segment-body .sno-6a247120c9e37 p:not(.infographic-widget-container p), \n.sno-story-body .sno-6a247120c9e37 h5,\n.segment-body .sno-6a247120c9e37 h5 {\n    color: #006325;\n}\n</style>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Outside of SUNY Old Westbury, Martinez is dedicated to to her faith.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I&#8217;m very active in my church,” said Martinez. “We are in holy week, it’s a busy week. When </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">you are a server, there is a lot to do.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">And she is also dedicated to her loved ones. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“When I&#8217;m not in church, I spend time with the family,” said Martinez. “I go out sometimes with </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">my family, we take turns taking each other to lunch, breakfast, or dinner.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This aspect is something that has been with her ever since she was young.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“When I was young, I was never a party person,” said Martinez. “I always made sure to spend </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">time with my family. You never know how long you have.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As Martinez considers retirement after 38 years of service, her work remains reflected in the </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">students she has assisted throughout her time at SUNY Old Westbury.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I believe I am still doing a good job,” said Martinez. “But everything must come to an end. Thirty-eight </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">years. I think I have done enough.”</span></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'AN498', NULL, '2026-04-28 08:00:44', 0, 'Year-round, students preparing for or entering college are consistently reminded to complete their financial aid applications. For many, financial aid is not just an option but a necessity, serving as the bridge between ambition and access to higher education. Yet despite its importance, the process can feel overwhelming and confusing, especially for students who lack…\n', NULL, NULL, 16),
('ed3fdc23-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Junior Jayda Austin on facing her fears and finding herself', 'junior-jayda-austin-on-facing-her-fears-and-finding-herself-need-photo', NULL, '<p class=\"p1\">Everybody deals with the challenge of balancing school and extracurriculars, but for Jayda Austin, the process has been about finding herself through it all.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Austin, a third-year student at SUNY Old Westbury, is active in several on-campus organizations. She serves on the executive boards of the Black Student Union and the All the Right Moves dance team, and she also works as an orientation leader.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“I’m involved in a lot of things, but I also dread the fact that I’m involved in a lot of things because I like solitude,” Austin said. “But I do try to maintain a social life, because you’ve got to put yourself out there.”</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Being involved in her community has always been something Austin was naturally drawn to.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“I did step, I was in dance, I was in cosmetology club, I was in choir club and I was also a student ambassador because I would go to the district meetings for my grade,” Austin said of her high school years.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">However, during those years, COVID-19 made Austin less involved because of quarantine and remote learning. After graduating, she wanted to make sure that did not continue.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“You don’t just want to be going to class and going home, so I wanted to put myself out there in that kind of space,” Austin said.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Austin returned to dance in college through All the Right Moves, and it helped her rediscover qualities she knew were still there.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“It taught me leadership and dedication again,” Austin said.</p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\"sno-collection sno-collection-120571206312035\">\n                    <div class=\"sno-story-deck\">Like this story? Read about other SUNY Old Westbury Panthers!</div>\n                        <div class=\"collection-area\" data-link-type=\"story\" data-collection-ids=\"12057,12063,12035\" data-collection-title=\"Like this story? Read about other SUNY Old Westbury Panthers!\">\n                                                    <div class=\"collection-grid-item-wrap\" data-postid=\"12057\">\n                    <div class=\"collection-grid preview-card\">\n                                                    <img decoding=\"async\" class=\"\" src=\"uploads/Screenshot-2026-03-31-at-5.14.10-PM.png\" data-ratio=\"0.88253477588872\" data-shape=\"Square\" alt=\"Chevaun Cooper poses for a portrait against a mural-lined wall on March 16, 2026. PHOTO BY: THIERRY SANZ\">\n                            <div class=\"collection-grid-overlay\">\n                                <a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/12057/student-life-clubs-events/profiles/senior-chevaun-coopers-long-road-to-the-finish-line/\" class=\"collection-title\">\n                                    Senior Chevaun Cooper\'s long road to the finish line                                </a>\n                            </div>\n                                            </div>\n                </div>\n                                            <div class=\"collection-grid-item-wrap\" data-postid=\"12063\">\n                    <div class=\"collection-grid preview-card\">\n                                                    <img decoding=\"async\" class=\"\" src=\"uploads/Screenshot-2026-03-31-at-5.13.47-PM.png\" data-ratio=\"1.3291925465839\" data-shape=\"Square\" alt=\"Shaquana Ricketts, a junior at SUNY Old Westbury, sits in front of a colorful campus mural reading “speak out” reflecting a message of student voice and expression. PHOTO BY: JULIA-LYN CHEATHAM\">\n                            <div class=\"collection-grid-overlay\">\n                                <a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/12063/student-life-clubs-events/profiles/from-academic-probation-to-confidence-and-success-one-students-journey/\" class=\"collection-title\">\n                                    From academic probation to confidence and success: one student\'s journey                                </a>\n                            </div>\n                                            </div>\n                </div>\n                                            <div class=\"collection-grid-item-wrap\" data-postid=\"12035\">\n                    <div class=\"collection-grid preview-card\">\n                                                    <img decoding=\"async\" class=\"\" src=\"uploads/8948EF9A-E056-4E92-A8E4-4B317ED3A534-1200x900.jpg\" data-ratio=\"1.3333333333333\" data-shape=\"Square\" alt=\"Lenore Walsh, athletic director at SUNY Old Westbury, in her office at the Clark Athletic Center on Mar. 23, 2026. PHOTO BY: KATHERINE CAMPBELL\">\n                            <div class=\"collection-grid-overlay\">\n                                <a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/12035/student-life-clubs-events/profiles/director-of-athletics-lenore-walsh-on-coaching-life-lessons-and-suny-old-westbury-pride/\" class=\"collection-title\">\n                                    Director of Athletics Lenore Walsh on coaching, life lessons and SUNY Old Westbury pride                                </a>\n                            </div>\n                                            </div>\n                </div>\n                            </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-collection-120571206312035 {\n    background: #ffffff;\n    border-top: 0px solid #dddddd;\n    border-right: 0px solid #dddddd;\n    border-bottom: 0px solid #dddddd;\n    border-left: 0px solid #dddddd;\n    padding: 15px 0px;\n}\n.sno-collection-120571206312035 .collection-area {\n    gap: 15px;\n    display: grid;\n    width: 100%;\n    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr));\n}\n.sno-collection-120571206312035 .collection-grid-item-wrap {\n    border-radius: 8px;\n}\n.sno-collection-120571206312035 .collection-photo-wrap {\n    aspect-ratio: 1;\n}\n.sno-collection-120571206312035 .sno-story-deck {\n    text-align: center;\n    background: #ffffff;\n    color: #000000;\n}\n.sno-collection-120571206312035 .sno-collection-description p {\n    text-align: center;\n    color: #000000;\n}\n.sno-collection-120571206312035 .collection-tile-text {\n    background: #eeeeee;\n    color: #000000;\n}\n.sno-collection-120571206312035 .collection-tile-text a {\n    color: #000000;\n}\n.sno-collection-120571206312035 .collection-photo-wrap {\n    background: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-collection-120571206312035 .collection-photo-wrap img {\n    object-fit: cover}\n.sno-collection-120571206312035 .collection-grid img {\n    object-fit: cover}\n.sno-collection-120571206312035 .collection-grid {\n    aspect-ratio: 1;\n    background: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-collection-120571206312035 .collection-grid-overlay,\n.sno-collection-120571206312035 .collection-grid-nophoto {\n    background: #000000aa;\n    color: #ffffff;\n}\n.sno-collection-120571206312035 .collection-grid-overlay a,\n.sno-collection-120571206312035 .collection-grid-nophoto a {\n    color: #ffffff;\n}\n.collection-viewer-transition-active,\n.modal-story-collection {\n    background: #ffffff;\n}\n.sno-collection .sno-story-deck {\n    font-family: Source Serif Pro;\n    font-weight: 600; \n    line-height: 1.35em;\n    font-size: 44px;\n}\n.sno-collection .sno-collection-description {\n    font-size: 32px;\n    font-family: Karla;\n    font-weight: 400;\n    font-style: normal;\n    line-height: 1.3em;\n    margin-bottom: 10px;\n}\n.sno-collection {\n    margin-top: 0;\n    padding-top: 0;\n    padding-bottom: 0;\n}\n.collection-area p,\n.collection-grid.preview-card,\n.collection-tile-text {\n    font-family: Source Serif Pro;\n    font-size: 20px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n\n</style>\n<p class=\"p1\">Austin then joined the Black Student Union out of a passion for the Black community and to connect with student leaders, which opened the door to more opportunities.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">But alongside those opportunities are the internal struggles she faces as a student balancing many responsibilities across different campus organizations.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“I’m scared of saying I can do something and then not doing it the way people expect,&#8221; Austin said. &#8220;And my biggest fear is not accomplishing my goals. I struggle with self-doubt, and when things get overwhelming, I just want to quit, even if it’s something small.”</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">However, through her experiences in the organizations she is part of, she has learned to work past her self-doubt.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“I wouldn’t say they didn’t change how I see myself,” Austin said. &#8220;I feel like they solidified more what I knew about myself. I know that I can handle overwhelming things, and even if I am annoyed and I complain, I’ll still get it done.&#8221;</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">This mindset helps her push through even challenging obstacles, including within the organizations she is part of, like All the Right Moves dance team, with its upcoming May show, which is a team-led performance.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“We’re a little bit on a time crunch, so it’s just a little trying to get the whole vision, especially when you have to cooperate with a bunch of different people,” Austin said. “But that’s just something that we have to overcome.”</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">With this semester ending and senior year approaching, Austin continues to look forward to the future and growing not only as a student but as a person.</p>\n<p class=\"p1\">“I’m still working towards me,” Austin said. “I just know that the foundation of who I am is what I’m manifesting, what I’m working toward, and then I’m just excited to see who I become in the next 10 years.&#8221;</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'SP598', NULL, '2026-04-29 08:00:12', 0, 'Everybody deals with the challenge of balancing school and extracurriculars, but for Jayda Austin, the process has been about finding herself through it all. Austin, a third-year student at SUNY Old Westbury, is active in several on-campus organizations. She serves on the executive boards of the Black Student Union and the All the Right Moves…\n', NULL, NULL, 16),
('ed4026f8-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Panther fun at the 5th annual Sports Bash', 'panther-fun-at-the-5th-annual-sports-bash', NULL, '<snsgallery data-photo-ids=\"12180,12182,12181,12183,12189,12191,12184,12185,12190,12192\"></snsgallery>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'CJ673', NULL, '2026-04-22 13:03:32', 0, '', NULL, NULL, 13);
INSERT INTO `content` (`id`, `type`, `title`, `slug`, `description`, `content`, `url`, `approval_status`, `author_id`, `editor_id`, `created_at`, `is_featured`, `excerpt`, `video_url`, `featured_image`, `category_id`) VALUES
('ed408271-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Senior Richard McKenzie plans graduation for self and 5-year-old daughter', 'senior-richard-mckenzie-planning-graduation-for-self-and-5-year-old-daughter', NULL, '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">With graduation right around the corner, many people are getting their gowns and outfits ready to walk across the stage. But media and communications major Richard McKenzie is planning two graduations: his and his five-year-old daughter Averi’s. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“That would be a treat,” McKenzie said. “For both of us to graduate, me in May and her graduation is scheduled for June.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">McKenzie originally started his college career at Alfred State College as a veterinarian major but transferred to SUNY Old Westbury in 2014 after deciding to completely change his career.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I was actually in my junior year before I transferred,” McKenzie said. “And kind of started all over in a sense.”  </span></p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_12212\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-12212\" style=\"width: 300px\" class=\"wp-caption alignright\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-small wp-image-12212\" src=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_7320-300x225.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_7320-300x225.jpeg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_7320-600x450.jpeg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_7320-1200x900.jpeg 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_7320-768x576.jpeg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_7320-1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_7320.jpeg 2001w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-12212\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Richard Mckenzie sits in the SUNY Old Westbury editing suit, preparing to edit videos, on April 6, 2026. PHOTO BY: ANN BUNCH</figcaption></figure>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As McKenzie was starting his entire school career over, he found work at Appellate Advocates, a non-profit law firm based in Manhattan, working there for nine years.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“It wasn&#8217;t like it was something I was pursuing,” McKenzie said. “I was a temp agent, and I ended up temping for that law firm, and they actually liked the way I worked and the way I carried myself.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">McKenzie eventually became a paralegal for a full year before deciding to continue his education at SUNY Old Westbury as a media and communications major.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“I&#8217;m not an individual that likes to leave things unfinished,” McKenzie said.  “And having started college and not completed it really bothered me in one aspect of my life, and I never truly gave up on pursuing or obtaining my degree in a sense.” </span></p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\"sno-collection sno-collection-121621214512118\">\n                    <div class=\"sno-story-deck\">Like this story? Read about other SUNY Old Westbury Panthers!</div>\n                        <div class=\"collection-area\" data-link-type=\"story\" data-collection-ids=\"12162,12145,12118\" data-collection-title=\"Like this story? Read about other SUNY Old Westbury Panthers!\">\n                                                    <div class=\"collection-grid-item-wrap\" data-postid=\"12162\">\n                    <div class=\"collection-grid preview-card\">\n                                                    <img decoding=\"async\" class=\"\" src=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_0477-1200x900.jpeg\" data-ratio=\"1.3333333333333\" data-shape=\"Square\" alt=\"Eliliana Martinez, senior financial aid advisor for the Educational Opportunity Program at SUNY Old Westbury, in her office on April 1, 2026. PHOTO BY: ANGELES NERI\">\n                            <div class=\"collection-grid-overlay\">\n                                <a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/12162/student-life-clubs-events/profiles/eliliana-martinez-on-38-years-of-service-faith-and-the-importance-of-thank-you/\" class=\"collection-title\">\n                                    Eliliana Martinez on 38 years of service, faith and the importance of \'thank you\'                                </a>\n                            </div>\n                                            </div>\n                </div>\n                                            <div class=\"collection-grid-item-wrap\" data-postid=\"12145\">\n                    <div class=\"collection-grid preview-card\">\n                                                    <img decoding=\"async\" class=\"\" src=\"uploads/1000006281-1200x900.jpg\" data-ratio=\"1.3333333333333\" data-shape=\"Square\" alt=\"Despina Drakopoulis, an intern with The Catalyst, on SUNY Old Westbury campus grounds. April 1, 2026. PHOTO BY: EDEN IEVA\">\n                            <div class=\"collection-grid-overlay\">\n                                <a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/12145/student-life-clubs-events/profiles/how-psychology-major-despina-drakopoulis-became-a-lead-reporter-for-the-catalyst/\" class=\"collection-title\">\n                                    How psychology major Despina Drakopoulis became a lead reporter for The Catalyst                                </a>\n                            </div>\n                                            </div>\n                </div>\n                                            <div class=\"collection-grid-item-wrap\" data-postid=\"12118\">\n                    <div class=\"collection-grid preview-card\">\n                                                    <img decoding=\"async\" class=\"\" src=\"uploads/PROFILEPROJECTPICWFM-1200x943.jpg\" data-ratio=\"1.2725344644751\" data-shape=\"Square\" alt=\"Rayvin Dawkins, senior at SUNY Old Westbury, at the Media Innovation Center at SUNY Old Westbury in April, 2026. PHOTO BY: JACK CITARELLA\">\n                            <div class=\"collection-grid-overlay\">\n                                <a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/12118/student-life-clubs-events/profiles/skateboarder-and-aspiring-videographer-rayvin-dawkins-on-passion-and-fear/\" class=\"collection-title\">\n                                    Senior and aspiring videographer Rayvin Dawkins on passion and fear                                </a>\n                            </div>\n                                            </div>\n                </div>\n                            </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-collection-121621214512118 {\n    background: #ffffff;\n    border-top: 0px solid #dddddd;\n    border-right: 0px solid #dddddd;\n    border-bottom: 0px solid #dddddd;\n    border-left: 0px solid #dddddd;\n    padding: 15px 0px;\n}\n.sno-collection-121621214512118 .collection-area {\n    gap: 15px;\n    display: grid;\n    width: 100%;\n    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr));\n}\n.sno-collection-121621214512118 .collection-grid-item-wrap {\n    border-radius: 8px;\n}\n.sno-collection-121621214512118 .collection-photo-wrap {\n    aspect-ratio: 1;\n}\n.sno-collection-121621214512118 .sno-story-deck {\n    text-align: center;\n    background: #ffffff;\n    color: #000000;\n}\n.sno-collection-121621214512118 .sno-collection-description p {\n    text-align: center;\n    color: #000000;\n}\n.sno-collection-121621214512118 .collection-tile-text {\n    background: #eeeeee;\n    color: #000000;\n}\n.sno-collection-121621214512118 .collection-tile-text a {\n    color: #000000;\n}\n.sno-collection-121621214512118 .collection-photo-wrap {\n    background: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-collection-121621214512118 .collection-photo-wrap img {\n    object-fit: cover}\n.sno-collection-121621214512118 .collection-grid img {\n    object-fit: cover}\n.sno-collection-121621214512118 .collection-grid {\n    aspect-ratio: 1;\n    background: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-collection-121621214512118 .collection-grid-overlay,\n.sno-collection-121621214512118 .collection-grid-nophoto {\n    background: #000000aa;\n    color: #ffffff;\n}\n.sno-collection-121621214512118 .collection-grid-overlay a,\n.sno-collection-121621214512118 .collection-grid-nophoto a {\n    color: #ffffff;\n}\n.collection-viewer-transition-active,\n.modal-story-collection {\n    background: #ffffff;\n}\n.sno-collection .sno-story-deck {\n    font-family: Source Serif Pro;\n    font-weight: 600; \n    line-height: 1.35em;\n    font-size: 44px;\n}\n.sno-collection .sno-collection-description {\n    font-size: 32px;\n    font-family: Karla;\n    font-weight: 400;\n    font-style: normal;\n    line-height: 1.3em;\n    margin-bottom: 10px;\n}\n.sno-collection {\n    margin-top: 0;\n    padding-top: 0;\n    padding-bottom: 0;\n}\n.collection-area p,\n.collection-grid.preview-card,\n.collection-tile-text {\n    font-family: Source Serif Pro;\n    font-size: 20px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n\n</style>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">McKenzie has never been alone; his girlfriend of sixteen years and his daughter have helped push him forward and pursue his goal.  </span></p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_12210\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-12210\" style=\"width: 300px\" class=\"wp-caption alignleft\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-small wp-image-12210\" src=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_2667-300x242.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"242\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_2667-300x242.jpeg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_2667-600x483.jpeg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_2667-1200x967.jpeg 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_2667-768x619.jpeg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_2667-1536x1237.jpeg 1536w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_2667.jpeg 2001w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-12210\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Richard McKenzie, Crystal Anthony and Averi McKenzie on a Disney Cruise on March 23, 2026. Photo provided by Richard McKenzie.</figcaption></figure>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“She&#8217;s also another driving force for why I would want to say I want to complete my degree,” McKenzie said about his daughter. “I want to be a positive role model and example for her to see that ‘my dad doesn&#8217;t give up on things.’ And it kind of will fuel her in a sense in the future to not give up on certain things in life.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Long days have been a major issue for McKenzie, keeping him away from home more often than not.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“My classes are from 8 a.m. till 8 p.m. and my internships are in between that,” McKenzie said. “So, I technically don&#8217;t go home at all.” </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">McKenzie’s motivations of fatherhood stem from his own childhood experiences, only having his mother and mostly absent father.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Not having him around consistently, not having him there at my good times . . . really shaped me,” McKenzie said. “It made me understand my emotional reactions to it; it made me think more logically about a lot of things in my life.” </span></p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_12209\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-12209\" style=\"width: 200px\" class=\"wp-caption alignright\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-small wp-image-12209\" src=\"uploads/IMG_1398-1-e1777468194216-200x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"200\" height=\"300\" srcset=\"uploads/IMG_1398-1-e1777468194216-200x300.jpg 200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_1398-1-e1777468194216-400x600.jpg 400w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_1398-1-e1777468194216-800x1200.jpg 800w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_1398-1-e1777468194216-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_1398-1-e1777468194216-1024x1536.jpg 1024w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_1398-1-e1777468194216.jpg 1334w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-12209\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Richard McKenzie and 3-year-old Averi McKenzie in 2024. Photo provided by Richard McKenzie.</figcaption></figure>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">And while long days have kept McKenzie separated from Averi more than he would like, he does not let that stop him.  </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“My time is not going to waste to anything because I&#8217;m pursuing my degree,” McKenzie said. “And in the long run it&#8217;s going to benefit my daughter and my family if — when, not if — when I do obtain this degree in the next five weeks.”</span></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'AB347', NULL, '2026-04-30 08:00:37', 0, 'With graduation right around the corner, many people are getting their gowns and outfits ready to walk across the stage. But media and communications major Richard McKenzie is planning two graduations: his and his five-year-old daughter Averi’s.  “That would be a treat,” McKenzie said. “For both of us to graduate, me in May and her…\n', NULL, NULL, 16),
('ed40d725-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'CRU Bible study offers a faith-based event to students searching for spiritual connections', 'cru-bible-study-offers-a-faith-based-event-to-students-searching-for-spiritual-connections', NULL, '<p><span class=\"FeedbackEditor__selected__H3jkg\">As more young adults search for meaning and connection, some college students are turning to faith &#8211; based communities for support.</span></p>\n<p>At SUNY Old Westbury, Cru, a student-led Christian organization, will host a Bible study on May 7 from 1:30 P.M. to 2:30 p.m. in New Academic Building Room 1100. The event is open to all students and will include small group discussions, scripture readings and light refreshments.</p>\n<p>Cru is part of a national organization that creates faith-based communities on college campuses. At SUNY Old Westbury, the group focuses on helping students explore faith while building relationships in a supportive environment.</p>\n<p>“Cru is an organization on campus where people can come together, learn more about the love of Jesus and grow as a community,” said Devon Duncan, vice president of Cru.</p>\n<p>The Bible study is designed to be interactive and welcoming, with students breaking into small groups to discuss scripture and relate it to their own experiences.</p>\n<p>“We will come together, break down the Bible and have questions in small groups where we are able to talk and connect with people,” Duncan said.</p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\"sno-collection sno-collection-121621214512131\">\n                    <div class=\"sno-story-deck\">Like this story? Read more about SUNY Old Westbury!</div>\n                        <div class=\"collection-area\" data-link-type=\"story\" data-collection-ids=\"12162,12145,12131\" data-collection-title=\"Like this story? Read more about SUNY Old Westbury!\">\n                                                    <div class=\"collection-grid-item-wrap\" data-postid=\"12162\">\n                    <div class=\"collection-grid preview-card\">\n                                                    <img decoding=\"async\" class=\"\" src=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_0477-1200x900.jpeg\" data-ratio=\"1.3333333333333\" data-shape=\"Square\" alt=\"Eliliana Martinez, senior financial aid advisor for the Educational Opportunity Program at SUNY Old Westbury, in her office on April 1, 2026. PHOTO BY: ANGELES NERI\">\n                            <div class=\"collection-grid-overlay\">\n                                <a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/12162/student-life-clubs-events/profiles/eliliana-martinez-on-38-years-of-service-faith-and-the-importance-of-thank-you/\" class=\"collection-title\">\n                                    Eliliana Martinez on 38 years of service, faith and the importance of \'thank you\'                                </a>\n                            </div>\n                                            </div>\n                </div>\n                                            <div class=\"collection-grid-item-wrap\" data-postid=\"12145\">\n                    <div class=\"collection-grid preview-card\">\n                                                    <img decoding=\"async\" class=\"\" src=\"uploads/1000006281-1200x900.jpg\" data-ratio=\"1.3333333333333\" data-shape=\"Square\" alt=\"Despina Drakopoulis, an intern with The Catalyst, on SUNY Old Westbury campus grounds. April 1, 2026. PHOTO BY: EDEN IEVA\">\n                            <div class=\"collection-grid-overlay\">\n                                <a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/12145/student-life-clubs-events/profiles/how-psychology-major-despina-drakopoulis-became-a-lead-reporter-for-the-catalyst/\" class=\"collection-title\">\n                                    How psychology major Despina Drakopoulis became a lead reporter for The Catalyst                                </a>\n                            </div>\n                                            </div>\n                </div>\n                                            <div class=\"collection-grid-item-wrap\" data-postid=\"12131\">\n                    <div class=\"collection-grid preview-card\">\n                                                    <img decoding=\"async\" class=\"\" src=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_2796-1200x900.jpeg\" data-ratio=\"1.3333333333333\" data-shape=\"Square\" alt=\"Annessa Babic, Chapter President of UUP and professor at SUNY Old Westbury, next to her pin board in her SUNY Old Westbury office. April 2, 2026. PHOTO BY: JEDIDIAH ZERVOS\">\n                            <div class=\"collection-grid-overlay\">\n                                <a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/12131/student-life-clubs-events/profiles/annessa-babic-adjunct-professor-union-leader-adventurer/\" class=\"collection-title\">\n                                    Annessa Babic: adjunct professor, union leader, civil rights activist, adventurer                                </a>\n                            </div>\n                                            </div>\n                </div>\n                            </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-collection-121621214512131 {\n    background: #ffffff;\n    border-top: 0px solid #dddddd;\n    border-right: 0px solid #dddddd;\n    border-bottom: 0px solid #dddddd;\n    border-left: 0px solid #dddddd;\n    padding: 15px 0px;\n}\n.sno-collection-121621214512131 .collection-area {\n    gap: 15px;\n    display: grid;\n    width: 100%;\n    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr));\n}\n.sno-collection-121621214512131 .collection-grid-item-wrap {\n    border-radius: 8px;\n}\n.sno-collection-121621214512131 .collection-photo-wrap {\n    aspect-ratio: 1;\n}\n.sno-collection-121621214512131 .sno-story-deck {\n    text-align: center;\n    background: #ffffff;\n    color: #000000;\n}\n.sno-collection-121621214512131 .sno-collection-description p {\n    text-align: center;\n    color: #000000;\n}\n.sno-collection-121621214512131 .collection-tile-text {\n    background: #eeeeee;\n    color: #000000;\n}\n.sno-collection-121621214512131 .collection-tile-text a {\n    color: #000000;\n}\n.sno-collection-121621214512131 .collection-photo-wrap {\n    background: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-collection-121621214512131 .collection-photo-wrap img {\n    object-fit: cover}\n.sno-collection-121621214512131 .collection-grid img {\n    object-fit: cover}\n.sno-collection-121621214512131 .collection-grid {\n    aspect-ratio: 1;\n    background: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-collection-121621214512131 .collection-grid-overlay,\n.sno-collection-121621214512131 .collection-grid-nophoto {\n    background: #000000aa;\n    color: #ffffff;\n}\n.sno-collection-121621214512131 .collection-grid-overlay a,\n.sno-collection-121621214512131 .collection-grid-nophoto a {\n    color: #ffffff;\n}\n.collection-viewer-transition-active,\n.modal-story-collection {\n    background: #ffffff;\n}\n.sno-collection .sno-story-deck {\n    font-family: Source Serif Pro;\n    font-weight: 600; \n    line-height: 1.35em;\n    font-size: 44px;\n}\n.sno-collection .sno-collection-description {\n    font-size: 32px;\n    font-family: Karla;\n    font-weight: 400;\n    font-style: normal;\n    line-height: 1.3em;\n    margin-bottom: 10px;\n}\n.sno-collection {\n    margin-top: 0;\n    padding-top: 0;\n    padding-bottom: 0;\n}\n.collection-area p,\n.collection-grid.preview-card,\n.collection-tile-text {\n    font-family: Source Serif Pro;\n    font-size: 20px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n\n</style>\n<p>The event is open to all students, including those who may not identify as Christian. Duncan said the goal is to create a space where people feel comfortable asking questions and sharing perspectives.</p>\n<p>“Anyone is welcome,” Duncan said. “I had a friend who was Muslim come, and we were able to share our perspectives.”</p>\n<p>For many students, that sense of openness can help reduce feelings of isolation.</p>\n<p>“In a group setting, you see there are people just like you going through things,” Duncan said. “You are not alone.”</p>\n<p>That sense of connection reflects a broader national trend. Research from the Barna Group, a research organization that studies faith, culture, leadership, and generational trends, shows that <a href=\"https://www.barna.com/research/young-adults-lead-resurgence-in-church-attendance/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Gen Z and millennials are becoming more open to faith and attending church more frequently than older generations</a>.</p>\n<p>Additional Barna research found that <a href=\"https://www.barna.com/trends/teens-curious-about-jesus/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">77% of teens are at least somewhat motivated to keep learning about Jesus, pointing to growing curiosity about spirituality.</a></p>\n<p>Still, this shift is not without complexity, as students navigate different beliefs, skepticism and personal struggles while exploring faith.</p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_12220\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-12220\" style=\"width: 300px\" class=\"wp-caption alignleft\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-small wp-image-12220\" src=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_4011-300x225.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_4011-300x225.jpeg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_4011-600x450.jpeg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_4011-1200x900.jpeg 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_4011-768x576.jpeg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_4011-1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_4011.jpeg 2001w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-12220\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Christine Keller, an adjunct professor of the History and Philosophy Department at SUNY Old Westbury, speaks about religion and community in the Panther Pad on April 22, 2026. PHOTO BY: JULIA WALTER</figcaption></figure>\n<p>Christine Keller, an adjunct professor of the History and Philosophy Department at SUNY Old Westbury, said the trend may be connected to the challenges students face today.</p>\n<p>“Many students struggle with anxiety and uncertainty about what is going on in the world,” Keller said. “They are looking for some sense of connection and community.”</p>\n<p>Keller said religion has evolved over time, becoming more open and accessible to younger generations. She pointed to the 1960s as a turning point when religious institutions began to loosen strict rules and make practices more accessible.</p>\n<p>“In the past, it was more like you listen to what you are told, and you do not question things,” Keller said. “Now students are able to obtain answers to questions that can help guide them in life.”</p>\n<p>Faith-based campus groups can offer support as students navigate stress, independence and personal growth.</p>\n<p>“It helps them establish a sense of community and feel more connected,” Keller said. “That can reduce anxiety and help them move forward.”</p>\n<p>For Duncan, that impact is what makes Cru important on campus.</p>\n<p>“I feel like we tend to feel like we are isolated,” Duncan said. “But in a group setting, you can see there are people just like you going through things.”</p>\n<p>As students continue to navigate the pressures of college life, events like Cru’s Bible study offer a space not only to explore faith but also to connect with others and feel supported.</p>\n<p>“If you feel lost, if you feel like you are not seen, there is a God who loves you and sees you,” Duncan said. “We just want to provide a place where people feel welcome.”</p>\n<p><em>Cru Bible Study. May 7 at 1:30–2:30 p.m., New Academic Building Room 1100 at SUNY Old Westbury. <span class=\"FeedbackEditor__selected__H3jkg\">Free and open to all students.</span></em></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'JW623', NULL, '2026-05-01 08:00:33', 0, 'As more young adults search for meaning and connection, some college students are turning to faith – based communities for support. At SUNY Old Westbury, Cru, a student-led Christian organization, will host a Bible study on May 7 from 1:30 P.M. to 2:30 p.m. in New Academic Building Room 1100. The event is open to…\n', NULL, NULL, 10),
('ed412f03-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Free trip to Leslie-Lohman Museum of Art to support LGBTQ+ community', 'free-trip-to-leslie-lohman-museum-of-art-to-support-lgbtq-community', NULL, '<p><span class=\"FeedbackEditor__selected__H3jkg\">SUNY Old Westbury students will have the opportunity to engage with queer art and history through an upcoming trip to the <a href=\"https://leslielohman.org/\">Leslie-Lohman Museum of Art</a>. Designed as a larger, more immersive event, the trip reflects a growing effort to expand student experiences beyond traditional learning. </span></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://oldwestbury.campuslabs.com/engage/event/12414005\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">The Leslie-Lohman Museum Trip </a>will take place on Friday, May, 1, from 11 a.m. to 1 p.m. The trip, hosted by <a href=\"https://oldwestbury.campuslabs.com/engage/organization/owrainbow\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">OW Rainbow</a> and <a href=\"https://oldwestbury.campuslabs.com/engage/organization/historyandphilosophy\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">the History and Philosophy Club</a>, invites students to attend a museum that focuses on showcasing queer-focused art in New York, featuring thousands of art pieces made by LGBTQ+ people.</p>\n<p>Attendees will be picked up at the Student Union at 11 a.m. and should expect to have their transportation, museum tickets and lunch to be paid for by the school. Students can expect to view a variety of art pieces made by LBGTQ+ artists, including exhibits created to give different perspectives of queer love.</p>\n<p>The goal of the event is to show people the importance of LGBTQ+ art and history, to show that LGBTQ+ individuals want to be safe and heard in the world.</p>\n<p>“We hope people take away that we’re still here during this climate that we’re in, in America,” said Beranna Beckett, president of OW Rainbow.</p>\n<p>Beckett said the museum is an important part of LGBTQ+ representation.</p>\n<p>“In the current climate, where a lot of queer and people of color’s voices are being taken away and removed, this stands as a place that wants to be here and wants to be shown,” Beckett said. “We are still going to keep doing what we do, no matter what and contribute to our communities.”</p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\"sno-collection sno-collection-117011196211775\">\n                    <div class=\"sno-story-deck\">Like this story? Read more about SUNY Old Westbury!</div>\n                        <div class=\"collection-area\" data-link-type=\"story\" data-collection-ids=\"11701,11962,11775\" data-collection-title=\"Like this story? Read more about SUNY Old Westbury!\">\n                                                    <div class=\"collection-grid-item-wrap\" data-postid=\"11701\">\n                    <div class=\"collection-grid preview-card\">\n                                                    <img decoding=\"async\" class=\"\" src=\"uploads/IMG_9237-1200x900.jpg\" data-ratio=\"1.3333333333333\" data-shape=\"Square\" alt=\"Photo one: Student Alyssandra Membreno, center, sits with peers inside the\nWomen’s, Gender &amp; Sexuality Studies Center on Oct. 26, 2025. The WGSS\nCenter has become home to the new Trans Collective, a student-led space for\ntrans and nonbinary students to connect and build community. PHOTO BY:\nDESPINA DRAKOPOULOS\">\n                            <div class=\"collection-grid-overlay\">\n                                <a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/11701/news/a-space-to-just-be-the-rise-of-the-trans-collective-at-suny-old-westbury/\" class=\"collection-title\">\n                                    “A Space to Just Be:\" The Rise of the Trans Collective at SUNY Old Westbury                                </a>\n                            </div>\n                                            </div>\n                </div>\n                                            <div class=\"collection-grid-item-wrap\" data-postid=\"11962\">\n                    <div class=\"collection-grid preview-card\">\n                                                    <img decoding=\"async\" class=\"\" src=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/processed-411F64A1-982F-4247-B166-9D2F0F64360D-1200x901.jpeg\" data-ratio=\"1.3318534961154\" data-shape=\"Square\" alt=\"Students gather in the SUNY Old Westbury Campus Center, reflecting the strong female presence on campus following the university’s recognition on Newsweek&#039;s and Gender Fair’s list: America’s Best Colleges for Women 2026. PHOTO BY: DESPINA DRAKOPOULOS\">\n                            <div class=\"collection-grid-overlay\">\n                                <a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/11962/news/suny-old-westbury-ranks-on-newsweek-list-americas-best-colleges-for-women-2026/\" class=\"collection-title\">\n                                    SUNY Old Westbury ranks on Newsweek list: America\'s Best Colleges for Women 2026                                </a>\n                            </div>\n                                            </div>\n                </div>\n                                            <div class=\"collection-grid-item-wrap\" data-postid=\"11775\">\n                    <div class=\"collection-grid preview-card\">\n                                                    <img decoding=\"async\" class=\"\" src=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/Pixabay-1200x800.jpeg\" data-ratio=\"1.5\" data-shape=\"Square\" alt=\"Pixabay\">\n                            <div class=\"collection-grid-overlay\">\n                                <a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/11775/opinion/suny-old-westbury-was-built-on-social-justice-i-want-it-to-stay-that-way/\" class=\"collection-title\">\n                                    SUNY Old Westbury was built on social justice. I want it to stay that way.                                </a>\n                            </div>\n                                            </div>\n                </div>\n                            </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-collection-117011196211775 {\n    background: #ffffff;\n    border-top: 0px solid #dddddd;\n    border-right: 0px solid #dddddd;\n    border-bottom: 0px solid #dddddd;\n    border-left: 0px solid #dddddd;\n    padding: 15px 0px;\n}\n.sno-collection-117011196211775 .collection-area {\n    gap: 15px;\n    display: grid;\n    width: 100%;\n    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr));\n}\n.sno-collection-117011196211775 .collection-grid-item-wrap {\n    border-radius: 8px;\n}\n.sno-collection-117011196211775 .collection-photo-wrap {\n    aspect-ratio: 1;\n}\n.sno-collection-117011196211775 .sno-story-deck {\n    text-align: center;\n    background: #ffffff;\n    color: #000000;\n}\n.sno-collection-117011196211775 .sno-collection-description p {\n    text-align: center;\n    color: #000000;\n}\n.sno-collection-117011196211775 .collection-tile-text {\n    background: #eeeeee;\n    color: #000000;\n}\n.sno-collection-117011196211775 .collection-tile-text a {\n    color: #000000;\n}\n.sno-collection-117011196211775 .collection-photo-wrap {\n    background: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-collection-117011196211775 .collection-photo-wrap img {\n    object-fit: cover}\n.sno-collection-117011196211775 .collection-grid img {\n    object-fit: cover}\n.sno-collection-117011196211775 .collection-grid {\n    aspect-ratio: 1;\n    background: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-collection-117011196211775 .collection-grid-overlay,\n.sno-collection-117011196211775 .collection-grid-nophoto {\n    background: #000000aa;\n    color: #ffffff;\n}\n.sno-collection-117011196211775 .collection-grid-overlay a,\n.sno-collection-117011196211775 .collection-grid-nophoto a {\n    color: #ffffff;\n}\n.collection-viewer-transition-active,\n.modal-story-collection {\n    background: #ffffff;\n}\n.sno-collection .sno-story-deck {\n    font-family: Source Serif Pro;\n    font-weight: 600; \n    line-height: 1.35em;\n    font-size: 44px;\n}\n.sno-collection .sno-collection-description {\n    font-size: 32px;\n    font-family: Karla;\n    font-weight: 400;\n    font-style: normal;\n    line-height: 1.3em;\n    margin-bottom: 10px;\n}\n.sno-collection {\n    margin-top: 0;\n    padding-top: 0;\n    padding-bottom: 0;\n}\n.collection-area p,\n.collection-grid.preview-card,\n.collection-tile-text {\n    font-family: Source Serif Pro;\n    font-size: 20px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n\n</style>\n<p>Jillian Crocker, director of women’s, gender and sexuality studies, otherwise known as the WGSS, at SUNY Old Westbury, emphasized the educational value of these experiences. She noted that representation – whether in art, history, or schoolwork – helps students understand how their personal identities connect to larger narratives.</p>\n<p>“Learning about their history is an important piece about understanding how their story fits in with the stories of so many others who have come before them,” Crocker said.</p>\n<p>About 39% of LGBTQ+ young people seriously considered attempting suicide in the past year, according to a <a href=\"https://www.thetrevorproject.org/survey-2024/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">2024 U.S. National Survey</a> on the mental health of LGBTQ young people conducted by the Trevor Project, a crisis intervention and suicide prevention organization for LGBTQ youth.</p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_12228\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-12228\" style=\"width: 300px\" class=\"wp-caption alignleft\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-small wp-image-12228\" src=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_6106-300x225.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_6106-300x225.jpeg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_6106-600x450.jpeg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_6106-1200x900.jpeg 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_6106-768x576.jpeg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_6106-1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_6106.jpeg 2001w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-12228\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Beranna Beckett, OW Rainbow president at SUNY Old Westbury, holds up pride flags in the Women’s, Gender and Sexuality Center on April 15, 2026. PHOTO BY: HAILEY MATTHEWS</figcaption></figure>\n<p>Campus initiatives and events that center around the identities of LGBTQ+ individuals can play a meaningful role in countering those experiences by fostering a sense of connection and belonging on college campuses.</p>\n<p>Crocker also highlighted the importance of LGBTQ+ initiatives and programs on college campuses.</p>\n<p>“Support for programs like WGSS, support for LGBTQ+ studies programs, whether as a minor or as a major, hiring initiatives that underscore folks with expertise in LGBTQ+ studies and WGSS who can teach those courses from their areas of specialization,” said Crocker. “I think are all very important ways that colleges can invest in the academic fields of LGBTQ+ studies and the WGSS more broadly.”</p>\n<p>Including LGBTQ+ inclusive policies and practices in schools were linked to students’ sense of self-worth, according to a study published by the <a href=\"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12577476/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">National Institutes of Health.</a></p>\n<p>Despite progress, challenges remain. Queer artists and creators still face barriers to recognition and funding in mainstream spaces. Crocker emphasized the need for continued support.</p>\n<p>“The more that we can do to support artists and writers,” Crocker said. “The more space we create for marginalized voices to come to the surface.”</p>\n<p>Ultimately, the trip aims to create not only an educational experience, but also a sense of shared belonging, reinforcing the value of representation both on campus and beyond.</p>\n<p>“It feels more and more important to take up space and show that we are present, we’re not going anywhere,” said Beckett. “We want to be safe and heard.”</p>\n<p><span class=\"FeedbackEditor__selected__H3jkg\"><a href=\"https://oldwestbury.campuslabs.com/engage/event/12414005\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><em>The Leslie-Lohman Museum Trip</em></a></span><em><span class=\"FeedbackEditor__selected__H3jkg\"> hosted by OW Rainbow and the History and Philosophy Club at SUNY Old Westbury. 11 a.m. on Friday, May 1. Transportation, tickets and lunch paid for by the school. </span></em></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'HM127', NULL, '2026-04-30 13:48:31', 0, 'SUNY Old Westbury students will have the opportunity to engage with queer art and history through an upcoming trip to the Leslie-Lohman Museum of Art. Designed as a larger, more immersive event, the trip reflects a growing effort to expand student experiences beyond traditional learning.  The Leslie-Lohman Museum Trip will take place on Friday, May, 1,…\n', NULL, NULL, 10),
('ed4186a3-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'University offers free snacks and beverages at event during finals week', 'university-offers-free-snacks-and-beverages-at-event-during-finals-week', NULL, '<p><span class=\"FeedbackEditor__selected__H3jkg\">As finals week approaches, many students at SUNY Old Westbury find themselves overwhelmed with exams, deadlines and long study hours. During this stress, basic needs like eating and staying hydrated are often pushed aside. </span></p>\n<p>On May 7 from 1:30 p.m. to 2:30 p.m., the Commuter Student Association will host a &#8220;finals support station,&#8221; offering free snacks, drinks and study essentials to help students recharge during one of the most demanding times of the semester.</p>\n<p>For some students, this kind of support is more necessary than it might seem. Genesis Telles, a junior at SUNY Old Westbury, said finals week can become intense.</p>\n<p>“I felt overwhelmed to the point where my basic needs like eating or drinking felt unimportant,&#8221; she said. &#8220;My focus was solely on my grades and wanting to pass my classes. Luckily, my supportive family is always there for me and constantly reminds me to take care of myself as my health should be a priority.”</p>\n<p>Her experience reflects a common pattern among college students who often prioritize academic performance over their physical well-being during high-stress periods.</p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_12233\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-12233\" style=\"width: 300px\" class=\"wp-caption alignright\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-small wp-image-12233\" src=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_0628-300x225.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_0628-300x225.jpeg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_0628-600x450.jpeg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_0628-1200x900.jpeg 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_0628-768x576.jpeg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_0628-1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/IMG_0628.jpeg 2001w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-12233\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Faylon Robinson, a nurse at SUNY Old Westbury, sitting in the Wellness Center’s Meeting room on April 27, 2026. PHOTO BY: ANGELES NERI</figcaption></figure>\n<p>“Lack of nutrition will affect not only energy levels, but it also affects every aspect of your well-being,” said Faylon Robinson, a nurse at the Health and Wellness Center at SUNY Old Westbury. “We all need nutrition on a daily basis in order to function at a maximum.”</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4583157/\">Research from the National Library of Medicine</a> supports this, showing that from a stress perspective, the eating behaviors of students are affected by psychological stress and heightened anxiety during exam times.</p>\n<p>Additionally, a <a href=\"https://hsrc.himmelfarb.gwu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1360&amp;context=gw_research_showcase\">report from The George Washington University</a> notes that 73% of students report that their eating habits change during high-stress times.</p>\n<p>By providing free and accessible snacks and drinks, the CSA’s finals support station aims to support both the physical and mental well-being of students, particularly commuters who may not always have easy access to campus resources. Telles said that support systems already exist on campus but are sometimes underutilized.</p>\n<p>“The pantry, tutoring center and the health and wellness center can provide support for students during these critical times,” she said. “We have all these resources around us; students should use them to their advantage.”</p>\n<p>Her advice to fellow students reinforces the importance of maintaining healthy habits during finals week.</p>\n<p>“As a fellow student myself, I suggest students sleep and eat well because if you don’t, your brain won’t be able to work to its full potential,” Telles said.</p>\n<p>Robinson also encourages students to be proactive.</p>\n<p>“Prepare for that period,” she said. “There are lots of healthy snacks out there that they can purchase and stock up on. Preparing for a stressful period is what is important.”</p>\n<p><em><span class=\"FeedbackEditor__selected__H3jkg\">Finals Support Station. Thurs., May 7 at 1:30 p.m., Campus Atrium at SUNY Old Westbury. Free snacks and beverages. </span></em></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'AN498', NULL, '2026-05-05 08:00:54', 0, 'As finals week approaches, many students at SUNY Old Westbury find themselves overwhelmed with exams, deadlines and long study hours. During this stress, basic needs like eating and staying hydrated are often pushed aside.  On May 7 from 1:30 p.m. to 2:30 p.m., the Commuter Student Association will host a “finals support station,” offering free…\n', NULL, NULL, 10);
INSERT INTO `content` (`id`, `type`, `title`, `slug`, `description`, `content`, `url`, `approval_status`, `author_id`, `editor_id`, `created_at`, `is_featured`, `excerpt`, `video_url`, `featured_image`, `category_id`) VALUES
('ed41cf43-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Mock interview practice and free headshots help students prepare for jobs and internships', 'mock-interview-practice-and-free-headshots-help-students-prepare-for-jobs-and-internships-need-photos', NULL, '<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Every college student hopes to find a job after graduation, but the interview process can be a major hurdle. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">To help students with little interview experience and those who get last-minute jitters, SUNY Old Westbury will host mock interviews aimed at improving career readiness.</span></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://oldwestbury.campuslabs.com/engage/event/12278433\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Mock Interview Day</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> will take place Friday, May 8, from 11 a.m. to 1 p.m. in Panthers Pad in the Student Union. The event, hosted by Sophomore Jump and the Academic Planning Center, will give any students the chance to practice interviews with alumni and other campus professionals for free.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The event will give students a minimum of one practice interview that would take roughly 30 minutes in total. 20 minutes for the interview, and 10 minutes of feedback. Depending on attendance, there may be a wait. Because of that, there will also be an opportunity for professional headshots between interviews, as well as complimentary beverages. Students are encouraged to wear professional attire for photos.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“We want students to have good active listening skills, professional behavior, body language, all the nonverbal communication skills that you need in interviewing, as well as having a professional presence,” Kailtin Janes, sophomore class dean and event organizer, said. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Janes said the event provides a safe space to practice answering questions and networking skills.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Mock Interview Day is a place to make all of the mistakes,” Janes said. “Do everything wrong, and then you&#8217;re gonna get that feedback so that when you are on an actual interview, you are not making those same mistakes.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The need for events like this stems from the growing career-readiness gap among college students. </span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The National Association of Colleges and Employers reports in its 2024 Student Survey and 2025 Job Outlook </span><a href=\"https://www.naceweb.org/career-readiness/competencies/the-gap-in-perceptions-of-new-grads-competency-proficiency-and-resources-to-shrink-it#:~:text=Similarly%2C%20the%20gap%20is%20quite,their%20resumes%20or%20during%20interviews\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">that students and employers agree on the importance of communication, critical thinking and professionalism. However, students believe they are much more proficient in these areas than employers do.</span></a></p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_12239\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-12239\" style=\"width: 300px\" class=\"wp-caption alignright\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-small wp-image-12239\" src=\"uploads/Sophie-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" srcset=\"uploads/Sophie-300x225.jpg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Sophie-600x450.jpg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Sophie-1200x900.jpg 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Sophie-768x576.jpg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Sophie-1536x1152.jpg 1536w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Sophie.jpg 2001w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-12239\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Jerilyn Marinan McLaughlin, director of Career Planning and Development, in her office at SUNY Old Westbury on April 22, 2026. PHOTO BY: SOFIE POPOTTE</figcaption></figure>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“The skills gap is real,” Jerilyn Marinan McLaughlin, director of Career Planning and Development at SUNY Old Westbury, said. </span></p>\n<p><span class=\"FeedbackEditor__selected__H3jkg\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Students often feel anxious during these interviews because they wonder how to effectively communicate their skills when they lack direct experience related to the position they are applying for, McLaughlin said.</span> Around 47% of college students feel that they’re not confident in their ability to find a job after they’re done with college, according to a 2023 <a href=\"https://www.theforage.com/blog/news/forage-career-readiness-survey\">survey published by Forage</a>, website that offers free virtual job simulations.</span></p>\n<p><span class=\"FeedbackEditor__selected__H3jkg\">“It’s higher stakes, and I know students feel that,” said Kaitlin Janes, the president of Sophomore Jump. “That’s why I think mock interview is such an important practice for students.”</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The need for activities like Mock Interview Day is ultimately essential to students’ career readiness. </span><a href=\"https://open-publishing.org/journals/index.php/jutlp/article/view/738\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">A 2024 peer-reviewed study published in the Journal of University Teaching and Learning Practice found that interview practice can improve self-efficacy and boost confidence.</span></a></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For every student hoping to enter the workforce after graduation, events like Mock Interview Day are more than just an event <b>— </b>they are one more step toward professional success.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">“Career readiness is not just a Career Planning and Development initiative,” McLaughlin said. “It is a college initiative. It should be happening everywhere.”</span></p>\n<p><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Mock Interview Day hosted by Sophomore Jump and the Academic Planning Center at SUNY Old Westbury. 11 a.m. to 1 p.m. on Friday, May 8 in Panthers Pad of the Student Union. Free admission.</span></i></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'EI902', NULL, '2026-05-06 08:00:49', 0, 'Every college student hopes to find a job after graduation, but the interview process can be a major hurdle. To help students with little interview experience and those who get last-minute jitters, SUNY Old Westbury will host mock interviews aimed at improving career readiness. Mock Interview Day will take place Friday, May 8, from 11…\n', NULL, NULL, 10),
('ed42172e-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'What is a seed bomb? I am glad you asked.', 'what-is-a-seed-bomb-i-am-glad-you-asked', NULL, '<p><span class=\"FeedbackEditor__selected__H3jkg\">Sunshine and seed bombs? Actually, they do go together. Students have an opportunity to connect with peers and restore the beauty of the SUNY Old Westbury campus with these small bundles of joy.</span></p>\n<p>Seed the Change will take place on Wednesday, May 6, from 1:30 to 2:30 p.m. in the <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/why-old-westbury/visit-old-westbury\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Campus Center Atrium.</a> The event is hosted by the Environmental Sustainability and <a href=\"https://libguides.oldwestbury.edu/c.php?g=1455027&amp;p=10925955\">Melittology Club</a>.</p>\n<p>The atrium will transform into a hub where students can gather for a hands-on seed bomb workshop. These small, biodegradable globes are made from a precise mix of clay, compost and native seeds. Seed bombs are designed to restore local biodiversity.</p>\n<p>While the physical goal of this workshop is to enhance the campus landscape, it serves a dual purpose, providing a significant impact on student mental health and environmental ingenuity.</p>\n<p>Exposure to green spaces results in mental restoration and increased positive emotions and decreased anxiety and rumination. Improved mindfulness can result from exposure to green space as well, according to <a href=\"https://hsph.harvard.edu/news/time-spent-in-nature-can-boost-physical-and-mental-well-being/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Harvard School of Public Health</a>. For college students, engaging with nature through seed bombing provides a sensory remedy for the pressure of final exams and academic hardship.</p>\n<p>“These seed bombs help with an urban setting by providing a chance,” said Nikki Rodgers, a chemistry laboratory technician at SUNY Old Westbury. “A chance by providing survival for those seeds, by giving them the nutrients, by giving them protection.”</p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_12243\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-12243\" style=\"width: 300px\" class=\"wp-caption alignright\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-small wp-image-12243\" src=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/kp-300x225.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/kp-300x225.jpeg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/kp-600x450.jpeg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/kp-1200x900.jpeg 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/kp-768x576.jpeg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/kp-1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/kp.jpeg 2001w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-12243\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Seeds being grown on the SUNY Old Westbury campus on Apr. 28, 2026. PHOTO BY: KORRINA PLAIR</figcaption></figure>\n<p>Beyond restoration for local biodiversity, Seed the Change serves a more profound purpose. With the end of the semester and final exams approaching, the event motivates students to connect with their bodies and foster mindfulness towards the environment.</p>\n<p>“We release a good amount of good dopamine and good chemicals in our body, and it allows us to regulate our nervous system, reducing fatigue, and allowing us to reset in a sense,” said Rodgers.</p>\n<p>A 2024 study from <a href=\"https://digitalcommons.georgiasouthern.edu/honors-theses/934/#:~:text=This%20study%20highlights%20the%20importance,near%20them%2C%20using%20proxemic%20zoning.\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Georgia Southern University</a> found that academic libraries can create a conducive learning environment by providing natural lighting and it emphasizes the role that environmental factors can play.</p>\n<p>“It helps us increase physical, mental and emotional stabilization of our body by just having access to sunlight and green spaces,” said Rodgers.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9358038/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">In terms of mental restoration</a>, an article that included researchers at Cornell University, said college students talked about the importance of light and views from interiors because that is where they spend the majority of their time, both studying and working. The research also said that students expressed wanting to see more blurring between the indoors and out, with interior gardens or plantings, and windowed areas that lead out to natural courtyards.</p>\n<p>“Everything connects in a giant web,” said Rodgers. “You end up creating inclusion, equality, and humanitarianism. You create just general academic flourishment.”</p>\n<p>Events like Seed the Change emphasize the importance of students&#8217; mental health and the ability workshops like these have to create a welcoming environment, carrying out activities to get students one-on-one time with nature.</p>\n<p>“It helps us decrease our kind of stress levels,” said Rodgers. “It helps us increase physical, mental and emotional stabilization of our body by just having access to sunlight and green spaces.”</p>\n<p><em><span class=\"FeedbackEditor__selected__H3jkg\"><span class=\"\">Seed the Change</span>. Wed., May 6 at 1:30 p.m., Campus Center Atrium at SUNY Old Westbury. Free admission. Free food and refreshments.</span></em></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'KP547', NULL, '2026-05-04 08:00:29', 0, 'Sunshine and seed bombs? Actually, they do go together. Students have an opportunity to connect with peers and restore the beauty of the SUNY Old Westbury campus with these small bundles of joy. Seed the Change will take place on Wednesday, May 6, from 1:30 to 2:30 p.m. in the Campus Center Atrium. The event is…\n', NULL, NULL, 10),
('ed426971-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Harmonia/Discordia spring 2026 magazine release party', 'harmonia-discordia-spring-2026-magazine-release-party', NULL, '<p><span class=\"FeedbackEditor__selected__H3jkg\"><span class=\"\">After a full semester of hard work, editing, and putting their hearts on paper, Harmonia/Discordia is holding their</span><a href=\"https://oldwestbury.campuslabs.com/engage/event/12396175\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"> spring 2026 release party </a>on May 11, and invites all SUNY Old Westbury students and staff to attend.</span></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://oldwestbury.campuslabs.com/engage/organization/owenglishwrites\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">A club of critical essayists, creative writers and editors,</a> the club publishes two magazines a year of both critical and creative writing, as well as photography, collages and artwork of all types.</p>\n<p>“It’s a celebration, not only of the student contributors, but also the student editorial team who put a lot of work in, in the semester to get this work out,” said Elizabeth Schmermund, an assistant professor in the English Department and faculty advisor of Harmonia/Discordia.</p>\n<p>The release party will have some mingling, snacks, drinks and also students reading aloud their published work.</p>\n<p>“It’s very social,&#8221; said Schmermund &#8220;One of the best aspects of Harmonia/Discordia is that the students who are involved form a community. It’s not just a campus-based community, it leads to friendships even after graduation.”</p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_12248\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-12248\" style=\"width: 300px\" class=\"wp-caption alignleft\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-small wp-image-12248\" src=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/IMG_7448-300x225.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/IMG_7448-300x225.jpeg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/IMG_7448-600x450.jpeg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/IMG_7448-1200x900.jpeg 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/IMG_7448-768x576.jpeg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/IMG_7448-1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/IMG_7448.jpeg 2001w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-12248\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Professor Elizabeth Schmermund sits in her office; she holds two previous versions of the Harmonia/Discorida publications, on April 21, 2026. PHOTO BY: ANN BUNCH</figcaption></figure>\n<p>It’s not just English majors who are published, it&#8217;s anyone on campus with the drive to write.</p>\n<p>“There’s a lot of different writers in Harmonia, and everyone has their own style,” said Lori Yamond, a junior and president of the club. “Anyone can join, which is fun because sometimes we’ll get majors who are so oddball from English, but people have a passion to write and Harmonia is where you can channel that passion.”</p>\n<p>Literacy rates in the U.S. fluctuate but<a href=\"https://nces.ed.gov/surveys/piaac/2023/national_results.asp\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"> have regressed since COVID-19 hit the nation</a>, according to the National Center for Education Statistics, an organization that runs annual cyclic studies on competency of United States adults.</p>\n<p>This depletion in English proficiency extends to SUNY Old Westbury as well.</p>\n<p>“I think it&#8217;s been part of a larger issue that may even predate COVID,” said Schmermund, faculty advisor of Harmonia/Discordia. “It may even predate generative AI, but one of the steps I’m taking is that I’m doing a lot of in class writing assignments.”</p>\n<p>Yet the Harmonia/Discordia isn’t only for writers who have already written, but for anyone who wants to develop creative and critical writing skills or develop as an author.</p>\n<p>“Rejection is part of the game, but sometimes you get really good feedback,” said Schmermund. “And I know that our Harmonia/Discordia student editors will accept a work and say ‘Hey, we noticed this one part in this piece needs citations here,’ and it&#8217;s the same for our creative pieces.’”</p>\n<p>For students with a fear of critiques, Harmonia/Discordia is a place to learn perseverance in the name of publication.</p>\n<p>“If it&#8217;s something that you love, keep writing, you don’t let anyone scare you away from what you love to do,” said Schmermund. “And also writing is less about talent and more about putting that work in and keep going even in the face of fear.&#8221;</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://www.thenationalliteracyinstitute.com/2024-2025-literacy-statistics\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">With the National Literacy Institute reporting that 54% of American adults reading below sixth grade levels,</a> the club is also a place to learn how to better one’s reading and writing skills.</p>\n<p>“Joining the editorial team is a really good way,” said Schmermund. “When submissions are selected, it&#8217;s all anonymous, so no one knows who submitted what. It&#8217;s essentially an anonymous workshop, so you can use that to revise and move forward from there.”</p>\n<p>Brianna Leconte, a junior at SUNY Old Westbury who is experiencing her first publication in the Harmonia, has first-hand experience with writing and the emotions that come with it.</p>\n<p>“I started writing since I was in elementary school and I’ve wanted to be published since middle school,” said Leconte. “I was so happy. It&#8217;s surreal as a writer, It&#8217;s hard to put yourself out there. It&#8217;s unbelievable.”</p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_12249\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-12249\" style=\"width: 225px\" class=\"wp-caption alignleft\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"wp-image-12249 size-small\" src=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/IMG_7512-e1777643088199-225x300.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/IMG_7512-e1777643088199-225x300.jpeg 225w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/IMG_7512-e1777643088199-450x600.jpeg 450w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/IMG_7512-e1777643088199-900x1200.jpeg 900w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/IMG_7512-e1777643088199-768x1024.jpeg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/IMG_7512-e1777643088199-1152x1536.jpeg 1152w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/IMG_7512-e1777643088199.jpeg 1501w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 225px) 100vw, 225px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-12249\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">A copy of Harmonia/Discordia 2026 sits on a table in the SUNY Old Westbury New Academic building on April 27, 2026. PHOTO BY: ANN BUNCH</figcaption></figure>\n<p>The release party, one of many over the past two decades, is open to all with a desire to create, build lifelong bonds, develop students&#8217; confidence in their literacy skills, and perhaps build a legacy.</p>\n<p>“There’s that question everyone asks you: What do you want to leave behind? And writing is my thing,” said Leconte. “I want just a piece of that out there for people to resonate with and connect with.”</p>\n<p><em><span class=\"FeedbackEditor__selected__H3jkg\">Harmonia/Discordia spring 2026 magazine release party. May 11, 2026 at 1:30 p.m. at SUNY Old Westbury in the New Academic Building, Room 3123.  Free admission. Drinks and snacks will be served. </span></em></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'AB347', NULL, '2026-05-07 08:00:40', 0, 'After a full semester of hard work, editing, and putting their hearts on paper, Harmonia/Discordia is holding their spring 2026 release party on May 11, and invites all SUNY Old Westbury students and staff to attend. A club of critical essayists, creative writers and editors, the club publishes two magazines a year of both critical and creative…\n', NULL, NULL, 10),
('ed42c069-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Lavender Graduation ceremony offers space for LGBTQ+ students to be recognized at SUNY Old Westbury', 'lavender-graduation-ceremony-offers-space-for-lgbtq-students-to-be-recognized-at-suny-old-westbury', NULL, '<p>As the semester comes to a close, students prepare to walk on stage and celebrate their accomplishments as they transition into adulthood. For LGBTQ+ students, in particular, the thought of presenting themselves authentically in a large ceremony can be daunting. Enter the <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/division/office-student-affairs/center-student-leadership-and-involvement/lavender-grad\">Lavender Graduation Ceremony</a>.</p>\n<p>The Lavender Graduation Ceremony was designed to recognize and honor LGBTQ+ students during a divisive time in the United States. It aims to help the school continue its commitment to fostering a diverse and inclusive environment for all students.</p>\n<p>Lavender Graduation will take place at 1:30 p.m. on Tues., May 5,  in the Panther Pad at the Student Union at SUNY Old Westbury. This event, which is sponsored by the Center for Student Leadership and Involvement invites LGBTQ+ students, staff and allies to celebrate the achievements of graduating LGBTQ+ students. The ceremony will include a keynote speaker, a student speaker and the presentation of lavender cords that graduates can wear during commencement.</p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_12255\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-12255\" style=\"width: 300px\" class=\"wp-caption alignleft\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"wp-image-12255 size-small\" src=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Kamsi-e1777645801958-300x225.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Kamsi-e1777645801958-300x225.jpeg 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Kamsi-e1777645801958-600x450.jpeg 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Kamsi-e1777645801958-1200x900.jpeg 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Kamsi-e1777645801958-768x576.jpeg 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Kamsi-e1777645801958-1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Kamsi-e1777645801958.jpeg 2001w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px\" /><figcaption id=\"caption-attachment-12255\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Paul Ferrante, director of Center for Student Leadership and Involvement, a the Student Union at SUNY Old Westbury in April 2026. PHOTO BY KAMSI AGU</figcaption></figure>\n<p>“A Lavender Graduation ceremony helps uplift the LGBTQ+ community and allies,” said Paul Ferrante, event organizer and director of Center for Student Leadership and Involvement. “We’re recognizing and celebrating the achievements of our students and our community members. It’s a time for us to come together and celebrate all the hard work our community has done, whether it’s through academics, social justice or advocacy.”</p>\n<p>Ferrante said that hosting a Lavender Graduation helps build community and support systems for LGBTQ+ college students. According to a <a href=\"https://news.gallup.com/poll/656708/lgbtq-identification-rises.aspx\">2025 study published by Gallup News</a>, 23% of Generation Z people in the United States identify as LGBTQ+.</p>\n<p>However, many LGBTQ+ students have reported facing discrimination while attending college. A <a href=\"https://williamsinstitute.law.ucla.edu/publications/lgbtq-colleges-grad-school/\">2022 study published by the Williams Institute</a> at the University of California, Los Angeles, shows that 32% of LGBTQ+ college students faced harassment from their peers. Additionally, a study 15% of LGBTQ+ college students have changed their appearance and mannerisms to avoid harassment.</p>\n<p>Victoria Lapkiewicz, an intern at the Women’s, Gender and Sexuality Studies Center at SUNY Old Westbury, said spaces like Lavender Graduation can help address those challenges.</p>\n<p>“In the past, schools weren’t always safe spaces, and people weren’t always protected from discrimination,” Lapkiewicz said. “Lavender Graduation gives students a space where they can embrace who they are with support from friends and faculty.”</p>\n<p>Even with progress in creating more inclusive campuses, challenges still exist. Lapkiewicz said one common issue is a lack of respect for students’ identities.</p>\n<p>“Sometimes people don’t take pronouns seriously, and that can make students feel less included,” she said.</p>\n<aside>\n    <div class=\"sno-collection sno-collection-117011192211729\">\n                    <div class=\"sno-story-deck\">Like this story? Read more about SUNY Old Westbury!</div>\n                        <div class=\"collection-area\" data-link-type=\"story\" data-collection-ids=\"11701,11922,11729\" data-collection-title=\"Like this story? Read more about SUNY Old Westbury!\">\n                                                    <div class=\"collection-grid-item-wrap\" data-postid=\"11701\">\n                    <div class=\"collection-grid preview-card\">\n                                                    <img decoding=\"async\" class=\"\" src=\"uploads/IMG_9237-1200x900.jpg\" data-ratio=\"1.3333333333333\" data-shape=\"Square\" alt=\"Photo one: Student Alyssandra Membreno, center, sits with peers inside the\nWomen’s, Gender &amp; Sexuality Studies Center on Oct. 26, 2025. The WGSS\nCenter has become home to the new Trans Collective, a student-led space for\ntrans and nonbinary students to connect and build community. PHOTO BY:\nDESPINA DRAKOPOULOS\">\n                            <div class=\"collection-grid-overlay\">\n                                <a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/11701/news/a-space-to-just-be-the-rise-of-the-trans-collective-at-suny-old-westbury/\" class=\"collection-title\">\n                                    “A Space to Just Be:\" The Rise of the Trans Collective at SUNY Old Westbury                                </a>\n                            </div>\n                                            </div>\n                </div>\n                                            <div class=\"collection-grid-item-wrap\" data-postid=\"11922\">\n                    <div class=\"collection-grid preview-card\">\n                                                    <img decoding=\"async\" class=\"\" src=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/Byron-Director-Shot-1.jpeg\" data-ratio=\"1.4746543778802\" data-shape=\"Square\" alt=\"Byron Hurt speaks during a filmed interview as part of his work examining masculinity and social accountability. Photo courtesy of Byron Hurt. \">\n                            <div class=\"collection-grid-overlay\">\n                                <a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/11922/student-life-clubs-events/events/filmmaker-byron-hurt-talks-masculinity-misogyny-gender-and-homophobia/\" class=\"collection-title\">\n                                    Filmmaker Byron Hurt talks masculinity, misogyny, gender and homophobia                                </a>\n                            </div>\n                                            </div>\n                </div>\n                                            <div class=\"collection-grid-item-wrap\" data-postid=\"11729\">\n                    <div class=\"collection-grid preview-card\">\n                                                    <img decoding=\"async\" class=\"\" src=\"uploads/Liam-photo-by-Henry-Wilson-1200x900.jpg\" data-ratio=\"1.3333333333333\" data-shape=\"Square\" alt=\"Liam McCloskey, a student at SUNY Old Westbury. Nov. 17, 2025. PHOTO BY: HENRY M. WILSON\">\n                            <div class=\"collection-grid-overlay\">\n                                <a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/11729/opinion/men-need-mental-health-support-not-ostracization-ready-to-publish/\" class=\"collection-title\">\n                                    Men need mental health support, not ostracization                                </a>\n                            </div>\n                                            </div>\n                </div>\n                            </div>\n    </div>\n</aside>\n<style>\n.sno-collection-117011192211729 {\n    background: #ffffff;\n    border-top: 0px solid #dddddd;\n    border-right: 0px solid #dddddd;\n    border-bottom: 0px solid #dddddd;\n    border-left: 0px solid #dddddd;\n    padding: 15px 0px;\n}\n.sno-collection-117011192211729 .collection-area {\n    gap: 15px;\n    display: grid;\n    width: 100%;\n    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr));\n}\n.sno-collection-117011192211729 .collection-grid-item-wrap {\n    border-radius: 8px;\n}\n.sno-collection-117011192211729 .collection-photo-wrap {\n    aspect-ratio: 1;\n}\n.sno-collection-117011192211729 .sno-story-deck {\n    text-align: center;\n    background: #ffffff;\n    color: #000000;\n}\n.sno-collection-117011192211729 .sno-collection-description p {\n    text-align: center;\n    color: #000000;\n}\n.sno-collection-117011192211729 .collection-tile-text {\n    background: #eeeeee;\n    color: #000000;\n}\n.sno-collection-117011192211729 .collection-tile-text a {\n    color: #000000;\n}\n.sno-collection-117011192211729 .collection-photo-wrap {\n    background: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-collection-117011192211729 .collection-photo-wrap img {\n    object-fit: cover}\n.sno-collection-117011192211729 .collection-grid img {\n    object-fit: cover}\n.sno-collection-117011192211729 .collection-grid {\n    aspect-ratio: 1;\n    background: #dddddd;\n}\n.sno-collection-117011192211729 .collection-grid-overlay,\n.sno-collection-117011192211729 .collection-grid-nophoto {\n    background: #000000aa;\n    color: #ffffff;\n}\n.sno-collection-117011192211729 .collection-grid-overlay a,\n.sno-collection-117011192211729 .collection-grid-nophoto a {\n    color: #ffffff;\n}\n.collection-viewer-transition-active,\n.modal-story-collection {\n    background: #ffffff;\n}\n.sno-collection .sno-story-deck {\n    font-family: Source Serif Pro;\n    font-weight: 600; \n    line-height: 1.35em;\n    font-size: 44px;\n}\n.sno-collection .sno-collection-description {\n    font-size: 32px;\n    font-family: Karla;\n    font-weight: 400;\n    font-style: normal;\n    line-height: 1.3em;\n    margin-bottom: 10px;\n}\n.sno-collection {\n    margin-top: 0;\n    padding-top: 0;\n    padding-bottom: 0;\n}\n.collection-area p,\n.collection-grid.preview-card,\n.collection-tile-text {\n    font-family: Source Serif Pro;\n    font-size: 20px;\n    line-height: 1.4em;\n}\n\n</style>\n<p>Events like Lavender Graduation aim to counter those experiences by providing a space where students feel seen and supported, especially during a major milestone like graduation. They can also have a direct impact on how students feel on campus.</p>\n<p>“Lavender Graduation is an important way for queer students to be visible,” said Jillian Crocker, an associate professor and the director of the Women’s, Gender and Sexuality Studies program at SUNY Old Westbury  “And for queer students to articulate the ways in which their identities have shaped their experiences as a college student.”</p>\n<p>Both Crocker and Ferrante said that they advocate for more LGBTQ+ campus initiatives such as Drag Queen Bingo and Queer Coffee Hour. Additionally, clubs and organizations such as Old Westbury Rainbow and Trans* Collective regularly hosts meetings that allow for queer and transgender students to bond over shared experiences, form community and honor LGBTQ+ history.</p>\n<p>“They are efforts all around campus to support queer identified students from the time they enroll at Old Westbury through their commencement,” Crocker said, “so while Lavender Graduation is one way, the WGSS center and WGSS program work to create inclusive communities and opportunities for leadership and exploration for queer students.</p>\n<p><em>Lavender Graduation Ceremony hosted by Center for Student Leadership and Involvement at SUNY Old Westbury. 1:30pm on Tues., May 5 in Student Union Panther Pad. Refreshments included. Free admission. <a href=\"http://forms.cloud.microsoft/pages/responsepage.aspx?id=NJAI9TPyEk-nFji39JBDcCWmpK1gHhdJmHOChyZU1G1UMzhTTkdNMlIxVk9KWjhJTEdRQkxVSTRRQyQlQCN0PWcu&amp;route=shorturl\">Registration encouraged</a>. </em></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'AC769', NULL, '2026-05-01 10:37:45', 0, 'As the semester comes to a close, students prepare to walk on stage and celebrate their accomplishments as they transition into adulthood. For LGBTQ+ students, in particular, the thought of presenting themselves authentically in a large ceremony can be daunting. Enter the Lavender Graduation Ceremony. The Lavender Graduation Ceremony was designed to recognize and honor LGBTQ+…\n', NULL, NULL, 10),
('ed42fe32-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'video', 'How one student rated a burger at the SUNY Old Westbury cafeteria. VIDEO BY: JULIA-LYN CHEATHAM', 'how-one-student-rated-a-burger-at-the-suny-old-westbury-cafeteria-video-by-julia-lyn-cheatham', NULL, '', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'JC956', NULL, '2026-05-05 08:11:28', 0, '', NULL, NULL, 15),
('ed434324-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'video', 'Marcela Torres, assistant professor of visual arts, talks about the power of art. VIDEO BY: DYLAN DEMPSTER', 'marcela-torres-assistant-professor-of-visual-arts-talks-about-the-power-of-art-video-by-dylan-dempster', NULL, '', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'DD221', NULL, '2026-05-05 08:22:18', 0, '', NULL, NULL, 15),
('ed43866e-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'video', 'It’s that time of the year again: finals! VIDEO BY: MARK LAYVEY', 'its-that-time-of-the-year-again-finals-video-by-mark-layvey', NULL, '', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'ML776', NULL, '2026-05-09 09:34:40', 0, '', NULL, NULL, 15),
('ed43cb44-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'K-pop club might be gone, but interest in the music genre remains', 'k-pop-club-might-be-gone-but-interest-in-the-music-genre-remains', NULL, '<p>While students at SUNY Old Westbury might not talk about K-pop as much as hip-hop, K-pop is a popular music genre at the university. It can also inspire a sense of comfort among fans.</p>\n<p>During a regular Monday, on April 13, 2026, student Cheyanne Paul heard an unexpected lecture regarding the subject.</p>\n<p>“It was something that I was interested in,” said Paul. “I feel like we learned very good things when it comes to the depth, the background, the culture, the traditions and how it&#8217;s improving and still improving on to this day.”</p>\n<p>Professional musician and professor Paul Carlon, who teaches Music of Global Culture at SUNY Old Westbury, decided to introduce his class to the world of K-pop, which is a subject that is often of interest to music lovers all around the world but also here at SUNY Old Westbury. Carlon showed a video of K-pop sensation BTS performing on The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon.</p>\n<p>“I try and cover a lot of various styles from around the world,” said Carlon. “That includes traditional music and contemporary music. I couldn&#8217;t not cover K-pop, you know, I mean, it&#8217;s so current and so big right now.”</p>\n<p>K-pop, also known as Korean pop, originated back in 1950 with a three member girl group called The Kim Sisters. They successfully performed on the Ed Sullivan Show 22 times. Then in 2012, Psy, also known as Park Jae-sang, released the global success “Gangnam style,”a song described to mock Seoul&#8217;s Gangnam district, an area prominent for high end luxury.</p>\n<p>“I liked the music when I was in middle school and it just clicked with me,” said Nicole Howard, a senior in media and communications at SUNY Old Westbury.</p>\n<p>K-pop was so popular at SUNY Old Westbury that there was once a club dedicated to the genre of music. Rumor has it that the reason the club fell in 2025 was due to the lack of members. With the rise of popularity for K-pop at SUNY Old Westbury, some have thought about bringing back the club. Howard, for one, thinks it could be fun.</p>\n<p>&#8220;I don&#8217;t know, maybe like an event just like playing the music, doing karaoke,&#8221; she said.</p>\n<p>Kiarra Taylor, a freshman who loves K-pop, also thinks a club could be a good idea.</p>\n<p>“I think it would be cool to get someone who&#8217;s good at dancing there so we can learn to choreograph,” Taylor said.</p>\n<p>Greta Gibson, a freshman and a K-pop fan, said she would welcome a new club.</p>\n<p>&#8220;I think that would be really interesting and I would probably join,&#8221; Gibson said.</p>\n<p>The benefits of K-pop, she said, go beyond the music.</p>\n<p>&#8220;I really got into them when I was in a difficult time in my life,&#8221; she said. &#8220;And it really helped me though that I just really like their unique music.&#8221;</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'MM948', NULL, '2026-05-13 10:16:08', 0, 'While students at SUNY Old Westbury might not talk about K-pop as much as hip-hop, K-pop is a popular music genre at the university. It can also inspire a sense of comfort among fans. During a regular Monday, on April 13, 2026, student Cheyanne Paul heard an unexpected lecture regarding the subject. “It was something…\n', NULL, NULL, 1),
