('ed48ac7a-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'SUNY OW Ranked One of the “Best Colleges” for Value in New Money Magazine Issue', 'suny-ow-ranked-one-of-the-best-colleges-for-value-in-new-money-magazine-issue', NULL, '<p>SUNY Old Westbury has been ranked among the “best colleges” in terms of greatest value in <em>Money Magazine</em>’s recent “Best Colleges for Your Money 2019” issue.</p>\n<p>According to the publication, OW ranked 256 out of 744 four-year colleges across the U.S. <em>Money</em> cut down its ranking by only including institutions that had at least 500 students, had sufficient reliable data that could be analyzed, were not in financial distress, and have a high graduation rate.</p>\n<p>The data collection and analysis for the rankings were led by the American Institute for Research (AIR), and <em>Money</em> directed quality control. <em>Money</em> believes that “going to school shouldn’t be a lifetime of debt,” so this data collection and practical analysis was offered to help students and families find high quality, yet affordable colleges.</p>\n<p>All schools were evaluated by using twenty-six factors in three categories: quality of education, affordability and outcomes. The factors that contributed to the results include estimated tuition costs without aid, percentage of students receiving aid, median student’s debt, early career earnings, and SAT/ACT score.</p>\n<p>According to the survey, SUNY OW graduates’ median debt at graduation is $17,000, which is considered much lower than the national average, and their early career earnings within the first three years of work is estimated at $48,100.</p>\n<p>“SUNY Old Westbury has a very, very good value,” said Jacob Heller, assistant vice president for Institutional Research and Assessment. “Students receive extensive aid [and] students graduate in a reasonable amount of time.” Some students agree that SUNY OW has successfully offered them the best value by combining affordability and equality.</p>\n<p>Nina Crawford, a media and communications major at OW, says she is pleased with her decision to enroll here since she will graduate from OW debt free. “I think it’s the best college for my money,” she said.</p>\n<p>Heller believes that while this acknowledgement from <em>Money Magazine</em> is great, there are other factors that make OW among the best in terms of value.</p>\n<p>“A student should look to see if the college offers the major that they want,” he said. “Do they get to know the faculty, is it the kind of community where they will feel comfortable, can they take courses that works around their schedules, will they get a good education.”</p>\n<p>Heller hopes that this achievement “will bring Old Westbury to the attention of people who might have otherwise not looked at it.&#8221;</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'TC527', NULL, '2019-10-19 15:13:07', 0, 'SUNY Old Westbury has been ranked among the “best colleges” in terms of greatest value in Money Magazine’s recent “Best Colleges for Your Money 2019” issue. According to the publication, OW ranked 256 out of 744 four-year colleges across the U.S. Money cut down its ranking by only including institutions that had at least 500 students, had sufficient reliable data that could…\n', NULL, NULL, 1),
('ed48f2cc-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'SUNY Old Westbury’s Panther Pride Homecoming', 'suny-old-westburys-panther-pride-homecoming', NULL, '<p><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"wp-image-4144 size-medium aligncenter\" src=\"http://www.oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/IMG_D2BB8BF6CA3C-1-399x500.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"399\" height=\"500\" /></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The 12th annual Panther Pride homecoming ended with the selection at the formal event of Alejandro Mateo as king and Joy ALonge as queen. Festivities included the Fall Festival, the International Food Fair, the Faculty vs. Staff softball game, a Fraternity and Sorority Expo, an Alumni Meet and Greet, a flag football pick-up game, and many more.</p>\n<p>Expectations for this year’s Homecoming were high as always, especially when it came to the Homecoming committee who helped to plan this year’s events.</p>\n<p>Vice President of Student Affairs and Chief Diversity Officer, Usama Shaikh, who is also Co-Chair of the Homecoming Committee, said before the event, “The members of the Panther Pride Committee are very excited about the upcoming Homecoming events. We have worked hard to put together events that we expect will meet the interests of all members of the Old Westbury community.”</p>\n<p>The Dean of Students and Co-Chair of the Homecoming Committee, Claudia Marin-Andrade, stated prior to the festivities, “Due to the collaborative approach in having students, faculty, and staff on the planning committee, I think all of the events will go over [with teachers and students] very well.”</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'TC527', NULL, '2019-10-19 15:32:58', 0, '  The 12th annual Panther Pride homecoming ended with the selection at the formal event of Alejandro Mateo as king and Joy ALonge as queen. Festivities included the Fall Festival, the International Food Fair, the Faculty vs. Staff softball game, a Fraternity and Sorority Expo, an Alumni Meet and Greet, a flag football pick-up game, and many more. Expectations for this year’s Homecoming were…\n', NULL, NULL, 1),
('ed49363d-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'video', 'OW Responds to Global Climate Change', 'ow-responds-to-global-climate-change', NULL, '<p><strong>SUNY Old Westbury faculty Prof Karl Grossman and students respond to the recent Global Climate Strike Event.</strong></p>\n<p><iframe loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/r7-N6XU8SG8\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'TC527', NULL, '2019-10-22 14:37:23', 0, 'SUNY Old Westbury faculty Prof Karl Grossman and students respond to the recent Global Climate Strike Event.\n', NULL, NULL, 15),
