('ed761dea-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'National Hispanic Heritage Month 2023', 'national-hispanic-heritage-month-2023', NULL, '<div class=\"wp-block-image\">\n<figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-238-300x195.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8006\" style=\"width:408px;height:265px\" width=\"408\" height=\"265\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-238-300x195.png 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-238-600x389.png 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-238-768x498.png 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-238.png 1031w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 408px) 100vw, 408px\" /></figure>\n</div>\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><sup>Photo credit: pefcu.blog</sup></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Hispanic Heritage Month started first as Hispanic Heritage Week, and then it expanded to a month with the purpose of celebrating the culture and contributions of American citizens whose ancestors came from Spain, Mexico, the Caribbean, Central America, and South America.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">According to a publication from&nbsp;<a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fmealsonwheelsmd.org%2F&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7Cbcc4ccd4eacf40ee1a7b08dbbd44c093%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638311875198462009%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=ALfFkIs5xbsv0iww%2B9Un0Syj3841HcSiX0LUNpXqlN8%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">mealsonwheelsmd.org</a>, the idea of expanding the Hispanic heritage celebration from a week to a month &#8220;was introduced by US Representative Esteban E. Torres (CA) [in 1987], who proposed expanding the celebration to one month. The next year, in 1988, Senator Paul Simon (IL) put forth a similar bill. It was this bill that was signed on August 17th, 1988, creating National Hispanic Heritage Month.&#8221;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">This recognition of the Hispanic Heritage Month celebration is important because Hispanics have helped to carry the legacy of this country with their hard work, family devotion, faith, and passion, making the U.S. strong and prosperous.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Hispanic Heritage Month celebrates a vivid culture with beautiful and diverse traditions that were carried to the U.S., helping its people stay connected to their roots, teaching their children the language and how to embrace their heritage, and helping others create a sense of empathy toward people in the Hispanic community.&nbsp;Hispanics have been successful in maintaining their customs while assimilating into American culture.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">A lot of Hispanic countries, such as Guatemala, Salvador, Honduras, Nicaragua, Costa Rica, Mexico, and Chile, have their Independence Day celebrations in the middle of September.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Usually, Hispanic embassies organize parades and other cultural events during the month of September.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Those parades are held in New York City. During those events, typical food is served, music is played, and dances are performed from each country. There are themed floats that are used as decorations to portray something relevant for each country on different days within the same month.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Exploring and celebrating Hispanic culture is another way to expand your knowledge and show respect and appreciation for diversity. If you are Hispanic, that is an opportunity for you to reconnect with your roots and create beautiful memories while having a good time.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>But why do Hispanics celebrate Hispanic Heritage Month?&nbsp;</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Hispanic Heritage Month should be celebrated because Hispanics “are also a vital part of the American population,” according to a report from&nbsp;<a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fminorityhealth.hhs.gov%2F&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7Cbcc4ccd4eacf40ee1a7b08dbbd44c093%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638311875198462009%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=%2FcutPVLoylO%2FldL10X35jw8gaAHOIZKqiK2CkyD4TyY%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">minorityhealth.hhs.gov</a>. “The Hispanic population in the United States accounts for 19% or 1 in 5 Americans, according to the 2020 census,” which means that this community is the nation&#8217;s second largest racial or ethnic group after non-Hispanic whites.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">According to a commentary from the Executive Director of the Hispanic Chamber Janessa Calderon published at&nbsp;<em><a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fourquadcities.com%2F&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7Cbcc4ccd4eacf40ee1a7b08dbbd44c093%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638311875198462009%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=4sSE5mP%2FKDLZbriOB0aJFE7KiwgMIOaRvToqFA2zjAw%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">ourquadcities.com</a></em>, we should celebrate the Hispanic Heritage Month because it “provides [Hispanic people] with a unique opportunity to honor [their] rich cultural heritage, recognize [their] accomplishments, and reaffirm [their] commitment to fostering growth and unity.”</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Both Hispanics and non-Hispanics can enjoy, celebrate, and be inspired by the celebration of Hispanic Heritage Month to learn and experience new music, new food, new dances, and create new memories.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>Ways to celebrate the Hispanic Heritage Month</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>1. Try some Hispanic dishes</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">You can go to different restaurants that serve Hispanic food and try some of their dishes.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">You only need to pick one Hispanic country, search for a restaurant from that region, and immerse yourself in the flavors of that new culture.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>2. Take an in person or a virtual tour to a museum</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">You can experience Hispanic culture through the arts.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">You can visit a museum and look at the art created by the most important painters, sculptures, and other kinds of artists that come from any Hispanic country.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">One example can be &#8220;La Casa Azul, which is Mexican artist Frida Kahlo&#8217;s former home. The name literally translates to the Blue House. Now, it&#8217;s a museum dedicated to her work and life,&#8221; noted the Boys &amp; Girls Clubs of America in Parent Resources in their article published at&nbsp;<em><a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fbgca.org%2F&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7Cbcc4ccd4eacf40ee1a7b08dbbd44c093%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638311875198462009%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=qIFjYZY5SDvT2ZWSmyBeR%2Bw%2BRSAVmL8LaT1Zdyu%2FiSI%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">bgca.org</a>.</em></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">This is a way to understand how the Hispanic culture is and what they offer to the world while celebrating that culture.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>3. Take part in cultural activities and celebrations</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">You can have a deeper understanding of a Hispanic nation&#8217;s culture and the reasons behind why some things are done the way they are by participating in one or more of its cultural events or celebrations.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">You can go to some parades in New York City, you can join some friends in their celebrations, or you can search online for some cultural events that are going on in your area to commemorate Hispanic heritage and attend them.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">You can also watch those celebrations and cultural events on television from the comfort of your home.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">4.&nbsp;<strong>You can try some of the traditional dances from different Hispanic countries.</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">If you consider every floor, a dance floor or you are simply curious to see how those dances are, it is time to search for ways to learn Hispanic dances such as salsa, punta, bachata, merengue, samba, tango, cumbia, and others.<br>You can look at some YouTube videos, you can join a dance academy, or you can ask your Hispanic friend to teach you some dancing moves.</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'LG167', NULL, '2023-09-24 18:50:13', 0, 'Photo credit: pefcu.blog Hispanic Heritage Month started first as Hispanic Heritage Week, and then it expanded to a month with the purpose of celebrating the culture and contributions of American citizens whose ancestors came from Spain, Mexico, the Caribbean, Central America, and South America. According to a publication from mealsonwheelsmd.org, the idea of expanding the Hispanic…\n', NULL, NULL, 1),
('ed767471-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Ole Worm Statue Unveiled at Old Westbury', 'ole-worm-statue-unveiled-at-old-westbury', NULL, '<div class=\"wp-block-image\">\n<figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-239-1023x1536.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8009\" style=\"width:242px;height:363px\" width=\"242\" height=\"363\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-239-1023x1536.png 1023w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-239-400x600.png 400w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-239-800x1200.png 800w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-239-768x1153.png 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-239-200x300.png 200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-239.png 1066w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 242px) 100vw, 242px\" /></figure>\n</div>\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><sup>Statue at the start of the event. Photo Credit: Vincent Arroyo.</sup></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">On September 19, SUNY Old Westbury unveiled its newest statue, a bust depicting 17th century Danish physician Ole Worm. The event was held in the afternoon on the Campus Center Meadow Terrace. Announced by University President Dr. Timothy E. Sams at the recent&nbsp;<a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.oldwestburycatalyst.org%2F2023%2F09%2F20%2Ffall-convocation-2023%2F&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7Cafd4a7f8789443acc12508dbbd41ef03%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638311863101841751%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=6SlqZ0k1Y%2BYpc1FHNO%2B1fmhWD4cxK4yMWoDIjKoTryQ%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Fall Convocation</a>, the purpose of the event was to show students’ creativity.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Ole Worm, as per&nbsp;<a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FOle_Worm&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7Cafd4a7f8789443acc12508dbbd41ef03%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638311863101841751%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=9E3Ryqw06LA7Qu1YQVowKsz3TbOpV3Pj9le2k3va4tU%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Wikipedia</a>, was a Danish physician, natural historian, and a professor at the University of Copenhagen in the 17th century. Described as a “perpetual student,” Ole Worm lived to learn, and it seems his marble gaze is meant to inspire students to be their very best academic self.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Earlier in the day, rumor had it that the statue had been defaced, leading this reporter to believe that something inappropriate had been drawn on Ole Worm’s storied face. Or maybe his head had been cut off, a la the classic&nbsp;<em>Simpsons</em>&nbsp;episode.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Covered in a tarp, an ocean of students waited with bated breath to see what had become of the statue. As the bust was unveiled, it became apparent that the “defacing” of the&nbsp;<em>Ole Worm&nbsp;</em>bust was more harmless than previously thought.</p>\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\">\n<figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-240-1023x1536.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8010\" style=\"width:249px;height:373px\" width=\"249\" height=\"373\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-240-1023x1536.png 1023w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-240-400x600.png 400w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-240-800x1200.png 800w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-240-768x1153.png 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-240-200x300.png 200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-240.png 1066w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 249px) 100vw, 249px\" /></figure>\n</div>\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><sup>Students Decorating <em>Ole Worm</em>. Photo Credit: Vincent Arroyo.</sup></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">As revealed on their&nbsp;<a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.instagram.com%2Fwgsscenterow&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7Cafd4a7f8789443acc12508dbbd41ef03%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638311863101841751%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=2WvQgdtBuAnHIwUnQ2%2BbnZ%2BJYgtgVWP1R956f3CLxsE%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Instagram</a>, the Women’s, Gender and Sexuality Studies Center (WGSS) had taken it upon themselves to give&nbsp;<em>Ole Worm</em>&nbsp;a makeover, writing popular phrases and hashtags on the podium. “Love is love” said one and “#BLM” read another. Lighthearted moments like this are what make SUNY Old Westbury special, and a message for love and unity can hardly be classified as “defacing.”&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">After a brief word from Vice President of Student Affairs, Randall Edouard, students were invited to go up and decorate the statue. Most opted to wear plastic gloves and paint Ole Worm with their hands. In fact, the very first thing someone did is give&nbsp;<em>Ole Worm</em>&nbsp;a dark green handprint on his face.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Afterwards, students lined up to the Mister Softee trucks for their free ice cream. As for how the students felt, they seemed generally fond of the experience, or rather, fond of the free ice cream. “Free ice cream is pog,” said Bryan, a first year. Most students, when asked their opinions on the event, gave the age old platitude, “It’s nice.”</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'VA153', NULL, '2023-09-24 18:55:15', 0, 'Statue at the start of the event. Photo Credit: Vincent Arroyo. On September 19, SUNY Old Westbury unveiled its newest statue, a bust depicting 17th century Danish physician Ole Worm. The event was held in the afternoon on the Campus Center Meadow Terrace. Announced by University President Dr. Timothy E. Sams at the recent Fall Convocation,…\n', NULL, NULL, 1),
('ed76eac2-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Shift. Breathe. Expand. Painting in Space', 'shift-breath-expand-painting-in-space', NULL, '\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">September 10 &#8211; October 20</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Amelie A. Wallace Gallery</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">SUNY Old Westbury</p>\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\">\n<figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-241-1200x800.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8014\" style=\"width:351px;height:234px\" width=\"351\" height=\"234\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-241-1200x800.png 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-241-600x400.png 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-241-768x512.png 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-241-1536x1023.png 1536w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-241-300x200.png 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-241.png 1600w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 351px) 100vw, 351px\" /></figure>\n</div>\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><sup>Photo Credit: Vincent Arroyo.</sup></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><br>Until October 20, the Amelie A. Wallace Gallery will be hosting&nbsp;<em>Shift. Breathe. Expand. Painting in Space</em>, an exhibition of works by artists Eleanna Anagnos and Alexis Granwell. Before the opening reception, there was a performance by improvisational dancer Christina Gesualdi, with musical accompaniment by Jesse Kudler.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Curated by art historian Tally de Orellana, the works are characterized by their use of paper as a medium in and of itself. The art pieces shown were produced over the last decade, and highlight the artists’ ability to rethink a seemingly ordinary surface like paper.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Eleanna Anagnos primarily creates wall pieces, utilizing natural elements that allows her work to embody the environment she’s inhabiting. Since staying in Mexico, she has been inspired by glyphs, Aztec pyramid designs, and the ancient techniques of the paper medium.</p>\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\">\n<figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-242-1200x800.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8015\" style=\"width:346px;height:231px\" width=\"346\" height=\"231\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-242-1200x800.png 1200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-242-600x400.png 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-242-768x512.png 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-242-1536x1023.png 1536w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-242-300x200.png 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-242.png 1600w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 346px) 100vw, 346px\" /></figure>\n</div>\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><sub>Photo Credit: Vincent Arroyo.</sub></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Alexis Granwell creates painted sculptures, this time out of paper, that evoke our manmade and natural environments. Granwell’s work showcases a deep introspection into what it means to be human, specifically a woman, in this time and how we can move past such narrow thinking.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Anagnos and Granwell met in 2019 and found common ground in their art, and interest in using paper as a form of expression. Over the following years the two would meet virtually and collaborate. Their two studios, in Mexico City and Philadelphia respectively, became one.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">The exhibit is categorized into three parts: Shifting, which focuses on the mixing of cultural ideas on art, Breathing, which focuses on the liberation of the feminine idea, and Expanding, which centers on the expansive use of paper.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">While much is written on the intellectual ideas of these works, it is equally important to note that they are simply aesthetically pleasing on top of it all. Granwell’s sculptures have an otherworldly, alien look to them. The colors highlight this, as you wouldn’t expect these contrasting shades to work so well together.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\">\n<figure class=\"aligncenter size-full is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-243.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8016\" style=\"width:362px;height:272px\" width=\"362\" height=\"272\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-243.png 883w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-243-600x450.png 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-243-768x576.png 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-243-300x225.png 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 362px) 100vw, 362px\" /></figure>\n</div>\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><sub>Photo Credit: Vincent Arroyo.</sub></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Anagnos’ works on the other hand, are firmly on planet Earth, but evidence of an age long gone. The hangings are hardly recognizable as anything even remotely like paper, with sharp popcorn textures and natural hues.Texturally, these art pieces exist outside of classification, like a new species of insect. The artists’ works, though aesthetically contrasting, feed off one another, creating a new visual lexicon.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">On the bottom floor of the gallery is the proverbial Rosetta Stone for this new lexicon: two shelves showing a rainbow array of geological shapes. They look like rocks but they could just as easily be paper, either way, the point still stands. While not literally translating what the viewer has seen, it&#8217;s a nice reminder of the form these artworks come from. It’s as if Anagnos and Granwell are saying, “These are the shapes, colors and textures as you know them, now allow us to show you what they can be.”</p>\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\">\n<figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-244-1023x1536.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8017\" style=\"width:229px;height:343px\" width=\"229\" height=\"343\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-244-1023x1536.png 1023w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-244-400x600.png 400w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-244-800x1200.png 800w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-244-768x1153.png 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-244-200x300.png 200w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-244.png 1066w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 229px) 100vw, 229px\" /></figure>\n</div>\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><sub>Photo Credit: Vincent Arroyo.</sub></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">The terms shifting, breathing and expanding have a literal meaning in this exhibit but they also convey the matter-of-fact existence of the pieces themselves. Evidenced by Anagnos’&nbsp;<em>Queen</em>&nbsp;(2019), a turquoise hanging which casually flows with wind from the A.C., showing whatever side it wants you to see. It is impossible to look over these paintings, these sculptures, without being hyper aware of their place in reality.</p>\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\">\n<figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-245-112x300.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8018\" style=\"width:147px;height:393px\" width=\"147\" height=\"393\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-245-112x300.png 112w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-245-224x600.png 224w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-245-449x1200.png 449w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-245-574x1536.png 574w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-245.png 598w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 147px) 100vw, 147px\" /></figure>\n</div>\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><sub>Photo Credit: Vincent Arroyo.</sub></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Granwell’s sculptures, most notably&nbsp;<em>What Sits Inside Yourself</em>&nbsp;(2023), are intricate masses connected to themselves via stretching paper tendons. The sculptures tell us that our understanding is a huge mass, clouded with melancholic color, and that to clear this haze we must stretch into ourselves, whatever that means to the viewer.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Prior to the opening reception, there was an interesting performance by dancer Christina Gesualdi, and musician Jesse Kudler. The performance comprised abstract acoustic guitar and a thumping wood block from Kudler, with Gesualdi hopping, rolling, shifting and moving with the moment. To me, it seemed like a religious experience. Throughout the performance, Kudler and Gesualdi looked at each other as if in an esoteric ritual.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\">\n<figure class=\"aligncenter size-full is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-246.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8019\" style=\"width:241px;height:322px\" width=\"241\" height=\"322\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-246.png 496w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-246-450x600.png 450w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-246-225x300.png 225w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 241px) 100vw, 241px\" /></figure>\n</div>\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><sub>Photo Credit: Vincent Arroyo.</sub></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Being an improvisational dancer, Gesualdi worked with the energy she got from the art. “I was being present in the moment,” Gesualdi said when asked what she thought, “sort of engaging with the energy.” As her outfit, a blue collar jumpsuit, indicates, she is a worker, and at the mercy of those above, whether it&#8217;s art, a godlike being, or just human impulse.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">The whole thing had this reporter thinking about their place in the grand scheme of it all.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Just as Anagnos and Granwell feed off their environments, just as Gesualdi and Kudler feed off the art, and just as the viewer feeds off their perceptions. Then, and only then, does the critic come in and feed off the leftovers.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">While it’s still at the Amelie A. Wallace Gallery, be sure to visit these contemplative works of art and feed your brain some well-earned introspection.</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'VA153', NULL, '2023-09-24 19:07:57', 0, 'September 10 – October 20 Amelie A. Wallace Gallery SUNY Old Westbury Photo Credit: Vincent Arroyo. Until October 20, the Amelie A. Wallace Gallery will be hosting Shift. Breathe. Expand. Painting in Space, an exhibition of works by artists Eleanna Anagnos and Alexis Granwell. Before the opening reception, there was a performance by improvisational dancer Christina…\n', NULL, NULL, 1),
('ed77408d-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', '“Just Love”: A Call for Change and Unity', 'just-love-a-call-for-change-and-unity', NULL, '<div class=\"wp-block-image\">\n<figure class=\"aligncenter size-full is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-248.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8026\" style=\"width:276px;height:276px\" width=\"276\" height=\"276\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-248.png 1000w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-248-600x600.png 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-248-70x70.png 70w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-248-768x768.png 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-248-300x300.png 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 276px) 100vw, 276px\" /></figure>\n</div>\n\n\n<p class=\"has-text-align-left wp-block-paragraph\"><sub>Bassett’s single cover for his new song, “Just Love.” Photo Credit:&nbsp;<a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fgenius.com%2FJoshua-bassett-just-love-lyrics&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7Ce411f110c9f14bb670ac08dbbd5bde81%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638311974521299076%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=9bLongaLYQyBkS6I2bUyDZylkmKvx%2Fa7c%2FhLD63wj54%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\">Genius.com</a></sub></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><br>It’s not often that songs expressing universal love, crisis awareness and prevention, and unity end up being chart-toppers in our current society. In fact, none of the top ten songs on the&nbsp;<a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.billboard.com%2Fcharts%2Fhot-100%2F2023-08-19%2F%23&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7Ce411f110c9f14bb670ac08dbbd5bde81%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638311974521299076%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=ObBzufNla0PCcfod9UKNRyHxL1GyGoXuG35GTZ0qXEo%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\">Billboard Hot 100</a>&nbsp;chart for the week of September 23 address these themes. This isn’t to say the top ten songs aren’t deserving of their successes. However, songs with deeper, universal messaging for change and awareness&nbsp;<em>do&nbsp;</em>exist, even though they may not receive significant attention.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">On September 22, 2023, pop-singer Joshua Bassett released a new single called, “Just Love.” The song promotes saving lives through spreading love to&nbsp;<em>all</em>, including oneself and one&#8217;s community. The self-directed&nbsp;<a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fyoutu.be%2FeklVBh_Kji8%3Fsi%3DW8_zA2ABxiTdEj7K&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7Ce411f110c9f14bb670ac08dbbd5bde81%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638311974521299076%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=Tbuv%2BqUFR%2FX%2B0pGTh%2FSoQookzP7I2SPnTcGUh7%2BWeyE%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">music video</a>&nbsp;captures the personal struggles of three main characters, ranging from what appears to be a kid to a teengager to a young adult. At the beginning of the video, Bassett confirmed the scenes with the parents fighting were fictional. However, the musical interest of the child and the curly brown-haired appearance of the other two male characters can make a viewer wonder if this portrays Bassett at different points in his own life.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">The characters undergo evident loneliness, depression, substance abuse, and life with domestic abuse between parents. In his song, Bassett raises the question, “what if we just love?” He implies how&nbsp;<em>we</em>&nbsp;can save those souls and support the people who need it the most through love. One set of lyrics that stands out in the song and promotes this theme is, “too many havе lost their lives and too many tears wе&#8217;ve cried &#8217;cause we couldn&#8217;t seem to see the light.”&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Towards the end of the music video, there is a unity between people from different backgrounds, experiences, identities, and struggles inside of a Church, reflecting Bassett’s religious background and motivation. The soulful sound of the song also reflects his Christian religion. Bassett enters the Church with the three main characters, which can symbolize his self-discovery and/or how he wished he felt welcomed during his youth.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">The music video also gives attention to soldiers. When Bassett sings, “in the black ties they fight, &#8217;bout who&#8217;s wrong or right, while the innocent die,” a mother looks at a remembrance photo of her veteran son who passed away. This could imply he passed away fighting in a loveless war or that the veteran was a suicide victim. Bassett listed statistics at the end of the video, writing, “More veterans die from suicide than at war.”</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Among these statistics includes additional facts about suicide, varying types of abuse, trafficking, hunger, and poverty in hopes to raise awareness and encourage his viewers to be the change. One statistic displayed is, “A report of child abuse is made every ten seconds in the United States. (25 times since the start of this video).” He then concluded the video with another written remark, saying, “It ends with us. It ends with love.”&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">The harrowing statistics may seem to reach a broader demographic and may not hit close to home. However, mental health, specifically depression and suicide, ranked as the top health concern for Nassau and Suffolk Counties, according to a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.lihealthcollab.org%2Ffilesimages%2FNews-Blog%2FPRs%2FCommunity%2520Health%2520Assess%2520Survey%2520Release%2520March%25202023.pdf&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7Ce411f110c9f14bb670ac08dbbd5bde81%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638311974521299076%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=Yoj5Hwl6EXANq71z0tDOsAPHWo46JJymxEKjHJggQMo%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">press release</a>&nbsp;from the Long Island Health Collaborative on March 29, 2023. Concerns about drug and alcohol abuse followed.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">The Interagency Task Force on Human Trafficking’s&nbsp;<a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fotda.ny.gov%2Fprograms%2Fbria%2Ftrafficking%2F2021-Human-Trafficking-Annual-Report.pdf&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7Ce411f110c9f14bb670ac08dbbd5bde81%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638311974521299076%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=nFhewW3ymb2aENc2HZPpF6GIeLTgqdhTkt1XFkki2Fc%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">2021 Annual Report</a>&nbsp;said, “Human trafficking referrals continued to spike in 2021, with 344 cases referred to New York State –more than in any prior year since the referral process was started in 2007.” 295 of these referrals were confirmed and 52 were from the Long Island and lower Hudson Valley regions.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">The&nbsp;<a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwebbi1.health.ny.gov%2FSASStoredProcess%2Fguest%3F_program%3D%252FEBI%252FPHIG%252Fapps%252Fchir_dashboard%252Fchir_dashboard%26p%3Dit%26ind_id%3DHd24&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7Ce411f110c9f14bb670ac08dbbd5bde81%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638311974521299076%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=Gk5reqTt8FM6hPxslWxv1er7cOkJ1xFeam141%2BbPfnY%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">State of New York reported</a>&nbsp;that the suicide mortality rate per 100,000 people from 2018 to 2020 was 640 people on Long Island alone. 248 of these deaths were in Nassau County and 392 were in Suffolk County. In December of 2022,&nbsp; “suicide rates among veterans [were] twice as high as among the civilian population,” according to the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fnyhealthfoundation.org%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2022%2F12%2Fveteran-suicide-in-new-york-state-the-latest-trends-dec-2022.pdf&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7Ce411f110c9f14bb670ac08dbbd5bde81%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638311974521455297%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=DIkx8olgxP00XUyEgAgqAHsLJKQY%2BRENuO81OS46AF0%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">New York Health Foundation</a>, with veterans ages 18-54 “experienc[ing] the highest rates of suicide.”</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Resources are available to help with these crises. The&nbsp;<a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Flongislandcrisiscenter.org%2F&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7Ce411f110c9f14bb670ac08dbbd5bde81%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638311974521455297%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=dgC%2BQrUpN%2BBF55DZrcYOZjMUb3iho7vMymThKdHUw%2Fc%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Long Island Crisis Center</a>&nbsp;(LICC), a non-profit organization that specializes in confidential short-term crisis counseling, can be reached at (516)679-1111. SUNY Old Westbury offers resources, as well. The&nbsp;<a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.oldwestbury.edu%2Fdivision%2Foffice-student-affairs%2Fstudent-health-center&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7Ce411f110c9f14bb670ac08dbbd5bde81%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638311974521455297%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=XOlqA%2BhiP%2BCiWpB%2FEnpwvPePDuyk83H3fNNeIm28Prs%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Student Health Center</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.oldwestbury.edu%2Fdivision%2Foffice-student-affairs%2Fcounseling-psychological-wellness-services&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7Ce411f110c9f14bb670ac08dbbd5bde81%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638311974521455297%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=mzi4U4bMmZ7NjM30Go3DuBZmRBcb3lkTUmRle2sj9jA%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Counseling &amp; Psychological Wellness Services&nbsp;</a>are located in the I-Wing of the Campus Center, also known as the “Wellness Wing.” Their respective phone numbers are (516) 876-3053 and (516) 876-3250. Additional information is available on their websites. Resources that Bassett listed in his music video description are as follows:</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">“Suicide and Crisis Lifeline – 988</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">National Domestic Violence Hotline – 1-800-799-7233</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Substance Abuse and Mental Health Service – 1-800-662-4357</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">National Center for Missing &amp; Exploited Children – 1-800-843-5678</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">National Call Center for Homeless Veterans – 1-877-424-3838 and Press 1</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">National Human Trafficking Hotline – 1-888-373-7888”</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">You are not alone.&nbsp;</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'JV368', NULL, '2023-09-24 20:47:42', 0, 'Bassett’s single cover for his new song, “Just Love.” Photo Credit: Genius.com It’s not often that songs expressing universal love, crisis awareness and prevention, and unity end up being chart-toppers in our current society. In fact, none of the top ten songs on the Billboard Hot 100 chart for the week of September 23 address these themes. This…\n', NULL, NULL, 1);
INSERT INTO `content` (`id`, `type`, `title`, `slug`, `description`, `content`, `url`, `approval_status`, `author_id`, `editor_id`, `created_at`, `is_featured`, `excerpt`, `video_url`, `featured_image`, `category_id`) VALUES
('ed779556-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'The Ultimate Guide to Panther Pride', 'the-ultimate-guide-to-panther-pride', NULL, '\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/hc-1.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8049\" style=\"width:380px;height:253px\" width=\"380\" height=\"253\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/hc-1.png 1024w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/hc-1-600x400.png 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/hc-1-768x512.png 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/hc-1-300x200.png 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 380px) 100vw, 380px\" /><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"><sup>Students at Panther Pride Kickoff Lunch 2022. Photo Credit: <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.facebook.com%2FSUNYOldWestbury%2Fphotos%2Fpb.100055272986898.-2207520000%2F10161311889156062%2F%3Ftype%3D3&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7C476c6edf8cd6494cceaa08dbbe401ffc%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638312954858033916%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=zTmWyJ42HmzRy62FmPxw%2BcFUwugwyv%2Bkxk1clv9oKmI%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\">SUNY Old Westbury Facebook</a></sup></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">This week marks the start of our annual&nbsp;<a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.oldwestbury.edu%2Fpantherpride&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7C476c6edf8cd6494cceaa08dbbe401ffc%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638312954858033916%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=M3mQzT%2FCrsPN%2FfMkGWZlrBaIONq3YHXbt4pNf14GyP8%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\">Panther Pride Homecoming</a>! From Wednesday, September 27 to Saturday, September 30, enjoy a series of on-campus events, activities, and fun! Here’s a detailed schedule of what to expect.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>Wednesday, September 27, 2023</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Foldwestbury.campuslabs.com%2Fengage%2Fevent%2F9248168&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7C476c6edf8cd6494cceaa08dbbe401ffc%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638312954858033916%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=Xh1rKNGxqs%2BfEHMfUiIemk4iNf06KFUanpl1Wc3PGeQ%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Panther Pride Kickoff Lunch</a>&nbsp;(2:30 p.m. in the Campus Center Atrium): Join the OW community for a celebration of the beginning of Homecoming. Lunch will be served to attendees, including a nacho bar and Italian ices.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Foldwestbury.campuslabs.com%2Fengage%2Fevent%2F9345635&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7C476c6edf8cd6494cceaa08dbbe401ffc%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638312954858033916%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=62sQqmwqGPGkii8zKgIyuw6QoUFCHAbRQR96H0NMd8E%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Alumni Career Night</a>&nbsp;(5:30 p.m. in NAB 1100): Hear from former OW Men’s Basketball players about adjusting to their professional careers “from the locker room to the board room.” Take this opportunity, hosted by Alumni Affairs, to learn from mentors who were once in&nbsp;<em>your</em>&nbsp;shoes. Free food will be served and pre-registration is required for attendees. For RSVP information, check&nbsp;<a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Foldwestbury.campuslabs.com%2Fengage%2Fevent%2F9345635&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7C476c6edf8cd6494cceaa08dbbe401ffc%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638312954858033916%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=62sQqmwqGPGkii8zKgIyuw6QoUFCHAbRQR96H0NMd8E%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Panther Connect</a>.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Foldwestbury.campuslabs.com%2Fengage%2Fevent%2F9427753&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7C476c6edf8cd6494cceaa08dbbe401ffc%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638312954858033916%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=aRxK4rJ7Dh81nrRySvObESaTgWSw4t9OdC%2FgT8hcigs%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Meet the Royal Court</a>&nbsp;(7:30 p.m. at the Student Union Panthers Pad): Candidates for this year’s royal court will get to meet and speak to the OW community. Attendees can also enjoy some Domino’s Pizza! Learn more about how the Royal Court functions on&nbsp;<a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.oldwestbury.edu%2Fpantherpride%2Froyal-court&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7C476c6edf8cd6494cceaa08dbbe401ffc%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638312954858033916%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=iAkGfecuT%2BxTi0K6ctlWMIu5HByAB6nXt6emP%2BaXHS0%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">their website</a>.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>Thursday, September 28, 2023</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Foldwestbury.campuslabs.com%2Fengage%2Fevent%2F9338283&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7C476c6edf8cd6494cceaa08dbbe401ffc%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638312954858033916%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=X4xZn841WZBjuAG88fa6xXZRWS8v%2BluFxyxruHK%2FE2g%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Fuel Up with Commuter Outreach</a>&nbsp;(10:00 a.m. &#8211; 12:00 p.m. in the Campus Center, Parking Lot): CSLI, SGA, and Commuter Outreach are bringing the Buzz’d truck to campus for some coffee and tea to help “fuel you up” for Homecoming. The first 100 students, faculty, and staff to attend can enjoy their drinks for free!</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">“Cookie Hooky” Hour (12:00 p.m. throughout Campus): Look out for the President’s Cabinet traveling throughout campus for free cookies and treats!</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Cake-Off Decorating Competition (2:30 p.m. in the Campus Center Atrium): While decorating cakes requires pre-registration, you could still attend this annual tradition and see which team’s cake you think shows their Panther Pride the best!</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Foldwestbury.campuslabs.com%2Fengage%2Fevent%2F9402251&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7C476c6edf8cd6494cceaa08dbbe401ffc%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638312954858033916%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=BMPvRgS8EaC8Yw%2BKge5tCSPBp0gH8MchFQHqP7cp3mg%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Stay Up at the Union</a>&nbsp;(11:59 p.m. &#8211; 4:00 a.m. in the Student Union Multipurpose Rooms): Get ready for an overnight party at the Student Union! The Campus Activities Board hosts a “White Lie” themed night of fun, games, free food, and giveaways! Show up with a white shirt and write your own white lie on it.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>Friday, September 29, 2023</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Foldwestbury.campuslabs.com%2Fengage%2Fevent%2F9432494&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7C476c6edf8cd6494cceaa08dbbe401ffc%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638312954858033916%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=0GdnlmYDpb6bwr9bh2qFX9Fukif1EFkGeH1tnDDjW7Q%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Food Truck Friday</a>&nbsp;(1:00 p.m. &#8211; 3:00 p.m. at the Jackie Robinson Athletic Complex): The “Trini Bites” Food Truck will be joining the OW community to serve some Caribbean food. The first 150 students to show up will receive free “Roti Bowls.”</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Foldwestbury.campuslabs.com%2Fengage%2Fevent%2F9427751&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7C476c6edf8cd6494cceaa08dbbe401ffc%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638312954858033916%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=4jum17UsncwgKtJczN8PVWtJwK039SGNEkxLbc2t2qQ%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Student vs. Faculty/Staff Softball Game</a>&nbsp;(2:30 p.m. at the Jackie Robinson Athletic Complex): That’s right! Your professors, advisors, and other faculty and staff will be playing against the students in a fun softball game. Go cheer them on!</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Alumni Networking Reception (5:30 p.m. &#8211; 7:30 p.m. at The City Cellar Wine Bar &amp; Grill): Reconnect with your peers at this alumni-only reception! All tickets have already been reserved, so if you missed out this year, be sure to stay tuned with Panther Pride updates next year on&nbsp;<a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.oldwestbury.edu%2Fpantherpride&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7C476c6edf8cd6494cceaa08dbbe401ffc%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638312954858033916%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=M3mQzT%2FCrsPN%2FfMkGWZlrBaIONq3YHXbt4pNf14GyP8%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">their website</a>&nbsp;or on SUNY Old Westbury social media accounts.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Foldwestbury.campuslabs.com%2Fengage%2Fevent%2F9268516&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7C476c6edf8cd6494cceaa08dbbe401ffc%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638312954858190159%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=qqzqsZi2R9Jer%2BasiP4x4Kpy0Nn5EF9EyxLR1TIeyzA%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Fraternity and Sorority Expo</a>&nbsp;(8:00 p.m. at the Maguire Theater): Join FSL in, “Channel Surfing,” as OW’s fraternities and sororities perform to celebrate homecoming. Doors will open at 7:00 p.m. and students and their guests must RSVP via&nbsp;<a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Foldwestbury.campuslabs.com%2Fengage%2Fevent%2F9268516&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7C476c6edf8cd6494cceaa08dbbe401ffc%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638312954858190159%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=qqzqsZi2R9Jer%2BasiP4x4Kpy0Nn5EF9EyxLR1TIeyzA%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Panther Connect</a>&nbsp;in advance.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>Saturday, September 30, 2023</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.oldwestbury.edu%2Fnews-events%2F2023-fall-open-house&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7C476c6edf8cd6494cceaa08dbbe401ffc%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638312954858190159%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=FuFBuQ3m8lijZXiCdLOs4VINtC%2BsDzVRmdO1FU1psmE%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Admissions Open House</a>&nbsp;(9:00 a.m. &#8211; 1 p.m. at the Campus Center, NAB, and Student Union): If you want to join the OW community, this event is for you! You can learn about what OW has to offer and catch a glimpse at some of our homecoming fun!</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">OW Alumni Tailgate (10:00 a.m. at the Clark Center Parking Lot): It’s exactly what it sounds like! Alumni can tailgate for PantherFest, and set up grills and chairs. Alumni pre-registration is required.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Women’s Soccer Game (11:00 a.m. &#8211; 1 p.m. at the Jackie Robinson Athletic Complex): The women’s soccer team will face the United States Merchant Marine Academy. Cheer on the Panthers with friends, family, and the OW community!</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">OW Roast (11:30 a.m. at the Jackie Robinson Athletic Complex): Enjoy a hotdog from the Vice President for Enrollment Management and Marketing, Bryan Terry, and a cold non-alcoholic drink during the soccer game. Alumni pre-registration is required.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Meet the President (12:30 p.m. &#8211; 1:30 p.m. in the Student Union Panthers Pad): Take this opportunity to meet with OW President, Timothy E. Sams. You can learn about the University’s path, goals, and accomplishments.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Alumni Tent (1:00 p.m. &#8211; 5 p.m. at the Meadows Terrace): This alumni-only event is a place to reconnect, have lunch, and meet the President. A list of scheduled activities will be sent to registered alumni prior to the event. Alumni may bring guests. Pre-registration is required.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Foldwestbury.campuslabs.com%2Fengage%2Fevent%2F9248163&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7C476c6edf8cd6494cceaa08dbbe401ffc%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638312954858190159%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=xoxcCi7ojFXkmJrh%2FRxQTKxpFAC%2FiL%2FQH29MkADhNv4%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">PantherFest Carnival and Family Day</a>&nbsp;(1:00 p.m. &#8211; 5 p.m. at the Jackie Robinson Athletic Complex): This carnival is open to OW students, faculty, staff, and their families! Show your families your Panther Pride and let them join in on the fun! Alumni can attend, but pre-registration is required.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Foldwestbury.campuslabs.com%2Fengage%2Fevent%2F9345745&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7C476c6edf8cd6494cceaa08dbbe401ffc%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638312954858190159%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=w6Gnsw%2BFiDzqDhu04IWW5BVWT9u1OfSG0ttx8kOL%2BU0%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\">Salute to Hip-Hop Concert</a>&nbsp;(5:30 p.m. &#8211; 8:00 p.m. at the John &amp; Lillian Maguire Theater): Celebrate 50 years of hip-hop at this musical event! OW alumni, Kool Moe Dee ‘87 and Darryll “DLB” Barksdale ‘97 with the Fearless Four, will be performing. Special guests, Joe$ki Love and KimieChen, will also perform. Pre-registration is required for alumni, OW students, faculty/staff, and the general public.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Foldwestbury.campuslabs.com%2Fengage%2Fevent%2F9402260&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7C476c6edf8cd6494cceaa08dbbe401ffc%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638312954858190159%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=Ltqj0W5GHsMB8OhqMlon9a3s34U%2B2SqLyHDyFaUURUk%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\">Royal Court Coronation</a>&nbsp;(9 p.m. &#8211; 1 a.m. at the Student Union Multipurpose Rooms): The OW Royal Court Royalty will be crowned for the Freshman, Sophomore, Junior and Senior classes. This will be the final Panther Pride Homecoming event and is open to current students and their approved guests.</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'JV368', NULL, '2023-09-26 18:29:35', 0, 'This week marks the start of our annual Panther Pride Homecoming! From Wednesday, September 27 to Saturday, September 30, enjoy a series of on-campus events, activities, and fun! Here’s a detailed schedule of what to expect. Wednesday, September 27, 2023 Panther Pride Kickoff Lunch (2:30 p.m. in the Campus Center Atrium): Join the OW community for a…\n', NULL, NULL, 1),
('ed77f231-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Rice Pudding: The Origin and Variations of the Recipe', 'rice-pudding-the-origin-and-variations-of-the-recipe', NULL, '<div class=\"wp-block-image\">\n<figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-251-300x200.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8074\" style=\"width:409px;height:273px\" width=\"409\" height=\"273\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-251-300x200.png 300w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-251-600x400.png 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-251-768x512.png 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-251.png 1200w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 409px) 100vw, 409px\" /></figure>\n</div>\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><sup>Colombian-style rise-putting. Photo Credit: <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fblog.amigofoods.com%2F&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7Cd0248ccbf7d343fddac408dbc033f5c5%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638315101692118249%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=9PT5Z1%2FI3bf3xzuTIhufGNNj85hUOJcaZE11wKrA%2BuQ%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\">blog.amigofoods.com</a>. </sup></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Rice pudding is a Latin American dessert that can be found all over the world due to its simple ingredients and incredible taste. It has some variations from country to country, but each recipe shares some similarities. </p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">It’s not a seasonal or celebratory dish. Just a wonderful, hearty, sweet bite that everybody loves. It can be served warm or cold everywhere, and you can add extra flavor to it.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">The only difference between countries when making rice pudding is the addition of some extra flavors, which can vary.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>The origins of rice pudding</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">The exact origins of the rice pudding are unknown, and there are many beliefs around it.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">According to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fblog.amigofoods.com%2Findex.php%2Fother-latin-foods%2Farroz-con-leche-latin-rice-pudding%2F&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7Cd0248ccbf7d343fddac408dbc033f5c5%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638315101692118249%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=1j2PmQd0PTmlswrItTSoulVzTrD9JqzRn5S%2Beges388%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">amigofoods.com</a>, “During the Fatimid era, around the 12th century, many new desserts were created” and “the tradition carried on through the next three centuries, where Egypt and the Levant diligently [continued] creating new sweet and savory dishes.” Therefore, rice pudding is believed to have been created around that era.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Others believe that rice pudding, “has its roots in India and China many thousands of years ago. It&#8217;s thought to have come to Europe around the 14th century. However, it was around even earlier as a type of rice pudding used medicinally for stomach upsets in Roman times,” according to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.thedailymeal.com%2F1294416%2Frice-pudding-history%2F&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7Cd0248ccbf7d343fddac408dbc033f5c5%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638315101692118249%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=gkTXmYADDvssxrkGXWDL8%2B1NXIH4m%2BKmNzVRT2yXcp4%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">thedailymeal.com</a>.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>So, what ingredients do other countries add to the preparation of rice pudding to make it unique?</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Rice pudding, or arroz con leche, is made with cow milk, white rice, and sugar, which are basic ingredients in every kitchen around the world.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Typically, vanilla flavoring is used throughout Nordic and Anglo-Saxon nations to add an extra flavor to the rice pudding.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">The Spanish version has the classical addition of butter, cinnamon sticks, and a dash of tangy lemon.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">According to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fyourfriendinreykjavik.com%2Fthe-almond-porridge%2F&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7Cd0248ccbf7d343fddac408dbc033f5c5%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638315101692118249%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=HtzxXg26gh13fEaAPNoco%2FX9IkKvtFup7r4OQ8qEjYY%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">yourfriendinreykjavik.com</a>, in Finland, they eat rice pudding for breakfast, and when they eat it as a side dish, they add almonds as a sign of good luck.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">In Italy, orange peels are added to enhance the flavor of the rice pudding.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">In Iran, the dessert is traditionally made with saffron, and in northern India, it’s made with cardamom, according to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linsfood.com%2Fpersian-saffron-rice-pudding-sholeh-zard%2F&amp;data=05%7C01%7Clgarci26%40oldwestbury.edu%7Cd0248ccbf7d343fddac408dbc033f5c5%7Cf5089034f2334f12a71638b7f4904370%7C0%7C0%7C638315101692118249%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000%7C%7C%7C&amp;sdata=TfjXhtFmHSQejsz04oDE4cUGxabp94f2CuAaKW5JuJY%3D&amp;reserved=0\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">linsfood.com.</a></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">In Colombia, people add toppings like cheese, cinnamon powder, and raisins to the mixture.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Peruvians combine rice pudding with a sweet purple maize jelly, stewed with fresh and dried fruits, which is eaten as a side dish.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">In the Caribbean, rice pudding is served with grated coconut or condensed milk.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>How to prepare the perfect rice pudding&nbsp;</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>Prep Time:&nbsp;</strong>5 minutes</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>Cooking Time:&nbsp;</strong>20 minutes.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>Total Time:&nbsp;</strong>25 minutes</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>Servings:&nbsp;</strong>4 people</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>Ingredients</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\">\n<li>6 cups of water.&nbsp;</li>\n\n\n\n<li>2 cups of whole milk&nbsp;</li>\n\n\n\n<li>½ cup sugar</li>\n\n\n\n<li>½ teaspoon salt</li>\n\n\n\n<li>½ cup long-grain white rice</li>\n</ul>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>Instructions</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\">\n<li>In a large saucepan, add ½ cup of long white rice and six cups of water. Bring to a boil over medium-high heat until the rice is cooked.</li>\n\n\n\n<li>Add ½ cup of sugar, ½ teaspoon of salt, and 1 cup of milk. Stir in the rice occasionally and reduce the heat to low.</li>\n\n\n\n<li>Once thickened, remove from heat, add the rest of the milk, and stir.</li>\n\n\n\n<li>Add your favorite toppings to the rice pudding.</li>\n\n\n\n<li>If you want to serve it warm, set it to room temperature for about 10 minutes, or you can serve it chilled by refrigerating it for one hour; it all depends on your preference. Then, it’s all ready to be eaten!</li>\n</ol>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'LG167', NULL, '2023-09-29 00:46:38', 0, 'Colombian-style rise-putting. Photo Credit: blog.amigofoods.com. Rice pudding is a Latin American dessert that can be found all over the world due to its simple ingredients and incredible taste. It has some variations from country to country, but each recipe shares some similarities.  It’s not a seasonal or celebratory dish. Just a wonderful, hearty, sweet bite that…\n', NULL, NULL, 1),
('ed783911-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'podcast', 'News from the World of Media!', 'news-from-the-world-of-media', NULL, '<h2><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-8087\" src=\"https://www.oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/NMB-1-Balloons-Headlines-Boxes-Rect-1024x768.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"610\" height=\"458\" /></h2>\n<h2><strong>This Week on New Media Beat:</strong></h2>\n<audio class=\"wp-audio-shortcode\" id=\"audio-8082-1\" preload=\"none\" style=\"width: 100%;\" controls=\"controls\"><source type=\"audio/mpeg\" src=\"https://www.oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/NMB-1-Web-2023-09-28.mp3?_=1\" /><a href=\"https://www.oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/NMB-1-Web-2023-09-28.mp3\">https://www.oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/NMB-1-Web-2023-09-28.mp3</a></audio>\n</br>\n<ul>\n 	<li><strong>UK: </strong>Can YouTube Verification Slow the Misinformation?</li>\n 	<li><strong>Mexico:</strong> Are Journalists Safe?</li>\n 	<li><strong>El Salvador: </strong>Press Freedom Under Bukele?</li>\n 	<li><strong>India: </strong>Can AI Anchors Be Trusted?</li>\n 	<li><strong>Ukraine: </strong>Is the Government&#8217;s X Campaign Effective?</li>\n 	<li><strong>Belarus:</strong> How Does Lukashenko Treat the Press?</li>\n</ul>\n<!-- /wp:post-content -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n\n<a href=\"https://www.newmediabeat.org/\"><strong>New Media Beat</strong></a> covers new media news from around the world. NMB is a production of  Media Studies students from the <a href=\"https://www.oldwestbury.edu/\" target=\"_self\" rel=\"noopener\">SUNY College @ Old Westbury.</a>   We scour the web for news about about the world of media, journalism and technology.\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n</br></br>\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\nNMB is co-produced by Alex Hajko &amp; Aidan Bongiorno. Our engineer is Alex Hajko.  Our hosts are Judy Imasogie and Daniel Jefferson.\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n</br></br>\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\nThe NMB Podcast streams live on <a href=\"http://www.owwrny.org/\">Old Westbury Web Radio</a> Thursdays from 10:00-11:00 AM EST.  Can&#8217;t listen live? Our podcast will be <a href=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/?cat=17\">posted</a> for your listening pleasure every Friday afternoon.\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n</br></br>\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\nFollow<strong> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/OWWRGMN\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">@OWWRGMN</a></strong> for a curated feed of the latest new media news for aspiring media professionals.\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'TC527', NULL, '2023-09-29 19:03:07', 0, 'This Week on New Media Beat: UK: Can YouTube Verification Slow the Misinformation? Mexico: Are Journalists Safe? El Salvador: Press Freedom Under Bukele? India: Can AI Anchors Be Trusted? Ukraine: Is the Government’s X Campaign Effective? Belarus: How Does Lukashenko Treat the Press? New Media Beat covers new media news from around the world. NMB is a production of  Media Studies…\n', NULL, NULL, 1),
('ed78ca81-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'Horoscopes', 'horoscopes', NULL, '\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>Aries: March 21–April 19</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-252.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8103\" style=\"width:203px;height:203px\" width=\"203\" height=\"203\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-252.png 332w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-252-70x70.png 70w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-252-300x300.png 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 203px) 100vw, 203px\" /><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"><sub><sup>Photo Credit: horoscope.com</sup></sub></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Cultivate an attitude of gratitude and be positive. Give yourself what you really need. You have been going through some troubles, but they will end if you start using affirmation words and start believing in your full potential.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Don’t be afraid to be adventurous and have good conversations with influential people, because they will be the ones helping you discover your purpose in life.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>Taurus: April 20–May 20</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-253.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8104\" style=\"width:207px;height:207px\" width=\"207\" height=\"207\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-253.png 336w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-253-70x70.png 70w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-253-300x300.png 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 207px) 100vw, 207px\" /><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"><sub><sup>Photo Credit: horoscope.com</sup></sub></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Right now, is the time to follow your instinct. You will experience the death of a loved one, and your emotions will fluctuate but it will not interfere with your career.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Be attentive to anyone who may want to sabotage you at work. You need to think fast and change some of your next moves to confuse the enemy and prevent harm. &nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>Gemini: May 21–June 21</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-254.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8105\" style=\"width:199px;height:199px\" width=\"199\" height=\"199\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-254.png 326w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-254-70x70.png 70w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-254-300x300.png 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px\" /><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"><sub><sup>Photo Credit: horoscope.com</sup></sub></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">This is the time to pursue a new job opportunity in another country and learn another language. Get rid of toxic people that are blocking your way to success and forge new friendships.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">This time, someone will arrive into your life to help you financially, now that you are starting a new chapter of your life.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>Cancer: <em>June 22–July 22</em></strong></p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-255.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8106\" style=\"width:203px;height:203px\" width=\"203\" height=\"203\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-255.png 334w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-255-70x70.png 70w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-255-300x300.png 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 203px) 100vw, 203px\" /><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"><sub><sup>Photo Credit: horoscope.com</sup></sub></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">This is the time to start thinking about yourself and cultivate self love, so you can be ready for your next romantic relationship.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Don’t be afraid to go out of your comfort zone and involve yourself in situations that will help you to grow spiritually. Explore your creative side. It may help you on this journey of discovering and loving yourself more.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>Leo: July 23–August 22</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-256.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8107\" style=\"width:203px;height:203px\" width=\"203\" height=\"203\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-256.png 344w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-256-70x70.png 70w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-256-300x300.png 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 203px) 100vw, 203px\" /><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"><sub><sup>Photo Credit: horoscope.com</sup></sub></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">The message for you is to stop what you are doing and start focusing on your family. Ask your partner for some advice on how you should manage your budget more effectively and put your pride aside. This is not your time to start new businesses, or buy a new house, or you will encounter some financial hardships that may cost you your partner.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>Virgo: August 23–September 22</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-257.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8108\" style=\"width:200px;height:200px\" width=\"200\" height=\"200\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-257.png 322w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-257-70x70.png 70w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-257-300x300.png 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px\" /><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"><sub><sup>Photo Credit: horoscope.com</sup></sub></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Your relationship is going through its prime. Don’t ruin it! Slow down and avoid any arguments. Work on your communication skills, and be more attentive with your partner. This is also the time to get married and buy a new house.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Your health may be at risk. Change your eating habits and go for an annual checkup. Stop being stubborn and follow the doctor’s advice, so you will be fine.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>Libra: September 23–October 23</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-258.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8109\" style=\"width:203px;height:203px\" width=\"203\" height=\"203\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-258.png 342w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-258-70x70.png 70w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-258-300x300.png 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 203px) 100vw, 203px\" /><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"><sub><sup>Photo Credit: horoscope.com</sup></sub></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">You will have the opportunity to grow spiritually and you will have to lead an important project. This is your moment! If you&#8217;ve been working through some issues or trying to make some tough decisions, this is the time to ask for help and end that cycle of bad luck. Say yes more often and enjoy the privileges that come with it. Be positive and don’t settle for less.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">You will encounter the love of your life, and you will get married before the end of the year.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>Scorpio: October 23-November 21</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-259.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8110\" style=\"width:210px;height:210px\" width=\"210\" height=\"210\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-259.png 356w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-259-70x70.png 70w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-259-300x300.png 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 210px) 100vw, 210px\" /><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"><sub><sup>Photo Credit: horoscope.com</sup></sub></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Someone that wants to ruin you is trying to discover your major secret, but don’t worry. There will be another person that will help you to prevent a major incident.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">This is your time to be serious about your future. Focus and study more to pass some important exams that will define your career path.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>Sagittarius: November 22-December 21</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-260.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8111\" style=\"width:192px;height:192px\" width=\"192\" height=\"192\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-260.png 338w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-260-70x70.png 70w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-260-300x300.png 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 192px) 100vw, 192px\" /><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"><sub><sup>Photo Credit: horoscope.com</sup></sub></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">If you have a relationship, or a job that is too much for you, this is the time to let them go and start over. You will encounter a childhood friend that will help you to start over, and this friendship may turn into a romantic relationship.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Don’t be afraid to love and travel, because this is your season to be loved and discover new adventures.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>Capricorn: December 22-January 19</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-261.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8112\" style=\"width:193px;height:193px\" width=\"193\" height=\"193\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-261.png 320w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-261-70x70.png 70w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-261-300x300.png 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 193px) 100vw, 193px\" /><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"><sub><sup>Photo Credit: horoscope.com</sup></sub></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">If you are in a relationship, this is the time to teach your partner how to treat you better. Do what you can to keep the peace, whether that’s giving each other space or reaching out to a couples’ counselor. This is not a good time to get engaged or make new friendships.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Academically you will find some challenges but you will overcome those challenges with satisfactory results that will help you to achieve the job of your dreams.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>Aquarius: January 18-February 19</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-262.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8113\" style=\"width:188px;height:187px\" width=\"188\" height=\"187\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-262.png 368w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-262-70x70.png 70w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-262-300x298.png 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 188px) 100vw, 188px\" /><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"><sub><sup>Photo Credit: horoscope.com</sup></sub></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">You are going to have many disagreements with your clients, but always remain humble and diligent, turning those disagreements into something positive that may benefit you.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Focus on your career because this is the year for you to succeed. You will graduate with honors, and you will be promoted at work for your excellent work.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><strong>Pisces: February 19-March 20</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-263.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8114\" style=\"width:210px;height:199px\" width=\"210\" height=\"199\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-263.png 330w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/image-263-300x284.png 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 210px) 100vw, 210px\" /><figcaption class=\"wp-element-caption\"><sub><sup>Photo Credit: horoscope.com</sup></sub></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">You will have the opportunity to travel more, and you will encounter new people that will help you to reconnect and understand your past. This is the time for you to reconnect with your family. It will be good for your soul and will help you to heal and find happiness.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">Awaken your creative side and make it the source of your income. You have a hidden talent that will bring you success.&nbsp;</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'LG167', NULL, '2023-09-30 21:49:00', 0, 'Aries: March 21–April 19 Cultivate an attitude of gratitude and be positive. Give yourself what you really need. You have been going through some troubles, but they will end if you start using affirmation words and start believing in your full potential.  Don’t be afraid to be adventurous and have good conversations with influential people,…\n', NULL, NULL, 6),
('ed7940bb-61ed-11f1-98fa-60cf847a2597', 'article', 'SUNY Old Westbury Pays Tribute to 50 Years of Hip Hop', 'suny-old-westbury-pays-tribute-to-50-years-of-hip-hop', NULL, '\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"></p>\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\">\n<figure class=\"aligncenter size-full is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-271.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8147\" style=\"width:402px;height:300px\" width=\"402\" height=\"300\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/image-271.png 632w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/image-271-600x448.png 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/image-271-300x224.png 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 402px) 100vw, 402px\" /></figure>\n</div>\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><sup>Photo credit: Aidan Bongiorno. Joe$ki Love.</sup></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">SUNY Old Westbury&#8217;s homecoming week continued with a concert, paying tribute to the last 50 years of hip hop. Many performers took the stage on September 30th, at the&nbsp;John &amp; Lillian Maguire Theater. They gave&nbsp;students a glimpse of the past and reflected on the popularity and generations of hip hop music.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">The Maguire theater had a full crowd Saturday night, many students, alumni, staff, and family members were in attendance. As the crowd entered the theater, hip hop music was blasting from the speakers on the stage giving a sense of that upbeat feeling that hip hop is known for.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">The concert consisted of two alumni performers,&nbsp;Moel Dewesei who goes by his hip hop name Kool Moe Dee (Class of ’87), being one of them. He is widely known as the creator of “fast rap,” a style used by a lot of hip hop artists to prove his or her skills. Dewesei’s best hits are “How Ya Like Me Now” (1988), “Wild Wild West” (1989), and “I Go To Work” (1989)<em>.&nbsp;</em></p>\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\">\n<figure class=\"aligncenter size-full is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-272.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8148\" style=\"width:397px;height:294px\" width=\"397\" height=\"294\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/image-272.png 772w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/image-272-600x445.png 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/image-272-768x569.png 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/image-272-300x222.png 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 397px) 100vw, 397px\" /></figure>\n</div>\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><sup>Photo credit: Aidan Bongiorno. The Fearless Four.</sup></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">The second alumni performance was by Darryll “DLB” Barksdale (Class of ’97), with his group called the Fearless Four, they are widely known for their hits “Rockin’ It” (1982) and “Problems of the World (1982). The group was the first to sign with the major record label, Elektra Records, to produce the album “Creepin up on Ya” (1994).</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">The concert also had performances from two famous hip hop performers, including Joe$ki Love, who performed his platinum-selling 1986 single “Pee Wee’s Dance,” and KimieChen, an artist from Linden, New Jersey. KimieChen is in the early stages of her hip hop career. She’s inspired by the sounds of artists like Aaliyah, Diana Ross and the Supremes, Mary J. Blige and Toni Braxton.</p>\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\">\n<figure class=\"aligncenter size-full is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"uploads/image-273.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-8149\" style=\"width:365px;height:340px\" width=\"365\" height=\"340\" srcset=\"https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/image-273.png 818w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/image-273-600x559.png 600w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/image-273-768x715.png 768w, https://oldwestburycatalyst.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/image-273-300x279.png 300w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 365px) 100vw, 365px\" /></figure>\n</div>\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"><sup>Photo credit: Aidan Bongiorno. KimieChen</sup></p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\">The concert overall was a smashing success and a great way to wrap up homecoming weekend. A variety of students that attended described the concert as “thrilling” while some called it “vibrating,” “up-lifting,” and “a true tribute to hip hop.”&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n', NULL, 'APPROVED', 'AB740', NULL, '2023-10-04 09:58:17', 0, 'Photo credit: Aidan Bongiorno. Joe$ki Love. SUNY Old Westbury’s homecoming week continued with a concert, paying tribute to the last 50 years of hip hop. Many performers took the stage on September 30th, at the John & Lillian Maguire Theater. They gave students a glimpse of the past and reflected on the popularity and generations of hip…\n', NULL, NULL, 1);
